<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>News from the ACIJ</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><H1>A.C.I.J. NEWS PAGE</H1></CENTER>

<CENTER><H3>New developments and updates from the ACIJ</H3></CENTER>

<HR WIDTH=100%>

<H3>WELCOME TO THE ACIJ</H3>
<PRE></PRE>
This news page sets out some of the main activities of the Centre over 1995 and more recent times, and indicates some future directions. The news page will be updated as time permits and developments occur.<P>
Over the past year, there has been a steady stream of publications, seminars, books, courses and education resources put out by the Centre, all helping to raise the profile of journalism teaching at UTS.<P>
The Centre receives infrastructure support and subcontracting work for student publications from the University, but no direct funding, Salaries and running costs are paid for largely out of earnings from sales of publications, seminar fees, etc. Ideas and offers on funds for the Centre are invited. All donations are tax deductible.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Awards to the Centre</H3>

In a clean sweep for the ACIJ, the Journalism Education Association in 1995 awarded its four annual prizes for print journalism to the Centre's two serial publications, Reportage and Snoop. The national Osmar White Awards for Student Journalism are made in tribute to the veteran war journalist. Snoop investigative journalism magazine was jointly awarded Best Student Publication for its second issue which focussed on the private investigation industry and privatisation of public services. A story it carried on the privatisation of prisons was awarded Best Postgraduate News Feature. In Reportage Media Bulletin, a story on a long forgotten document on the cost of the Olympics won Best News Story, while the cover story of issue No 3 on media harassment of a sex discrimination witness won the Best Undergraduate News Feature.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Reportage Media Bulletin</H3>

Reportage is Australia's only magazine looking at the work and performance of journalists, together with research on journalism practice. Reportage has published research on journalism issues including the sources used by Australia's foreign correspondents, the nature of reporting of Aboriginal deaths in custody, and the media representation of the Mabo debate. Student pieces in the magazine have won two JEA awards in 1995. The public response to the magazine has been impressive. Some recent reader feedback includes "most interesting" from Prof Noam Chomsky, and "excellent" from John Pilger. Subscribers are welcome. <P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Snoop</H3>

Snoop is a magazine of investigative journalism, and is produced twice a year primarily by journalism students in the "Publications: Techniques and Practice" class. Snoop is a competitive outlet for high quality journalism from UTS student journalists. The magazine itself and an article from it won two prizes in the JEA awards last year. The magazine has undergone a major redesign with the current issue, and consideration is being made for changing its style further during 1996. <P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Hidden Stories Seminar Series:</H3> 
<H4>The death of 'truth' on East Timor</H4>

On 16 October 1995, the Centre held a seminar to mark the 20th anniversary of the killing of five Australia-based journalists in Balibo, East Timor, and the killing on 8 December 1975, of another Australian journalist in Dili. Extensive media coverage resulted in part from the ACIJ seminar. The Centre also published a new booklet, titled 'The Balibo Incident in Perspective', by former Australian consul to Dili, James Dunn, who wrote: "The killing of the journalists was undoubtably the worst and the most wanton act of its kind in the history of Australian journalism". The booklet became the focus of much media and government attention. Copies are still available.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Young People and the Media Seminar</H3>

The Centre held a sell-out seminar at the State Parliament House theatrette in November 1995, to examine the effects of the media reporting on young people. The Centre has previously published detailed research on how young people are portayed in the media. It attracted high-profile journalists and media producers, as well as many young people and youth workers. A joint project with Sydney City Council, the seminar brought together those on both sides of the cameras (and pens) to develop an alternative way of reporting young people. A publication is planned.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Signposts to Asia and the Pacific</H3>

This AusAID-supported project is a World Wide Web information database, on which Chris Conlon has been working half-time since June 1995 with Anna-Marie Antonio recently joining as a part-time researcher. The database will provide hard-to-get information primarily on countries of our region, in what will become a major tool for Australian journalists. Wendy Bacon and Alan Knight are principal researchers on the Project Team. The project is due for completion in June 1996.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>George Munster Award for Freelance Journalism</H3>

This national award for freelance journalism is administered by the Centre and was presented at a small ceremony in November. This year the $1,000 award was won by Jim Colman for a series of articles on urban planning and design issues published in The Sydney Review. A special commendation was also given to Jill Margo for her series on mens health in the Sydney Morning Herald. It is the tenth year the award has been made, and it is advertised nationally each year in July. It is Australia's only national award for freelance journalism.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Continuing Education Program</H3>

Our program of continuing education courses has been developed by Bonita Mason, the Centre's continuing education officer. These professional development courses have proved popular with journalists and others wanting to both polish and develop new skills. Courses conducted have included: Feature Writing; Sub-editing for Print Journalists; Power Searching for Media Professionals; Journalism for Organisations; Journalism for Community Groups; and Publishing on the Web. The 1996 schedule of courses is available on from our ACIJ homepage.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Internet Research Project</H3>

A Vice-Chancellor's Development Fund grant is being used to develop internet-based journalism research. Research has commenced to assess internet access and useage as well as conduct story and background research and to develop contacts. The difficulties and opportunities of internet-based research have been established and a journalism research project is underway.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Relationship with University of Papua New Guinea</H3>

The visit to PNG by Peter Cronau in June 1995 allowed the Centre to initiate a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) between the South Pacific Centre for Communication and Information in Development (SPCenCIID) at the University of Papua New Guinea (UPNG) and the ACIJ. The draft MOU allows for co-operation on a number of levels between UPNG and UTS. For example, selected articles from the UPNG journalism students' newspaper, Uni Tavur, will shortly be appearing on the ACIJ Internet Site. In August Associate Professor Wendy Bacon visited UPNG to teach in their new Graduate Certificate in Investigative Journalism. A UPNG book on the media in the Pacific area is being distributed in Australia by the Centre.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Nius Bilong Pasifik</H3>  

'Nius Bilong Pasifik' is a book on the media in the Pacific region, published by the University of Papua New Guinea Press and distributed in Australia by the ACIJ. The book includes a chapter on the media coverage of the conflict on Bougainville. It is a book 'unique in its topic and scope', so one reviewer said.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Under Pressure: the Asia Pacific Media</H3>

The Centre is to publish in April 1996 a book with the Media Entertainment & Arts Alliance (MEAA) and the International Federation of Journalists (IFJ), titled 'Under Pressure: the Asia Pacific Media', with contributions from a wide range of Asia and Pacific journalists and researchers. This has developed from an IFJ/MEAA conference held in Sydney in 1995.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Books in development</H3>

Three books are presently in development. In early manuscript form is one book on Sources and another on Media Accountability. Being finalised is 'Everybody's Business', a resource book on company and land searches.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>Visitors to the Centre</H3>

The Centre is the focus of overseas visitors interested in journalism education. We have recently hosted visits from journalists, editors, researchers and educators from Singapore, the Solomon Islands, Indonesia, East Timor, Singapore, the USA, Canada, Britain, Hong Kong, and student journalists from Brazil and Spain.<P>
<PRE></PRE>

<H3>How you can help</H3>

The Centre needs support in many ways and everyone can assist. For example there is a 10% discount available for a limited period on several publications the Centre has including 'Nius Bilong Pasifik' and our library research guide 'Mastering the Maze'. Please consider giving these and other ACIJ publications as gifts. We are also looking for new people for our Continuing Education Program. If you have ideas that you think the Centre may be interested in, tell us. <P>
ACIJ NEWS PAGE will be a regular feature our web site outlining our ideas, projects and directions. Look in on us again soon. 
<P>Thanks for visiting our site.

<PRE></PRE>


<B>Peter Cronau<BR>
Director</B>
<P>
ACIJ, UTS, PO Box 123, Broadway, NSW 2007<BR>    
Tel (02) 330 2488   Fax (02) 281 2967<BR>   
E-mail: 
<A HREF="MAILTO:p.cronau@uts.edu.au">p.cronau@uts.edu.au</A> 
