<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>ACIJ Resources</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">


<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=230>
<IMG HEIGHT=100 ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/images/logo-acij.gif"> </td>
<td width=30><BR></td>
<td>
<center><Font size=5><B>BOOKS, REPORTS, VIDEO, AND MANUALS FROM THE ACIJ</B></font></center>
</td></tr></table>
<PRE></PRE>

<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>EAST TIMOR: 
THE BALIBO INCIDENT IN PERSPECTIVE</B></FONT><BR>
by James Dunn
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The deaths of five Australian-based journalists in Balibo, East Timor, on 16 October 1975 was "undoubtably the worst and the most wanton act of its kind in the history of Australian journalism," writes James Dunn, former Australian diplomat. The prior knowledge of the Australian government to the impending Indonesian invasion of East Timor meant that the journalist's deaths were covered-up and have been to this day. <BR>  
40pp; 1995<IMG HSPACE=10 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"> Cost $5.95
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>NIUS BILONG PASIFIK: 
MASS MEDIA IN THE PACIFIC</B></FONT><BR>
edited by David Robie
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
This book - the first comprehensive resource book on the South Pacific news media - provides a critical appraisal of the Pacific regions emerging media organisations and their  output. Sixteen of the region's most prominent journalists and media educators explore the nature and problems facing contemporary Pacific mass communications industry. Detailed country profiles provide social, political and media information on each country. Produced by the University of PNG, with assistance from the ACIJ.<BR>  
285pp; 1995<IMG HSPACE=10 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif">Cost $19.95
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>THE ENVIRONMENTAL EFFECTS OF MOUNT LYELL OPERATIONS ON MACQUARIE HARBOUR AND STRAHAN</B></FONT> <BR>by Alexandra de Blas
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Supressed for 16 months, this detailed report exclusively published by the ACIJ, lifts the lid on the effects of 100 years of mining at the Mt Lyell copper mine. Following threats of defamation action the University of Tasmania declined to publish this work. Since the report's publication, the author of the report has been awarded the Vincent Fairfax Ethics Award.<BR>  
1994<IMG HSPACE=10 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif">Cost: $30
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<Font size=5><B>MAGAZINES </B></font>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B>REPORTAGE  MEDIA BULLETIN</B></FONT> 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Media magazine of the ACIJ.  It reports on issues mis-represented or under-represented in the mainstream media, as well as offering insightful analyses of the media's approach to these issues.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Subscription for Four Issues: <BR>
$15 Individual; $30 Organisation (incl post/handling)
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>SNOOP </B></FONT> 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
This award-winning biennial magazine of investigative journalism combines the cutting edge of journalism with a fresh and entertaining style.  Snoop  tackles stories outside the mainstream news and current affairs agenda, and is an outlet for students and upcoming journalists.  
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Annual Subscription: <BR>
 $10 Individual; $20 Organisation  (incl post/handling)
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<Font size=5><B>REPORTS</B></font>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B>MEDIA ACCOUNTABILITY</B></FONT>
<BR>A source book of discussion and materials
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Why are sections of the media on the nose? What does it mean to say the media should be accountable to the public? On what do journalists base their claim of privilege  in regard to protection of confidential sources? Media experts canvass various proposals for reform. Appendices include newspaper cuttings, excerpts from judgments and law reform reports.
<BR> Publication expected early 1995  Order in advance.<IMG HSPACE=10 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif">Cost: $20
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>JOURNALISM AND THE LAW</B></FONT>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
A series of papers on the way journalists report on the law and the way the law interferes with the work of journalists. Ian Temby, QC, talks of inadequacies in reporting corruption investigations; Jenny Brockie explains the techniques she uses to circumvent defamation; Prof. David Flint, Australian Press Council chair, compares foreign laws on confidential sources; Wendy Bacon speaks about the way the law interferes with investigative journalism.
<BR> 	Cost: $10
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>THE PRACTICES, PRIORITIES AND PREJUDICES OF FOREIGN REPORTING</B></FONT>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
How fair is the media on foreign affairs? These papers look at the strengths and weaknesses of the Australian media's coverage of foreign affairs. 
<BR>Cost: $10
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>YOUTH AND THE MEDIA</B></FONT>
<BR> by Debra Adelaide
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
This unique report looks at the representation of young people in the print media. It examines stories published in a range of metropolitan, regional, suburban and youth oriented publications, and finds the images of young people are largely negative stereotypes. A ground-breaking work.   
<BR>Cost: $15
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>REPORTING BUSINESS</B></FONT>
<BR>by Brian Toohey, Julianne Schultz, Zoltan Matolcsy
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Analyses business reporting in the 1980s and looks at some ethical dilemmas facing business journalists. A survey found that business reporters, editors and producers often lack the resources to do more than support the established viewpoints.  Analyses the changing style of business journalism. 
<BR>Cost: $15
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>NEWS ON NEWS</B></FONT>
<BR>by Diane Powell
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
A study of the way News Ltd newspapers report the commercial activities of News Corpn. By examining coverage of Compass Airlines, the News Ltd debt restructuring, the annual results and AGM in 1991, this report throws new light on the way a major media group reports its own commercial activities.
<BR>Cost: $10
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>ACCURACY IN AUSTRALIAN NEWSPAPERS</B></FONT>
<BR>by Julianne Schultz
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
How accurate are our papers and what do they do when they get it wrong? Examining the accuracy of four Sydney newspapers, the correction policies of all major Australian newspapers, and surveys the attitudes of prominent people towards the issue.
<BR>Cost: $5
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<Font size=5><B>VIDEO</B></font>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B>MAKING A DIFFERENCE</B></FONT>
<BR>Produced by Kitty Eggerking
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Looks at how infotainment news values like 'conflict'  have dominated coverage of Aboriginal and ethnic issues in the Australian media. It gives a voice to those affected by negative coverage, and shows how perceptions of ethnic and indigenous people have been shaped. Concludes that by balancing traditional news values with empowering images, we can in fact make news positive. An 18 minute documentary especially suitable for schools and TAFE colleges.	 
<BR>Cost: $40
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<Font size=5><B>RESOURCES FOR TRAINING, RESEARCH & REPORTING</B></font>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<FONT SIZE=+1><B>THE FRONT PAGE AND BEYOND</B></FONT>
<BR>by Julie Duncan
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Our popular five-volume work manual for basic journalism training. Adopted by the major metropolitan newspaper employers, the manual is suitable for journalism educators, colleges and media organisations. 		 
<BR>Cost: $175 (incl post and pack).
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>MASTERING THE MAZE</B></FONT>
<BR>by Christine Fogg
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
A specialised national guide for journalists and other researchers which describes how to access the enormous amount of information freely available to journalists in libraries Australia-wide. Written for journal-ists and researchers working in the media, it emphasises electronic information resources and includes a select list of CD-ROM databases available in state and tertiary libraries.            	 
<BR>Cost: $8	
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>EVERYBODY'S BUSINESS</B></FONT>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
A hands-on manual for investigating companies and land ownership in Australia.  Begins with a step-by-step guide to company searches, land title searches, use of stock exchange and other libraries and on-line searches. Interviews with journalists, environmentalists and community workers on relevance of business investigations and research strategies  Case studies of stories where company and land investigations have been used. An excellent resource for journalists, researchers, students, community activists, and unionists.           	 
<BR>Cost: $20	
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1><B>SIGNPOSTS</B></FONT>
<BR>by Kitty Eggerking and Diana Plater
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
 This 152 page practical guide book begins with the findings on the media made by the various inquiries into racism in Australia.  It includes a guide to non-racist language, codes of practice and news charters.  Designed for working journalists as well as journalism students, Signposts  contains a detailed contact list of relevant Aboriginal and ethnic organisations.           	 
<BR>Cost: $20	
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

