<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Introduction</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Introduction<br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="images/interbw75.gif"></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">An introduction to<BR>
 Intersections with Asia</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">by Alan Knight</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The day of the western foreign correspondent is almost over. The safari suited reporter who interprets Asian events and files his stories down crackling telephone lines already exists more in the minds of adventure novelists than in the electronic reality of the late twentieth century. News no longer moves in one direction, back to the Western metropolis on linear cables. Instead, journalists across the world are increasingly bound together in a seamless web of information which covers almost everyone and everything, from the glass towers of Hong Kong to the jungles of Cambodia. It follows that any discussion of the future of international reporting must go beyond the metropolis and its neo-Orientalist preconceptions; it must also consider un-western perspectives of News.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Bouncing the News</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Journalists can no longer hide behind national boundaries, ignoring the impact of their reporting on neighbouring countries. Satellite television, interactive news services, improved telephone and fax services and the internet do not acknowledge border checkpoints, challenging politicians' attempts to censor or direct news. But these new technologies, spread by rapidly rising affluence, also allow wrong or insensitive reports to bounce rapidly around the region's media, encouraging disharmony and discrimination. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Reports of a racist politician receiving support in Australia can be transmitted instantly to audiences across the ASEAN nations, threatening negotiated trade and diplomatic arrangements. Asian governments which may not themselves espouse media freedoms can choose to interpret such reports as evidence to support caricatures of Australians as unreconstructed white supremacists. Australian reporters meanwhile can be characterised as "congenital liars" by Asian politicians seeking to bolster sagging domestic political support. Reports detailing ruling family corruption in Jakarta can likewise be regarded as a direct insult to the national interest and constructive international diplomacy.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Fiction or Friction</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Australia which has the longest tradition of a free press in the region, is in danger of being unfairly castigated for its journalists' robust approach to reporting, if not their insensitivities to non-Western cultures. Australian working journalists' lack of self-analysis means that many assume that value systems which they learn in Australia are universal. When foreign correspondents with such views arrive in south east Asia, this ignorance of "other" media procedures, can be interpreted as cultural arrogance. The collision between differing  journalism value systems can result in what  Singapore's Senior Minister, Lee Kuan Yew calls "friction". Australian journalists' long held identification with what they call Western interests and what many Asians identify  as the old colonial powers make them easy targets for increasingly well connected and articulate Asian critics. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Even conservative news organisations recognise the need for change. The former Editor in Chief of The Australian , Paul Kelly, said that  Australian journalists should try to be sensitive to cultural differences, as a matter of professionalism:
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<!--Begin quote table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=330>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=40><P></TD>
<TD>"I think that we still find it difficult in as much as our cultural predilections are to the  United States and to the UK, and we must continue to cover those parts of the world because they're important in their own right and their certainly very much the areas of interest for a lot of our readers. But by the same token it's enormously important for us to expand and improve our coverage of Asia far more than what we've been able to do. I think this is going to be an ongoing and difficult challenge for the Australian media." 
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End quote table-->
<br>
Australians are coming to understand what many Asians have long recognised. Negative and stereotypical reporting is not only inaccurate and ethically wrong; it can have a direct and rapid impact on national economies as well as international relations.  Singaporean consumers can easily choose other than "racist" Aussie beef. Malaysians can send their children to someone else's universities. Wealthy Indonesians can do their Christmas shopping in Hong Kong instead of Sydney. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#top">Return to top</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="intro02.html">Next section</A> ] 
</CENTER></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="index.html">Homepage</A> ] 
[ Introduction ] 
[ <A HREF="program.html">Program</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A> ]
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br> 
[ <A HREF="panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A> ]
</CENTER></B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="resources/dot_clear.gif"><br> 
<FONT SIZE=-1><B>Copyright &copy 1996.  <BR>
The copyright on this paper belongs to the author.</B></FONT>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Body Table-->

