<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>Crisis in Australian Broadcasting - A Report</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist">
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=RIGHT>
<H1>The Crisis in Australian Broadcasting<BR>A Report</H1><BR>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=70><BR></td>
<td width=390>
<H4><B>"None of our leaders has accepted as legitimate the mildly<BR> inquisitive, sometimes provocative and mainstream public<BR> broadcasting system in the form of the ABC. Because they<BR> 
can't completely control this taxpayer-funded agency,<BR> 
reprisals have come in the form of funding strangulation."<BR>
<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Quentin Dempster, ABC TV</B></H4>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=50><BR></td>
<td width=375>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Attacks on the ABC and SBS signal a crisis for the independence of Australia's public broadcasting system. The Australian Centre for Independent Journalism held a public seminar in August to discuss the situation. This report by Sumegha Agarwal.</FONT>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<IMG HEIGHT=32 ALT="T"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/../resources/T_cap.gif">he present crisis in public broadcasting arises out of three recurring questions surrounding public broadcasting. These are questions of effective control or editorial independence, the changing role of a national broadcaster, and the issue of continued funding for a public broadcaster.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">While these questions get discussed, the process of doing so is eating into the very fundamentals of public broadcasting.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">The spectre around role of public broadcasting is raised so much that it could mean facilitating the breach of an election promise by the present government. In his election campaign, Prime Minister John Howard committed in the party manifesto on public broadcasting to maintain existing levels of Commonwealth funding and triennial funding for the ABC and SBS. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">

<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">On July 16, the Minister for Communications and Arts, Senator Alston, announced that ABC funding will be immediately reduced by 2 per cent, and for the next financial year will be reduced by a further $55 million with no further guarantees beyond that. SBS too is groaning under a 2 per cent cut to its budget.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">The budget cuts have angered and frustrated thousands of people in the country and thus while 30,000 thronged the Domain in Sydney on August 4 to raise their voice in support of the ABC, at the University of Technology, Sydney (UTS), journalists, journalism students and journalism educators assembled one morning, on August 15, to discuss the crisis in public broadcasting. The seminar was organised by the Australian Centre for Independent Journalism (ACIJ) at UTS, and was chaired by Alan Knight, Director of the ACIJ.
</td>
<td width=50><BR></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=50><BR></td>
<td width=375>
<IMG HEIGHT=32 ALT="L"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/../resources/L_cap.gif">iz Jacka, a media analyst and Dean of Humanities and Social Sciences at UTS, Quentin Dempster of the ABC's 7.30 Report, Jeune Pritchard, Talks Editor with the ABC's Radio National, and Daniela Thorsch, of SBS TV's Insight current affairs program, discussed their concerns about public broadcasting.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">On the role of public broadcasting Dempster quoted Robert Hughes's analysis of American culture which identified the lack of a mainstream public broadcasting system in the USA as a contributing factor to the collapse of social cohesion in that society. Referring to the Port Arthur massacre where Howard announced that Australia would not be following America in its gun culture perversity, Dempster said if Howard does not take a similar un-American course when deciding on the future of public broadcasting in Australia "it will be a national tragedy."

<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">

<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">Robert Hughes has argued that in an American context, Nixon, Reagan and Bush had aggressively attacked the American public broadcasting system. Dempster said, in an Australian context, one could delete Nixon, Reagan and Bush and insert Fraser, Hawke, Keating and Howard. The agenda is to marginalise the ABC, to continue the strangulation of funding under Hawke and Keating.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">Dempster argued the Howard government has no mandate from the public to interfere with the ABC, when a Senate select committee headed by Senator Richard Alston last year concluded "that the basic structure of the ABC is sound and that the need for a quality national broadcaster is greater today than it was a decade ago."
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">Now this same person, in his new capacity as Minister for Communications and Arts has announced a review of the ABC Charter, into its role and functions. The standing of the Alston committee findings is now uncertain.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">

<BR><IMG HEIGHT=32 ALT="J"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/../resources/J_cap.gif">eune Pritchard argues that the outcome of the Bob Mansfield review can be predicted. The ABC has accepted a $55 million cut next year, and is likely to see a collapsing of the networks. Pritchard considers the existence and survival of public radio as a national issue. "It is a issue in this country. It is about cultural and intellectual life in this country."
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">Liz Jacka said, "The present attacks behove us to think very carefully about how public service broadcasting serves the whole community and to think about those sections of the community that don't use public service broadcasting, and about the role of public service broadcasting in this particular time."
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">Alan Knight said,"It's simply not possible to insulate news and current affairs, as their wider organisations go into tail spins." Less competition caused by less resources devoted to public broadcasting would inevitably mean less of the specialised reporting needed to cover increasingly complex issues in a faster moving world, Knight added.
</td>
<td width=50><BR></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=50><BR></td>
<td width=375>
<FONT=+1><B>The cuts and the aftermath: at  the ABC</B></FONT>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<IMG HEIGHT=32 ALT="T"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/../resources/T_cap.gif">he 2 per cent budget cut announced for this year will mean, according to Quentin Dempster,"industrial execution of an estimated 1,300 staff - almost one in every four."
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">"In-house drama, features and documentary are at risk, and the ABC will become a transmitter for hire by private investors willing to bankroll productions for the export and cable markets after a domestic free-to-air showing," he said.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">Speaking about Radio National, Pritchard stated "there is a point beyond which you can't maintain the network." Current overall cuts would mean a cut of $1 million for Radio National which is over 70 per cent of their budget. With such cuts, Pritchard thinks it will be an extremely painful and difficult task to save the network and maintain it as a specialist network.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">"Senator Alston lobbed a grenade that we would lose $55 million next year. This will decimate ABC Radio; well be looking at only having about two networks," she said.
</td>
<td width=50><BR></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=50><BR></td>
<td width=375>
<FONT=+1><B>The BBC and  the ABC</B></FONT>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<IMG HEIGHT=32 ALT="I"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/../resources/I_cap.gif">n other countries public service broadcasting began when there was nothing else in the broadcasting sphere. Australia is extremely unusual because it has had a mixed system of public and commercial broadcasting from the beginning. Thus the role broadcasters played in our society was quite different explained Jacka.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">The BBC takes 18 billion a year, six times what it costs to run the ABC. It has four to five times as many staff and is funded by a license fee. Compared to other broadcasters, the ABC is extraordinarily efficient, small and cheap, says Jacka. Dempster asserted that the ABC is the most cost effective public broadcaster in the world.
</td>
<td width=50><BR></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=50><BR></td>
<td width=375>
<FONT=+1><B>The cuts and the aftermath: at SBS</B></FONT>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
"The SBS newsroom is one of the best equipped newsrooms in the country. But there is no one in it anymore," said Daniela Thorsch. "You can go in and throw something and you would not hit anybody, all you will is the pot plants which are about to be taken away because they are too expensive.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">"The cuts that have happened at SBS are far greater than 2 per cent. The reason is that our entire budget is far too small for what we are attempting to do. We have this constant problem of taking on new programs, new ideas, new directions and not having the money to fund them."
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<IMG HEIGHT=32 ALT="A"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/../resources/A_cap.gif">ccording to Thorsch, the budget cut means losing around 75 people out of a total staff of 766. "On top of that almost all the freelancers and all the casuals have been put off. All the people who are working there are trying to hold the whole thing together, people are going down like flies. The greatest staff loss is happening among journalists in television and radio - people who make programs, who contribute to doing what we're meant to be doing." 
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">Thorsch said the Budget cuts could mean reducing the quality of what is being produced now  meaning fewer documentaries and in-depth programs, and less variety. "People are feeling helpless, hopeless, alienated. The redundancy process has been very painful and morale sapping. They worry 'will we be merged with the ABC?' I cant see that the ABC can even contemplate any such expansion, given the problems they have themselves."
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">News and current affairs programming has had many changes to accommodate the budget cuts. The focus has now shifted to international news and the future of locally produced programs like Insight is very uncertain.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">In the middle of all these redundancies, said Thorsch, a lot of money is being put into capital and equipment development. A new TV studio and a child care centre have been approved recently, and digital television is looming. 
</td>
<td width=50><BR></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=50><BR></td>
<td width=375>
<FONT=+1><B>Independence of SBS and its relationship with the ABC</B></FONT>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<IMG HEIGHT=32 ALT="T"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/../resources/T_cap.gif">horsch raised the issue of editorial independence for SBS. As an independent corporation, SBS legally has its independence; "but of course, independence from what, independence from whom?. "A lot of what SBS does is really determined by a need for the ethnic communities to deliver their votes to whichever government thats in power," said Thorsch.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">Daniela proposed that "SBS has to define itself in its relationship with the ABC which a lot of people at SBS see as moving into a multicultural area, which they must do, given that over 30 per cent of Australians come from non-English speaking backgrounds." 
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">"The old insecurity even about our raison detre has hit us again," said Thorsch.
</td>
<td width=50><BR></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=50><BR></td>
<td width=375>
<FONT=+1><B>Who is to be the advocate</B></FONT>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<IMG HEIGHT=32 ALT="J"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/../resources/J_cap.gif">eune Pritchard recalled there was huge resistance at the very high level of management of what was happening in regard to public seminars, such as those organised by Phillip Adams. "It caused a convulsion among both staff and management about do we become our own advocates. I think we have to," she concluded.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">Pritchard talked of the huge response they got from people following the public rallies at many places in the country. But she said "I dont know if this public support will be enough to stop the cuts next year."
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">Liz Jacka cautioned that those who belong to cultural elites and who are attached to institutions like public service broadcasting have a certain kind of self-interest. "We also work in them, so we do have a self-interest in preserving them. We also have cultural, journalistic and moral values shaped by them, so when they come under attack we do feel emotionally upset and we articulate these arguments about preserving the national identity."
</td>
<td width=50><BR></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=50><BR></td>
<td width=375>
<FONT=+1><B>The future directions</B></FONT>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<IMG HEIGHT=32 ALT="J"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/../resources/J_cap.gif">acka feels we have not paid attention to currents of change occurring abroad in the broadcasting and communications environment over the last few years. In Australia, the debate has been focused on commercial radio, pay TV, and tele-communications policy, overshadowing the discussion on public service broadcasting, according to Jacka.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">She suggested looking beyond the immediate impacts to longer more historic changes that are occurring in the communications environment and to come up with something quite intelligent to defend public service broadcasting now.
</td>
<td width=50><BR></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=50><BR></td>
<td width=375>
<FONT=+1><B>Q &A Session</B></FONT>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<IMG HEIGHT=32 ALT="T"ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/../resources/T_cap.gif">he seminar attracted questions and comments from the audience.  Eva Cox suggested that there actually is a desperate need to work on broad-based solutions, to get ourselves together and put a case for widening a public sector which includes public broadcasting. 
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">She said much has been said at the seminar about what has happened in the ABC and SBS but this does not address the actual problem. She expressed concern that "in the last few years we have had no defence for the public sector at all, in any area of official business of the ALP and the Coalition." 
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">Alan Knight said that reductions to the ABC and SBS spending may even be part of a plan.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">"These cries about budget black holes which apparently came as such a terrible shock after the election, may be nothing more than a transparent excuse to implement long standing political agendas which have been previously and repeatedly rejected by voters" said Knight.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">

<I>(Prepared with assistance in transcription by Prabh Dev Singh, Alex Wood, and Helen Sandstrom.)</I>
</td>
<td width=50><BR></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=50><BR></td>
<td width=375>
<FONT SIZE=+1>The Australian Centre for Independent Journalism is keeping the discussion alive on the issues around public broadcasting with its 'Save the ABC' working group. 
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">
The group will hold its first meeting on Wednesday, September 4, from 1 to 2pm at the ACIJ, Room 503, 5th floor, 755 Harris Street, Ultimo, Sydney. All welcome.</FONT>
</td>
<td width=50><BR></td>
</tr></table>

