<HEAD><TITLE>Submission to the ABC Review</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist">
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>Submission to the ABC Review</H1><BR>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<FONT SIZE=+1>August 1996.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Submission by the Department for Social Communication and Journalism, University of Technology, Sydney and the Australian Centre For Independent Journalism.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=5 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
PO Box 123<BR>
Broadway, NSW 2007<BR>
Phone:  61 2 95142488<BR>
Fax:      61 2  2812976<BR>
E-mail: acij@uts.edu.au
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Contributors:
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Assoc Professor Wendy Bacon (Dept head)<BR>
Alan Knight (ACIJ  Director and Snr lecturer)<BR>
Peter Cronau (ACIJ)<BR>
Penny O'Donnell (lecturer)<BR>
Brenda Mattick (lecturer)<BR>
Chris Spurgeon (lecturer)<BR>
Christine Fogg (lecturer)<BR>
David Robie (lecturer)<BR>
Jo Hawke (researcher)

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

For further information contact:
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Jo Hawke<BR>
email: Jo.Hawke@uts.edu.au. <BR>
Fax to: 6122812976<BR>
Phone: 95141950 (w)<IMG HSPACE=15 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">95604090 (h). </FONT>
</td>
</tr></table>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<H3>INTRODUCTION</H3>

<IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

This submission has been collated from contributions from  members of the Department of Social Communication and Journalism at UTS and the Centre for Independent Journalism following discussions between members and with students. It is specifically concerned with the reporting of news and current affairs at the ABC and is based on extensive practitioner and academic experience in the field by all contributors.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

The submission identifies a series of concerns by the contributors that we seek to have taken into account by the ABC Review. It is organised around the Inquiry's Terms of Reference with a special focus on news and current affairs in Section 3 (a). It concludes with seven summary recommendations.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

News and current affairs are central to  nine of the 11 radio, television and multi-media services provided by the ABC. The work of journalists, therefore, is integral to the interpretation and delivery of these services according to the current ABC Charter. A  particular form of professional journalism has developed at the ABC that has little currency in the commercial sector. It has been shaped and cultivated by its statutory standing as an independent and public institution and by specific requirements of the Charter. In taking seriously its commitment to the development of public affairs and ethical journalism, the ABC has developed forms of journalistic practices that have fostered the innovation of cultural representations, various genres of public affairs and the application of diverse informational technologies.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

As the Terms of Reference clearly state, the inquiry is required to review all ABC services and Mr Bob Mansfield has clearly stated his intention to rewrite the ABC's Charter (The Australian. August 23, 1996). Since this inquiry was established, there has been marked restructuring by current management including  substantial reductions in the staffing, resourcing and presentation of ABC news and current affairs.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR> 

This submission argues that recommendations from this Review  can provide the grounds to interrupt the current approach to restructuring  at the ABC and recommend a series of changes to the government and to the broadcaster that address the Review's terms of reference without striking at the broadcaster's  core news and current affairs functions.
</td>
</tr></table>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<H3>REVIEW OF ABC FUNCTIONS</H3>

<H3>Section 1.</H3>

This submission argues that national news and current affairs and related programming is the central aspect of the ABC's focus and effectivity which is directed towards developing the public life and dialogue about Australian society and Australia's role in the world. Any refinement of the scope of current ABC activities need to ensure the enhancement and not the reduction of these public life services.

<H3>Section 2.</H3>

The importance of the ABC's presence as a non-commercial broadcasting sector has been heightened under current government policy objectives. The Broadcasting Services Act, 1992 is concerned primarily with providing for competitive commercial services and has severely reduced directive regulation in programming services. Given this context - and in light of the anticipated outcome of accelerated competition from the Government's 1997 inquiry into commercial broadcasting  under the Act - the role of the ABC in providing programming that is not dependent on competitive markets is essential. Given this:

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

a) The ABC needs to review and enhance its historical role as a major innovator in programming and the use of new technologies.
Such a commitment to innovation requires risk-taking in the programming field that carries the possibilities of failure. It is this risk-taking which generates innovation, however, and constitutes the central difference between the public and commercial broadcasting sectors.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

b) In particular, the ABC needs to strengthen and diversify its forms of news and current affairs services. A strong national news and current affairs base acts not only to provide information but inspires the extension of public affairs across programming genres to feed locally produced programs such as comedy and drama.
</td>
</tr></table>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=2 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<H3>Section 3.</H3>

a) This submission will concentrate largely on the following section with regard to the nature of ABC news and current affairs. It includes specific discussion pieces about different aspects of news and current affairs from various contributors and is organised as separate discussions about i)  independence,  ii)   accuracy,  iii)  impartiality and  iv)  comprehensiveness as identified in the terms of reference.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

i) Independent  news and current affairs require structural, political and cultural distancing from powerful influences that can shape news and current affairs. These include influences from commercial, professional and political sources. Given the inevitable restructuring of the ABC funding base and the reductions in public funding, major considerations are necessary.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">*Future funding options need to be structured to ensure they have no direct impact on the content of news and current affairs programming. There is clear evidence that direct commercial funding of media sources influences both editorial and marketing strategies in the commercial media sectors.  More indirect funding approaches, such as the example of Britain's Channel Four funding structure, provides an example of a commercial funding base that has implemented effective accountability measures for market influences. A similar policy approach in Australia, however, would require dramatic policy changes. 
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">*Journalists' own professional culture needs to be considered. It is important that sufficient resources are provided to ensure journalists can act and evaluate news and current affairs independently of other media sources and agendas (such as a dependence on AAP news service and ratings competition with commercial services). It therefore requires a cultural independence from intra-professional pressures to conform to new agendas that can only develop from a strongly resourced and institutionally supported foundation of independent journalistic practice.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">* It is important that the principle of ABC's funding be  clearly redefined as public  as distinct from political.   To overcome wide-spread concerns that the Review was convened as a form of political interference, the inquiry needs to be specific and judicious in its definitions of the terms of reference and its subsequent recommendations for regulations and mechanisms to ensure clear distinctions between the ABC as a provider of 'public 'rather than directly 'political' services. The interpretation of the requirement for news and current affairs to be accurate, impartial and comprehensive, as discussed below, is an opportunity for just such clarifications.
</td>
</tr></table>

<BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
ii) Accurate  news and current affairs requires extensively researched, documented,  factually correct and well-argued  information. Accurate news and investigations, therefore, requires a strong research base. This includes journalist access and training on the Internet, the provision of extensive and accessible library resources, and the expenses to cover extensive investigations of issues. Both journalists and library staff need to be able to have the time and resources to access commercial online databases such as DIALOG, AUSINET, LEXIS-NEXIS. It is only because the ABC has provided such a resource and training base up to now, that it has achieved its status as the standard bearer of professional, accurate and ethical journalism. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

In particular, the ABC's historic achievements in  Investigative Journalism needs to be understood as a major incentive to provide a highly professional and well resourced news and current affairs department. The investigative role played by the ABC in Australian current affairs was clearly identified in a 1993 research project by the  Australian Centre for Independent Journalism.( The Journalism and The Law, ACIJ, 1993). The project found ABC television and radio to be Australia's major outlet for investigative journalism followed by The Age and Sydney Morning Herald newspapers.  In examining 20 individual investigative stories across Australia between 1989 and 1992 , it was clear that very little substantial investigative journalism was pursued by commercial television outlets or by News Ltd newspapers. Stories covered by the ABC alone included a Golden Walkley award winning program on Four Corners on Aboriginal Deaths in Custody which contributed to the establishment of a National Royal Commission. They also included reports on deaths caused by asbestos and an exposure of scientific fraud. These and many other stories had been originally seen by researchers in commercial television who simply did not have the time, resources or editorial support to pursue the difficult issues or evidence involved. Necessary resources required for this form of journalism  can include seemingly minor details such as funding to meet interviewees  in order to assess credibility. Without a commitment to such detail, accuracy in news and current affairs cannot be sustained. Loss of this kind of resource support can lead to a professional culture that does not encourage or facilitate the 'pro-active' form of journalism required for innovative and accurate current affairs. Discouragement in such pro-active journalism has already been noted by some commentators about sections of ABC news that have been suffering cost-cutting for some time. This needs to be investigated and rectified immediately.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

The Australian Centre for Independent Journalism and UTS's Department of Journalism broadly define investigative journalism as involving in-depth research and the publication of information and fresh perspectives which are socially significant. It is on the basis of the ABC's current affairs achievements that its programs  continue to be used as the benchmark for high quality journalism in Australian journalism schools as well as training centres overseas. The UTS department has about 40 undergraduates who major in Journalism each year and has the largest postgraduate journalism education department in Australia. In hand with other department's around the country, UTS draws heavily on ABC news and current affairs as a professional yardstick. Moreover, the University of Papua New Guinea's South Pacific Centre for Communication and Information in Development (SPCCID) also extensively uses ABC approaches to news and current affairs to formulate the foundations of their professional practice. It should remain a central consideration, therefore, that the ABC news and current affairs does not only provide important domestic and internation new, but also provides an essential educational resource  in other  countries in the development of quality journalistic professional practice.
</td>
</tr></table>

<BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
iii) Impartial  journalism is one of the most contentious aspects of ABC news and current affairs and needs clear definition. The government has  openly criticised ABC news for 'bias' and, according to the SMH,  the new ABC Chair Donald McDonald was instructed by Communications Minister Richard Alston's department to instil <I>'higher standards of professionalism and integrity to provide a greater level of public confidence in the ABC's objectivity' </I>(our italics) (SMH July 13, 1996 p39).

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

It needs to be clearly understood that objectivity and impartiality have quite different meanings in journalistic practice. Public discussion around issues of bias at the ABC, however, has not fully recognised these differences. The way the inquiry defines what good professional practice in news and current affairs should be, provides an opportunity to distance itself from  allegations of political interference.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

The notion of journalistic objectivity  needs to be understood as being rooted in the early development of professional practice in western journalism at the turn of the century. It is scientifically based and promotes the notion that the news sources can be quantitatively measured and delivered through definable techniques of data collation. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

This notion continues in certain public discourses of media criticism and is promoted particularly by institutions such as the political party system. This is because a technical idea of measurable media representations through content analysis is a quick and effective form of critique and defence in a marketing strategy that relies heavily on immediate responses to media reports.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

Journalists and social scientists have for many years, however, been working to reformulate the principle of fairness in reporting to take account of the social context in which reporting occurs. What has emerged as the most commonly understood notion of fairness is that of impartiality  or balance.  These notions imply a series of value judgements which are made in the collation and presentation of public affairs material. These judgements depend on training and education. As a form of professional practice impartiality requires the practitioner to be able to argue they  shaped and presented their news in the most informed, well-researched and fairly-presented form possible. Whilst this approach may not always provide for an quantifiably equal representation of all interests involved, it may be the professional judgement of the journalist - ie made from a self-consciously reflective distance - that some interests require more extensive or more critical coverage than others. This approach recognises journalism as an evaluative and contextualised professional practice.  Rather than inhibiting this approach, a genuinely impartial  news service needs to ensure that the conditions and culture of reflective reportage is encouraged. This approach can be made explicit and accountable through  mechanisms such as implementable Codes of Standards or Ethics. Conflating the broad notion of impartiality to a notion of objectivity and its technical breaches of 'bias'  can only quell intelligible forms of professional practice and diminish the excellence of ABC news and current affairs.
</td>
</tr></table>

<BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
iv) Comprehensive  news and current affairs services require a commitment to a range of audience needs that cannot be met by market mechanisms. Moreover, the provision of news and current affairs as a national service must be retained to ensure that the diversity of this comprehensive service is commonly shared by the various 'publics' that make up the nation and the domain of a national public affairs. This aspect of the submission focuses on three areas. First, it discusses diversity in domestic news, secondly, the restructuring of South East Asian news bureaux and thirdly, the use of multimedia to enhance news and current affairs services at the ABC.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">

<BR><IMG HSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">* A comprehensive national news service requires the representation of a great range of domestic sources  and issues, thereby ensuring strong and ongoing input into the provision of service by state and regional journalists. A comprehensive and diverse output can only be provided by a similarly comprehensive and diverse input. This needs careful practical consideration in light of the closures of regional offices currently underway and the reduction of specialist or 'round' reporting. Only through such structural and programming diversity  can news and current affairs give voice to many 'publics' who are denied access through commercial news. In particular, we can point to the ongoing criticism by organisations such as the Royal Commission into Aboriginal Death in Custody (1991), The Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission's national Inquiry into Racist Violence (1991) and the University of Technology, Sydney's Racism, Ethnicity and the Media Project (1994)  over reporting of indigenous Australian  affairs.  Whilst the ABC has lead Australian news and current affairs in addressing changes to the coverage of these issues, its committment to an interpretation of comprehensive   news and current affairs requires a specific definition in terms of providing media voices and services to people denied access by commercial programming.
</td>
</tr></table>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<BR><IMG HSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">** The ABC's commitment to comprehensive reporting has ensured that it is the only news organisation that produces its own news from South-East Asia. Despite Government and Opposition agreement on the need to be better informed about the region to our north, most Australian based news organisation largely have used generic news produced by foreign owned international news services to report the region. While such agencies can be relied on to offer mainstream stories (particularly those of interest in New York, London and Paris), they cannot produce Australian specific stories which could be of great importance for Australian businesses, Government and community groups.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

The ABC sought to address this problem by correctly making South East Asia a news priority and maintaining and expanding the most extensive network of Radio and Television news bureau in Asia (David Hill. 'Speech Notes', Sydney: ABC Corporate Relations. 27.3.94). ABC Foreign Correspondents were based in Hong Kong, Hanoi, Singapore (to be closed this year) and Bangkok, with part-time stringers located in Kuala Lumpur, Phnom Penh and Manila. In comparison, News Ltd which owned one national  and six metropolitan daily  newspapers (representing more than two thirds of metropolitan newspaper distribution in Australia), had only two correspondents in the region, both reporting for the national daily, the Australian.  Channel Nine had a British stringer operating under contract in Hong Kong. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

These centres are already under consideration for restructuring. Reorganising the news services in a way that continues to delivers excellence in international news could include:
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">- slowly replace the use of generalist reporters carrying country specific responsibilities with specialist reporters with a region wide brief, as does Asiaweek. Savings from closed bureaux could provide for country visits by the journalists who would largely work from Australia by telephone and the Internet.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">- expand the use of locally based casual journalists (stringers) who could be properly paid in light of savings from not having to supply expatriate accommodation.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">- Maintain key bureaux with long-term appointments rather than short-term contracts, a practice which has proven successful for the Far Eastern Economic Review.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">- Ensure that all appointments require proficiency in at least one Asian language.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">- Implement a training course which introduces all prospective foreign reporters and editors to the region's histories, cultures, politics and economies.
<BR><IMG HSPACE=8 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">- Nominate a sub-editor/producer to act as an Asian desk editor whose work is to ensure that stories from Asia are not displaced by ephemeral local, US or British sources stories as has been implemented by the West Australian.
</td>
</tr></table>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<BR><IMG HSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">***The ABC's commitment to the innovative use of new technologies and and their use in the development of news and current affairs services is well represented by  ABC Internet publishing and research. This week the ABC's online site is one year old. This site already demonstrates the ABC's commitment to not only providing forums for critical discussion and debate about new and emerging media technologies, but also to explore the potential of these media to serve new audiences or to  allow for new and productive kinds of interaction. Hot Chips was the first Australian television show to have its own Website. The http:// Website experimented with the ways in which a television program could interact with a Website, and vice-versa: 'a Website which drives a TV show, and a TV show which drives a Web-site. In addition, a 'radio incarnation' called Click-on was developed creating a particularly interesting media-mix. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

In a related innovation, the ABC's 'Explore Your Interests' page shows another dimension in providing high quality information and entertainment services to the growing online community. Annonated lists which review relevant sources are organised and presented in a visually interesting way that help combat 'information overload'. The ABC has provided a significant and useful Internet presence that provides an excellent learning resource for Journalism students who are coming to terms with the problems and potential of new media technologies. It is the breadth and depth of content and research behind it that ensures that this Website does not degenerate into an irrelevant technology site.


<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

(b) This submission has argued that strong national news and current affairs services are foundational to the development of the range of social dialogues necessary to develop a national identity in a culturally diverse country like Australia. It provides the basis for a shared information service that should be developed from a diverse set of structural and cultural conditions for practices in journalism and broadcast programming as argued above.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

c) The ABC's capacity to contribute to a sense of national identity will be most felt by rural and other marginal communities and groups not well served by the commercial sector, such as youth and children. It is these groups that suffer the greatest impact and loss of services by budget-driven restructuring . Yet it is these communities whom the ABC is again required by the Terms of Reference to specifically serve. Restructuring of ABC services needs to be organised in a manner that can provide this strong foundation in public affairs from which a diversity of quality and cross-genre programming can be developed in focussed areas.
</td>
</tr></table>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=2 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<H3>Section 4.</H3>

The submission calls here for particular consideration to be given to the nature and conditions of employment in news and current affairs. Given the Review's instructions to make its considerations in the context of the government's 'broader fiscal strategy', strategies of employment rationalisation become primary.  While this submission recognises restructuring will lead to some employment cutbacks it has argued that this should not occur in the core or foundational services of news and current affairs when it diminishes the employee's  capacity to meet their public broadcasting responsibilities.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

 A further important consideration in restructuring is not just the numbers of people employed but which people continue to be employed at the ABC. Alongside the Special Broadcasting Service, the ABC is the only mass media institution in Australia that is legally bound (under section 22B of the Public Services Act) to adopt equal employment practices to ensure career opportunities for women, Aborigines, Torres Strait Islanders, people from non-English speaking backgrounds and people with physical or mental disabilities. Since 1988, the ABC has implemented action programs to this end, most notably there are employment targets to encourage indigenous and non-Anglo Australian to seek jobs in the ABC and to encourage women to seek promotions to senior management.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

Change in the mass media's workforce composition is inevitably slow and incremental. Australian experience has shown that it will not occur without a formal institutional commitment to affirmative action programs. Moreover, these programs immediately impact on parrallel programming policies. As indigenous media trainer Lester Bostock reminds us, it is less likely that a white news editor will choose a racist story, angle or image if there is an indigenous (or non-Anglo) journalist sitting nearby.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

These employment programs are crucial, therefore, to the future of the ABC. The best way to guarantee the provision of independent news and current affairs, high quality locally produced information and entertainment and services for significant groups that are currently not well served by other broadcasting services, is to train and maintain a workforce that is culturally and socially diverse. 
</td>
</tr></table>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=2 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<H3>SUMMARY RECOMMENDATIONS.</H3>

<B>1.</B><IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">That a new ABC Charter identify a series of core services built around a strong and well resourced public affairs department with an explicit commitment to excellence and independence in news and current affairs.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>2.</B><IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">That the Charter clearly identify the role of professional practice in the provision of these services, defining these practices in a manner that protects them from political and commercial interference.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>3.</B><IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">That the Charter retains its commitment to innovative and comprehensive broadcasting in a manner requiring diversity in employment and programming strategies.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>4.</B><IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">That the Charter specifies a commitment to the use of new technologies to develop services and activities in order to serve a range of public needs.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>5.</B><IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">That the Review's findings be made in support of excellence and diversity in news and current affairs despite current management strategies in budget restructuring that has already significantly reduced the possibilities for public affairs programming. Suggested recommendations include the reconsideration of regional and state news bureaux, the restoration of specialist rounds in reporting and the retention of multi-media services. Other suggestions to restructure the Asian region bureaux without diminishing the importance of Australian produced international news are included in Section 3 (a) (iv).
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>6.</B><IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">That the review recommends the protection and enhancement of investigative journalism as a key distinguishing feature of ABC professional journalism.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>7.</B><IMG HSPACE=5 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif">That the Review recognises the relationship between news and current affairs and its cross-over with other public affairs genres, such as comedy and drama. These relationships are central to the role of the ABC as a major cultural influence on national dialogues and  the creation of identities within the nation.
</td>
</tr></table>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><IMG alt=acij logo BORDER=0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=25 HEIGHT=27 SRC="/../images/tiny-logo-acij.gif"></td>
<td width=430><A HREF="crisis.html">Return to The Crisis in Australian Public Broadcasting</A>
</td></tr></table>


</BODY> 
</HTML> 

 
