<DOCHDR>
http://acij.uts.edu.au:80/ACIJ/Tonga/tonga-Gov.html 138.25.138.98 19970110073941 text/html 10306
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: MacHTTP/2.2
Message-ID: <aefc3d6d.291@138.25.138.98>
Date: Friday, 10-Jan-97 18:39:41 GMT
Last-Modified: Tuesday, 15-Oct-96 16:35:10 GMT
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 10071
</DOCHDR>
<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>JAILING OF TONGAN JOURNALISTS</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>Response from the Tongan Government<BR>
to criticism of the jailings</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=485 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="tonga-free.html"><B>[Tongan Journalists Free!]</B></A><BR>
<A HREF="tonga.html">[Jailing of Tongan Journalists]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-ACIJ.html">[ACIJ condemns attack]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-PJR.html">[PJR protests]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-IFEX.html">[IFEX response]</A><BR>  
<A HREF="tonga-IFJ.html">[IFJ response]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-Times.html">[Message from Tonga Times]</A>  
[Response from the Tongan Government]<BR> 
<A HREF="tonga-RSF.html">[RSF response]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-terrorism.html">['Media terrorism']</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-PCRC.html">[PCRC, Fiji, response]</A>
<A HREF="tonga-PFIN.html">[PFIN response]</A><BR>
<A HREF="tonga-PINA.html">[PINA appeal to king]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-chronicle.html">[Tongan Chronicle report]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-otherweb.html">[Other Web sources of information]</A><BR>
<A HREF="tonga-what.html">[What you can do]</A>
</CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=485 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>On September 26 the Tongan Prime Minister's office forwarded an Information Paper to the ACIJ outlining details of the charges. The main points follow: </B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
 The Tongan Times falsely reported that Parliament was impeaching the Minister for Justice and for ther "wrongdoings" which they falsely listed. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
This is the equivalent of publishing that someone was being tried in court, when in fact no complaint had been filed. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Therefore the Tongan Times had breached the right of the House and of the Minister of Justice, to be reported correctly about. Secondly it also violated the right of the public to receive information from the product which they had bought.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Accordingly, the House, based on Clause 70 of the Constitution, charged Messrs Moala and 'Akau'ola with libellous publication, and therefore contempt of the House. ...
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
As confessed by 'Akilisi Pohiva in the House, after two weeks of probing by the House, it was he who gave the Tonga Times the libellous information and for publication. Accordingly, he too, based on Clause 70 of the Constitution, was charged with contempt of the House. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
[Note: Clause 70 of the Constitution states - If anyone shall speak or act disrespectfully in the presence of the Legislative Assembly it shall be lawful to imprison him [sic] for thirty days and whoever shall publish any libel on the Legislative Assembly, may be imprisoned for not exceeding thirty days.]
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Although contempt charges are not accompanied by hearings as in a court trial, Parliament allowed the three men full opportunity to ansmer the allegations, and to have legal counsel. Moala and 'Akau'ola had a legal counsel, Pohiva did not.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The Hearing took place the whole of Thursday morning and afternoon, fully attended by the press and the public.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
After lengthy debate, the House, on the evening of 19th Sept, 1996, voted on two matters. The first was whether the accused were guilty or not guilty of contempt of the House. The House voted by 19 to 2 that they were guilty. The second matter the House voted on was the penalty ... The House voted 10 to 8 in favour of imprisonment for 30 days. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
[Note: The vote to find the men guilty was passed 19-2. Fifteen eligible voters are unelected appointees of the King. Of the nine elected representatives, four voted 'guilty', two voted 'not guilty', and three were unable to vote (Pohiva and two absentees). On the vote on whether to apply a penalty of jailing, all seven present elected representatives voted against the penalty. It passed 10-8.] ... 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
AFP and Radio Australia (and Radio New Zealand) contacted the Prime minister's Office for information ... no other media service in the world has condescended to ask the Tongan Government, or the office of Parliament, for the facts.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Despite this above, Government has received numerous ill researched and therefore, incorrect, unjust, biased and malicious press condemnations. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
As evident from the facts above, the issues were not freedom of the press, nor the right of the public to be informed about matters of public interest.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The actual issues, suppressed by most of the overseas media, were the right of the House and the Minister for Justice to be reported truthfully, and the right of the people to correct information from the newspaper they paid for.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Both of these are fundamental human rights, and are elementary demands of the principles of natural justice. Both rights, however, were violated by Moala, 'Akau'ola and Pohiva, and are still being violated by many overseas organisations and Media Services.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Despite this regretable reality, of Media Terrorism against Tonga, we are still hopeful, that reputable Media Services such as those noted below, will one day ask for the facts, and will one day publish them:
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
World Press Freedom Committee (USA), Australian Centre for Independent Journalism, Pacific Journalism Review (PNG), National Press Club (PNG), Pacific Star Pty Ltd (PNG), World Association of Newspapers (France), Word Publishing Co Ltd (PNG), Journalists Training Organisation (NZ), NZ Engineering Printing and Manufacturing Union, Amnesty International (UK), New Zealand Herald, and many other print and radio media. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The history of the Media provides very meagre evidence of voluntary corrections of misinformation. To do so, is bad for the actual authors of the misinformation, for the reputation of the Media organisation, and of course for their sales.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Accordingly we accept with deep sorrow, that despite all the foregoing, there is no way at all for the misinformation to be corrected, or for the corrections to be equally highlighted as the misinformation was, by the Media services involved.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Our primary duty of course is not to the press, especially those with proven injustices. Our primary duty is to our people, and they are aware of all the above facts.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
[Note: There followed a statement that the motion to impeach the Justice Minister had been tabled in the House of Assembly on September 23, and that "The House then voted that there is a case to answer.".] 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>'Esta Fusitu'a<BR>
Acting Chief Secretary and Acting Secretary to Cabinet</B> 
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=485 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=20><BR></td>
<td width=450>
<CENTER><A HREF="#top">[Return to top]</A> <A HREF="tonga-Times.html">[Previous section]</A> <A HREF="tonga-what.html">[Next section]</A></CENTER>
<BR> 
<CENTER>
<A HREF="tonga-free.html"><B>[Tongan Journalists Free!]</B></A><BR>
<A HREF="tonga.html">[Jailing of Tongan Journalists]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-ACIJ.html">[ACIJ condemns attack]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-PJR.html">[PJR protests]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-IFEX.html">[IFEX response]</A><BR>  
<A HREF="tonga-IFJ.html">[IFJ response]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-Times.html">[Message from Tonga Times]</A>  
[Response from the Tongan Government]<BR> 
<A HREF="tonga-RSF.html">[RSF response]</A>  
