<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>JAILING OF TONGAN JOURNALISTS</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>JAILING OF TONGAN JOURNALISTS</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=485 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=20><BR></td>
<td width=450>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="tonga-free.html"><B>[Tongan Journalists Free!]</B></A><BR>
<A HREF="tonga.html">[Jailing of Tongan Journalists]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-ACIJ.html">[ACIJ condemns attack]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-PJR.html">[PJR protests]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-IFEX.html">[IFEX response]</A><BR>  
<A HREF="tonga-IFJ.html">[IFJ response]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-Times.html">[Message from Tonga Times]</A>  <A HREF="tonga-Gov.html">[Response from the Tongan Government]</A><BR> 
<A HREF="tonga-RSF.html">[RSF response]</A>  
['Media terrorism'] 
<A HREF="tonga-PCRC.html">[PCRC, Fiji, response]</A>
<A HREF="tonga-PFIN.html">[PFIN response]</A><BR>
<A HREF="tonga-PINA.html">[PINA appeal to king]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-chronicle.html">[Tongan Chronicle report]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-otherweb.html">[Other Web sources of information]</A><BR>
<A HREF="tonga-what.html">[What you can do]</A>
</CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=485 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=70><BR></td>
<td width=370>
<B>Asia-Pacific Network reports Tongan government on 'media terrorism'</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>Tongan government denounces 'media terrorism' </B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The Tongan government today bitterly condemned international media organisations protesting over the jailing of two journalists and an MP, accusing them of waging "media terrorism" against the Pacific kingdom. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Acting Chief Secretary 'Eseta Fusitu'a said the government had received a series of "incorrect, unjust, biased and malicious" press condemnations following last week's jailing of two newspaper editors and a commoner parliamentarian who is also a publisher and broadcaster. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Taimi 'o Tonga editor Kalafi Moala and subeditor Filokalafi 'Akau'ola and pro-democracy movement leader 'Akilisi Pohiva were jailed on Friday for 30 days for contempt of Parliament after the weekly newspaper published a story about an untabled impeachment notice. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The front page story in the September 4 edition under the headline "Parliament impeaches minister for justice" reported allegations of abuse of office against Justice Minister Tevita Tupou. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Since the three men were jailed, the motion has been tabled this week in the Legislative Assembly and the parliament voted there is a case to answer.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Radio Tonga said it was the first time the Assembly had approved a motion to impeach a minister.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Acting Chief Justice John Lewis has refused a Supreme Court application for a writ of habeas corpus on behalf of the two journalists, Moala and 'Akau'ola. Pohiva did not seek an appeal. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>Media protests have continued to flow into the kingdom.</B> 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
In a statement defending government actions faxed to several protesting media organisations today, including the Papua New Guinea-based Pacific Journalism Review and the Australian Centre for Independent Journalism, Fusitu'a claimed the issue was not one of "freedom of the press, nor the right of the public to be informed about matters of public interest". 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
He said the issues were "the right of the House and the Minister for Justice to be reported truthfully, and the right of the people to correct information" in the newspaper.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
"Both of these are fundamental human rights, and are the elementary demands of the principles of natural justice," Fusitu'a said. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
"Both rights, however, were violated by Moala, 'Akau'ola and Pohiva, and are still being violated by many overseas organisations and media services. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
"Despite this most regrettable reality, of media terrorism against Tonga, we are still hopeful that reputable media services will one day ask for the facts, and will one day publish them."
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
He praised Agence France-Presse news agency, Radio Australia and Radio New Zealand for contacting the government for information. But condemned a list of protesting media organisations.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Fusitu'a criticised the World Press Freedom Committee (USA), Australian Centre for Independent Journalism (Sydney), Pacific Journalism Review (PNG), National Press Club (PNG), Pacific Star Pty Ltd (PNG), World Association of Newspapers (France), Word Publishing Co Ltd (PNG), NZ Journalists Training Organisation (NZ), NZ Engineering Printing and Manufacturing Union, Amnesty International (UK) and the New Zealand Herald and "many other" print and radio media.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
"The history of the media provides very meagre evidence of voluntary corrections of misinformation. To do so is bad for the actual authors of the misinformation, for the reputation of the media organisation, and of course for their sales," Fusitu'a said.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
However, media monitoring sources in Sydney said the government had failed to recognise the difference between the role of "news gathering" media organisations and those "protesting" over the jailing. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Among other reactions,the International Federation of Journalists, the world's largest organisation of journalists, representing more than 400,000 journalists in 95 countries, expressed "dismay" and appealed for their release.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
"This act of punishment is a clear violation of freedom of expression and opinion," said senior vice-president Christopher Warren in a letter to King Taufa'ahau Tupou.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
"Given the widespread anxiety of human rights organisations and journalist colleagues in the Asia-Pacific region, I hope you will intervene to release unconditionally those journalists that have been jailed. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
"The IFJ also asks you to intervene to guarantee the rights of journalists in Tonga, who belong to our member organisation, the Pacific Journalists Association.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Warren said the IFJ was concerned that this attempt to punish and intimidate journalists and to impose systems of media control "are an offence to democracy and undermine the capacity of people to participate openly in society".
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Tonga's 28-member Legislative Assembly is dominated by 19 unelected representatives of Tonga's noble families plus nine elected people's representatives.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Although a majority of the people's representatives voted for the contempt ruling, all seven present voted unanimously against the prison sentence (the overall vote was 10-8 in favour).
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
One of the jailed men, 'Akau'ola was detained for 26 hours last February after his newspaper published a letter criticising Police Minister Clive Edwards. An Auckland-based Agence France Presse correspondent who has reported Tongan affairs closely, Michael Field, was barred from entering the kingdom for last month's Pacific Islands News Association convention. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>David Robie<BR>
Asia-Pacific Network<BR>
26 September 1996<BR></B>
</td>
<td width=30></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=485 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

