<A HREF="tonga-RSF.html">[RSF response]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-terrorism.html">['Media terrorism']</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-PCRC.html">[PCRC, Fiji, response]</A>
[PFIN response]<BR>
<A HREF="tonga-PINA.html">[PINA appeal to king]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-chronicle.html">[Tongan Chronicle report]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-otherweb.html">[Other Web sources of information]</A><BR>
<A HREF="tonga-what.html">[What you can do]</A>
</CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=485 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=70><BR></td>
<td width=370>
<B>Regional and international appeals to Tonga continue</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Regional and international condemnation of the Tongan Legislative Assembly's jailing of journalists Kalafi Moala and Filokalafi 'Akau'ola continues as the pair go into their second week of detention in the kingdom. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
In the latest appeals to free the Tonga 2, who are now held in Tonga's main prison:<BR>
The chairperson of the Media Council of Papua New Guinea, Anna Solomon, appealed to Tonga's King Taufa'ahau Tupou to do "what is right by your people." She said as the people of the Pacific Islands approach the 21st century "we expect our leaders to honestly take stock of outmoded draconian legislations that impede the course of democracy and throw out those laws which only serve the interests of the privileged few."
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The president of the Media Association of Solomon Islands, Julian Maka'a, said the 30-day jail sentence is "too harsh." "This action will no doubt really strengthen the focus for change in Tonga," he said. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The Canadian Committee to Protect Journalists, through executive director Wayne Sharpe, urged the King to "intervene and show your commitment to freedom of expression by ensuring the immediate release of the journalists." 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The World Press Freedom Committee, which links 37 journalistic organisations on five continents, said the people of a country have "the right to information about the activities of their government and its officials. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
"Those who flout such fundamental rights only diminish the international image of their countries," World Press Freedom Committee executive director Dana Bullen said.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>BACKGROUND</B><BR>
Moala and 'Akau'ola were on September 20th jailed for 30 days for "contempt" of the Legislative Assembly. This was because their newspaper, the weekly Times of Tonga (Taimi 'o Tonga), published details of an impeachment motion against Tonga's Minister of Justice, before it was submitted to the Legislative Assembly. The minister, who is appointed by the king and not elected, was alleged to have received his daily allowance for attending Legislative Assembly sessions even though he was in Atlanta leading Tonga's delegation to the Olympic Games.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The Times of Tonga was given details of the motion by pro-democracy movement parliamentarian 'Akilisi Pohiva. Moala and 'Akau'ola said they believed Pohiva had already submitted it to the clerk of the assembly. Pohiva was also jailed for 30 days by Tonga's Legislative Assembly, which is dominated by representatives of the kingdom's noble families and Ministers who are appointed by King Taufa'ahau Tupou.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>Nina Ratulele<BR>
Coordinator, Pacific Freedom of Information Network 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
September 30th 1996
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Pacific Freedom of Information Network,<BR>
Pacific Islands News Association Secretariat, Suva, Fiji<BR>
Phone: (679) 303623. Fax: (679) 303943</B>
</td>
<td width=30></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=485 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

