<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=485 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=70><BR></td>
<td width=370>
<B>PINA appeal given to King of Tonga</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
An appeal for the release of jailed Tongan journalists Kalafi Moala and Filokalafi 'Akau'ola has been personally handed to the Palace in Nuku'alofa, Tonga, by a representative of the regional Pacific Islands News Association (PINA).
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Nina Ratulele, PINA's Freedom of Information Network coordinator, gave the letter of appeal to the king's private secretary, 'Ofa Tu'i'onetoa, during a meeting at the Palace. Tu'i'onetoa said he would pass it on to King Taufa'ahau Tupou immediately.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The appeal is from PINA's president, Monica Miller, of American Samoa, on behalf of PINA members throughout the region.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Ratulele also met the Speaker of Tonga's Legislative Assembly, the Honourable Fusitu'a. She gave him a letter from the PINA president asking for his support for the appeal. The Honourable Fusitu'a assured Ratulele he would read the letter carefully.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Ratulele has also been given permission to visit the jailed journalists by Tonga's Police and Prisons Minister, Clive Edwards. Prison authorities say Moala has told them he does not want visits from anyone except close relatives. But Ratulele hopes to see him and 'Akau'ola later today. The pair are now ending the first week of their detention.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
[Note: Radio Australia reports that the two jailed journalists have declined to meet with PINA reporesentative, Nina Ratulele. No reason was stated.]
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Ratulele flew to Tonga from Fiji to deliver the appeals, visit the jailed the journalists, lobby on their behalf, and meet with PINA's members in the kingdom. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
PINA and the Pacific Freeedom of Information Network coordinated through the PINA Secretariat in Suva have led international appeals to free Moala and 'Akau'ola. PINA said Moala and 'Akau'ola were jailed for doing their duty - informing the people of Tonga about a matter which they had a right to know. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>BACKGROUND</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Moala and 'Akau'ola were on September 20th jailed for 30 days for "contempt" of the Legislative Assembly. This was because their newspaper, the weekly Times of Tonga (Taimi 'o Tonga), published details of an impeachment motion against Tonga's Minister of Justice, before it was submitted to the Legislative Assembly. The minister was alleged to have received his daily allowance for attending Legislative Assembly sessions even though he was in Atlanta leading Tonga's delegation to the Olympic Games. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The Times of Tonga was given details of the motion by pro-democracy movement parliamentarian 'Akilisi Pohiva. Moala and 'Akau'ola said they believed Pohiva had already submitted it to the clerk of the assembly. Pohiva was also jailed for 30 days.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>Pacific Islands News Association Secretariat,<BR>
Private Mail Bag,<BR>
Suva, Fiji.<BR>
Phone: (679) 303623.<BR>
Fax: (679) 303943
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
26th September, 1996</B>
</td>
<td width=30></td>
</tr></table>

