<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>JAILING OF TONGAN JOURNALISTS</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>Tongan Chronicle reports that court appeal rejected</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td>
</tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=485 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=20><BR></td>
<td width=450>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="tonga-free.html"><B>[Tongan Journalists Free!]</B></A><BR>
<A HREF="tonga.html">[Jailing of Tongan Journalists]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-ACIJ.html">[ACIJ condemns attack]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-PJR.html">[PJR protests]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-IFEX.html">[IFEX response]</A><BR>  
<A HREF="tonga-IFJ.html">[IFJ response]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-Times.html">[Message from Tonga Times]</A>  <A HREF="tonga-Gov.html">[Response from the Tongan Government]</A><BR> 
<A HREF="tonga-RSF.html">[RSF response]</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-terrorism.html">['Media terrorism']</A>  
<A HREF="tonga-PCRC.html">[PCRC, Fiji, response]</A>
<A HREF="tonga-PFIN.html">[PFIN response]</A><BR>
<A HREF="tonga-PINA.html">[PINA appeal to king]</A>  
[Tongan Chronicle report]  
<A HREF="tonga-otherweb.html">[Other Web sources of information]</A><BR>
<A HREF="tonga-what.html">[What you can do]</A>
</CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=485 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=70><BR></td>
<td width=370>
<B>Tonga Chronicle, 26 September 1996<BR>
Court rejects appeal on jailed journalists</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>NUKU'ALOFA:</B> Acting Chief Justice John William Lewis refused in the Supreme Court on Wednesday an ex-parte application for a writ of habeas corpus from Ekealafi Moala, editor of Taimi 'o Tonga, and his assistant Filokalafi 'Akauola. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
In handing down his judgment, Justice Lewis said that the Legislative Assembly had absolute privilege in [its] decision to detain the two journalists.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Parliament was entitled to absolute privilege over its internal proceedings and in a sense it was properly entitled to determine what words or actions will amount to contempt and the sanction which it should impose upon a person whom it found to have committed a contempt to the house, the judge said.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The applicants had asked that they be released from what they claimed was unlawful or unjustifiable detention because they were not members of the Legislative Assembly.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The said article was not published in the presence of the Legislative Assembly. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The Legislative Assembly could not lawfully invoke the Constitution upon them because the Assembly, which had a vested interest in this matter as the body that charged [them], found them guilty and sentenced them to 30 days in prison and because the procedure adopted by the Legislative Assembly was unfair and unjust.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Respondents were the Kingdom of Tonga and the Minister of Police. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
A People's Representative in the Legislative Assembly, Samuela 'Akilisi Pohiva, No 1 People's Representatives for Tongatapu, and two journalists have been imprisoned for 30 days after being found guilty of contempt against the Assembly on September 20.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The three began serving their sentences when the House adjourned shortly after midnight on September 20.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
After spending his first night's imprisonment at the Police Training School, Kolofo'ou, Mr. Pohiva was transferred under guard to Vaiola Hospital where he remained today after suffering from asthma attack. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The two journalists are being held at Hu'atolitoli Prison Station as of Wednesday, but since last week they [have been] held at two different police stations.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>Origin: Niuswire</B>
</td>
<td width=30></td>
</tr></table>

