<html>
<head><title> Pacific Media Watch: Damocles</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>Media Bill linked to sword of Damocles</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW 370: Pacific Media Watch: 6 December 1996
<P>
Title -- 370 MEDIA: Media Bill linked to sword of Damocles Date -- 8 December 1996
Byline -- John Millet
Origin -- Pacific Media Watch
Source -- Post-Courier (PNG), 6/12/96
Copyright -- Post-Courier
Status -- Unabridged
<P>
<HR>
<P>
MEDIA BILL LINKED TO SWORD OF DAMOCLES<BR>
Commission to dictate what journalists write</B> 
<P>
By John Millet<BR>
SECTION 28 of the proposed National Information and Communication Bill portrays the authority created by the Bill as Dionysius to media's Damocles. 
<P>
It reads in part: "Where the authority considers that it would be in the interest of the public to do so, the authority may .... suspend for such period ..... or revoke the certificate.
<P>
A media owner who operates without a certificate faces possible imprisonment up to four years. The Media Commission Bill is to media workers what the National Information and Communication Bill is to the media owners. Its Sword of Damocles is Section 12 which reads: "For the purpose of exercising its powers and functions, the Commission may make such orders, give such directions and do such other things as it sees it fit."
<P>
This means that the Commission could direct or order a journalist, writer, announcer, compere or presenter to write or say something. Failure to comply with an order or direction could bring a fine up to K2000. 
<P>
Section 28 makes it mandatory for the commission to withdraw a certificate of registration from a journalist, writer, announcer, compere or presenter whom the Commission finds to be "guilty of a serious offence which is detrimental to the interest of the public .... "
<P>
Whereas the Media Commission is mainly concerned with media workers. Its jurisdiction extends to media owners as well. That is the two Bills as drafted contain the potential for overlapping jurisdictions and contrary determinations but neither says which would prevail. This comes about in Section 19 of the Media Commission Bill.
<P>
"The Commission may make rules providing for the regulation of the media and its affairs ... "
<P>
Wasn't the CRC's first recommendation to the National Parliament that ".... existing legislation on the media provides sufficient rules in controlling the behaviour of the media industry and the government should not consider proposing any new restrictive laws ? And wasn't its final recommendation to the effect that licensing would be introduced only if self-regulation failed ? It would appear that somebody has made a judgment that self-regulation has failed. Who made such judgment and when, and where and how was it made ? 
<P>
A brief reading of these two Bills strongly suggests that their drafters have come up hard against truth, faced by many would-be regulators before them in liberal democratic societies, that it would not be easy to limit freedom of expression without destroying it. They have resolved the dilemma nevertheless with the heavy-handed approach, impossing unacceptable risks on society. The Media Council should quickly propose alternative arrangements. 
<P>
According to the Bills, how much power does the Minister wield, specifically and bluntly, can he "stack the board" ? The Minister in effect selects the chairman and deputy chairman and the director general of the National Information and Communications Authority and may terminate their appointments on grounds of "inefficiency, incapacity or misbehaviour". The Minister also selects three of the ten board members at this absolute discretion, one with specified experience and three representatives of particular interest groups. The Minister is not required to accept or consider nominees of the specified interest groups. Overall, apart from the ex-officio nominees of the Department of Finance and National Planning the board is very much the Minister's creation.
<P>
The Minister nominates the chairman and deputy chairman of the Media Commission. Various interest groups nominate the other seven members. The Minister, therefore, would not control the Commission. Nor would he control the Media Supervisor Supervisory Committee, provided for under the Media Commission Bill, unless the Commission wished him to do so by default. 
<P>
The main direct risk therefore would be for media owners rather than for media workers. It would take the form of the Minister or his creation closing premises down in the "interests of the public", after having given the owner the opportunity to present his case. Of course, indirectly, owner's risk is also worker's risk.
<P>
This would appear to make the media accountable to the MInister; and, under our structure of government, the allocation of Ministerial portfolios is the absolute prerogative of the Prime Minister of the day. Is this what "media accountability" means?
<P>
All media premises must be registered and licenced with the authority, renewable annually at unprescribed fees. Penalty - up to K10,000 for a corporation and K5000 for each director, default four years and six months imprisonment respectively.
<P>
The authority may revoke registration or suspend it for an unspecified period if, inter alia, it considers that it would be in the "interest of the public to do so", provided the certificate holder has first had the opportunity to put his case.
<P>
All journalists, writers, radio announcers and television comperes or presenters must apply annually for registration with the Commission and pay the associated fees (amount not specified) penalty K1000 for a first offender and K2000 for any subsequent offence.
<P>
The Commission may hold renewal or registration, inter alia, if the applicant "has failed to give a satisfactory explanation of any matter relating to his conduct or... practise.. "
<P>
The Commission shall withdraw a certificate of registration if it finds, inter alia that the holder is guilty of a serious offence which is detrimental to the interest of the public and the media industry." Aggrieved parties may seek a court review of the Commission's action. An unregistered practitioner faces a fine of up to K2000.
<P>
Complaints of improper conduct are to be heard by a Media Supervisory Committee. The Minister appoints no fewer than three certificate holders to the committee. The Commission may appoint any number of any persons to the committee. The Commission's proceedinhgs shall be closed to the public. 
<P>
Evidence shall be given on oath and witnesses may be examined. The committee may, as a result of an inquiry, suspend the defendant from practise; impose of a penalty of up to K5000; order compensation to be paid to the court for deregistration. Both the plaintiff and the defendant may appeal within 21 days to the court.
<P>
The National Information and Communications Board comprises 10 members, three of them ex officio. The other seven are appointed by the Minister, three in his absolute discretion. Three appointees represent the media, the rural sector the telecommunications respectively. One aoppointee is to be experienced in commercial law and business practise. The Minister may terminate an appointment on grounds of "inefficiency, incapability or misbehaviour." The appeals provision appears to be circular which is tantamount to there being no appeals provision. Six members form a quorum. Matters are decided by majority vote for the members present and voting. The chairman has a deliberate vote and a casting vote.
<P>
Paradoxically in a wider context of government's general privatisation policies the Authority has the power - nay, the obligation - as drafted the Bill would make it mandatory to own and operate media enterprises. Other powers include: providing guidelines on program content, determining local content, giving written instructions, requiring a licensee to discuss any matter or to give evidence or produce any document likely to assist the Authority. 
<P>
Section 62(m) requires the Authority to "authorise and promote ownership of broadcasting services". This meaningless statement would take on meaning for existing investors if it meant "local" ownership. This point needs clarification. The word "shall" in S26 should be replaced by the word "may". 
<P>
The Media Commission will comprise nine people, five of them will be nominated by private interest groups: journalists, lawyers, unions, churches, women. The Judicial Services Commission will nominate. The NEC will appoint the chairman and the deputy chairman. The Media Commission itself will nominate one member. The Act provides for alternatives and, potentially confusing, for "acting" members also.
<P>
Appointments may be terminated by NEC for the usual reasons and for "misconduct in respect of his ofice or otherwise." The Commission shall meet at least once a quarter. Six members constitue a quorum.<BR> 
+++niuswire
<P>
<Font size=1> 1996 Pacific Media Watch.<BR>
http://acij.uts.edu.au/pmw/ Contact: <A HREF="MAILTO:niusedita@pactok.net">niusedita@pactok.net</A></FONT 1>
</table>
<HR>
