<head><title> Pacific Media Watch:Tiong</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>Malaysian logging tycoon takes over newspaper</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW14: Pacific Media Watch: 15 November 1996
<P>
Title -- M56 MEDIA: Malaysian logging tycoon takes over newspaper
Date -- 15 November 1996
Origin -- Pacific Media Watch
Source -- Hong Kong Journalists' Association</B>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
Tiong Hiew-king, whose Malaysian logging group Rimbunan Hijau owns The
National daily newspaper in Papua New Guinea, is the new head of the Ming
Pao publishing group in Hongkong, says a new report..
<P>
Yu Pun-hoi sold his controlling stake in Ming Pao newspaper to Tiong in
October, according to the joint report "China's Challenge: Freedom of
Expression in Hongkong" prepared by the Hongkong Journalists' Association
and Article 19.
<P>
The report was presented at this week's Intersections with Asia: The Future
of International Journalism conference organised by the Australian Centre
for Independent Journalism at the International Media centre in Sydney.
<P>
Mr Yu "apparently needed the money to finance his ambitious satellite
television operation, the China television Network (CTN), the major market
for which is in Taiwan".
<P>
The Rimbunan  Hijau group's media interests have steadily grown in the past
few years. As well as The National in PNG, founded in 1993, it also owns
two radio stations in New Zealand and other news media.<BR>
