<head><title> Pacific Media Watch: NBC 'rot'</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>Stop the rot at NBC</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW16 The National (PNG): 19 November 1996
<P>
Title -- M64 MEDIA: NBC - 'Stop the rot'
Date -- 19 November 1996
Origin -- Pacific Media Watch
Source -- The National (PNG) editorial, 18/11/96
Copyright -- The National
Status -- Unabridged
<P>
<HR>
<P>
National editorial (Nov 18): 
STOP THE ROT AT NBC</B>
<P>
THE National Broadcasting Corporation began as a commission 23 years ago
this month.
<P>
Prior to 1973, radio broadcasting in the territories of Papua and New Guinea
was divided between the two authorities - the Australian Broadcasting
Commission's PNG service which began in 1946; and later, the Australian
administration's Department of Information and Extension Services network.
<P>
The ABC invested substantial funds in the development of radio in PNG.
Broadcasting House at 5-Mile was opened on Sept 5, 1962, and was acclaimed
as the most up-to-date facility of its kind in the Southern hemisphere.
<P>
The ABC's programs were initially directed at an expatriate audience; the
commission saw that as its duty to Australians working in a colonial
situation.
<P>
Hospital matrons had their daily injection of Gwen Meredith's radio serial
'Blue Hills', an Aussie version of 'The Archers'; and the hills were alive
with the sound of Maria Callas, Yehudi Menuhin, and the GUM Footwear Band.
<P>
At the end of the day, 'Evening Meditation', introduced by a piece of music
called 'Highland Lament' - Scottish, not PNG Highlands - sent the dimdims
scurrying for their last double whisky before bed.
<P>
It was Aunty at her most stiff upper lip.
<P>
As the years passed, the ABC began to take Papuan and New Guinean listeners
into account, with a number of innovative programs designed to inform and
entertain.
<P>
In particular, news services in Tok Pisin and Hiri Motu joined the
English-language broadcasts; the ABC played an honourable role in the
dissemination of information to the people of this country for some 20 years
before independence in 1975.
<P>
DIES, on the other hand, provided an essential locally-oriented service to
the districts in both territories. Radio East Sepik was the first station
opened, and others soon followed.
<P>
Rural information programs from agriculture, health, education and law
enforcement personnel played a major role in their broadcasts, and they
began a news service designed to reach as many listeners as practicable in
their own language.
<P>
Some stations were broadcasting news in up to six languages; the lingua
franca were Tok Pisin and Hiri Motu.
<P>
With self-government looming in November 1973, both the ABC and DIES moved
to establish one national broadcaster; by 1975, very few of the
newly-created provinces were without radio stations.
<P>
And what a success they proved to be! By the seventies, the radio network,
carried through three services, was a model for developing nations. Free
from political interference, and with program variety and standards that
would have done credit to any international broadcaster, the NBC looked set
for a prime role in the establishment and development of this brave new
nation.
<P>
What went wrong?
<P>
The national broadcaster of today is a pitiful shell of that splendid
organisation.
<P>
By the eighties, the seeds of its doom had already been sown. Successive
governments were not content to leave well alone. Appointment after
appointment to the then-commission were made for reasons of political
convenience.
<P>
Nepotism and personal greed became the hallmarks of far too many at
management level; the highly talented staff, nurtured over so many years,
were powerless in the face of arrogance, neglect, and ignorance.
<P>
Year after year, the national budgets reflected the abysmal attitude of
those responsible for the NBC's budget; taking inflation into account, the
NBC's income progressed steadily backwards, while the buildings,
transmitters, and equipment, all donated by Aunty ABC in 1973 and valued
then at more than K5 million kina, slowly rotted away.
<P>
And the future?
<P>
Emphatically yes, the NBC must have a future. Its services have never been
needed more than they are today. In the field of political education alone -
shamefully and scandalously neglected by every government since independence
- the role of the NBC could be amply justified.
<P>
And yes, the expertise to revive, stabilise, re-structure and redirect the
NBC is available - not at some horrendous cost from overseas experts, but
right here in the nation's capital.
<P>
All that is required is a national government that cares enough to identify
and exploit that wealth of knowledge and experience - and reap the benefit.<BR>
+++pacmediawire
<P>
<Font size=1> 1996 The National and Pacific Media Watch.</FONT 1>
</table>
