<head><title> Pacific Media Watch:Cartoon</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>Cartoonists must consult -- minister</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW10: Post-Courier (PNG): 15 November 1996
<P>
Title -- 341 MEDIA: Cartoonists must consult - minister
Date -- 15 November 1996
Byline -- Neville Togarewa and Peter Niesi
Origin -- Pacific Media Watch
Source -- Post-Courier (PNG), 15/11/96
Copyright -- Post-Courier
Status -- Unabridged
<P>
<HR>
<P>
By Neville Togarewa and Peter Niesi</B><BR>
Justice Minister Arnold Marsipal yesterday told Parliament that cartoonists
ought to, as a matter of courtesy, inform leaders if they are going to use them
as subjects of illustrations.
<P>
Mr Marsipal was responding to concerns raised by Wewak MP and former Attorney
General Bernard Narokobi about a cartoon in The National newspaper yesterday
dipicting Sir Michael Somare's comments that the judiciary was misinterpreting
the legislator's intentions. The cartoon shows a judge urging criminals to "go
home and behave" with Sir Michael Somare thinking "too very soft".
<P>
Mr Narokobi saw the cartoon as potentially demeaning to the integrity of the
judiciary and wanted to know whether it represented the views of the Justice
Minister and if not, what was he going to do about the cartoonist and the
publisher.
<P>
Mr Marsipal said that PNG is a democratic country and the freedom extends to
the media and artists.
<P>
He said that it did not represent his views as he respects the law and the
judiciary.
