<head><title> Pacific Media Watch: NBC</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>Coffin closes for NBC</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW09: Post-Courier (PNG) editorial: 15 November 1996
<P>
Title -- 339 MEDIA: Editorial -- Coffin closes for NBC
Date -- 15 November 1996
Byline -- Editorial
Origin -- Pacific Media Watch
Source -- Post-Courier (PNG), 15/11/96
Copyright -- Post-Courier
Status -- Unabridged</B>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
Hundreds of radio broadcasters employed by the National Broadcasting
Corporation and their families will go hungry from today because there is no
money to pay their fortnightly wages.
<P>
What a shame.
<P>
At a time when politicians find plenty of time to criticise private media
groups and use government resources to curb press freedom, they have
shamelessly forgotten about their number one media responsibility - to keep the
national and the provincial radio stations on air.
<P>
Having discarded it and handed over responsibility to provincial governments
without providing funds, they have delivered the final blow to the staff.
<P>
Only this week the Prime Minister stood up in Parliament and acknowledged the
importance of radio as the only means of communication that can get messages
across to the bulk of the people of Papua New Guinea whereas newspapers reach a
much smaller audience, especially in the rural areas.
<P>
That is true. So why is it that successive governments have never allocated
enough funds to NBC to carry out its duties as specified in the Broadcasting
Commission Act ?
<P>
In the 1997 general elections, the Government will need the NBC like never
before.
<P>
Only the radio network can enable the Government to talk directly to the people
quickly and with so much ease.
<P>
The leaders of today will be judged by history as the very ones who destroyed
the people's radio network. They slowly but surely suffocated it over 21 years
until today when they finally delivered the last blow to the staff and their
families. May the Karai Service and all the provincial radio stations rest in
peace. We weep at the passing of a great radio service. 
+++pacmediawire
<P>
<Font size=1> 1996 Post-Courier and Pacific Media Watch.</FONT 1>
</table>
