<head><title> Pacific Media Watch: Cash</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>No pay for NBC staff</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW12 The National (PNG): 15 November 1996
<P>
Title -- M57 MEDIA: NBC faces funding crisis
Date -- 15 November 1996
Byline -- Ennio Kuble
Origin -- Pacific Media Watch
Source -- The National (PNG), 15/11/96
Copyright -- The National
Status -- Unabridged
<P>
<HR>
<P>
NO PAY FOR 2000 NBC STAFF<BR>
Corporation lacks funds after overspending
<P>
By ENNIO KUBLE</B><BR>
PORT MORESBY: Pay cheques of more than 2,000 employees of the National
Broadcasting Corporation nationwide will no longer be honoured by the Bank
of Papua New Guinea.
<P>
Although the bank could not be contacted to confirm this, sources from the
NBC finance department said their workers will be without pay for the two
pay-days of this month.
<P>
The source said that due to over-expenditure, both operational and salary
funds for November were used up in the first week of this month.
<P>
As there are no more funds available to transfer to the banks by the Finance
Department, pay cheques are being dishonoured since early this week, the
source said.
<P>
The source said the management is thinking of using the December's funds but
that depends on approval from the Finance Department.
<P>
Attempts to get comments from the officer in charge of the NBC finance
failed.
<P>
Finance Department officials were also unavailable for comment yesterday.
However, Radio Western Highlands station manager Winterford Suharupa said
his staff were aware of the problem.
<P>
Mr Suharupa said officials from the head office here had not informed him.
However, he received the information from other sources.
<P>
He said it is true that the NBC had run out of money for this month.
However, the ordinary employees should not be penalised for that.
<P>
He said the NBC should find alternative ways to pay the staff.
<P>
Mr Suharupa said he had deposited his cheque on Thursday and was not sure
whether the bank would release the money or not.
<P>
He said though his staff have performed their normal duties this week, it
would be different next week.
<P>
And the kind of action they will take will be determined in the next week's
meeting, he said.
<P>
He also said his station has not received any funding from the provincial
government for this year's operations. The K15,000 budgeted by the
provincial government has not been released, he added.<BR>
+++pacmediawire
<P>
