<head><title> Pacific Media Watch: PINA</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>PINA concerned over new threats to free expression</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW18: Pacific Islands News Association: 19 November 1996</B>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
The Pacific Islands News Association (PINA) today again appealed to the
Tongan authorities to respect the fundamental human rights to freedom of
expression and information.
<P>
PINA president Monica Miller, of American Samoa, expressed deep concern over
events in the kingdom in the past few days.
<P>
They indicate a continuing effort to intimidate pro-democracy movement
members who exercise their right to free speech and news organisations who
report what they say, she said.
<P>
PINA said Tongan police on Friday November 15 took to the police station and
questioned pro-democracy politicians 'Akilisi Pohiva and Teisina Fuko and
Times of Tonga newspaper deputy editor Filokalafi 'Akau'ola.
<P>
The police released 'Akau'ola after about half an hour, PINA said. Pohiva
and Fuko were detained overnight before being released without being
charged.
<P>
The pair are both People's Representatives in the kingdom's Legislative
Assembly.
<P>
They were then given notices from the police saying they are under
investigation for alleged sedition and for defamation of King Taufa'ahau
Tupou lV, PINA was told.
<P>
The police action followed publication in the Times of Tonga of an interview
with Fuko and further comments published in Pohiva's pro-democracy
publication Kele'a.
<P>
PINA has English translations of the comments, which were published in the
Tongan language.
<P>
In any nation which respects fundamental rights the supposedly offending
comments would be regarded as legitimate comments on a matter of public
interest, Miller said.
<P>
The comments were in reaction to statements by the king in a Tongan
magazine, Matangi Tonga.
<P>
The king was critical of the People's representatives in the Legislative
Assembly.
<P>
The assembly is dominated by representatives of the kingdom's noble families
and by ministers who are appointed by the king and not elected. It also
includes People's representatives - such as Pohiva and Fuko - elected by
Tonga's commoners.
<P>
<B>Nina Ratulele<BR>
Coordinator<BR>
Pacific Islands News Association Secretariat<BR>
46 Gordon St, Suva, Fiji<BR>
Phone: (679) 303623. Fax: (679) 303943<BR>
e-mail: 75070.2637@compuserve.com (mark e-mail message to the attention of
Nina Ratulele)</B>
<P>
<Font size=1>Pacific Media Watch. http://acij.uts.edu.au/pmw/</FONT 1>
</table>
