<head><title> Pacific Media Watch:SPJ</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>SPJ joins Tongan protests</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW15 Society of Professional Journalists: 19 November 1996
<P>
Title -- M63 MEDIA: SPJ joins Tongan protests
Date -- 19 November 1996
Origin -- Pacific Media Watch
Source -- Society of Professional Journalists (USA),18/11/96 
<P>
<HR>
<P>
SPJ JOINS TONGAN PROTESTS</B>
<P>
I am distressed to learn, again, that the Tonga government has targeted a
journalist for arrest and detainment. As we did in September, the Society of
Professional Journalists calls upon the government to end its campaign of
intimidation against reporters.
<P>
Free societies have a vigorous and free press able to report freely on actions
and issues of interest to the citizens.  
<P>
SPJ also joins with the Pacific Media Watch in expressing great alarm at
reports regarding the possible registration and licensing of journalists.
Such actions would compromise the independence of the press and certainly
would raise questions about who is -- and who can't become -- a "registered
journalist" -- in Papua New Guinea.  
<P>
SPJ believes a free press means just that -- a press free to report,
accurately, fairly and with balance and responsibility, the developments in a
community. 
<P>
Sincerely,
<P>
<B>Steve Geimann<BR>
SPJ President<BR>
in Chicago, Illinois<BR>
<A HREF="MAILTO:SGeimann@aol.com">SGeimann@aol.com</A></B><BR>
+++pacmediawire
<P>
<Font size=1> 1996 Pacific Media Watch.</FONT 1>
