<head><title> Pacific Media Watch: AFP</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>2 Tongan MPs face charges of sedition</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW22: The National (PNG): 18 November 1996
<P>
Title -- M68 TONGA: 2 Tongan MPs face charges of sedition
Date -- 26 November 1996
Origin -- Pacific Media Watch
Source -- The National (PNG), 18/11/96 (delayed)
Copyright -- Agence France-Presse
Status -- Unabridged
<P>
<HR>
<P>
2 TONGAN MPs FACE CHARGES OF SEDITION</B>
<P>
AUCKLAND: Tongan pro-democracy politicians who were taken into police
custody on Friday were out of jail yesterday and vowing to fight sedition
charges laid against them over their writings.
<P>
For the leader of the pro-democracy movement, Legislative Assembly member
'Akilisi Pohiva, it was the second spell in jail in the kingdom this year
while for another MP, Tesino Fuko, it was his first spell in jail.
<P>
Both men told AFP in a telephone interview yesterday they were picked up by
police from their homes on Friday night on documentation signed by Attorney
General Tevita Tupou.
<P>
Tupou is also the Minister of Justice and earlier this year Pohiva launched
a bid to have him impeached for going to the Atlanta Olympic Games in the
US without permission of the assembly.
<P>
When the independent Times of Tonga published details of Pohiva's notice of
impeachment the assembly sent Pohiva, Times editor kalafi Moala and deputy
editor Filokalafi 'Akau'ola to jail for 30 days for being in contempt of
the assembly.
<P>
They served 26 days in jail before the Supreme Court ordered their release
because procedures used by the assembly had been found unconstitutional.
<P>
Pohiva and Fuko said they were taken to jail because of articles they have
written.
<P>
"They put us in jail and then yesterday (Saturday) subjected us to a very
long, five-hour interview," Pohiva said.
<P>
"They told us it would go on for several days, but yesterday (Saturday)
they released us."
<P>
Pohiva said international publicity, including an appeal by Amnesty
International, was behind their quick release.
<P>
However, they have been charged with sedition although no dates for
hearings have been given.
<P>
He said his interrogation was related to an article he had written in his
pro-democracy movement's Kele'a newspaper.
<P>
Tonga's 100,000 commoners elect nine representatives while the kingdom's 30
nobles elect nine of their own to sit in the 30-seat assembly.
<P>
The 12 members of cabinet are appointed for life terms by the Pacific
island's King Taufau'ahau Tupou IV. - AFP<BR>
+++pacmediawire 
<P>
<Font size=1> 1996 Pacific Media Watch.<BR>
http://acij.uts.edu.au/pmw/ Contact: <A HREF="MAILTO:niusedita@pactok.net">niusedita@pactok.net</A></FONT 1>
</table>
