<head><title> Pacific Media Watch: Protest</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>Pacific Media Watch protests over Tongan arrests</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW13: Media statement: 17 November 1996
<P>
Title -- M59 MEDIA: Pacific Media Watch criticises Tonga, PNG
Date -- 17 November 1996
Origin -- Pacific Media Watch
Source -- PMW
<P>
<HR>
<P>
17 November 1996
<P>
Prime Minister Baron Vaea<BR>
Prime Minister's Office<BR>
Hala Taufa'ahau<BR>
Kolofo'ou<BR>
Kingdom of Tonga<BR>
<P>
Fax: (676) 23888
<P>
PACIFIC MEDIA WATCH PROTESTS OVER TONGAN ARRESTS</B>
<P>
Pacific Media Watch today protested over the reported arrests of two Tongan pro-democracy politicians and a journalist on sedition charges.
<P>
"We protest over the campaign of media harassment and suppression of freedom of expression by the Tongan government which has led to the detention of journalists and politicians for the third time in less than a year," PMW said in a statement.
<P>
PMW also voiced its "serious concern" over recent developments in Papua New Guinea where reports have said the Constitutional Review Commission was promoting draft media legislation designed to introduce registration for journalists and media organisations.
<P>
Pacific Media Watch is an independent group of journalists and academics monitoring censorship and media freedom issues in the region.
<P>
According to Amnesty International, two Tongan politicians, 'Akilisi Pohiva and Tesino Fuko, are reportedly being detained in police cells in Nuku'alofa while the deputy editor of the <B>Taimi 'o Tonga</B> newspaper, Filokalafi 'Akau'ola, has been released.
<P>
Amnesty said they were believed to be facing sedition charges over newspaper articles calling for greater democracy in the kingdom.
<P>
'Akau'ola was arrested with two pro-democracy supporters in February for "angering" Police Minister Clive Edwards.
<P>
On September 19, 'Akau'ola, his editor Kalafi Moala, and Pohiva, were jailed for 30 days for alleged contempt of Parliament for publishing a story about an impeachment motion against a minister. The motion for proceedings to begin was adopted by the Legislative Assembly the week after their jailing.
<P>
The Supreme Court ordered their release a week early because their imprisonment breached constitutional rules.
<P>
Pacific Media Watch called for the release of the detained Tongans.
<P>
It also urged Papua New Guinea's Constitutional Review Commission to seriously reconsider the implications of its legislative moves during its two weeks of "consultations".   
<P>
"PMW notes that the proposed legislation is out of step with the recommendations of the CRC media committee's findings in June that supported self-regulation, and it appears to be a violation of the democratic principles of news media and journalist independence," the statement said.
<P>
Pacific Media Watch cited Clause Nine of the International Federation of Journalists' "declaration of principles of conduct" which states: "Journalists worthy of that name shall deem it their duty to observe faithfully [the code]. Within the general law of each country the journalist shall recognise in professional matters the jurisdiction of colleagues only, to the exclusion of every kind of interference by governments or others."
<P>
Papua New Guinea has had a long and proud tradition of a vigorous and independent news media and has contributed much to building the nation, says the statement. 
<P><B>
Signed:
Peter Cronau and David Robie<BR>
Co-directors<BR>
Pacific Media Watch<BR>
Fax: (61-2) 9281 2976</B><BR>
+++pacmediawire     
<P>
<Font size=1>Pacific Media Watch.</FONT 1>
</table>
