<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Snoop:Smackspotting The life of an undercover cop in Cabramatta</TITLE></HEAD>
  
<BODY BACKGROUND="../IMAGES/bgyellow.gif" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=600 NOSHADE> 
 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=600>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=100 ROWSPAN=2 VALIGN=middle ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Winter<BR>1996</FONT></TD>
<TD width=500 valign=middle align=center><IMG WIDTH=400 SRC="../IMAGES/snoop.gif"></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=+1><I>A Magazine of U.T.S. Journalism - Internet Edition</I></FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=600 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=2 WIDTH=600>
<TR>
<TD width=100 valign=top align=center>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=2>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Next Story<BR><A HREF="cops.htm"><I>Bladder Cops</A></I></FONT></B><BR>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2><P><A HREF="smack.htm#related"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Related<BR>Stories</FONT></B></A><BR>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><A HREF="../journos.htm"><FONT SIZE=+1>The <BR>journalists</FONT></A></B><BR>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="cover.htm">Return to Contents</A><BR></FONT></B><P>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
</TD>

<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Smackspotting.<BR> The life of an undercover cop in Cabramatta.</FONT><BR></B></CENTER>
<P>
<I>Wearing your oldest tracksuit, hanging out in bars and regularly
buying heroin may not sound like a promising career path. But,
as <A HREF="../journos.htm#mgirdham">MELISSA GIRDHAM</A> and <A HREF="../journos.htm#sharris">SONIA HARRIS</A> report, it's all in a day's
work for undercover cop Garth Hazell.</I>
<P>
GARTH Hazell is an undercover cop. He's been working the streets
of Cabramatta for over a year now. His assignment? <I>Operation
Hammer</I>: a crackdown on Cabramatta's rampant street heroin
trade. In the past year, Hazell has arrested more than 300 dealers
- that's an average of two arrests a day.
<P>
&quot;Undercover work is the best way to catch drug dealers,&quot;
he says. &quot;If an undercover police officer buys [the heroin],
he's got it in his hands and he can give evidence.&quot;
<P>
Hazell's work is confined exclusively to the streets. He cruises
Cabramatta wearing his oldest, grubbiest clothes and says he pretends
to be of low intelligence (&quot;you just mimic the dealers&quot;).
<P>
Wired with a microphone and camera, Hazell approaches dealers
randomly while his fellow officers observe from a distance as
back-up.
<P>
&quot;Police always watch from buildings with binoculars &#133;
and you give them signs when the deal is complete. You then walk
away from the scene and the police come in and make the arrest,&quot;
says Hazell. &quot;Undercover police don't get involved in the
arrest so they don't draw attention to themselves and can buy
again. You have so much rotation of police in Cabramatta so one
face is not there for too long doing undercover work.&quot;
<P>
Street-dealing heroin is the base of the drug pyramid. The 5-T
gang, with its band of loyal supporters, is virtually untouchable
at the top of the heroin hierarchy.
<P>
&quot;The 5-T gang don't really deal much themselves any more,&quot;
says Hazell, &quot;they get all the school kids to do it for them.
They'll give them a couple of caps of heroin or some money to
deal for them.&quot;
<P>
The recent high rate of arrest means young dealers are more switched-on
than ever. According to Hazell, they're prepared to go to any
lengths to protect themselves from being caught.
<P>
&quot;[They] often store drugs in the mouth or in balloons. They've
been known to keep it in the lobes of their ear. There's no place
sacred for them,&quot; he says.
<P>
&quot;If a police officer comes along to search them, they swallow
it and retrieve it after the digestive process has taken place.
It doesn't sound very nice but that's what they do.&quot;
<P>
Despite Constable Hazell's tireless efforts, he says he ultimately
feels rather helpless. This is partly because the nature of the
trade means that, no matter how many dealers the police arrest,
there's always just as many ready to take their place.
<P>
&quot;You only have to walk into one of those stairwells in apartment
blocks and you see some disgusting vomit sights, needles, syringes
and balloons. And you think, 'people raise families here; they
walk out of their door and see such things.'&quot;
<P>
Hazell blames the media which persists in portraying Cabramatta
as a &quot;bulletin board for heroin.&quot;
<P>
&quot;Many addicts say they didn't know Cabramatta existed until
it was publicised in the news,&quot; says Hazell. &quot;Gaols
are filling up but the media keeps publicising Cabramatta as the
drug capital of the world, and you've got people as far as Canberra,
Port Macquarie and Queensland coming down to buy heroin ... The
media just makes our job a lot harder.&quot;
<P>
Hazell will shortly return to uniformed patrol, after more than
a year's service on the streets pretending to be a smack fiend.
<P>
&quot;After a year and a half it gets hectic,&quot; he says. &quot;You
just get sick of it. Sick of drugs, sick of druggies, sick of
the whole lot.
</TD> 
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
</CENTER>
<BR>
</TD>
</TR>

