<TD ALIGN=LEFT><FONT SIZE=2>Pic by Lara McKinley
</FONT></TD></TD>
<TR><TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Bladder Cops<BR></FONT></B>
<P>By <A HREF="../journos.htm#dbrowne">David Browne</A></CENTER>
<P>
&quot;THIS'LL show up cocaine, opiates, and THC, that's marijuana,&quot;
explains a helpful salesman holding up a small container that
looks vaguely like the type of safety cup that small children
drink from. &quot;The results are what we call presumtive positive,
which means it just flags a positive result. The employer would
have to get the results verified by a lab before they could take
action,&quot; he continues cheerfully. Two middle aged guys wearing
suits and name tags interrupt the interview, asking questions
about prices and grabbing handfuls of brochures. My inter-viewee
senses a business opportunity and gives them a casual matey sort
of greeting before getting into the details &quot;This is 33 dollars
per unit but it's three tests in one &#133; &quot; I move on.
<P>
It's the 3rd National Alcohol and Other Drugs in the Workplace
Trade Show. From stall to stall in the plush Sydney Hilton ballroom
company reps are keen to show off their equipment - breathalysers,
urine tests, even a hair analysis - that can tell the police,
an insurance company, or increasingly, your employer whether you
have recently been using drugs. This is a growing business in
Australia and the mood is upbeat. One rep told me that although
sales for his do-it-yourself drug tests were still small they
were increasing 'exponentially'.
<P>
Drug testing employees is a phenomena many people associate with
American work culture, but it's been happening in Australia for
at least five years. Although there are no exact figures on the
level of drug testing in Australia, stories are starting to emerge
that show it is becoming part of our employment landscape.
<P>
A Sydney truck driver, says he has tested positive a number of
times. &quot;I smoke a fair bit [of marijuana] and it's in your
system for 28 days. So every time I've been tested it's come up
positive. They tried to sack me a while ago but backed off when
I got myself a solicitor,&quot; he said. Though the tests haven't
yet had any impact on his work prospects or lifestyle he says
he objects to the tests because of the attitude ingrained in the
procedures. &quot;If people realised what marijuana is about they
might have a different attitude to it,&quot; he said.
<P>
A mine worker from Queensland says he has been tested at work
and turned in a positive result for marijuana use. Though he was
not using the drug at work he was suspended for a short time,
but claims after two positive tests workers are offered the option
of attending a rehabilitation course or the sack. &quot;There's
a pretty good program because it's done with the union and all
that. It's fair that you get a couple of chances but you don't
get counselling until you fail,&quot; he said.
<P>
Tony Buon, a psychologist involved in workplace drug and alcohol
counselling, says it is impossible to say how many companies are
drug testing. &quot;I have on my books companies I know are testing
because they've consulted with us to do the education part or
the counselling. There is a least 100 major companies testing
in Australia. There could be ten times that amount for all I know
though,&quot; he said.
<P>
In 1992 the New South Wales Privacy Commission published this
disturbing account of an unnamed woman's experience when taking
part in a random drug test at work. &quot;I was led into a very
small room with a toilet, sink, and a desk. I was given a container
in which to urinate by the attendant. I waited for her to turn
her back before pulling down my pants, but she told me she had
to watch everything I did. I am a 40 year old mother of three
and nothing I have ever done in my life equals or deserves the
humiliation, degradation and mortification I felt,&quot; she said.
<P>
According to the New South Wales Privacy Commission, in 1991 11.5
per cent of Australian companies had some form of drug testing
procedures in place. The report concluded that the practice was
on the increase.These figures are small when compared with America.
Research from the same period showed that in any year over two-thirds
of the American workforce is likely to undergo drug testing.
<P>
Testing in the US gained momentum during the 1980s 'War on Drugs'
when President Reagan signed an executive order requiring all
government employees to be tested. Laws were then passed to ensure
that any company applying for a government tender had random drug
testing programs in place. Reagan even offered to be tested. Though
legend has it, the idea was dropped when a doctor pointed out
to the 70 year old President that he was taking several medications
that would show up in a test.
<P>
If recent events are anything to go by Bill Clinton does not intend
to be outdone by his Republican predecessors. In December last
year he announced that criminals entering the prison system would
face compulsory drug testing to &quot;break the cycle of crime
and drugs&quot;. Announcing the new initiative he noted approvingly,
&quot;All across our country employers have accepted responsibility
to reduce the level of drug use in the workplace. Teachers and
coaches have accepted the responsibility to reduce the level of
drug use in our schools.&quot; American employers now test workers
for traces of illicit drugs as well as high doses of legal substances
like caffeine, alcohol, and nicotine and a ruling in the US Supreme
Court last year made it legal for high schools to randomly test
students involved in sporting events.
<P>
The American Council for Civil Liberties claimed in a recent paper
that drug testing flourished in the US under the deregulated and
largely non-unionised industrial relations environment of the
1980s. This year over 15 million workers in the US will be given
drug tests by their employers. Critics claim the tests most commonly
used by employers are the cheapest and least reliable. Others
claim that tests are being used to screen workers who are pregnant
or who are taking medication for legitimate medical conditions.
But the most common complaint is that drug testing is a major
breach of individual privacy.
<P>
&quot;Testing really took off in Australia following Reagan's
push in the 1980s,&quot; said Tony Buon. &quot;What happened was,
American companies operating in Australia wanted to have the same
policies.&quot; Changes in Australia such as the decline of union
membership and the movement towards individual employment contracts
has provided an environment where such practices can be adopted.
Although according to Tony Buon this hasn't always been so. &quot;I
remember in the past people used to say we'd like to do drug testing
but the unions wouldn't let us,&quot; he said.
<P>
The internet has become an important meeting place for people
who want to protest against drug testing policies and organise
resistance. Usenet newsgroups like &quot;alt.drugs&quot; are flooded
with horror stories posted by Americans telling of tests gone
wrong and the indignity of having to piss in a cup for an employer.
<P>
One post told the story of a woman who tested positive for opiates
after eating two poppy seed muffins. In another, a woman claimed
that her husband had just been sacked for failing a random test.
&quot;He had an outstanding performance record, attendance record,
and was good enough to relieve for his supervisor. But none of
that mattered when they discovered 374 ng of benzylecognine [element
indicating cocaine use]. &quot;The point is, our life is now in
shambles because of a stupid invasion of privacy,&quot; she said.
<P>
The internet is not just a place for sharing stories on the horror
of the workplace drug test. It is also becoming a place where
people seek information on how to beat the tests. The <I>Anti-Bladder
Cops Society</I> is based around a homepage on the World Wide
Web that contains a huge amount of information on the various
tests, how they work, how accurate they are, what drugs they test
for, and most importantly - how they can be beaten. 
<P>
A FAQ (frequently asked questions) archive titled <I>Fooling the
bladder cops</I> lists dozens of approaches to defeating the drug
tests. These include scientific methods like ingesting substances
that neutralise drug traces in the body, tricks like exchanging
samples, and legal avenues like demanding employers sign contracts
making them liable for any misuse of the sample or any errors.
While most of the information appears credible, even ingenious,
a few of the methods described seem a little extreme. For example,
in a section titled &quot;Injecting&quot; the document reads:

<P>
<I>&quot;There's a way to use substitution even when you're under
the strictest supervision. Athletes trying to pass tests for anabolic
steroids have been known to empty their bladders, and have the
substituted urine injected directly into their bladders via needle.
It was shown in a motion picture like &quot;Wildcats&quot; or
something. While theoretically possible, it's painful and subject
to infection. (kids - don't try this at home:).&quot;</I>
<P>
Justin Gombos, an American, who compiled <I>Fooling the bladder
cops</I> claims to have no special expertise except having always
taken an interest in beating the system. He claims that the drug
war in America is being taken to absurd levels by the authorities
and that the testing laws demonstrate &quot;how totalitarian this
country [America] has become&quot;.
<P>
Contacted via e-mail, Gombos made it clear that he believes drug
testing is a threat to individual rights. &quot;I believe drug
testing is a violation of our Constitution; it's very unjust.
Drug testing is a threat to the civil liberties of all employees,&quot;
he said. He feels so strongly about the issue that he claims people
should boycott companies that test. &quot;I would suggest that
job applicants refuse any employer willing to exploit them in
this manner,&quot; he said.
<P>
Frank Ross is another American who uses the internet to voice
his opposition to drug testing. He believes that Australians should
attempt to stamp out testing before it reaches the same proportions
as America. &quot;[Drug testing] has to be challenged in the political
arena and you have to build a popular consensus around it. In
the US, drugs have been portrayed as the source of all evil by
government and corporate propaganda, so that some people appear
to be willing to relinquish their rights for the 'cause', the
War on Drugs,&quot; he said.
<P>
According to Ross if the issue is productivity and occupational
health and safety, as many companies claim, then employees who
are using drugs, either on the job or in their own time, would
be easy to detect without testing procedures. &quot;The War on
Drugs is a moral crusade and the government or a company has no
right to dictate morality. If an (off-the-job) drug user performs
well in his job then why should he be terminated? If drug taking
is indeed such a hazardous and mentally debilitating activity
then surely the manager will detect a marked reduction in performance
on the job?,&quot; he said. 
<P>
So, as Australia rushes towards full enterprise bargaining and
union membership continues to plummet should we be worried about
going down the same path as America? Patrick Cook, who distributes
do-it-yourself drug testing kits for a European pharmaceutical
multinational, was keen to down play comparisons with the US.
&quot;I think it is unlikely Australia will head in the same direction
as America because of the cultural differences between the countries,&quot;
he said. &quot;The emphasis is on occupational safety, and testing
is only being carried out in areas like mining, transport, and
heavy industry where there are clear dangers in having workers
intoxicated, or working at a reduced level in the workplace. I
really think it can only work in Australia with a cooperative
approach.&quot;
<P>
A paper released in 1992 by the Australian Council of Trade Unions
(ACTU) claimed that drug abuse costs the nation $18.9 billion
a year in medical expenses and lost productivity. This figure
is considered a conservative estimate. There are also obvious
benefits to testing employees in high risk areas such as airlines,
and heavy industry where intoxicated workers could endanger their
own lives and the lives of others.
<P>
But according to Cathy Butcher, the ACTU's Occupational Health
and Safety Officer, drug testing is a superficial answer to the
problem of drug abuse, and it has more to do with policing than
examining the causes of the problem. &quot;Far too many employers
are seeing the problem as catching and disciplining individual
workers. For years we've been fighting against the image of the
careless worker, now we are faced with the myth of the drunk or
drugged worker who is the scapegoat for poor safety and low productivity,&quot;
she said.
<P>
&quot;So if drugs and alcohol are seen as a health and safety
issue then you address them in the same way you address other
health and safety issues. It becomes a simplistic approach when
you say that you are dealing with drugs and alcohol by testing
people, without saying 'Is there anything within the workplace
that feeds that, that contributes to a person using drugs?,'&quot;
she said.
</TD> 
</TR>

