</TABLE>
</TD>

<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="internet.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=203></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Internet Integrates</FONT><BR></B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<I>
One group in our community seems set to reap profound benefits
from being part of tha global computer network we call the Internet.
The disabled. But even here there is hype. <A HREF="../journos.htm#kdyson">KIERAN DYSON</A> reports.</I>
<P>
The Internet is a powerful tool allowing users to inform and educate
themselves, socialise, consume and perform tasks, all on a world
wide scale by simply connecting their home or office computer
to a phone line via a modem.
<P>
For many disabled users these benefits can radically transform
lifestyles. The Internet may come to represent a world where,
for the first time, they can experience sub-stantial interaction
with others with ease and on equal terms.
<P>
An organisation which took early advantage of the Internet is
the Disability Information and Resource Center of South Australia
which is dedicated to improving the lifestyles of disabled people.
As well as providing its existing information service through
its Website, the center established an electronic bulletin board
system, called Common Ground, in 1993.
<P>
The system, which has 1000 registered users, was designed as an
interactive space where people with disabilities and others could
discuss issues affecting their lives.
<P>
System Operator, David Wallace, says Common Ground has become
an instrument of empowerment. &quot;The bulletin board is a great
medium for breaking down barriers that isolate people socially,
whether this be through a physical disability which limits their
mobility, or any other disability affecting their social interaction
in some way. It brings people together in a virtual sense.
<P>
&quot;In that respect, it's opened up complete new worlds for
some people. In fact we have quite a few registered users who
previously had no other means of communication. A lot of them
use it as a communication tool especially, and not just in a social
sense, but also to communicate with relatives who they may not
have been able to communicate with successfully before.&quot;
<P>
Common Ground was also set up to enable users to interact with
organisations and government bodies about relevant issues such
as public transport access and wheelchair standards.
<P>
Like most bulletin boards and newsgroups on the net, Common Ground
has evolved from just being a practical Internet facility to having
a strong community atmosphere. Two marriages have already resulted
from Common Ground meetings and David attributes these to the
nature of the system.
<P>
&quot;People feel they can come to Common Ground as a place in
its own right. There's people there they know and they feel that
they belong rather than just being yet another number on the network.&quot;
<P>
This sense of community plus the Internet's safeguard of anonymity,
is particularly useful for disabled users. Where many people with
disabilities suffer from prejudice and social stigma in the real
world, the virtual world of the Internet becomes a place where
they can express themselves without inhibitions and gain self-confidence,
before they decide to disclose their disability - if at all.
<P>
Melinda Smith is a 33-year-old Melbourne writer and Internet user
who suffers from Cerebral Palsy. She is also a member of Melbourne's
Computer Aid User Society (CAUS) and their representative for
Telstra's consultancy committee for disabilities. &quot;Apart
from that&quot;, she tells me via e-mail, &quot;I run my own business
in disability awareness training for TAFE schools and employment
services.&quot;
<P>
Last year Melinda had the best time of her life when she &quot;took
a wild plunge and went to the USA and Britain and stayed with
a number of people I'd met on my computer.&quot; She had been
e-mailing these people on a regular basis beforehand and had used
the disabled traveller forum, and other general traveller forums
on the Internet, to plan her trip. &quot;I received much more
info and first hand advice than if I had gone to the local travel
agent,&quot; she says.
<P>
In this instance, the Internet served as a social and practical
tool for Melinda who remains excited by the liberating experience
of using the technology to communicate.
<P>
&quot;I was introduced to the Internet in 1993 and my world just
changed from being in the world to being a part of it. It's a
very exciting way for people with disabilities to experience life
without a disability - and just BE. 
<P>
&quot;The best part about it is the freedom to be yourself and
nobody has to know what you look like or whether you speak like
the average person. I make a point of not mentioning my disability
until I feel that she/he has got to know ME first and by then
it's no big deal.&quot;
<P>
As a practical tool in the work place, the Internet can also be
invaluable, especially when it's easier for someone to read and
type words than it is to hear and speak them.
<P>
Stephen Pascoe, aged 41, is Network Manager for the Department
of Defence (Defence Science and Technology Organisation) and has
suffered profound progressive hearing loss since he was 17.
<P>
Stephen accessed the Internet through his work and has been using
e-mail to communicate within the organisation for seven years.
He says the Internet has been indispensable in helping him overcome
communication problems at work and allowing him to stay in touch
with friends, although, he adds, the process can be impersonal.
<P>
Having enjoyed such benefits from the Net, Stephen has run workshops
for other hearing impaired people as a way of introducing them
to the concepts of the Internet and the services available. But
Stephen fears inevitable progressions in computer technology may
isolate users with disabilities yet again.
<P>
&quot;At the moment the Internet is limited by speed, but when
it improves, the ability to use sound and voice (which is already
done to some degree) will be increased. Therefore where deaf people
can now use e-mail and chat programs to communicate with others,
if voice is added, this wonderful liberation is again lost to
them.&quot;
<P>
Another concern for disabled users is that ease of communication
in the virtual world may inadvertently restrict proper communication
in the real world. In a 1994 paper commissioned by Telecom entitled
&quot;People With Disabilities and the Information Superhighway&quot;,
its author, Christopher Newell, questioned the social ramifications
of technological aid.
<P>
&quot;At times, technological intervention is held out to be an
enabler, yet it is also important to realise that another fundamental
issue for people with disabilities is ensuring adequate social
contact, with such a hi-tech scenario raising implications for
human contact.&quot;
<P>
As physical contact in the real world becomes less of a necessity,
contact in the virtual realm poses new psychological complications
for the disabled. Able to revel in the freedom of anonymity when
communicating on the Internet, never-theless they must eventually
confront issues of self identity and self esteem.
<P>
For the first time in history people with disabilities have the
opportunity to participate in a community without fear of being
marginalised or shunned but if the dilemma to tell or not to tell
of one's situation isn't resolved first, on what foundation are
these new relationships built?
<P>
Douglas Lathrop, writing for &quot;Main-stream Online&quot; (a
lifestyle zine for people with disabilities) cuts to the core
of this underlying issue. He writes: &quot;...maybe the Information
Age will see people with disabilities shattering a history of
isolation. But it won't until enough of us have smashed the firewalls
that we've built for ourselves first.&quot;
<P>


<TR>
