<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="violenc.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=133></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT><FONT SIZE=2>Pic by Lara McKinley</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Faces of Domestic Violence</B></FONT><BR>
<P><A HREF="../journos.htm#lyoung">By Lynda Young</A></CENTER>
<P>
THURSDAY is Domestic Violence day at Waverley Courthouse and Michelle
Karaman is one of 23 women seeking an Apprehended Violence Order
on their husband or boyfriend. She is pretty, petite and used
to be proud of her long black hair which is now greying and matted.
She angrily pulls at it with both hands and protests sarcastically
to anyone who'll listen, &quot;He's taken away my life, you'd
think he'd spare the hair.&quot;
<P>
The small room they wait in has been set aside by the Domestic
Violence Assistance Scheme, a joint initiative of community workers
and solicitors involved in providing emotional and legal support
to survivors of domestic violence.
<P>
The provision of the room protects victims from the anxiety of
mingling with their alleged abusers. But Michelle is still worried
at the thought of seeing her husband who waits just outside the
door.
<P>
&quot;He's out there,&quot; she says with clenched teeth to her
daughter Debra. &quot;That bastard. After all he's put me through,
can you believe he denies everything?&quot;
<P>
Michelle's marriage to Fedai was hasty. They met when she was
just 16, 12 years ago in Turkey, and married within six weeks.
Michelle thought she was marrying a prince. He was charming and
handsome, but on the night of their wedding he beat her with a
chair because the stockings she borrowed from his mother kept
falling down during the ceremony.
<P>
Two months into the marriage Michelle was pregnant and Fedai,
who was 10 years her senior, moved them to Australia, away from
her family and friends, to take up a job offer. Within the first
week of their arrival Fedai left without explanation.
<P>
&quot;I was totally alone. My family didn't support the marriage
in the first place and were glad to be rid of me. I had no money
and barely spoke the language.&quot;
<P>
For a year she struggled to make ends meet cleaning houses and
waitressing. After the birth of her daughter Debra in 1985 she
heard from Fedai.
<P>
&quot;He begged me to take him back saying that he loved me. So
I did. I had nothing and I thought awful was better than nothing.&quot;
<P>
Five years and two more babies later Michelle was completely dependent
on Fedai. He had isolated her from any friends she made, forbid
her to work and beat her almost daily.
<P>
&quot;I didn't want to go anywhere or meet anyone because I was
ashamed. I always had bruises on my face and had completely lost
my identity.&quot;
<P>
For the next four years the violence became more intense. Michelle
would no longer react to pain or plead Fedai to stop. Her indifference
enraged him, so he added tools to the ritual beatings.
<P>
&quot;He poured hot oil from a pan on the stove over my head,
broke all my fingers on my hands with the end of an empty bottle
of scotch, and two years ago hit me with the car one morning when
I was walking down the driveway.&quot;
<P>
Michelle never told anyone about the beatings or went to hospital,
but secretly planned the day she would leave.
<P>
Michelle's case is just one of thousands. The New South Wales
Bureau of Crimes Statistics and Research (BCSR) recorded nearly
4000 cases in New South Wales of domestic violence in 1994, resulting
in only 16 convictions - an overall success rate of 0.04 per cent.
<P>
The Federal Bureau of Investigation believes that in the United
States domestic violence is the most unreported crime, and estimates
that it is ten times more unreported than rape.
<P>
Similar results were found by the Australian Bureau of Statistics
in April 1990, when survey figures reflected an estimate of 19
000 victims of domestic violence in a 12 month period, yet only
2200 were reported to police.
<P>
Maria Vucko, Coordinator of the Waverley Domestic Violence Court
Assistance Scheme, fears that the number of unreported incidences
will increase due to inadequate legislation, women not understanding
their rights, and lack of police education.
<P>
&quot;I've talked ad nauseam to police officers about the importance
of encouraging women to file criminal complaints so that we can
get some of the offenders a criminal history and put them away.
But when some of the people on the force are involved in domestic
violence cases of their own, my words fall on deaf ears.&quot;
<P>
Steve Heath, clerk of Waverley Court, agrees with Ms Vucko, and
believes there is much work to be done and that education is the
solution.
<P>
&quot;The police, historically, have not been compassionate with
women who call for assistance. They look at that kind of call
as more of an irritant and do not take it as seriously as, say,
a call involving a weapon. That's where the ignorance lies.&quot;
<P>
Mr Heath believes the legislation dealing with domestic violence
does not protect the victim. &quot;The legislation can exist without
the officers even knowing about it because of the constant amendments
to the Crime Act. That in itself is a huge gap of communication.
If the officers are not informed how can they pass on good counsel?&quot;
<P>
In response to the calls for more community education, a program
was launched in early 1996, promoting the involvement of police
in dealing with domestic violence.
<P>
Statistics from the BCSR show that 70 per cent of New South Wales
police work involves domestic violence. The Department for Women
has initiated training for service providers and professionals
working with survivors of domestic violence.
<P>
However, despite these government efforts, horror stories like
Michelle's are heard daily by counsellor Carol Maderious, from
the Botany Family and Child Care Centre, who assists on the monthly
rotation roster at the Scheme.
<P>
&quot;At least eight to ten victims pour into the Centre weekly
and they all have the same thought - that they can change their
man.&quot;
<P>
According to Ms Maderious, women involved in domestic violence
situations take on a martyr role, and accept their lifestyle as
normal because the man believes it to be true.
<P>
&quot;Most of the women have severely low self esteem and suffer
from chronic depression which is why it's a miracle if they break
the cycle and take the first step to admit the problem, get out
and get help. The recurring theme is that they all believe or
hope that the men are going to somehow get better if they can
act a certain way or fix their favourite foods.
<P>
&quot;But the reality is these men are mentally ill in some form
or another, or are repeating the vicious circle that was displayed
to them in their homes as children. I'm not saying this to excuse
the behaviour, but to emphasise my belief that these men cannot
be rehabilitated.&quot;
<P>
The relevant section of the New South Wales Crimes Act 1900 states
that a person may apply for an Apprehended Violence Order (AVO)
if someone intentionally:
<P>
<I> &#133; injures or threatens to injure, damages or threatens
to damage property, uses words or actions to intimidate or harass,
follows repeatedly, telephones repeatedly at home or work, behaves
indecently without consent, and/or gets someone else to injure,
harass or threaten.</I>
<P>
The law deals with domestic violence in two ways: criminal charges
of assault and/or an AVO. Criminal charges and an application
for an AVO can and should occur together, according to Bruce Mexon,
Senior Constable and Victim's Support Coordinator for the Waverley
Police.
<P>
 &quot;To get a conviction on a criminal charge related to domestic
violence is very difficult.&quot; This is shown by the statistically
low conviction rate in New South Wales in 1994. &quot;The fact
is we need documentation of all incidences which occurred, credible
witnesses for the prosecution and, unfortunately, it makes a dramatic
difference if the victim has obvious injuries, pictures or medical
reports ... when they come to court.&quot;
<P>
Judge Terry Forbes of Waverley Court agrees with Senior Constable
Mexon, and says that in most criminal cases, rulings will be made
according to the level of documented abuse. &quot;Mental abuse
weighs just as heavily as physical abuse, however, it's harder
to prove. Most cases heard are years in the making. With no physical
evidence, it comes down to the plaintiff's word against the defendant's.&quot;
<P>
This is where the legislation begins to fail. Hard evidence is
difficult to come by in most cases of domestic abuse, as women
rarely come forward and lodge a complaint against their husbands.
The woman feels trapped and usually cuts off support systems such
as her friends and family due to her feelings of self-blame.
<P>
Low income also plays a key role but is not always the norm. Ms
Vucko refers to a 'high profile' case she is currently working
on where the alleged victim, the wife of a prominent barrister
in New South Wales, has many wealthy friends and caring family
members. In cases such as this, the situation can be complicated
by status and reputation.
<P>
&quot;I use the example,&quot; she states, &quot;to simply prove
any socio-economic group is not exempt and the pattern of abuse
and control is the same regardless.&quot;
<P>
After the woman has applied for the AVO a magistrate issues a
summons for the appearance of the defendant at court or a warrant
for their arrest, depending on the severity of the complaint.
The person in need of protection need only satisfy the court 'on
the balance of probabilities' that fear exists. The magistrate
will then set an interim order or bail conditions placing restrictions
on the offender until the hearing. An interim order holds the
same weight as an AVO, but expires on the date of the hearing.
<P>
According to Domestic Violence Officer at the NSW Police Department,
Julie Stewart, the problem that results is that few criminal precedents
are set because women are encouraged to be satisfied with the
rulings from an AVO.
<P>
&quot;Most applications for AVOs result in an interim (order)
because criminal pursuits are not historically regarded as successful,&quot;
she says. &quot;Of the 4000 complaints filed in 1994, more than
80 per cent were settled with an interim. If we had that extra
80 per cent to draw on yearly, new precedents would surely be
set and women would feel more confident that the system was working
for them and not against.&quot;
<P>
&quot;Many times the men ignore the orders and the temptation
to repeat the offence becomes more important than a slip of paper,&quot;
says Ms Stewart.
<P>
Men who are not gaoled and receive a final order following an
interim order are usually given guidelines to follow for a period
of up to six months. These guidelines include distance restrictions,
no phone contact with the plaintiff, and no contact with friends
or family of the woman who has complained.
<P>
According to Carol Maderious, the women live in a state of fear
because the order relies on the perpetrator's self-control. In
many cases the final order is broken resulting in a more severe
injury or even occasionally murder.
<P>
&quot;This is simply not enough,&quot; says Carolyn Middleton,
assistant clerk of the Waverley Courthouse. &quot;I see the same
women in here over and over again, terrified because they got
a call or a letter or even saw their perpetrator. The system is
backlogged with repeat applications because we're trusting good
behaviour from criminals.&quot;
<P>
The law states that a defendant who breaches the final order can
be subject to a term of imprisonment, however, repeat offences
still happen.
<P>
Michelle is back at the Scheme room from her hearing; her hands
shake as she reads the interim order. &quot;This is what it comes
down to after 12 years and the mess he's made out of my life.&quot;
<P>
Her tone increases with each syllable. &quot;I had to take off
work, wait here four hours and that judge thinks this will keep
him out of my house?&quot;
<P>
Carol Maderious sits down next to her and tries to explain how
the system works. After five impatient minutes Michelle can take
no more. &quot;The system doesn't work for me, it works for him.
He can still do whatever he wants at the end of the day, can't
he? And at the end of the day I'm still afraid.&quot;
<P>
According to Waverley Court Clerk, Steve Heath, Fedai refused
to admit to any of Michelle's allegations but consented to the
Apprehended Violence Order.
<P>
&quot;He is promising the court that he won't assault, harass
or approach the plaintiff or the residence of the plaintiff for
two years,&quot; he said.
<P>
It will be Michelle's decision to renew the order if she wishes
to extend the period of court protection.
<P>
<B>AVOs</B> 
<UL>
<LI>is not a criminal offence
<LI>can be applied for by the victim or the police on behalf of
the victim
<LI>purpose is to provide protection from future violence
<LI>places conditions or restrictions on the offender
<LI>magistrate must be satisfied on the balance of probabilities
that fear is reasonable and justifiedl a breach of an AVO is a
criminal offence
</UL>

<P>
<B>CRIMINAL CHARGES</B> 
<UL>
<LI>offender, if found guilty, receives a criminal conviction
<LI>police lay the charges and prosecute the matter
<LI>purpose is to punish for offences which have already occurred
<LI>imposes a punishment
<LI>(eg bond, or prison)
<LI>must be proved beyond
<LI>reasonable doubt that the alleged offence occurred
<LI>the victim can usually be forced to give evidence
</UL>

<P>
Picking up the pieces
<P>
Cecilia Wheeler lived with her husband in Randwick for 25 years
until recently when Ronald Wheeler was sentenced by Magistrate
Terry Forbes at Waverley Courthouse.
<P>
Three days before the sentencing Ronald went into one of his unprovoked
rages and beat Cecilia repeatedly with a hard plastic water pipe.
She has just turned 49 but looks closer to 60. Her face is black
and blue, but she is smiling as Ronald has lost his right to contact
Cecilia and their two children, Evelyn and Mark, indefinitely.
<P>
Mr Wheeler sat weeping in the witness stand while the sentence
was read to him, slowly, as Magistrate Forbes wanted him to hear
every word.
<P>
&quot;The pain you have caused Mrs Wheeler and your children is
written all over her face today. The pain you are feeling for
losing your family forever is because of what you have done. Don't
feel sorry for yourself, Mr Wheeler, feel sorry for your family.&quot;
<P>
Ronald Wheeler was given the maximum sentence. He may never contact
his family, and if he breaches the order he will be immediately
taken to jail for five years.
<P>
After the order, Cecilia received supportive calls from friends
and community workers. &quot;I hope he breaches that order,&quot;
Cecilia says angrily. &quot;Then I'll know where he is all the
time.&quot;
<P>
Cecilia stayed in the abusive situation because she felt she had
no other alternative. &quot;What else could I do. He had control
of the money and of my life.&quot;
<P>
The beatings Cecilia experienced were always unprovoked and started
two weeks after their marriage. Verbal jabs were coupled with
the violence, &quot;he would wind up and hit me in the breast
and say now no one will ever want you because you're deformed.&quot;
<P>
After many years Cecilia stopped crying and like Mark just withdrew.
&quot;I feel like I got hit by a double-decker bus everyday for
the past 25 years and now I just want some peace and quiet.&quot;
</TD> 
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
</CENTER>
<BR>
</TD>
