<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Excavating an old Oz Rock
</FONT><BR></B>
<P>By <A HREF="../journos.htm#jmoore">Joanna Moore</A></CENTER>
<P>
<P>
CYNICS say the Australian music industry is dead; that it hit
its peak in the '80s with the likes of Midnight Oil, Crowded House
and INXS. They say that venues are shutting down and that there's
not enough new bands emerging to displace the 'Farnsey and Barnesy'
stronghold. These cynics obviously haven't heard of Grinspoon,
Raven, Ode to a Goldfish, or Porcelien. They haven't heard of
Unearthed.
<P>
Unearthed is a nationwide competition run by the ABC's youth radio
network Triple J. Born from the station's longstanding desire
to support young Australian musicians, the competition aims to
discover and promote new bands from regional areas around the
country.
<P>
&quot;It took quite a while to get to the point where we felt
Unearthed was the best way to achieve our aims,&quot; says Bronwyn
McConvill, the competition's co-ordinator.
<P>
But when the former federal government encouraged the expansion
of Triple J into regional Australia, the Unearthed idea began
to take shape.
<P>
McConvill describes the project's aims as twofold:
<P>
&quot;We wanted to get Triple J out into the regional areas; both
programs and staff. We are a national network; we wanted to get
a feel for Australia, instead of just broadcasting from Sydney.&quot;We
also wanted to assist young musicians in regional Australia ...
and give them a chance of national exposure,&quot; she says. 
<P>
But McConvill believes the competition is ultimately about young
Australians, be they musicians or not.
<P>
&quot;Young people love hearing what other young people are up
to,&quot; she says. &quot;Because the shows are broadcast from
each regional area, the listener gets a feel for that area - a
chance to hear what is happening in other young people's lives.
Capital city listeners hear about Lismore or Rockhampton through
the words and music of the area's young residents.&quot;
<P>
By July this year, Triple J will have 'unearthed' all the regional
areas to which it presently broadcasts.
<P>
The competition has already been successful in increasing audiences
and venues for live music in regional Australia. Venues have capitalised
on the success of Unearthed and have been giving local bands regular
gigs.
<P>
In Rockhampton, for instance, a concert featuring 13 local bands
was recently staged following the town's huge response to the
Triple J competition.
<P>
&quot;With any luck,&quot; says McConvill, &quot;I think [venues
and regional acts] will gradually get over 'pub rock' and bloody
cover songs ... Bands are finding they can be original, and can
be accepted.&quot;Indeed the deluge of original new bands makes
judging the Unearthed competition extremely difficult, according
to McConvill. She says the judges are essentially &quot;looking
for a song to play on the radio; no particular genre, just a song
that sounds great.&quot;
<P>
Most of the hundreds of demo tapes sent in by aspiring bands have
been cheaply recorded in bedrooms and garages. McConvill says
that judging the competition is more often than not a matter of
&quot;hearing through a bad recording&quot;.
<P>
The winner from each region is awarded a recording session in
the Triple J studios. With professional assistance, they produce
a slick DAT demo tape which they can take to record companies.
<P>
Some of the winners have already met with success as a result
of the competition.
<P>
Lismore band Grinspoon, one of the first bands to be &quot;unearthed&quot;,
gained a spot in the 1995 Triple J Hottest 100 with their song
<I>Sick Fest</I>. The band was also included on the prestigious
Homebake festival bill.
<P>
Porcelein, the Broken Hill winners, played at the recent Livid
Festival in Brisbane; while Gold Coast winners, Communion, have
just snared a breakthrough record deal with the prestigious Mushroom
label.
<P>
Perhaps the most significant thing about Unearthed, however, is
that it shows that Australian music is alive and well. Venues
are hiring these young bands, and crowds are swelling in support.
Australian music, it seems, is on the rise.
</TD> 
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2>
