<LI> <A HREF="#STAFF">Staff</A>
<br>
<LI> <A HREF="#STUDENT">Student awards</A><br>
</Font size =4></Strong><br><br><p></UL></UL></ul></ul>
<HR>
<A HREF="#Index"><IMG WIDTH=30 ALIGN=BOTTOM  SRC="images/Samlogo.gif"></A> <Font size=4><B><A NAME="BACK">Background:</A></Font></B>
<P>
No other journalism educational institution in the Pacific offers anything substantial in the field of Third World or development journalism, most following Australian or New Zealand models. 
<P>
The centre attracts journalism students or professional journalists and library/information students and professionals from around the region -- mainly Melanesia -- seeking further qualifications.
<P>
The centre enables trends within library and information sciences to be developed. A meeting of talents and minds in the centre with a developmental orientation offers an attractive change for a more positive contribution from the resources available.
<P>
Among tertiary institutions with close ties to the centre is the  <A HREF="http://acij.uts.edu.au/"> Australian Centre for Independent Journalism  </A>  ( ACIJ ) at the University of Technology, Sydney. A draft Memorandum of Understanding is being prepared between the two universities.
<P>
Associate Professor Wendy Bacon of the ACIJ assisted the centre under a UNESCO funded consultancy in developing a graduate Certificate of Investigative Journalism course.
<P>
<HR>
<A HREF="#Index"><IMG WIDTH=30 ALIGN=BOTTOM  SRC="images/Samlogo.gif"></A> <Font size=4><B><A NAME="CONTACT">Contact information:</A></Font></B>
<P>
Head, South Pacific Centre for Communication and Information in Development (SPCenCIID), PO Box 320, Uni PO, National Capital District, Papua New Guinea. Fax: (675) 3267191. Email: <A HREF="MAILTO:journupng@pactok.peg.apc.org">journupng@pactok.peg.apc.org</A>
<P>
<B>Associate membership:</B><BR>
Associate membership benefits include free subscription to centre publications, 25 per cent discount on centre books, 25 per cent on centre external seminars and courses, and notification of centre activities. Individual: US$10. Institutional: US$100 a year.
<P>
<HR>
<A HREF="#Index"><IMG WIDTH=30 ALIGN=BOTTOM  SRC="images/Samlogo.gif"></A> <Font size=4><B><A NAME="GOALS">Centre goals:</A></Font></B>
<P>
The centre seeks to assist national development through enhancing professional capabilities and service attitudes in the fields of communications (journalism and media studies) and library and information services, and by providing a facility for research and study in these fields.
<P>
The goals of the centre are to:
<P><UL><LI>Produce qualified staff at para-professional, junior-professional and professional levels for library and information units. 
<P>
<LI>Produce qualified journalists for professional media roles in press and broadcast services, government information agencies and public relations units. 
<P>
<LI>Provide courses and seminars to extend the ability of professional journalists and other information workers. 
<P>
<LI>Provide development communication courses. 
<P>
<LI>Provide courses to enhance the ability of people in charge of school libraries and enhance the information skills of school students. 
<P>
<LI>Provide course to enhance information skills at university level and to develop the institutions' information culture. 
<P>
<LI>Provide research on Papua New Guinea and South Pacific media and mass communication issues.
<P>
<LI>Provide research to develop knowledge and understanding of library and information science PNG and the region, and through this research to develop new approaches to village and community information services. <P>
<LI>Provide expertise through consultancy and other means to government, industry and the community.
</UL>
<HR>
<A HREF="#Index"><IMG WIDTH=30 ALIGN=BOTTOM  SRC="images/Samlogo.gif"></A> <Font size=4><B><A NAME="HISTORY">History:</A></Font size=4>
<P>
<Font size=3>In 1989 a Department of Library and Information Studies (DLIS) was established within UPNG's Faculty of Education. This was coupled with a bachelor's degree course in library and information studies. 
<P>
Journalism began at UPNG in 1974 as an autonomous unit funded by the New Zealand Government for five years. Although it is the biggest and oldest tertiary journalism programme, its resources had been neglected while student numbers have grown and technological development and publishing had been growing at an increased pace.
<P>
The centre was created in January 1995. </Font> 
<P>
<HR>
<A HREF="#Index"><IMG WIDTH=30 ALIGN=BOTTOM  SRC="images/Samlogo.gif"></A> <Font size=4><B><A NAME="PROGRAMS">Programs:</A></Font></B><BR>
<UL><LI><Font size=3>Diploma in Library and Information Studies
<P>
<LI>Diploma in Media Studies
<P>
<LI>Bachelor in Library and Information Studies
<P>
<LI>Bachelor of Journalism
<P>
<LI>Bachelor of Science (Information Management) 
<P>
<LI>Postgraduate: Certificate in Investigative Journalism
<P>
<LI>Lahara: Diploma in Educational Studies (Teacher-Librarianship)
<P>
<LI>Certificate in Information Studies (Records Management)</UL></Font>
<P>
<HR>
<A HREF="#Index"><IMG WIDTH=30 ALIGN=BOTTOM  SRC="images/Samlogo.gif"></A> <Font size=4><B><A NAME="STAFF">Academic staff:</A></Font></B><P><Font size=3>
<UL><LI><B>Rhonda Eva</B>, lecturer in library and information studies and Head of Centre. 
<P>
