<head><title> About Pacific Journalism Review</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#70DBDB">
<A HREF="index.html"><IMG SRC="../images/PJRmast.gif" width=150  ALT="Pacific Journalism Review masthead"></A>
<HR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475>
<TD WIDTH=200 align=left>http://acij.uts.edu.au/PJR/issues/about.html</TD> </TABLE>
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<h2>About Pacific Journalism Review</h2>
<B>Pacific Journalism Review</B> is a journal covering Pacific media issues and communication. While one objective is research into Pacific journalism theory and practice, the journal is also interested in advertising, communication, information technology, government, media studies, politics and public administration. 
<p>
It also has a special interest in environmental and development studies in the media and communication -- and indigenous media in the region. But <B>PJR</B>   also aims to be very readable and lively with illustrations, graphics ... and cartoons.
</P>
The journal is published by the University of Papua New Guinea's South Pacific Centre for Communication and Information in Development 
<A HREF="http://acij.uts.edu.au/UniTavur/UniT_SPCenCIID.html"> (SPCenCIID)</A> in Port Moresby and is hosted on the Web by the Australian Centre for Independent Journalism's 
<A HREF=http://acij.uts.edu.au/> <B> Online Journalist</b></A>. <P>
Three volumes have been published since November 1994 with the latest edition featuring cartoons by former 
<A HREF="http://acij.uts.edu.au/UniT_Home.html">Uni Tavur</A>   cartoonist Campion Ohasio, of the Solomon Islands.<P>
<H3>Editorial Board:</H3>
<B>Editor:</B> David Robie, Lecturer in Journalism, UPNG.<BR>
<B>Advisers:</B>Associate Professor Wendy Bacon, Head of of the Department of Social Analysis and Journalism, University of Technology, Sydney<BR>
Philip Cass, Lecturer in Journalism, University of the South Pacific, Suva<BR>
Peter Cronau, Editorial Director, Australian Centre for Independent Journalism, UTS<BR>
Rhonda Eva, Head of SPCenCIID, UPNG<BR>
Dr John Evans, Development Manager, University of PNG Press<BR>
William Ferea, Lecturer in Philosophy and Journalism, UPNG<BR>
Ekonia Peni, Senior Journalist, National Broadcasting Commission, PNG<BR>
Alan Robson, Lecturer in Politics, UPNG<BR>
Sorariba Nash, Lecturer in Journalism, UPNG<BR>
Neville Togarewa, Senior Journalist, <I>PNG Post-Courier</I>
<P>
<B>Details:</B> ISSN 1023 9499. 150 mm x 230 mm. Illustrated. <A HREF="author.html">Index</A> by author. <A HREF="subs.html">Subscriptions: </A>Development Manager, University of Papua New Guinea Press, Unisearch PNG Ltd, PO Box 320, University Post Office, National Capital District, Papua New Guinea.  Fax: (675) 326 0127. <P>
Editorial inquiries to the Editor: <A HREF="MAILTO:David.Robie@uts.edu.au">David Robie</A><P>
<P>
Copyright  1996 <B>Pacific Journalism Review, </B> SPCenCIID and the contributors. <BR>
<P>
</table>
