<CENTER><TABLE COLSPEC="L20" BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=3 CELLSPACING=2>
<TR><TD>
<Font size=3><B>We hope to soon have an interactive "toktok" page in partnership with Pactok. Watch this space. A selection of recent letters are presented here.</B>
<P>
8 December 1996
<H3>GREAT SERVICE</H3>
David, thanks for the great service that you do here. Enjoy the holidays.
<P>
Charlie Scheiner<BR>
[East Timor Network]<BR>
<A HREF="MAILTO:cscheiner@igc.apc.org">cscheiner@igc.apc.org</A><BR>
<A HREF="MAILTO:timor-info@igc.apc.org">timor-info@igc.apc.org</A>
<P>
7 December 1996
<H3>WONDERFUL NIUS</H3>
David, thanks for your websites. <A HREF="http://www.pactok.net.au/docs/nius/">Niugini Nius</A> is wonderful.  I am currently working as technical editor on one of the largest computer titles over here [in the UK], and to be able to read even a couple of stories a day from PNG is fantastic for keeping in touch with what's going on, and dreaming of how of get back out there.  Keep up the good work, and if you need any PC software let me know.  I can't promise anything, and it may take some time to come through, but it may be worth a try. 
<P>
Matthew Loney<BR>
Ex-editor<BR>
Eastern Star, Alotau<BR>
<A HREF="MAILTO:Matthew_Loney@zd.com">Matthew_Loney@zd.com</A>
<P>
PS. If you see Eric Tapakau (from Alotau) please say hello from me, and tell him that I'm
trying to find the Sex Pistols CD and T-Shirt that he wanted.
<P>
8 November 1996
<H3>MICROPICK AWARD</H3> 
<IMG SRC="../images/micropick.gif">David, thanks for Cafe Pacific and your fine work!  We have awarded you a MicroPick for content.
<P>
Best regards,
<P>
Mitch Leventhal, Ph.D<BR>
<A HREF="MAILTO:mitchlev@microstate.com">mitchlev@microstate.com</A><BR>
<A HREF="http://microstate.com">The Microstate Network</A>
<P>
6 November 1996
<H3>KANAK WEBSITE?</H3>
<Font size=3>Aloha, I teach 20th century Pacific Islands history here at the University of Hawaii (I have used <A HREF="david_books.html">Blood on Their Banner</A> as a text), and I have been searching for a reliable, up-to-date source of news on events in Kanaky/New Caledonia. Radio Australia covers it sporadically, and Tahiti-Pacifique is predictably superficial. Could you suggest a site? 
<P>
I am especially interested in hearing whether it is true that last April, the French Premier told delegates from Kanaky that independence was no longer an option, apparently abrogating the Matignon Accords and the whole rationale for the 1998 vote. I have heard via the French version of Radio Australia news that the RDO (Sako's mainly Wallisian party) has come out in favor of "association" as a compromise step toward further sovereignty. Do you know about this? Our library normally subscribes to Les Nouvelles Caledoniennes, a mediocre source of news at best, but the university is having a budget crisis, so we have received no issues this year. 
<P>
Thanks for any assistance (or leads) you may have the time to provide me.
<P>
Sincerely, David A. Chappell<BR>
University of Hawai'i<BR>
<A HREF="MAILTO:dchappel@hawaii.edu">dchappel@hawaii.edu</A>
<BR><LI><I>Unfortunately, the Kanaks don't seem to have seized on the Web opportunities in the way that the Bougainville and East Timor movements have. I've networked your letter seeking helpful responses. Why not try <A HREF="http://www.hookele.com/paclink/index.html">http://www.hookele.com/paclink/index.html</A> -- The Pacific Link -- a new activist website?</I>
<P>
31 October 1996
<H3>RURAL VANUATU PAGE</H3>
David Robie -
I've just had a look at your site, including the Pacific Links page. 
I see you have a link to Kiaman Buluk's site about Port Vila Vanuatu. 
You might want to have a look at my site (http://www.silk.net/personal/scombs/vanuatu.html - "Vanuatu - A Canadian's Perspective") about rural Vanuatu to complement Kiaman's. It's a collection of things I've written about rural Vanuatu after living and working on an outer island (Malekula) for two years and in Vila for another three years.  Even while living in Vila, my work as Vanuatu's first Regional Development Planning Adviser continued to take me throughout the islands.  If you find the site suitable, you might want to add a link to it.
<P>  
Your site is well organized, good quality, and a welcome change from the tourism-oriented Pacific sites on the web.
<P>
Stan Combs<BR>
<A HREF="MAILTO:scombs@silk.net">scombs@silk.net</A><BR>        
<A HREF="http://www.silk.net/personal/scombs/vanuatu.html">Vanuatu - A Canadian's Perspective</A><BR>
<LI><I>Done. Thanks.</I>
<P> 
31 October 1996
<H3>INFORMATIVE PAGE</H3>
<Font size=3>Liked your Home page very much. Very informative. I have printed some images so that Margaret Obi, who is speaking at UNSW today, can have some illustrative material and I can use these images in the future.
<P>
Is there any statement on Information Technology policy in PNG? For a country so large (and potentially wealthy), it seems poorly served.
How is Pactok progressing? 
<P>
In the meantime, people such as yourself continue to provide excellent
sources. I will look into your Library for any IT stories.
<P> 
Thanks, Grant McCall<BR>
Centre for South Pacific Studies<BR>
The University of New South Wales<BR>
<A HREF="MAILTO:g.mccall@unsw.edu.au">g.mccall@unsw.edu.au</A>
<P> 
19 October 1996
<H3>FANTASTIC LINK</H3>
Dear David, Thanks for the link to Cafe Pacific it looks fantastic. I wrote to your other page editor, with an idea I had about the future of Pacific Media sites and their relation to the South Pacific Information Network. What I thought might be an idea, is to put a site (with standard links to all yours and other Pacific Media outlets - with perhaps gif images of the websites for people to click onto. However, this would be just a sideline to the main purpose of the site. It would take a little bit of work on all our behalfs, but in the end would allow a fantastic resource to be developed which would bring all the news stories from around the region together in the one place, while at the same time keeping your own independence and news resources. 
<P>
However what would be great in this scenario, would be that not only would stories be archived, but people could do searches on particular areas they are interested in and get online results very quickly. What I am proposing is to develop a site similar to the SPIN calendar of events, while keeping the calendar format, it would have completely different fields. What I propose is that fields such as News Headline, Author and brief summary (perhaps keywords) be entered when a story hits your pages. 
<P>
Regards and Best Wishes,<BR>
'Alopi Sione Latukefu South Pacific Economic and Social Database<BR>
Australian National University.<BR>
<A HREF="MAILTO:Alopi.Latukefu@ncds.anu.edu.au">Alopi.Latukefu@ncds.anu.edu.au</A><BR>
<LI><I>Great idea, we'll work with that.</I>

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
