<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Do Asian news values deny freedom of expression?</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Do Asian news values deny<BR>
 freedom of expression?</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html#LOCSIN">Teodoro L. Locsin</A>. Publisher and editor in chief of Today and executive editor of the Philippines Free Press</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
This speech may have come too late. The notion of Asian values has already taken quite a beating lately. But the views echoed by CNN regarding James Riady's contribution to the Clinton campaign show we still need a few more nails on the coffin of Asian values.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Evidently speaking only with billionaire Chinese, CNN reported that Chinese in Hong Kong are wondering: Why all the fuss? William Overholt of Bankers Trust in Hong Kong dismissed the contributions as "pin money to these guys." But of course. The Cali cartel would think the same.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The Far Eastern Economic Review quoted an Indonesian businessman, Sofyan Wanandi: "I think we are all surprised, including the Riadys, by the [adverse] American reaction. Making such donations in Indonesia is very common." 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Common to whom, and who was surprised?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
As an Asian, I'll tell you what's common in Asia: Asian businessmen acting surprised and innocent when caught in the act of bribery and tax evasion. The ordinary Asian knows bribery is wrong, and common sense, says Jim Mann of the LA. Times, demands to know: If giving favours is an Asian custom, why is it only to people in high places? Evidently because the favour is expected to be returned. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
And Ian Buruma, in the 50th anniversary issue of Time Asia asked, "If democratic values are so uncongenial to Asians, why then did Asians from Rangoon to Seoul, from Manila to Beijing, demand them?" These smart questions were long overdue.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
But what really hurt so-called Asian values has been the flat rejection of them by the very peoples on whose behalf they were invoked, and whose real aspirations they seek to cancel.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In the past five years, quintessentially Asian societies  have taken the strongest stand for the most basic Western values: decency in the treatment of fellowmen, honesty in the conduct of government, accountability for official wrongs, rendering justice...
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Japan ousted prime ministers for such characteristically Asian behaviour of men in power as taking money from Lockheed and having fun with good-time girls.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
India is intent on punishing its ex-prime minister in this life according to a criminal code, and not in succeeding ones by the laws of karma.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Burma's military rulers are held in check by one woman who stands above them on a single democratic election many years ago.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
And Malaysia, despite its advocacy of Asian values, fired the trade minister who brazenly declared that kickbacks are integral to doing business in her country.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I refer you to China, which shoots corrupt government officials in the perverse tribute that a vice-riddled government pays to the Western virtue of honesty in the public service.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Korea put two presidents on trial, condemning one to death and the other to life in prison, for tyranny and corruption. Transgressions not so severely punished in the West since the execution of Charles I and the impeachment of Warren Hastings.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I speak of Pakistan, which threw out a military government in the name of democracy and is now celebrating the ouster of its democratically elected ruler for nepotism and corruption. And the new Pakistan government has imposed austere Calvinist restrictions on official privileges that, one might argue, conflict with the opulence traditionally associated with the Orient. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
What are these Asian values that time and action have exposed as hollow? You will not find a definitive list. For that is their marked characteristic: elusiveness to the understanding but readiness to come to the defence of official Asian abuses.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#top">Return to top</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="locsin02.html">Next section</A> ] 
</CENTER></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
