<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: One</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: One</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Teodoro L. Locsin.</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>(Reply to unrecorded question)</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
When the  in covering the Timorese problem, it's true, our reporters and editors will simply say that Indonesia's actions towards Timor is like this and that is basically to suppress the Timorese Freedom Movement. That's because we find it very hard as journalists to penetrate Indonesia and find out if in fact the people there have any opinion of the Timor problem. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
We're very well aware that since the issue is not even raised by the Indonesian government with their own people it's just the army acting on its own, and we don't have the kind of freedom of speech, we're really in a quandary. Are we to assume that silence gives consent and that all Indonesians agree with it? But to give, to make, silence give consent you should at least know what you are consenting to by your quietude. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
There are also real problems: to what extent Indonesians feel very strongly about their territorial claim, and I can understand as a Filipino how territory becomes very strong emotional issue (we have our claims to Saba of course).
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 1</B><BR>
I just wanted to ask one of the issues you didn't speak of, or I don't think you referred it, was the issue of self censorship if you're a journalist operating in one of the Asian, in some of the Asian countries. That seems to be very strong. how difficult is it to cross that border of self-censorship which sometimes becomes really the only obstacle: the government doesn't have to go any further than just creating this status quo, and the journalists will already begin to self censor.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Theodore Locsin</B><BR>
I've never been a foreign journalist, I've never taken the risks they take. I understand in places like Burma you really have to exercise self-censorship to get out of the country. But there was one I don't know if it qualifies, you can tell me if it's irrelevant when the issue of Ramos Horta entering the Philippines and offending Suharto came up, as a Filipino and as a journalist with very strong liberal feelings, I was of course in favour of Ramos Horta entering. But also as a Filipino who knows that the Indonesian military, the Indonesian government in the Philippines have for some reason I cannot fathom, always had very close cooperation. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The Indonesians have never taken advantage of our weakness, they did not take part in the Moslem secessionist rebellion. In fact, they guarded our southern borders. They did not train our military to suppress dissent. I must say that some of our officers went to army school in the United States and learnt some methods of interrogation there, but oddly enough, the officers, the Filipino officers who studied in Indonesia are our most professional officers. And they only confine themselves in the field of battle. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
So, when I had to do an editorial, one of my editorial writers wrote a very strong editorial against the government for banning Ramos Horta because it makes us like the Indonesians, then he was absent the next day and I had to write the next editorial. I had to be true to myself and I realised that, I gave an editorial that had everyone scratching their heads and wondering if, you know, there was schizophrenia in the office [laughter]. I really didn't know how to handle it, frankly. There was of course a cop-out by saying 'let him come after the APEC.' I cannot say that I resolved it satisfactorily.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 2. Jefferson Lee</B><BR>
On this issue, could, I don't know how thoroughly you read Australian newspapers, but one could take the somewhat schizophrenic editorial in the Australian newspaper this morning, which defends the Malaysian government's, and justifies, the Malaysian government's expulsion of people who are trying to have a peaceful conference just to discuss the East Timor issue, but then in the defence of that editorial it comes out towards the end and says however the reality of bilateral relationships within ASEAN means that such freedoms will not be tolerated and this is regrettable. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
My question is: In terms of Australia, which perceives itself as having perhaps as liberal and free and diverse media opinions as anywhere in the region except for perhaps the Philippines, do you think these attempts to defend Asian solidarity or Asian values or censorship within Asia an attempt to grovel and cajole on the one hand, or an attempt to be diplomatically nice to other countries in a sense, or do you think it's an attempt to invoke the same sort of censorship here in Australia that exists elsewhere in the region?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Theodore Locsin</B><BR>
Again, in the position I found myself in I can't be self-righteous here. But I think that in a situation like that Malaysians Filipinos were the ones actually who were thrown out 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 2. Jefferson Lee</B><BR>
The question is about Australian media values ... using Asian values to suppress ...
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Theodore Locsin</B><BR> 
The only thing I could say is that if your values are liberal and you are a journalist and you can only function under liberal values, then I would defend those values and I would judge Malaysian behaviour according to those values and say 'this is wrong'. I'm certain you are going to pick up the values of a dictatorship and import them here and say they're right. That was the position we took in the case of the Sy..., where they hanged that maid. I said well, that's fine. If the Singaporeans insist on rushing to judgment and stringing up that woman, let them do what they feel like. But what we have the power to do is to make Singaporeans extremely uncomfortable and unwelcome in our country because we are a democracy. And that we should insult them every day if we have to in our papers, which is what we did. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now they can do what they want on their end in fact they were insulting us in their papers but I have no obligation to repeat their insults or repeat their position on my side and say it's right. Because I happen to believe that there are absolute values. It's part of my profession. I have to believe there is a right and a wrong. A fact and a falsehood. That's the best I can do.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
