<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Training Journalists for the Newpaper Business</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Training Journalists for the Newpaper Business</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B><A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html#ARASU">Siva Arasu</A>. Head, Editorial Training Unit, Singapore Press Holdings.</B></FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>[the beginning of Siva Arasu's speech is completely off mike and not audible. Picks up half way through a sentence]</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
. . . liberty, freedom, democracy: they're wonderful ideals and I don't think anyone in this room here would deny that. But, coming from Singapore, all I can say is I can give you the Singapore perspective. And the title of my paper is essentially 'Journalism, time to cheer' and while I do not wish to deny anyone the right to hold on to what they see as the absolute truth, all I want to say is, what I say here is essentially what I see to be my truth. Before I go into my paper I would like to thank the Australian government for inviting my company, Singapore Press Holdings, to take part in this conference. My company published all the newspapers in Singapore and almost all the magazines. Our main paper is theStraits Times. It's my great pleasure to be here. Everyone I've met has been warm, wonderful, despite the current debate that's now raging in Australia. I won't go into the debate except to say that just before I left the Straits Times reported that Singaporeans buying holiday packages to Australia is up 10 per cent [laugh]. That's the good news. Now the not-so-good news for Australia is: will the Singapore government let the Special Broadcasting Service off the hook for implying, in its TV show 'Dateline', that Singapore had links with the druglord through its investments in Mienma. Maybe, but not likely. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The Singapore government is famous (or notorious, depending on which side you're on) for being relentless for forcing the media to correct any perception it creates which the government sees as wrong. It has taken action against several publications in the last nine years: the Asian Wall Street Journal, Far Eastern Economic Review; Time Magazine, and others. Some have been sued for hundreds of thousands of dollars, others have had their circulation restricted, cut back to only a fraction of their sales. In addition, these restricted copied can be distributed only if they do not carry any ads. You see the Singapore government believes commercial considerations rule journalism as in any other business. Is it right? The record shows that today many news organisations accept its demand for a right of reply, without any editing of its reply. But this tough and uncompromising attitude is not a recent phenomenon. It has a long history and it can be traced essentially to two momentous events in Singapore's media history. The first one happened 35 years ago. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
It was a time of great turbulence in Singapore. The editor-in-chief of the Straits Times was a gentleman called Lesley Hoffman. He and Mr Li Quan Yu - I don't think I need to tell you who Li Quan Yu is - were embroiled in a very public row. Mr Li was then the leader of the People's Action Party and he was trying to get into power. He also wanted a then Federation of Malaya to take us in as a member state. The Straits Times, Mr Li felt, was not helping his cause. So on May 18, 1959, he issued a warning. He would lock up any newsman who caused a strain in the relationship between Singapore and Malaya. Four days later the editor-in-chief of the Straits Times Lesley Hoffman, wrote a stinging page one editorial against Li. In bold headlines he said 'Bird of passage, I stay', he declared. A fortnight later, Li Quan yu's People's Action Party was elected into power in Singapore. Hoffman left immediately for Kuala Lumpar. The Straits Times for the first time is in its111 year history was published outside Singapore, in Kuala Lumpar. This went on until 1965 when Singapore left Malaysia and became independent. The paper was split. The Straits Times returned to  Singapore and Malaysia had the New Straits Times. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
This 1959 row was described in great detail by Mr Li in a newspaper interview he gave two years ago. He said in his interview, 'I said to Hoffman, "Look, I'm putting my life at stake. If I lose and the communists win I am in real trouble. You are sitting on the sidelines tapping away on your typewriter. What gives you this God-given right? Who gave you this right? I am seeking this right, and when I get in, I'm going to tell you how you should not run your paper. I won that right," he said.' The Straits Times paid dearly for that bad judgment. It took a long time for the hostility and suspicion which the pioneer PAP  leaders had felt towards the Straits Times and newsmen to dissipate. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now, more than 30 years later, ironically the Straits Times is often jeered for being so much of the PAP establishment. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The other event took place in the 70s. Two newspapers closed down because the PAP government said, they have allowed foreign interest to use their pages to stir up the ground because Singapore was doing too well. On May 14 1971 the Eastern Sunclosed down. It could not go on because its senior editorial team had resigned after Li Quan Yu accused it of being involved in a black operation in Singapore. He also said the paper had received $4 mill from Chinese communist agents in Hong Kong. The papers' chairman was Datin Okow who lived in Hong Kong. Now, five days later a second paper, also in English, the Singapore Herald, said it needed $4.5 mill to keep on going. Again, the backer of this paper was from Hong Kong, Ms Oshien. She said she would not be pumping any more money into the paper. She had already spent half a million dollars on it. Eight days later the Singapore Heraldclosed down. In two weeks Singapore went from having three English newspapers to one English newspaper in the morning market.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
These two events had a tremendous impact not only on journalism in Singapore but on journalists especially. Mr Li Quan Yu made good his word. He made it clear that the First Amendment, right to freedom of the press, has no place in Singapore. Singapore's constitutional right to freedom of speech and expression is subject to certain restrictions. What does it mean for journalists? What it means is, you have a role to play but you have to stay out of partisan role in active politics. At the same time you need to go beyond plain reporting. You have to shape public opinion to help build up a national consensus on important issues. So daily, in producing our papers, we walk a tightrope. Doing a constant balancing act between serving our readers, giving then what we think they want and what they should have, and serving the national interest. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#top">Return to top</A> ] 
