<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reporting Business in South-East Asia</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Reporting Business in South-East Asia</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html#MENZIES">Hugh D. Menzies</A>, consulting international  business journalist with a special interest in the Asia Pacific region, New York.</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Good morning.  I probably should give you a little personal background so
you know where my remarks are coming from.  I'm Australian by birth and
citizenship but spent a number of my formative years in Asia, where my
Trade Commissioner father helped rebuild Australian trade with Japan after
World War II and restart her trade with China during a meeting with Premier
Chou en lai in early 1956.   In 1961, I moved to New York and have
practised business journalism for most of the time since, writing and editing
for the likes of The New York Times, Business Week, Fortune, and
International Business magazine.  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Based as so much of it is on the eastern seaboard of the U.S., most notably
in New York, the American media still tends to an Atlantic bias in its
coverage.  At Business Week and International Business, in particular, I
successfully pushed for increased coverage of the Pacific Rim, including
Australia.  If you think that was a snap, should note that until every recently
most  Americans thought Australia was a small country in the middle of
Europe and, with the obvious exception of Vietnam, knew even less about
Southeast Asia.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
So I'm what you might call a reasonably  informed and very interested
outsider.  It is from that perspective my remarks are made. Other speakers
will give you far more specific and informed information about operating
within the region.  But on the theory that those who are close to the forest
sometimes cannot see if for the trees, I'll have a crack at describing the
forest from a distance
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
When I began practising business journalism in the mid-1960s, it was still
very much a back of the book activity.  Politics and social issues dominated
the front pages.  Even sports got better play than business news.  The Wall
Street Journal was still very much a trade paper.  Business Week, Forbes,
and Fortune were largely trade magazines.  TV covered business not at all. 
The vital issues of the day were The Cold War abroad and Civil Rights at
home.   And this in the country where it was said "the business of America is
business."
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The picture was even bleaker abroad, save for the Financial Times of
London and a couple of magazines like the Economist and the Far East
Economic Review.  Take Australia, a nation where business news gets
more coverage than most places.  In 1970, I returned home for the first time
in 12 years and was bowled over by vitality of Sydney, in particular. A mining
boom was in full swing, corporate asset stripping was all the rage, the
business scene was even more exciting than New York.  Besides Sydney
was drop-dead gorgeous.  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
A man could live here, I thought, and started talking to executives in the
media about starting a business magazine along the lines of Business
Week, for whom I then labored.   No, they said, not enough interest.  The
Financial Review meets the necessary demand. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
This story was much the same elsewhere. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#top">Return to top</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="menzies02.html">Next section</A> ]</CENTER></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
