<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Two</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Siva Arasu, Hugh D. Menzies, Brian Toohey.</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>(Answer to unrecorded question)</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Other speaker</B><BR>
I'd just add that in mirroring that there are more sides to that story. A significant number of journalists in the west don't like drawing attention to the intellectual property breaches in China because they're part of the geopolitical school espoused by people like, say, Henry Kissinger. 'Don't play these stories up because it'll ruin the overall relationship with China,' and the overall relationship with China is more important than some fuss over intellectual property rights. And I have vested interests in this in case one day my writing or singing or performing [laughter] is stolen by Chinese state media [laughter]. I think even on that issue there's nothing like a uniform western media approach in which only the business interests of particular western companies is being promoted.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Speaker 1</B><BR>
I think just to comment on that, I think that's true but I think the media's so diverse that the story gets out regardless of who wants to control it, the Realpolitik of: one group is trying to play it down, some other group picks it up, and everything is so competitive that finally you're forced to go with it if it's a real story. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question 1 John Tebbutt</B><BR> 
From stories that don't get covered to stories that plan to be covered ad nauseam, I'd like to just to take up on your comment on the conflicts of east and west values -the way that you've out it Brian -and ask if you've had any thoughts about how the Pauline Hansen issue has developed in Australia and the role that was identified for the media within that, and the very active role that was taken in dampening down the story, as many people in a range of areas from broadcasters and politicians and also other media took up that call in some way. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
For me it's been one of the first times that kind of public diplomacy aspect has really come out in a very public way. And I'm wondering if you have any comments about how national interests develop in Australia around stories like that.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Brian Toohey </B><BR>
I should by the way somehow or other orally put the phrase 'Asian values' in a quotation marks, I'm not suggesting ... I think there's a separate section in this conference about it. I'm not saying every Asian country reflects Asian values sort of summed up from the Singapore School or Le Puan Yu's version of Confucianism in which the ruled have to obey the rulers and the rulers have seemingly no obligations to the ruled. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
But in relation to the Pauline Hansen thing, there's certainly been a lot of talk -including talk from the main speaker last night at the dinner -that the media has some sort of obligation to dampen down that story because it'll harm Australias trade interests in Asia. But equally I think the media recognised that it wasn't simply Pauline Hansen speaking, she was in fact representing a significant viewpoint within Australia (if you can believe the opinion poll surveys) and that it'd be very foolish of the media to ignore the sort of attitudes that she was reflecting. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I certainly agree that there's been considerable suggestions that the media should down play this etc, but if they were to do so I think they would be ignoring a significant development in Australian politics.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
