<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsagency Reporting</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER>
<B><FONT SIZE="+2">Newsagency Reporting</FONT></B>
</CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html#O'LOUGHLIN">Peter O'Loughlin</A>, Bureau Chief, Associated Press</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Good afternoon. I have been asked to speak about the globalisation of international news services. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Well this is nothing new. It has been going on a for a long time ever since my own organisation, The Associated Press (AP) was founded in 1848 when six New York newspapers got together to share the cost of covering out of town news. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
At that time the newly invented telegraph had increased the speed and volume of news coverage in America, but foreign news remained a problem.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In those days before the transatlantic telegraph cable was laid, news from Europe was gathered from ships arriving at Halifax Nova scotia, their first land fall in America.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In 1849 Daniel Craig became APs first foreign correspondent sending news gathered from the steam ships at Halifax to Boston and New York, first by carrier pigeon and pony express and later by wire as telegraph lines extended north.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In 1851 AP opened its first bureaus in Washington and Albany, New York. When the telegraph cable was laid to London AP opened a bureau there.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In 1875 AP established the first leased wire dedicated exclusively to news transmission, linking New York and Washington and carrying up to 20,000 words a day.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Expansion then as now, followed improved communications.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Today, The Associated Press has 1,786 member newspapers in the United States, and 6,000 broadcast/tv outlets. It has 8,500 subscribers outside the U.S. It has 236 bureaus world wide, including 93 international bureaus and 3,500 employees. Our news goes out in 5 languages.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
AP remains a not for profit cooperative of the member newspapers who pay for their news and photo on a formula based on their circulations.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
AP has moved from hand written dispatches, carrier pigeons, to morse code, the first leased telegraph service, photo transmission by wire, then to satellite, digital delivery, radio, television and now the internet. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
AP coverage of The presidential elections last week went on the Internet as a multi-media package of text, graphics, photos, audio and video.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Although AP and its competitors had bureaus around the world before world war 11, coverage was restricted by the communications available, and the cost.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
International telephone calls were rare and expensive. Cables were charged by the word, which led to an abbreviated form of writing called cablese as a cost saving measure.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
