<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Three</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Three</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Peter O'Loughlin, Zainoor Sulaiman.</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>(Last part of answer to unrecorded question)</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
. . . the younger journalists coming through have grown up with computers in journalism schools and are seriously into the technology, often ahead of AP. They buy their own gear and a lot of them have been on Internet since it began. It's just impossible to function without it. If we introduce new software or new hardware, we run training programs to make sure everybody's up to speed on it. But technology is journalism these days. It's the same as, in the past, journalists could get away with the typewriter -could still get away with two finger typing on a computer -but I know journalists who've never seen a typewriter. So the technology is here and it's been here a long time. We introduced computers in 1982. So it's no mystery, and it's an integral part of journalism and should be an integral part of journalism training.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 1 Peter Hutchings</B><BR>
 My name's Peter Hutchings, I teach at the University of Western Sydney at Hawkesbury, in Humanities. I have a question which in a way picks up on some of the issues raised this morning. And I think both of your address of agency technologies talks to this. There seems to be an interesting conflict or potential conflict between the business of news and news values that you've got -I realise there's a different between agency and normal journalism in a certain way -but the emphasis on processing product for clients at higher and higher rates, together with some of the things we heard this morning about the dominant importance of journalism as an economic enterprise. I'm wondering where the content question comes into this and where content questions starts to rub up against that primary speed-of-processing/ business-oriented aspect of contemporary media goes.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Zainoa Sulaiman</B><BR> 
The exact reason why I think even for the ..., even for a writer to go into the business side to support the normal news operation. I'm not sure whether AP might agree, but without the other business we're talking about we cannot sustain. So in order to practice the normal news operations we need the support from the other news writing [Reuter???] business. Otherwise on news -as I explained earlier -if you go direct just the news, and hope to sell news just as news without, you know, repackaging as information, then I don't think we can survive. That's as simple as that.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Peter O'Loughlin</B><BR>  
I'd agree with that, but also -I'm not quite sure where you're coming from: are you suggesting that by increasing financial business coverage that we're in some way jeopardising the integrity of the news report? I mean, what's the point?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 1 Peter Hutchings</B><BR> 
I'm thinking of the way in which the emphasis on news production as a business may lead to the displacement of other kinds of values within news production . . . This morning . . . two of them spoke very much about how important business was, in the context of this region, how certain news decisions should be made with respect to larger national economic imperatives, and my question was sort of picking up in the context of a business where providing information is your business; where there's potential for conflict between other kinds of values to do with news media and the production of a product (which also happens to be news) -whether there may be conflict there. Whether that question of content, which you said you could talk about, would address those sorts of questions.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>O'Loughlin</B><BR>  
Could you give an example? You're being a bit vague with words like 'values' and things. Could you give us an example.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 1 Peter Hutchings</B><BR> 
Well, in a way what I've got in mind is the very fact that we can speak about the importance of the business of journalism, the economic importance of journalism as it was spoken about this morning, and the economic importance of journalism is considered to be a universal value. The fact that all news production corporations are corporations is considered universal, unarguable, but questions about journalistic integrity, responsibility for telling all the news, are seen to somehow be local values. and not universal values.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>O'Loughlin</B><BR>   
No, I . . . well, you do get local changes, some countries have different cultural histories that don't include a whole history of 400 years of print journalism, as everybody would know. But an organisation like my own, and that's the only one I can speak for, would see absolutely no difference between the way it would treat a business story or it would treat a general news story. It has to be done, it's got to be credible, and it's got to be true. And I don't see that there's any conflict at all. But in the end result news is a business, and that's why newspapers are in the business of news. And the number of newspapers is shrinking, the market for the news that providers like Bnahma and AP and Reuters and the other in the newspaper field, is shrinking. So, you have to find other sources of revenue. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
So, you diversify into things like television, audio -we've got I think 600 audio stations in the States that take the audio services we provide - and this is what we call 'non-traditional AP business'. Traditional is text, non-tradition is the other. And the revenue that we're getting from that side of the business is increasing, because it's replacing the revenue we're losing on the print side. So there is a conflict in that I suppose if you see it that way, but we wouldn't sacrifice the integrity of the news report, whether it's financial or the other, simply for the buck. And I don't think too many others would either.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#top">Return to top</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="session-three02.html">Next section</A> ] 
</CENTER></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
