<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Un-Western Perspectives on News</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Un-Western Perspectives on News </FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html#DIXIT">Kunda Dixit, Regional Director, Inter Press Service Asia-Pacific</A></FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In the county of Fairfax outside Washington DC, the cable TV system carries 120 channels to every home. There are three weather channels, the incoming and departures at Dulles Airport nearby and even a channel that divides up the screen into four parts and shows all four national networks simultaneously. Flying at 35,000 feet above Vietnam, yiou can now watch breaking news on teletype on your personal video screen: there has just been a fire in the Channel Tunnel.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Welcome to the peek-a-boo world of modern electronic media: a virtual universe of round-the-clock music, non-stop news as it happens, day-and-night movies and hourly weather micro-forecasts. In this "empty-v" age it is becoming increasingly difficult to tell the difference between a soap opera and a courtroom drama happening that instant on the other side of the world. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
And as it shrouds the world in a fog of uniformity, television's globalness casts a dark shadow over fragile cultures that cling to the edge of time. This new global civilisation as propagated by flashy multinational broadcasting is a juggernaut tearing through diversity, squishing native wisdom into a flattened gray mass.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Information, or what editors in newsrooms in Atlanta or London decide is worthwile for the world to know, is mixed up with amusement to be beamed to all corners of the globe. This is not just the "end of history", it is the end of geography. No place is too near or too far. Distance disappears, and if the line between real and unreal gets blurred, the defect is not in your set. When you can switch from genocide in Rwanda to Natural Born Killers on HBO at the flick of a remote, where does voyeurism end and escapism begin? The bluish aura of the cathode rays have hypnotised the world into a consumerist, free market, materialistic trance.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Even if channel surfing viewers can find a news bulletin amidst all the background radiation of talk shows, mini series and sports and then stay tuned long enough to inform themselves about what is really happening in the world around them, audio visual news is becoming less and less real.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The home screen is the world's new reality check. Whatever falls beyond the penumbra of its narrow beam does not exist. If an event has not happened on television news, it has not happened--a government falling in Togo hasn't fallen if there isn't a camera there to record it. And unless it is a "slow news day" not much else besides Bosnia, Chechnya or the Olympics actually "happen". The rest of the media, radio and newspapers, take their cue from television. It used to be the other way around. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Infotainment is a commodity, and today's news coverage reflects market forces and the desire of media moghuls to rule the airwaves. The public service role of media is being usurped by businesses for whom the definition of news is very simple: news has to sell, otherwise it is not news. Media companies have therefore become answerable to shareholders, and not to the public interest.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Media globalisation has meant media "gobble-isation". It is not a coincidence that news businesses are being taken over by conglomerates that also own entertainment empires. Disney owns ABC, Time-Warner has bought CNN. News networks are owned by corporations that also own cartoon channels and vast archives of Holywood films. What it means is that fewer and fewer people control the information we get. These few people, then, are setting the agenda for the rest of us--how we should behave, what we should buy, which credit card we must use, what we should wear, what movies we can't afford to miss, what we should eat, what we must smoke. They are telling us Saddam Hussain is a crook, free trade is good, it is OK for five percent of the world's population to consume half its resources. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#top">Return to top</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="dixit02.html">Next section</A> ] 
</CENTER></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
