<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsagencies in Transition</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Newsagencies in Transition</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html#TAPTIM">Tulsathit Taptim</A>, Deputy Editor, The Bangkok Nation.
</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
It's a great honour to have a chance to share my experience with you. I'd like to thank our host for giving us this opportunity.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
Before I came here, I asked myself a couple of basic questions. Regionwise, what actually is our newspaper's selling point? What real difference has The Nation made?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I realised that these seemingly simple questions are not that easy to answer. After all, journalists elsewhere are doing the same things that we have been doing. Searching for truth, attacking bad governments, fighting for people who suffer and so on.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
I have to confess that I have not discovered the exact answers to my own questions. But possible clues may lie in our attitude and policy, which I would like to talk about at this conference.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
The Nation has been serving as a forum for people who cannot freely write, speak and express their straightforward opinions in their own countries. This role was adopted partly because of our geography. Thailand is surrounded by Burma, Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos. Those countries are either under totally repressive regimes or experiencing fledgling freedom. As their closest neighbours, we consider it our responsibility to bring to the world their political, economic and social developments, as well as the voices that are locally muffled.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
For example, Aung San Suu Kyi has been writing for our publication. Her contributions - which touch upon a wide range of topics - have been steady even during recent threats and occasional clampdowns by the junta. We are a channel through which this brave woman has communicated with the outside world.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
Burmese in exile have also had their voices heard through The Nation. Our stand on Burma has always clashed with Asean's official policy. But our attitude on this is uncompromising. The term "neighbour" doesn't mean the neighbouring government, but the neighbouring people. And if the neighbouring people are suffering, we will do as much as we can to help them.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br> 	
We would like to do more for the people of Burma, but, unfortunately, all of our journalists have been banned from that country.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
One Asean journalist who is ostracised in his own country is serving as our correspondent. His reports and views have been constantly published by our newspaper.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
Apart from Burma, our stand on East Timor has been a subject of government criticism. I admit that sometimes we get too emotional. But there is definitely no such thing as a conspiracy. As an English language newspaper which can reach out beyond the Thai border, what we do is to act as a voice of people who badly need it, who have resorted to peaceful means in their struggle.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
East Timor Nobel peace prize laureate Jose Ramos-Horta and dissident Indonesian academic George Aditjondro, now exiled in Australia, have been contributors to The Nation.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
