<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Four</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Four</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Kunda Dixit, Tulsathit Taptim. Section One</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 1. Annamaria Anton.</B> <BR>
I'd like to address a question to Kunda Dixit. My name's Annamaria Anton, freelance journalist. Yesterday after various presentations it seems apparent that the economic imperatives of newsmaking, helped along by increasing global technology, is gaining ground over the higher ideals of the craft of journalism. How confident is IPS as a news media organisation, from a business point of view, that it will still continue to have a market out there, that there will be buyers of its alternative news products?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Kunda Dixit</B> <BR>
It's the best time to be in the business of alternative journalism, because so much of it is mainstream. If you can fill that niche and fill it well, professionally, credibly, in an original fashion, then the people will subscribe, as we have found in the Asia-Pacific in the last ten years that we've started out from zero. We're now -we used - fairly widespread. In fact, we've stopped calling ourselves alternative news. And the dividing line between alternative and not alternative is crumbling. One of our best clients is The Nation, and I think our philosophy is very similar: how do you have a point-of-view journalism without sacrificing credibility. And I think both The Nation and IPS are doing it very well. That's our best selling point.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Q.1 AA</B><BR>
Just to get a much more idea of the sort of selling potential as well by IPS news wire source: say, compared to AAP and Reuter. Can you talk a little bit about how much main media organisation in Asia -print, radio and electronic media -that use IPS? besides Thailand?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Kunda Dixit</B><BR>
Nowadays it's not really enough to say how many media clients you have, because through the internet you know, who knows? Anyone with a phone and a PC can log in and read your stuff. You don't know. In fact it's becoming a problem in selling. But the new technology has given us much more access to, made it cheaper, to deliver our news. The reason we were outpriced by the big boys was that we could not afford to sell our service through the teleprinter networks, which are very expensive. Now the cost of delivery is almost zero. And so we just have to add the price of the product and shoot it off to your client. And also it's become much easier to automatically categorise what your client needs. If someone needs only human rights, they get only human rights; they need environment, Asia Pacific, they get only environment, Asia Pacific. So yeah, the technology has made it much more possible to sell alternative news than before. We have about 40 to 45 clients in the region. Worldwide about 1500, media clients. But non-media? who knows.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 2. Chris [?]</B> <BR>
My name's Chris [?], I'm a freelancer. My question's to the gentleman from The Nation, which is a newspaper I've had a tremendous amount of respect for ever since May 1992 when I was in Bangkok during the uprising there, and the Thai print media did such a professional courageous job it was extraordinary example of the best journalism that really puts to shame a lot of the sycophantic nonsense that goes on in a lot of the western press. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
But my question -I've got a couple of questions -one of which you may not like to answer. Which is about the Thai monarchy. Hugh Menzies mentioned at the end of his speech this morning that it won't be long before the press starts dishing out the same sort of Di treatment to the Thai monarchy that the British monarchy receives. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Personally I received that view with tremendous amount of scepticism, which leads me on to the next point, about misinformation on the internet and the multimedia publishing information technology revolution that we're going through. We've had a lot about censorship; we haven't had much about misinformation, and I just wanted to know whether you wanted to make any comments about that, particularly as there's just recently been the anniversary in Thailand of the 1976 October Teim Sat  university massacre at which photographs -doctored photographs -of the royal family were used to launch a coup and gain popular support for the coup. And very reputable newspapers such as the Bangkok Post actually published those papers. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I'd like to hear your comments: 1. about the current political situation in Thailand, the current media situation, particularly what's happened since the Anand government, caretaker government, privatised and deregulated a lot of the media there. Thankyou.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Khun Tulsathit Taptin</B> <BR>
I think your first question is what we heard in the morning: how long the Thai monarchy can survive or can escape media criticism. Honestly speaking, and I hope there is no special branch from Thailand [laughter], honestly I think the monarchy itself is facing a very tough time in Thailand, but what has made its escape, what had enabled the monarchy to escape criticism is the King himself. The King has been able to maintain his role as a unifying force in Thailand. He has maintained his image as the highest institution in the country, despite all the scandal surrounding other loyal family members. The King has been able to keep a really good image with the Thai people. So as long as this King is on the throne I think the monarchy will be safe for as long as he stays. but after that I don't want to make any predictions. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Regarding your second question about misinformation, it's good that you raise that question. In 1976 during a massacre of students in university, misinformation lead to that tragedy. It's one of our darkest chapters in the nation's history. What happened was, at that time the government had absolute control over the media. It was a dictatorial government at the time. WE at The Nation tried to resist this. WE tried to report what was really going on, but sadly on that tragic day we were closed down by the government after [security?] people from the university campus and rape, beat and shot students to death. What we could do on that day -my senior journalist told me, I was still student at that time -what the Nation journalist could do on that day was just sit and watch and cry. Do nothing. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Maybe I, I missed your last . . . ?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Q. 2 [from the floor:] The last question was what changes have taken place particularly since the caretaker government . . . [indistinct] . . . And . . . privatised a lot of the media in Thailand in order to break up the military's monopoly of the media. I was just wondering what sort of a difference that had made. What you felt as a journalist: what difference has it made.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Khun Tulsathit Taptin</B><BR>
The most obvious difference is the Thai media has enjoyed more freedom. The contradiction is to let the media to compete to seek the truth, to bring out the facts that had been hidden. As I said before in my statement, there will be problems if the media enjoyed more freedom. It could undermine the government. In my country, over the past two years, in Thai newspapers, they describe the government as Thailand's, they describe the government as dogs, they could do this. But that cannot undermine a really good government, because the people will sooner or later they will know which one is a bad newspaper and which one is good.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
