<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Freedom of Expression and the End of Colonialism</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Freedom of Expression and the End of Colonialism</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html#MAK">Mak Yin-ting</A>, Chairperson, Hong Kong Journalists Association.
</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
According to many people, Hong Kong is one of the freest places in the region for the media, and is therefore regarded as the Asian information centre. A total of 59 dailies and 675 periodicals are published. Three commercial television companies, a satellite TV station and four radio broadcasters serve Hong Kong's six million people. The territory also accommodates a large number of international news agencies, newspapers with international readership and regional offices of overseas broadcasting corporations.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>To a great extent, though, press freedom has been the result of government self-restraint. Up until early 1993, a whole range of draconian colonial laws remained on the statute book. Since then, there have been changes, but some potentially crippling laws still remain. If implemented, they could return the territory to the dark ages before 1967 - the year when China's Cultural Revolution swept Hong Kong.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Slow Progress on Law Reform</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Before 1967, newspapers in Hong Kong had to submit proofs to the government before copies could be sold to the public, the authorities seized journalists' raw copy, and one pro-Beijing newspaper, Ta Kung Pao, was closed for six days.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Following the turbulence prompted by the Cultural Revolution, the colonial government realised the value of the press, whose support of government policies helped maintain peace and order in Hong Kong. Coupled with growing popular demands for democracy, the administration governed Hong Kong with a lighter and more diplomatic touch.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The touch might have been lighter, but the old colonial laws remained. The Television Ordinance, for example, allowed the vetting and prohibition of programs. And one TV programming regulation stipulated that a licensee had to broadcast news covering international and local affairs provided by sources or services approved by the government. The mind boggles...
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The Hong Kong Journalists Association (HKJA) for several years fought, without success, for changes to such laws. The situation changed when the new Governor, Chris Patten, arrived in Hong Kong in 1992, and pledged to review potentially harmful laws. Many laws have been changed since then, although not always to our satisfaction. For example, the repeal of subsidiary legislation under the Emergency Regulations Ordinance has been little more than cosmetic. And in the most sensitive area - security-related legislation - vital reform has been held up by confidential Sino-British negotiations.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
There is no doubt that bureaucratic conservatism has been a bar to more far-reaching change. Another reason has been China's attitude to amendments bringing colonial laws into line with section 16 of the Hong Kong Bill of Rights Ordinance, which mirrors article 19 of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights. The Hong Kong Bill of Rights was enacted after the suppression of the Chinese pro-democracy movement in June 1989, as a way to calm the fears of Hong Kong people.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
It has been widely accepted that the Hong Kong government will not press ahead with changes which might be opposed by China, unless they are of overwhelming importance. Indeed, the administration has promised to consult the Chinese government over some law reform proposals, including those relating to security legislation. Observers also note that the Chinese government would like to maintain the existing wide-ranging powers of the Hong Kong government after the July 1997 resumption of sovereignty. This itself might well be an obstacle to further reform.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
One example where the government may have given in to pressure from China has been the case of the so-called omnibus broadcasting bill, which was proposed to rationalise and bring together three existing<BR>
laws - the Television, Telecommunication and Broadcasting Authority ordinances. The government pledged to introduce the bill to the Legislative Council in 1995, but delays set in. In May 1995, the acting Secretary for Recreation and Culture, Fred Ting, announced that the bill had been shelved to avoid any clash with China over its contents. The following day, an embarrassed acting Chief Secretary, Michael Leung, felt compelled to declare that the bill was still "very much in the pipeline".
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>At the end of the same year, Mr Patten confirmed that it remained the administration's aim to introduce the bill into the Legislative Council during the 1995/96 legislative session. One month later, in January 1996, the new Secretary for Recreation and Culture, Chau Tak-hay, announced that the bill had been shelved. He claimed, without great conviction, that the move was necessary to allow the government to focus on "high priority tasks", including the introduction of a video-on-demand service and the deregulation of pay television.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>The Democratic Party - the political party with the most seats in the Legislative Council - called the move "disgraceful" and said it showed "that even routine legislation to ensure competitiveness and to keep pace with technology is being abandoned to appease China."
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
