<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Six</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Six</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Wendy Bacon, Jon Casimir, David Wilson. Section One</B></FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question. Errol Hodge.</B><BR>
Errol Hodge, Queensland University of Technology. A question for you Jon. You mentioned how great it was to be able to get all sorts of accounts of what happened in Beijing in June 1989. I can understand the benefits of being able to quote student spokesmen [sic] on what was their attitude to the pro democracy campaign, and to quote the Beijing government on what it thought of the campaign and the subsequent events. But how do you decide when it comes to trying to analyse what was the truth, how do you decide between the extremes of what the government propaganda is saying on the one hand and what the student spokesmen was saying on the other. As you know the student spokesmen circulated rumours which resulted in the account of what had happened that was given by Bob Hawke at the memorial service. How do you chose the truth? Isn't it safer to stick with foreign correspondents who are experienced in reporting this kind of event?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Jon Casimir</B> <BR>
Of course, if you want to take that tack. I think 'truth' is a - I mean, truth is a really tough subject to start discussing when you're talking about journalism. I am a believer that the age of objectivity is behind us, that it was a waste of space in journalism and the sooner we get around to admitting that it's a subjective form the better off we'll be. I didn't see the Tianenman stuff so it's a bit tough for me, but in the case of Sarajevo on line - I mean, truth in any of those situations is not only relative, it means so many different things, which is why I enjoyed, why I would call Sarajevo 'on-line journalism' is that every day there would be people emailing from Sarajevo about their daily experiences. There were people from both sides, there were people who were pro the war, people who were against the war, people who were burying their families, people who were getting out. All kinds of experiences. And they were all first hand. And to me that is journalism. It's a context. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now, it's not the only type of journalism, and the things you're talking about, the fact that we still need good journalists to give us a good perspective and that we need to attempt to find some sort of truth is also good, but neither of them - I mean, I think both of these things are helped by each other. If I can have a great journalist giving me a good perspective on an event somewhere, and I can an get some first hand, first person sense of reality about that event as well, then I'm happy.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Unidentified questioner</B> <BR>
This is a question to David. I thought that was quite humorous in a way that a head of a major corporation would actually respond to an email message, that basically Bloomberg's handling there, because as any of us know who are on email, the early days were terrific but not you get RSI from your delete button, you get overloaded, so I guess the same will apply to Bloomberg. If there were 100 journalists firing off that message he would've just deleted them all as well.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>David Wilson </B><BR>
Absolutely, and  . . . Yeah, I understand what you're talking about and believe me I face that everyday personally. I mean, going around the world, I end up coming in in the morning and there're dozens of email messages from my colleagues in the States that I have to get rid of. But understand, the distinction between our system and, say, the Internet. In the Bloomberg - to the extent that it's used to file [?] all the money if you will - it's a vital part of people's artillery if you will, and something they're paying very close attention to, so if the email message . . . [part of answer cut off by end of tape] . . . firing information around the world. I just found out yesterday that Australia's now the second country in the world where we have an entirely digital set-up OK. You're talking 56K, 64K lines world-wide. So you can deliver the message quickly and people will pay attention to it because I think it's something that it's very much a part of their day. Which is certainly an advantage to us when it comes to getting access to decision makers.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
