<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Intersections with Asia: Where the Media stands</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Intersections with Asia:<BR>
 Where the Media stands</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html#KELLY">Paul Kelly</A>, Editor in chief, The Australian newspaper</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Chair . . .</B> <BR>
Introducing the final speaker at today's conference. Our speaker is Mr Paul Kelly, who is one of Australia's most eminent journalists and editors. He is the editor of the Australian. He is a very active political reporter and commentator and also a prolific author of very interesting books on political events and personalities. I recommend his books as a very good read. Paul Kelly, since he's been at the Australian, has taken an increasing interest in Asian affairs and I think that the Australian and its product has reflected this. So to deliver the final address, I have much pleasure in welcoming Paul Kelly.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
Thanks very much Corrina. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I'm told that the conference over the last few days has been characterised by some interesting and vigorous papers and discussions about trends in journalism. This is very appropriate. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
One of the phenomenons of our time is globalisation. As journalists, we are often analysing trends in politics, business and technology, and so many of these trends today are driven by globalisation. And yet I tend to suspect that as an industry we are not as aware of how the phenomenon of globalisation is transforming our own activities, our own industry and our own operations. I'd like to address some of these issues today, with particular reference to the relationship between Australia and Asia.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
It's an age of instantaneous news. Television, CNN, radio. It's so easy to find out what he latest news is from virtually anywhere in the world. But the interesting aspect of this is that I often wonder to what extent we are actually learning more about the world as distinct with being bombarded with information about what's going on in various parts of the world. And I think that this is a particularly important point which goes to the heart of how in fact a journalist must operate. I'm concerned at the moment that there is a tendency in this country towards a more provincial and introspective outlook. I think that we were more genuinely interested in overseas events and overseas trends a few years ago than what we are at the moment. And I think that this is an issue we should carefully assess. When I look at our media coverage of Europe or of the recent United States election or of events in India or China I'm increasingly sceptical as to how beneficial the coverage of these countries and these events is inside Australia. And I think the risk is that too often the coverage is superficial and too often our understanding of what's really going on in these countries is far too superficial. I think this is an issue we have to consider very carefully as journalists and as an industry. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
One of the problems of course is that it's difficult when journalists are attempting to go beyond simply reporting the news of the day and they are attempting to analyse what's going on beneath the news and to identify the trends. Often it's hard because it's very complicated, it's difficult to work out what's happening. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Let's look at the recent United States election. Many people said to me the coverage in the Australian papers was boring, and I think there was quite a lot in this. It was just a contest between Bob Dole and Bill Clinton, and it looked pretty much from the start as though the result was a foregone conclusion. But to what extent did the coverage really address some of the underlying issues: the crisis of America democracy; the fact that the turnout was the lowest in 60 or 70 years (and in some ways the turnout was the most disappointing for 150 years); the fact that the Democratic party seems to have walked away from a lot of its roots, from a lot of the things it believes in; the fact that the election seemed to herald the complete death of Keynesian economics. To what extent were these issues really looked at and analysed during the course of the election campaign? It seems to me not very much. But the task of journalism is to get to the issues and - in this post-Cold War, post-ideological age - come to grips with the trends. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#top">Return to top</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="kelly02.html">Next section</A> ] 
</CENTER></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="../program.html">Program</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A> ]
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br> 
[ <A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A> ]
</CENTER></B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br> 
