<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Seven</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Paul Kelly. Section One.</FONT></B><br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question 1. Elizabeth [muffled] from AAP.</B><BR> 
I'm just wondering how much of a responsibility newspapers such as the Australian have placed - or how much responsibility do you take - in covering the race debate that's currently going on. Taking in mind the reaction it will probably have in Asia. What sort of editorial decisions, that sort of thing.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Paul Kelly</B><BR> 
Well, I think that we've got to cover the debate according to our judgment of its news value and it's quite clearly an important debate. We've had a bipartisan resolution passed in Federal Parliament on the issue; we've had a number of prominent Australians participate in the debate and make public comments - from the Prime Minister to the Opposition leader to the Foreign Minister to the Trade Minister to the former Prime Minister; we've had significant coverage of this issue by the overseas media. So clearly it is an important issue in its own right that the Australian media must cover. And I think in terms of our coverage we've got to cover it the way we'd cover any other story. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
We must ensure that our coverage is fair, that's balanced, that it's not unduly exaggerated. That we give different play to the various perspectives. I don't think that it would be right for the Australian media to censor itself in terms of this debate, or not report, because we would be concerned that the reporting of this issue would damage Australia abroad. We can't adopt that sort of approach. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Having said that I think that the most difficult issue to come to terms with in this debate was how to cover it at the start, when all that had really happened was one member of parliament who was an Independent had made some comments which were unrepresentative of the views of government or opposition or of the majority of the Australian people. And I think that you had to be careful, at that stage of the debate, in terms of the balance of the coverage, not to give too much emphasis to the views of one person who was an Independent Member of Parliament. What happened however was that the coverage of the views of that one person was taken up and many other people responded to that person hence the story gathered momentum and became a very significant story because many other people, from the Government and Opposition, became involved as did foreign governments. And in that sense of course the story had to be covered in the normal professional way that the media would bring to any other story. I've answered that at length because I think it's a very important issue and it's a very complicated issue.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 2 [muffled] former copyboy on the Australian back in David Armstrong's days.</B><BR> 
You talk about cultural sensitivity towards reporting the region, whatever region that might be. I'd like to find out how you, as an editor-in-chief, balance that cultural sensitiveness with - in the way, I hope it hasn't changed in the Australian , I know that every Monday night at about 9.15 everybody stops to have a look at 'Mediawatch' and you figured prominently in the Australian in last week's 'Mediawatch', and the accusation was exactly that. That in [??] the claim your foreign editor Greg Sheridan would make to cultural sensitiveness in the region, other journalists or other commentators might argue that it's not cultural sensitiveness as such. How do you balance that in your coverage, how do you judge when being sensitive to issues in the region - whether they be cultural or not - go beyond that into ineffectual and even wrong and factually wrong information? Like you know the article from Greg Sheridan previously to the UN security council vote, at the same time a newspaper in Portugal ran a very similar article saying it was very confident that Portugal was going to win. So I'd just like to find out how you balance all these cultural issues with factual journalistic fact.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Paul Kelly</B><BR> 
Well, the first point to make is that it's very important to get one's facts right. It's very important to ensure that stories published are accurate and balanced. That's the answer in relation to 'fact'. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now, I didn't see this 'Mediawatch' program so I don't know the precise issue that you are referring to. What I'd say about Greg Sheridan is that Greg is a very experienced and very professional journalist in his covering of the Asia-Pacific and has some very good contacts throughout the region, and I think has immeasurably enhanced the Australian media's coverage of the Asia-Pacific as a result of his contributions. both his news contributions and his analysis. Now if people are complaining about his analysis they're entitled to complain, and I've got no doubt that he is perfectly capable of doing more than defending himself. I'd simply say that I think he's a very good example of an Australian journalist who's travelled to the region a lot and made very substantial efforts to develop contacts in the region, and to develop an understanding of a lot of the political and social issues in the Asia-Pacific, yet write about them in a very competent and professional manner. In that sense I think he's a very good example of the sort of skills I was talking about. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
You ask a general question about how we balance these sensitivities. Well, we're talking about qualitative differences here. It's one thing to be sensitive, it's another thing to publish an inaccurate story, to publish a wrong story. That's being unprofessional. And I think the difference at the end of the day, ultimately, is clear. And it's a quite a distinct difference. These are qualitatively different things. You've got a certain number of facts, and you can put those facts into a story in all sorts of different ways, and what I'm saying is that one brings sensitivity to the coverage of the story. And I'm saying that one does that without compromising journalistic standards at all. I certainly believe that that's possible, and I believe that this really is the task that Australian journalists must tackle in their coverage of this part of the world.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20>
<br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
</TD>
