<HEAD><TITLE>SUBMISSION TO REVIEW OF ABC FUNCTIONS</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>SUBMISSION TO MANSFIELD REVIEW OF ABC FUNCTIONS</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<NOBR><A HREF="ABC-Preamble.html">[Preamble]</A> [Principles] <A HREF="ABC-Programming.html">[Programming]</A> <A HREF="ABC-Structure.html">[Structure]</A> <A HREF="ABC-Funding.html">[Funding]</A> <A HREF="ABC-Recommend.html">[Recommendations]</A></NOBR>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>Section 2. Principles</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

There is a compelling case for public service broadcasting in an Australian democracy.  The increasing concentration of media ownership, and the singular lack of diversity in newspapers and commercial news, makes the case even more important. It is crucial in this environment that the broadcasting system in Australia remain a mixed system of commercial and public service broadcasting. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

There is strong and persistent public support in Australia for the principles of public service broadcasting. Recent statistical evidence clearly shows that the ABC TV reaches 87% to 90% of Australian television viewers during any four week period, while ABC radio reaches 6,167,000 radio listeners each week.   On this basis we reject any notion that the ABC serves only an elite of the population, with 'high culture' tastes. The ABC must remain independent, especially of commercial influence, and must strive to extend its reach and the appropriateness of its content to the geographic, social and cultural diversity of the Australian population. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

We see no major problem with the present formulation of the ABC's charter, though there have clearly been difficulties for the organisation in meeting many contradictory demands. It has insufficient resources, an inappropriate management and internal funding structure, and it is hampered by a certain enduring 'high culture', BBC inheritance. We see it as imperative for the ABC to redefine itself as both more specialised and more inclusive, serving many publics, including young people.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

While the Charter requires the ABC only to 'take account of' the services provided by other broadcast sectors, the question of a 'complementary' role to commercial services has pervaded much public discussion. There has been a lot of confusion and disagreement about how the ABC can remain both 'comprehensive' and 'complementary'. We argue that these can both be achieved in the best sense if 'comprehensive' is taken to mean not ratings (as many people as possible at any one time) but 'reach' (how many people view over a longer time period). The ABC should aim to reach as many different communities of geography, taste and interest as possible. There is no longer such a thing as the 'general public', Australia being constituted by many publics, all of whom can be served, but not all at once. The ABC should aim to address these 'publics' serially rather than simultaneously. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

In many areas the ABC should be complementary to the commercial services (one could mount an argument that the ABC should not be producing or transmitting commercial-style soap operas or situation comedies at the present time, for example). However we are concerned at the implications of entrenching the notion of complementarity in a revised Charter. Trying to maintain a complementary profile has resulted in many frustrations for the ABC; JJJ's existence, for example, has been dogged by claims that it is encroaching on commercial radio's terrain. As far as we are aware, this problem is not as major for public service broadcasters which maintain a larger audience share due to their history as broadcast monopolies. It is a particular problem for broadcasters in a mixed system. The primary concern for the ABC must be the fulfilment of its enduring public service responsibilities rather than not allowing it to duplicate commercial activities at a particular moment.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

Similarly, if the ABC is to call on notions of 'national identity' in response to the notion of 'comprehensiveness', then it must define what is meant by that term. 'National' need not be understood as 'Federal', an understanding which has led to overcapitalisation in bricks and mortar (and management structures) in each State. Rather 'National' should be understood as a conglomerate of different publics (geographic, taste, interest, culture) at different times, as well as a single public national on occasions. The present Federal structure is inhibiting rather than contributing to the development of a fully National radio structure, understood in this more complex way.</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
