<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>SUBMISSION TO REVIEW OF ABC FUNCTIONS</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist">
</A><IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>SUBMISSION TO MANSFIELD REVIEW OF ABC FUNCTIONS</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<NOBR><A HREF="ABC-Preamble.html">[Preamble]</A> <A HREF="ABC-Principles.html">[Principles]</A> [Programming] <A HREF="ABC-Structure.html">[Structure]</A> <A HREF="ABC-Funding.html">[Funding]</A> <A HREF="ABC-Recommend.html">[Recommendations]</A></NOBR>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>Section 3. Programming</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

We assert that there is no program category or type that the ABC should a priori not do. However, in any program category or type the ABC should aim for innovation and quality. It must be allowed to take risks, to explore new genres and reach new audiences.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

The ABC should do what the commercial broadcasters will not do because of their specific relationship with the audience and advertisers. The ABC is obliged to reach new kinds of audience, to create new audiences where they previously did not exist - to perform the "R & D" of broadcasting. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

While ABC television should not be in the business of chasing ratings, it is essential that the ABC provide relevant programming for diverse groups - especially those that are not served by the commercial channels - and it should schedule these programs with the aim of reaching the largest segment possible of the relevant audience. To that end, scheduling of ABC programs should be done with regard to competition, to allow the maximum number of people to watch an ABC program, in preference to aggressively programming 'head to head' with high rating programs on commercial channels. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

In our view the Charter obligation for innovation should be interpreted as program innovation, examples of which would be Elle McFeast, Club Buggery, Andrew Denton, Hot Chips, http, Foreign Correspondent  and the like, as well as many of the documentary series which the ABC has screened. Too often however the notion of innovation has been confused with the notion of 'quality' with the ABC seen as necessarily the 'quality' broadcaster, compared with the 'crassness' the commercial 'mass' broadcasters.  We do not subscribe to this notion of quality.  The danger of connecting ABC with quality in this sense is that the concept is too easily read as unproblemmatic, and used as an excuse for the exercise of specific tastes in programming, or for the creation of hierarchies of genre (for example, hierarchies which prioritise news over children's programming, period drama over science fiction, drama over comedy etc). 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

So if the public broadcaster is to identify 'quality' as one of its goals, then it must define what it means by 'quality' within the various genres it broadcasts - quality in children's drama has different criteria than quality in news programming. We suggest also that the ABC might consider importing quality programming from countries other then Britain - eg documentaries from PBS in America, or from other public service broadcasters.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

As examples of genre specific definitions of quality, we discuss some types of programs below. This discussion is in no way indicative of a desire to limit the ABC to these, or to any particular type of program.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<B>News and Current Affairs</B><BR>
Quality News and Current Affairs programs are reliable, impartial and authoritative. What does 'reliable, impartial and authoritative' news and information services mean?  To be reliable means having a properly funded, professionally trained and well managed news organisation.  To be impartial is to subscribe to particular journalistic practices and to a notion of balance over time.  To be authoritative requires a sufficient range of sources and analysis, so that content can be accepted with confidence as both accurate and substantial.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

Clearly then public service broadcasting is different in character and in objective from other news services.  It is expected to be independent - of the state, of uninformed prejudice and of powerful interests in society.  Since business sentiment shapes the values and practices of commercial media, public service broadcasting must be separate from both the public and private sector.  This raises important questions about funding sources, to which we return later.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

Note too that size or composition of audience is secondary in a strictly formulated notion of public service news and current affairs broadcasting.  The objective is to make information available to the electorate, rather than audience for its own sake. Like Hansard, such a news service may be consulted by relatively few, but remains an essential and influential resource.  This is particularly the case in times of great moment, when people turn once again to the ABC.  

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

The ABC's international network of reporters is a highly prized resource in contrast to the concentrated sources used by commercial media for world news. We would even like to see more international programs drawing on this expertise, and note that Australia Television's late night news is appreciated by many Australians for its detailed attention to the region. This is ironic in view of the channel's target audience being in Asia. We return to Aus TV below. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

In sum, public service broadcasting requires a news and information service which has adequate funding, appropriate professional values, a wide mandate and legal and organisational structures which assure independence from government, business and other interests (including audience ratings) when presenting information.  The mandate is to inform a democracy, recognising that disagreement and occasional hostility to scrutiny are to be expected in the political realm.  The old injunction to public servants that they offer advice 'without fear or favour' is indeed a clich, but one which captures accurately the task in  hand.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<B>Drama</B><BR>
ABC drama should cater for all sections of the community - though not all at the same time. This means that it can aim programs at those sections of the community which, while they are served as part of a mass audience by the commercial networks, are not served in their cultural specificity by any. These groups can be served one after another, so that 'comprehensiveness' is achieved over a period of time, rather than in any one program.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

ABC drama has an obligation to the creative life of the community, including the nurturing of Australian creative talent, innovation and experimentation, and to fictionally render Australian history and contemporary life, even when it is unpalatable, politically unpopular and risky (though of course it does not have to do this all the time). We would expect ABC drama to be different from what is normally done by commercial networks, and to be a pioneering force. The organisation's drama record is in fact uneven, with startlingly original and successful recent programs such as Seven Deadly Sins, The Damnation of Harvey McHugh, Bordertown and Heartland, but nothing in the current season that approaches such achievement.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

The Australian Broadcasting Tribunal, in its inquiry into Australian content said that quality programs 'are good in their own terms at all levels, in all aspects and over as wide a range as possible'. It went on to say that quality programs 'result in high audience involvement and have an impact beyond the moment of their screening'

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

ABC Drama should be Australian (in the ABA's sense), should fictionally render Australian and contemporary life, commenting on our own society, including its relation to the rest of the world, be of high quality, be innovative and experimental. It should cover new subject matter, employing new stylistic devices, crossing established genre boundaries, embodying fresh perspectives or modes of address; it should take chances, risking not immediately finding an audience but hoping to challenge and change audience expectations. ABC drama should be audience-driven not ratings-driven - programs should have a clear sense of their audience but this need not be a mass audience. It should be diverse in style and format - the ABC should endeavour to move beyond the fixed and formulaic television forms, the series, serial and mini-series, and experiment with other formats which might serve the material better.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

Drama programs should also be diverse in subject matter so as to be of relevance to all sections of the Australian community - this relates especially to the needs of Aboriginal and multicultural audiences. It should be socially critical - the ABC should take risks in subject matter as well as style, and sometimes 'bite the hand that feeds it'. It should also foster new talent - this recognises that creative renewal in the 'art of television' cannot occur unless resources are given to training and encouraging new creative personnel; together with other agencies, including the Australian Film Commission (AFC) and the Australian Film Television and Radio School (AFTRS), the ABC has some responsibility in this area. It should contribute to cross-fertilisation between different cultural and aesthetic forms - television as the popular audiovisual medium and one ideally suited to genre-mixing can be the site of a very lively meeting of music, dance, sound, video art, visual design, performance of both the 'high art' and 'popular' varieties.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

Other entertainment genres
We have stressed how essential it is for the ABC to be active across many broadcast genres, although obviously not all equally all the time. It is unmistakeable that it is in the area of comedy and satire that the ABC has been most innovative and adventurous recently. Frontline has been a triumph, exhibiting many of the characteristics listed above. Roy and HG have pioneered a new genre of sports satire which has attracted young audiences. The declining role of the ABC in sports broadcasting is a striking pattern over the last two decades, to the point where the question arises of whether the ABC has any role here at all. Again the criterion of innovation and reaching new and diverse audiences must be paramount. We note here the excellent service the ABC performed in covering the Paralympic Games, but also our dismay that the Paralympic Federation in fact had to pay the ABC to do this. The organisation must have the resources to be able to cover such significant but minority events.  

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

We also note the ABC's fine record of producing and broadcasting programs for children, many of which find appreciative audiences overseas. Children are the audience most obviously not served by commercial logic, and the ABC must maintain its record of quality and commitment here. </FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
