<HEAD><TITLE>SUBMISSION TO REVIEW OF ABC FUNCTIONS</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>SUBMISSION TO MANSFIELD REVIEW OF ABC FUNCTIONS</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<NOBR><A HREF="ABC-Preamble.html">[Preamble]</A> <A HREF="ABC-Principles.html">[Principles]</A> <A HREF="ABC-Programming.html">[Programming]</A> [Structure] <A HREF="ABC-Funding.html">[Funding]</A> <A HREF="ABC-Recommend.html">[Recommendations]</A></NOBR>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>Section 4. Structure</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

The ABC must redefine its management structure to achieve the best possible broadcasting outcomes for its audience(s). To do this it must re-evaluate its historical evolution, and determine whether past practices are appropriate in the current circumstances. It must also determine which services will most effectively meet its broadcasting objectives.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<B>(a) Management Diversity</B><BR>
It is crucial that management in some ways reflects the diversity of the Australian population, and thus of the desired programming outcomes of the ABC. Programmers (or commissioning editors) in particular should have a diverse range of views in order to promote heterogenous programming and scheduling.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<B>(b) Regionalism</B><BR>
The ABC, as the national broadcaster, must address issues of regionalism. It is not necessary however that organisational divisions be made on State lines in accordance with the Federal system of Government. The historical division of the broadcasting public into States is inappropriate to the task of the national broadcaster in an age of global communications. While some audience members may identify with their State, and while laws may differ from State to State, it is difficult to mount a broadcasting reason for a State-Based organisation. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

The ABC should determine its required regional outcomes and then implement an appropriate management structure. At present it seems that the reverse is true - that the State management structure determines broadcasting outcomes. A far more sensible approach for regional programming would be a geographical division between geographic communities of interest - Albury/Wodonga, and The Gold Coast, are two obvious examples where regional concerns cross state boundaries.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

Regional participation in radio should be expanded by the production of more radio production in local centres. Regional participation in television may be achieved more effectively by the commissioning of independent regional program producers in television than by the current 'symbolic' presence of studios in State Capitals. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<B>(c) International models</B><BR>
For historical reasons, Australia has inherited the British variant of a single, centralised national broadcasting organisation offering both radio and television, with a charter which combines information, education and entertainment objectives.  Since the 1980s this has been supplemented by a Special Broadcasting Service attending to foreign language material, and by limited public funding for community radio and television.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

One could imagine government achieving public service broadcasting objectives through funding many different and smaller organisations - as with PBS in the United States - or by distributing the public service broadcasting fee to many broadcasters, as in New Zealand.  In each case, however, these alternative models violate some principles of public service broadcasting.  When funding is dispersed, as in the United States, no single organisation can rely solely on public money.  In Canada, public service broadcasting has become totally reliant on advertising.  While this may not directly affect editorial independence, commercial operations introduce a commercial logic about audience size and reach.  In New Zealand, the spreading of the licence fee over many broadcasters (none of which has a public service mandate) has reduced rather than enhanced the quality of service in many areas.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

In sum, an ABC is not the only way to realise public service broadcasting principles.  Yet there are important warnings in international experience in reaching too eagerly for alternatives.  Finding the best model for Australia may be a question not of principle but of the pragmatics of organisational design.  Whatever the problems, consolidation in a single national broadcaster is probably at present the most cost effective way to proceed.  Given the failure of radical change in New Zealand, and the clear and present dangers posed by advertising in the Canadian system, there is no firm basis for abandoning the Australian tradition of a single, public funded national broadcasting organisation.  Improvements should be achieved instead through better goal-setting, and consideration of the degrees to which the ABC should broadcast and/or produce its own programs.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

To this end, perhaps the Channel 4 model is the most appropriate to adapt to Australian needs. Channel 4 maintains a strong public service mandate and commissions independent production. We believe that for television it will be more cost effective to have a purchaser-provider arrangement for the production of television programs, especially drama and documentary. This would allow ABC TV to act more as a commissioning agent than it now does and to focus on programming outcomes rather than managing a complex and dispersed set of facilities and a large dispersed staff. This was appropriate in the early days when there was no independent production industry, but it makes less sense now. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

However there are dangers in this model, one being that with the loss of staff who carry the culture and history of Public Service Broadcasting in their daily practices, the value of Public Service Broadcasting may be lost. We believe that this can be counteracted by having a very robust Public Service Charter and a good system of accountability which at the same time absolutely protects the ABC's political independence. 

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<B>(d) Australia Television and Radio Australia</B><BR>
Television is ten times as expensive as radio. So while Radio Australia can provide a free and democratic alternative in areas of the world with repressive broadcasting regimes, Australia Television must use commercial sponsors, which alters the relationship of the ABC to its audience. It is questionable whether the foreign affairs benefits which Australia Television offers the nation are commensurate with its costs both in terms of money and integrity.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

Australia Television should cease to be funded by the ABC in the present manner. If the Government judges that clause 1(b) of the Charter should apply to television as well as radio, then Australia Television must be funded in the same way as Radio Australia, and not be expected to take sponsorship, which sets a dangerous precedent and in this case has failed anyway. Radio Australia should be expanded and given more resources.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<B>(e) Pay TV</B><BR>
It is one thing to say that the ABC should be involved in new technologies, it is quite another to say that the ABC should get into new types of services with new types of relations to audiences which is what Pay TV implies.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

It is important that mode of delivery not be confused with service. Pay TV is not a new technology, although it sometimes is delivered via (comparatively) new delivery systems such as satellite and cable. What it is rather is a new type of service which introduces a new relationship with the audience. As discussed below, the relationship between audience and broadcaster is determined largely by the way in which the broadcaster is funded. In an environment where audiences pay for a service, the relationship is more direct than where they do not. For the Public Broadcaster to enter the PayTV field, it must satisfy the greatest number of its subscribers at any time, and so must follow the commercial imperative of 'mass' or single 'niche' programming. As we are arguing that the best audience target for the ABC is in serial audiences, and because of the huge financial investment required, we believe that  Pay TV is best left to commercial operators.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

However a 'must carry' amendment should be made to broadcasting legislation to require commercial Pay TV operators to carry ABC programming.  The ABC should have the option of selling Pay TV rights of any program or group of programs to Pay TV providers who wish to retransmit (eg a package of arts documentaries for an arts channel; children's programs for a children's channel, etc). This will bring the ABC extra revenue without huge financial risk.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<B>(f) OnLine Services /Information Services</B><BR>
At present the major roles of the ABC online services are as an adjunct to radio and television services - whether program promotion, transcripts of radio programs, or audience feedback on radio and television via e-mail. These services have been enthusiastically adopted by certain groups, and may be bringing about new relationships between the organisation and its audience, and indeed, new forms of communication among audience members. The ABC is the only Australian broadcaster to have developed a substantial online presence, and the possibilities being created further establish its distinctive role. It is likely that the online services are in fact bringing new audiences to the ABC.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

It is important that the ABC retains a presence in Online services, and continues to develop the potential of these new forms to serve public service goals. Full transcripts of programs are available on ABC websites. This is a very valuable educational and public information resource, and contrasts, for example, with the way major newspapers' online presence is oriented towards selling the publication, providing excerpts only. It is less clear whether this new service is appropriate to the goals of a public service broadcaster in forms such as the provision of separate information services or the managing of user groups.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

While access to information and information literacy is a crucial area for consideration by Government, there is no good reason at present why the ABC should become involved in this initiative. If the government has a cultural policy regarding multimedia or internet services these should be provided through other means - the most obvious being the public library network, and telecommunications carriers. erceived radio/television duplication.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<B>(g) ABC/SBS Amalgamation</B><BR>
Inevitably in a review such as this, the possibility of an amalgamation between SBS and ABC will be discussed.
The most significant objection to such an amalgamation is that it is likely to lead to a 'backdoor' implementation of advertising or sponsorship policy at the ABC, a policy which would weaken the diversity of the broadcasting environment. The absence of advertising on ABC strengthens diversity - the audience has a choice between a station with ads and one without.
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

