<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>SUBMISSION TO REVIEW OF ABC FUNCTIONS</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>SUBMISSION TO MANSFIELD REVIEW OF ABC FUNCTIONS</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<NOBR><A HREF="ABC-Preamble.html">[Preamble]</A> <A HREF="ABC-Principles.html">[Principles]</A> <A HREF="ABC-Programming.html">[Programming]</A> <A HREF="ABC-Structure.html">[Structure]</A> [Funding] <A HREF="ABC-Recommend.html">[Recommendations]</A></NOBR>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>Section 5. Funding</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<B>(a) audience/broadcaster relationship</B><BR>
The provision of broadcasting services entails three different relationships between the broadcaster and the audience, according to the manner in which the broadcaster is funded.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

In the first, of a commercial provider, there is no direct relationship between audience and the broadcaster. The audience is commodified by the broadcaster and sold to advertisers in a lump. The audience can have an indirect effect on the broadcaster by turning off and affecting advertising revenue. In this relationship the audience must be treated as a 'mass' and programs must attract the largest audience most of the time.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
 
In the second, of subscription, the relationship is more direct because the provider will lose business if the service is not satisfactory to the audience. Here the audience is treated as consumer, but the broadcaster doesn't have to achieve the largest possible audiences most of the time. The broadcaster can address niche markets and still capture large markets and profits.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

In the third, funding through licence fees or government appropriation, the relationship is one where the provider can give not what the audience wants, but what the provider thinks the audience needs.  This has been defined as 'the public interest'. 'Public interest' can thus entail programs that create and foster a public or publics, encourage spaces of debate, contestation, the exercise of citizenship, the playing out of the democratic process. In this relationship the broadcaster is accountable to the public in how well it fulfils what has been agreed upon as the 'public interest' . What counts as the 'public interest' can change historically. We suggest that the Charter/Contract model we set out below would give the opportunity for having an open and public debate every seven years (as in the BBC Charter process) for determining what the public interest in broadcasting is, and how the ABC would fulfil it.

<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<B>(b)	Contract with government</B><BR>
We propose the Review consider a contract mechanism similar to agreements between the BBC and the British Government, and between the Australian Film Finance Corporation and successive Australian administrations.  We suggest that every seven (or perhaps five) years, government and the ABC should reach a detailed agreement.  This contract, consistent with the Charter, should set out the specific strategies to be employed by the Corporation in pursuit of its goals.  The contract should include performance indicators, such as proposed broadcast hours of Australian drama content and, if appropriate, proportions of material to be produced outside the organisation.  In return, government would agree to guaranteed levels of funding for the term of the contract.
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

