<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER AND CIVIL SOCIETY</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER<BR>
AND CIVIL SOCIETY</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> <A HREF="cox-02.html">[Political correctness and balance]</A> [The agora or forum]<BR>
<A HREF="cox-04.html">[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla]</A> <A HREF="cox-05.html">[The metros]</A> <A HREF="cox-06.html">[Radio National (RN)]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-07.html">[Social Capital and the ABC]</A> <A HREF="cox-08.html">[The displeased piper's wanted tunes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-09.html">[The ABC too timid with alternative views?]</A> <A HREF="cox-10.html">[Some proposals for changes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> <A HREF="cox-mr02.html">[A two day listening sample]</A></CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>The agora or forum</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The ABC rally in the Domain reminds us of the function this space had and still does provide. Like London's Hyde Park Corner, this strip of parkland provides a space where free speech was allowed to all who wanted to bring their soap boxes. Over recent times, the electronic media have replaced the public meeting and personal contact, and displaced public oratory. Therefore the functions of the agora or forum of ancient democracies need to be considered as part of any debate on the role of public broadcaster.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The Greek agora was the open space which served the market, the religious and civil societies, which in small civil communities could share a space in which none was dominant. The Roman forum lay between temples and capitol to provide a space for meetings and discussions. There were many exclusions from citizenship in these city states, such as women and slaves, and their models were by no means ideal democracies in modern terms. However, the basic assumption of spaces for meeting, debating, dissenting and cementing relationships should still remain a core base of a democratic and functioning society.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The importance of media in mass post industrial societies is dealt with in many publications and no doubt, submissions. As part of popular culture, it provides images, interactions and information which shapes and reflects the way we see ourselves, both as identity and relatedness to others. We do not want to deal with the specifics of how these complex roles of media create, affirm and deny  the ways in which we see ourselves, and act, but to suggest that the importance of maintaining a public broadcaster may have increased as a result of the expanding and diversifying of telecommunications, rather than being reduced.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The concept of a national broadcaster of both radio and TV may be misinterpreted as a relic of a simpler past when there was little in the way of alternatives. Then access to government owned public broadcasting would have been part of a developmental, modernising process which also sought to bind together a sparse and scattered population. The problems of the depression years, the need for nationhood and unity during the forties and the sense of unified Australia of the fifties would have been congruent with national broadcaster. Unlike the UK, we started in competition with commercial broadcasting, so our model is not the BBC.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Therefore, there needs to be spaces in which a range of debates can take place, where performances can be offered and enjoyed, and new ideas and concepts can seek both reactions and audiences. The role of news and current affairs is seen often as the pinnacle of the public broadcasting responsibilities, its particular roles as public broadcaster, need to be more than an accurate fact producer role.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
We need analysis and comment, documentaries and reports on other related activities in the community. We need a holistic approach to reflecting, creating and explaining diverse images and contexts for the daily 'news'. The ability of people to hear, see and interpret their lives and what is happening to them, to be able to act on their own behalf and recognise their connections to others, depends at least in part, on the way they see themselves and others on the media.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
At a very simplistic level, a demonstration by a group of 20 people on the news is more significant than 2000 ignored. The presence or absence of issues, of images and information from representation in the media is highly significant in the context of social, political and economic cultures. Those issues and concerns which fail to make it to the media, are often ignored in the community. Those groups whose legitimacy is affirmed by the media are much more politically and socially powerful than those who are ignored or negated.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The agora contains markets and governance as well as culture and faith. Professor Claus Offe from Humboldt University, Berlin, at a recent ANU seminar, set up a modern model of the Agora as a triangle with its angles representing the market, the state and the community. He pointed out that the question for us now was to find the balance between the three institutions so that no one dominates to the point of destroying the fragile balances which make up civil societies
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The ABC in its entirety provides access to a broad range of views and voices and offers its audiences choices. The market sector of broadcasting is limited by the perceptions of proprietors, the biases of advertisers, the limits of managers imagination and the objective of making money. Even though they hold licenses for use of public airwaves and can sell these if they make money, there is little or no obligation for them to be good corporate citizens or to offer services which have a public good component.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Some do in minor ways, either at owner whim, or as a good marketing strategy. However, if we are to see choices as important and public broadcasting as one of the possible benchmarkers of responsible broadcasting there are arguments to retain the present broad charter of the ABC. The existence of a public broadcaster should be seen as a public good rather than a private consumption item as it offers a benefit to all, including those who do not use it, by setting standards of ethical broadcasting and promoting social cohesion by mirroring diverse elements, not otherwise included.
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
