<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER AND CIVIL SOCIETY</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER<BR>
AND CIVIL SOCIETY</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> <A HREF="cox-02.html">[Political correctness and balance]</A> <A HREF="cox-03.html">[The agora or forum]</A><BR>
[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla] <A HREF="cox-05.html">[The metros]</A> <A HREF="cox-06.html">[Radio National (RN)]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-07.html">[Social Capital and the ABC]</A> <A HREF="cox-08.html">[The displeased piper's wanted tunes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-09.html">[The ABC too timid with alternative views?]</A> <A HREF="cox-10.html">[Some proposals for changes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> <A HREF="cox-mr02.html">[A two day listening sample]</A></CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>The ABC is not cultural spakfilla</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
There are many areas which are unbalanced in the commercial markets. In radio, for instance, there are shock jocks whose popularity is defined by their appeal to the ill informed and opinionated. There are also music stations who offer audiences little but sounds and snippets of news. There is a minute but hardworking community radio sector and some very specialised and limited narrowcasting groups.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
In market terms, one could say that the people vote with their fingers and seek out what they want. Therefore the argument might go, we should use the ABC to provide only those areas which government would like to see available. These may be news and current affairs as these should not be able to be affected by advertiser or station owners and maybe some cultural programs of limited popular appeal.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
To the cash strapped, the quick fixer or the economistic, such arguments may seem attractive. A public broadcaster which is designed only for minority programming is cheaper than one which offers a universal service. So one puts up arguments about filling the spaces left by the commercials and creating, maybe, programs for the powerful minorities who want the arts and some intellectual programming for the elites. With some news and current affairs and rural programs with some wallpaper of under-researched commentary from personalities and most people would be happy.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
This is the cultural spakfilla model. The public sector is there to provide the content which is not available on the commercials. However, these areas should not cost too much as the public sector should be targeted to the needy. Most of these groups are not needy and maybe pay radio or narrowcasting of these sectoral interests would be appropriate!
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
In radio, the need for ABC networks is more complex to describe. The scope of programming on commercial radio, and its presumed targeting at  niche markets suggests that many ABC audiences could not find homes in the spectrum. A day or two of listening to the talk stations in particular indicates fairly clearly that there are serious problems in removing any of the ABC networks in toto or even in part. See attachment for more detail and descriptions of the difference we monitored between these programs.
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
