<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER AND CIVIL SOCIETY</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER<BR>
AND CIVIL SOCIETY</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> <A HREF="cox-02.html">[Political correctness and balance]</A> <A HREF="cox-03.html">[The agora or forum]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-04.html">[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla]</A> [The metros] <A HREF="cox-06.html">[Radio National (RN)]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-07.html">[Social Capital and the ABC]</A> <A HREF="cox-08.html">[The displeased piper's wanted tunes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-09.html">[The ABC too timid with alternative views?]</A> <A HREF="cox-10.html">[Some proposals for changes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> <A HREF="cox-mr02.html">[A two day listening sample]</A></CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>The metros</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The present spectrum of ABC stations offer a range of views which may only sometimes be echoed on the commercial media. The greatest overlap is on the metros, and probably some rural stations. However, there are differences here which need to be widened rather than reduced, by which a broader range of people are represented in both presenters and those interviewed. The issues discussed on the networks may overlap but the way they are discussed is often very different.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The culture of the ABC stations recognises that there are diverse views and that diversity is often legitimate. Therefore the approach is often to explore issues rather than use interviews to push presenters' views. The intention is to inform as well as amuse and sometimes the interviews reach a high standard of exploration of complex issues.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
From my own experience of commercial interviews, the level of questions tends to be more superficial, the intention often to showcase the interviewer and sometimes to demolish the interviewee (personality radio). The range of people interviewed tends to be more limited and much of the process is chat, rather than exploration of ideas. This is not a judgement because many of these programs provide a useful function of connecting people through the presenter as neighbourhood focus, but these are not even semi serious interviews.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
There are some good and careful interviewers and presenters on the commercial media. However, these are a minority and the disappearance of the ABC would also put them at threat. The schlock jock approach would be seen to have 'won'. There are few proprietors of radio stations who would experiment with niche styles and audiences as most prefer to flock lemming-like to the shows that please the opinionated and market leading models.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The metros provide an alternative to those who want responsible albeit lighter presenters than on RN. This is an important service and one which should not be lightly abandoned. With their relatively high ratings, these service a wide range of families and offer a genuine choice of voices and views, not easily found elsewhere. However, they often imitate commercial radio by looking for interesting rather than good coverage of stories. And here they differ from the RN culture in the emphases and the depth of research.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The metros are part of an overall culture of public broadcasting which is framed within a charter and an ethos about inclusivity. They also provide a widely heard platform for the news and current affairs services which provide the base for their own and many  commercial services stories in their search for talent and stories. The metros could be improved and some of my criticisms are detailed below. In some ways they are too cautious about innovation and limited even in their broader scope.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The metros have few production and research resources. This is why they are cheaper to run. Like the commercials, they rely on radio news or the morning papers for their stories. However, their role is best understood against the role of Radio National. Their approach is limited and often they do not want the talent to open up the issue past the few points they have set as directions. There are many presenters who have a strong interest in certain areas and show considerable expertise in these. There are others whose backgrounds as journalists makes them inquisitive and they do explore issues. However, their limited resources often defeat good intentions and they offer a better version of personality radio in many cases.
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
