<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER AND CIVIL SOCIETY</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER<BR>
AND CIVIL SOCIETY</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> <A HREF="cox-02.html">[Political correctness and balance]</A> <A HREF="cox-03.html">[The agora or forum]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-04.html">[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla]</A> <A HREF="cox-05.html">[The metros]</A> <A HREF="cox-06.html">[Radio National (RN)]</A><BR>
[Social Capital and the ABC] <A HREF="cox-08.html">[The displeased piper's wanted tunes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-09.html">[The ABC too timid with alternative views?]</A> <A HREF="cox-10.html">[Some proposals for changes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> <A HREF="cox-mr02.html">[A two day listening sample]</A></CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>Social Capital and the ABC</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Last year's Boyer lectures (Eva Cox, A truly Civil Society, ABC 1995) introduced the term social capital into public policy debates. This is a concept which deals with the way social systems cohere, the processes by which we recognise both our communalities and differences. The role of media in the process of establishing not only national identity but reflecting the state of our social fabric is important in the future of the ABC.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Quality of life is about identity and social relationships as well as material wellbeing. Social capital is as important as financial ones in establishing social cohesion and acceptance of the norms and values of the institutional frameworks we share. Social capital develops in open societies and is formed in lateral, co-operative relationships built on trust, care, mutuality and civic responsibilities. Professor Robert Putnam, of the Harvard's Kennedy school writes of correlates of high social capital with both economic success as well as pleasant lifestyles.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
We have lost social cohesion with more people expressing fear of crime, increased sales of home security hardware, more cynicism about Government and Industry leaders and generally less faith in our ability to be decent human beings.  Corporatisation, privatisation, user pays, competition, targeting, reducing the size of the public sector, reducing the progressivity of taxes, growing inequalities both in and out of the workforce, all do little for social cohesion, for lateral relationships, for trust and recognition that we are all part of one society. Put this with technological changes, reduced birthrates, fewer full time unpaid workers, better education and higher expectations and the prognosis is poor.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
If we continue the economic development models in current favour, we need to recognise that these need to be matched with commitments to social development. A burst of Rotary, or a corporate sponsorship program which selects its targets with an eye on photo opportunities, is not an adequate replacement for a civic culture. We need specific cultures of civic concern, of mutual responsibility and recognition of the need for resourcing social capital formation.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
We tend to define problems of inequality and other ill effects of economic policies and practices as potentially harmful in two spheres: there is a concern that social cohesion will suffer through the creation of an underclass, which is not part of the society. There is also a less defined concern that we may destroy a more general social ethos, a commitment to a fair and just society which may have more general implications than the fate of an underclass.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
We are in danger of running down social capital and need to look at the consequences in the UK and USA of social systems which are fragmenting. In the Australian context, we have to be particularly careful when we make major changes to the cultural perception of the public sector and services. This occurs when we reduce the legitimacy and scope of the public sector as the provision of direct government services is part of our social glue.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
We have moved our language and sometimes our function of Government away from the concept of a civic culture and citizenship to the market forms of customer and customer service. This was done partly in response to obvious deficiencies in the way bureaucracies delivered services. Many of the practices of the public sector were neither functional or defensible but assuming the market is better is too simplistic a solution.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
There are many aspects of the ABC that could do with changing. The problems is that the present process is likely to undermine good change rather than encourage it. We are already seeing signs of anxiety, with management opposing coverage of the news of the cuts and internal counter moves. Fear of lack of balance already hobbles some program makers, and will be exacerbated.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Trust in ourselves and in others comes from recognising communality in diversity. Hearing the voices of the outsiders and those on the margins is part of creating social capital. Learning to disagree civilly, to hear other views and voices on services we all own are part of developing social trust. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Inclusiveness defines all of us as worthy of attention and hearing, but if only some of us are heard, the rest become the unknown and the frightening, alien Other. The ABC may not have been good at making enough space for diversity, but it was a damn sight better than anyone else. Yet it is just this access which is being criticised by the PM.
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<CENTER><A HREF="#top">[Return to top]</A> <A HREF="cox-06.html">[Previous section]</A> <A HREF="cox-08.html">[Next section]</A></CENTER>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> <A HREF="cox-02.html">[Political correctness and balance]</A> <A HREF="cox-03.html">[The agora or forum]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-04.html">[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla]</A> <A HREF="cox-05.html">[The metros]</A> <A HREF="Cox-06.html">[Radio National (RN)]</A><BR>
[Social Capital and the ABC] <A HREF="cox-08.html">[The displeased piper's wanted tunes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-09.html">[The ABC too timid with alternative views?]</A> <A HREF="cox-10.html">[Some proposals for changes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> <A HREF="cox-mr02.html">[A two day listening sample]</A></CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

