</DOCHDR>
<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER AND CIVIL SOCIETY</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER<BR>
AND CIVIL SOCIETY</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> <A HREF="cox-02.html">[Political correctness and balance]</A> <A HREF="cox-03.html">[The agora or forum]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-04.html">[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla]</A> <A HREF="cox-05.html">[The metros]</A> <A HREF="cox-06.html">[Radio National (RN)]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-07.html">[Social Capital and the ABC]</A> [The displeased piper's wanted tunes]<BR>
<A HREF="cox-09.html">[The ABC too timid with alternative views?]</A> <A HREF="cox-10.html">[Some proposals for changes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> <A HREF="cox-mr02.html">[A two day listening sample]</A></CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>How can they second guess the displeased piper's wanted tunes?</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The criticisms by government ministers are already showing effects so there may be no need to reduce the scope of the charter as the present managers may well turn off the much needed criticisms for fear of other cuts in future years. As an organisation and spokesperson which often puts up ideas outside the present range of accepted ones, I suggest that the coverage is already more timid and criticisms of the budget we have had as milder than necessary.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The cuts will make it harder to hear diverse views on the ABC, particularly those voices generally excluded from commercial media. People outside the 'loop' of accepted alternate views already have some difficulties in attracting adequate time to present less familiar possibilities. The ABC fails often in its will to take risks with new ideas or serious criticisms of accepted views. So the networks only partially balance the conservative and status quo biases of most other media.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
In the past few weeks, we have noted that presenters are almost apologetic if they only present critiques of government views and assure the presumably listening Government censors that the other side was, would or will appear shortly. We wish the same concern was expressed every time the Government has a free kick!
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
We need a gutsy national broadcaster, so we must preserve and enhance these capacities of the ABC. In particular, we need Radio National because the world in not simple. Many ideas need more than an interview in the midst of strip programming. To reflect and understand the complexities of society and present them well, program makers need time and resources.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
We fear the charter may be changed so the ABC becomes exclusive and stops representing all of us. Being a limited minorities station would marginalise the polite minorities further  and exclude the impolite ones.  It will no longer be the public broadcaster. In a time of rapid change, we need connections which enhance the social levels of trust we need to manage change. As a feminist, and someone committed to a more civil society, as someone whose views are often ahead of the mainstream, I am desperately worried that we will lose the capacity we have now to use the ABC to inform debate and create our linkages.
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<CENTER><A HREF="#top">[Return to top]</A> <A HREF="cox-07.html">[Previous section]</A> <A HREF="cox-09.html">[Next section]</A></CENTER>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> <A HREF="cox-02.html">[Political correctness and balance]</A> <A HREF="cox-03.html">[The agora or forum]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-04.html">[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla]</A> <A HREF="cox-05.html">[The metros]</A> <A HREF="Cox-06.html">[Radio National (RN)]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-07.html">[Social Capital and the ABC]</A> [The displeased piper's wanted tunes]<BR>
<A HREF="cox-09.html">[The ABC too timid with alternative views?]</A> <A HREF="cox-10.html">[Some proposals for changes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> <A HREF="cox-mr02.html">[A two day listening sample]</A></CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

