<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER AND CIVIL SOCIETY</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER<BR>
AND CIVIL SOCIETY</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> <A HREF="cox-02.html">[Political correctness and balance]</A> <A HREF="cox-03.html">[The agora or forum]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-04.html">[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla]</A> <A HREF="cox-05.html">[The metros]</A> <A HREF="cox-06.html">[Radio National (RN)]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-07.html">[Social Capital and the ABC]</A> <A HREF="cox-08.html">[The displeased piper's wanted tunes]</A><BR>
[The ABC too timid with alternative views?] <A HREF="cox-10.html">[Some proposals for changes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> <A HREF="cox-mr02.html">[A two day listening sample]</A></CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>The ABC too timid with alternative views?</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The ABC is accused of being partial to feminists and others who represent less mainstream views. This is not my perception and I am offering this personal view to indicate both the limits of one person's perception and whether of bias against the mainstream or lack of courage to support alternate views. As a frequent broadcaster offering views which may be seen as divergent, I am not satisfied that the ABC offers sufficient space to those promoting outside views. I have often seen media releases from feminist groups lose out to less significant, newsy or interesting stories because of nervous EPs.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
I am often used by EPs and researchers looking for briefings, phone numbers or other support and am willing to assist. I have many opportunities as well to present a comment in response to a question asked, but am also aware that being reasonable may mean that my comments are ignored in favour of more sensationalist approaches. While this is more common on the commercial networks, it also happens on the ABC where working within a combative news style is often more acceptable than exploring the story's dimensions.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
I am often also rejected as commentator with suggestions that I am over exposed. I acknowledge I do have reasonable access but this is mostly on the terms of the producer researcher. It is rarely that I have the capacity to frame my responses and control the issues being discussed. There are many men who are much more exposed than I am. There are regular commentators who are heard week in and out on news and public affairs as well as some of the specialist programs, but are not considered over exposed.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
There are rare exceptions. As the 1995 Boyer lecturer, I was offered a unique opportunity to develop and broadcast a range of ideas, not otherwise available. As a regular fortnightly broadcaster on Life Matters, I work happily with a group there to put forward ideas which are somewhat different. However, in most other cases, I have little control on whether the interview is used or how it is used.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
My views are validated by their popularity. The 1995 Boyers were the most popular ever, selling 5,000 copies despite poor supply as well as hundreds of copies on the internet while being broadcast. I am still being asked to address conferences as a result of the issues I raised. I also am reassured by the number of people, not only women, who welcome my Life Matters contributions and tell me so at conferences and even in supermarkets.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
I can only assume that there is some embarrassment at the success of the Boyers, and a lack of will to promote a public feminist spokesperson. Despite my wide legitimacy within a range of community organisations, churches etc and my almost mainstream status, there are many ABC producers both in radio and TV who find my views too divergent. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
I include this personal experience as just one example of many  others who have even less access. There are within the ABC many who are timorous, conservative and mainstream and these have considerable influence in the line up. Along with  many others who question many areas of public policy, I am concerned that few programs open up space for discussions of dissident views on any consistent basis.  Overall, these are not views which have received their due air time on the ABC and the programs which do offer time become anxious about their balance. There are some courageous producers, but there are, as in all organisations, many who prefer not to take risks. The ABC is better than the commercials in allowing diversity, but is still not good.
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

