</DOCHDR>
<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER AND CIVIL SOCIETY</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER<BR>
AND CIVIL SOCIETY</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> <A HREF="cox-02.html">[Political correctness and balance]</A> <A HREF="cox-03.html">[The agora or forum]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-04.html">[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla]</A> <A HREF="cox-05.html">[The metros]</A> <A HREF="cox-06.html">[Radio National (RN)]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-07.html">[Social Capital and the ABC]</A> <A HREF="cox-08.html">[The displeased piper's wanted tunes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-09.html">[The ABC too timid with alternative views?]</A> [Some proposals for changes]<BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> <A HREF="cox-mr02.html">[A two day listening sample]</A></CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>Some proposals for changes</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
How do you create a risk taking public broadcaster who both supports diversity and reflects the complexity of issues? The lesson from the present situation is that risk taking is not rewarded and being boringly mainstream is the only response. This has to be corrected. We need a funding system which allows the public broadcaster to be relatively free of major cuts and made more responsible for its own funding decisions.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
This is hard because the present culture is against this. The propositions tend to be to limit public spending and therefore the right to make cuts to the publicly funded is left in the public sphere. So maybe there needs to be a legislated base for funding so that at least cuts need to be supported by parliament. Maybe there should be an endowed body which provides at least some funding so that the old idea of the independence of the ABC through the licence fee can be revived in part.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>The charter</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
This should not be limited but expanded to recognise the changing role of media and multi media. The role of the ABC within this new environment needs to be defined, in part, as having a public goods function by being available to all free to air. There should be a restriction on the ABC moving in any substantial way into the provision of commercially based services in this area. Where the ABC develops products as offshoots of its main function as program maker eg Bananas, this is legitimate, but as a publicly funded body, it should not make commercial functioning its primary aim.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The prime focus should be free to air services on radio and TV and offering free services or at cost services on the Net. The corporatisation of the ABC needs to recognise that shifts to commercial operations as a priority,  make the ABC a non productive mix which has no clear brief. The distribution of resources in the new technological environment will be unequal and the ABC charter should possibly include a brief to offer free to air services to balance the system and provide for the information poor, as well as the rich.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The ABC must retain its roles as innovator, to encourage local music production and the arts. While there is support for many of these areas in the commercial and corporate sectors, this tends to be focused on the accepted and safe, so the ABC need to be there to encourage experimentation and the new.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The ABC must be there for all of us. Its role to balance the overall spectrum of broadcasters must be more clearly stated. So without becoming a minorities system, it must provide best practice examples of how a general broadcaster can be inclusive, not discriminatory. So its charter must be to create a national identity by ensuring all are heard so we can all feel part of the whole.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>Radio National must be retained, promoted and expanded. </B><BR>
The ABC generally, and RN in particular, need to promote their services as many people are unaware of their existence. I find many of my students are unaware of what is on offer or even the frequency. Yet, for the study they do, they need to listen and when they do, they often become converts. Therefore skimping on promotion is short sighted economy.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Savings should be partly in the management areas. There are probably savings in TV and it may be possible to use limited good overseas material on the local networks to maintain a quality network. Any attempt to water down the network and combine it with the metros, Newsradio or ABCFM will dilute the core functions and lead to an overall loss.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>No strip programming on RN,</B> this is metro territory and is not suitable for the national broadcaster. Retain the idea of produced stories and researched programs at recognisable times. Many RN listeners tune in for specific programs and they are lost if these move around. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>Do not seek out stars.</B> There are possible savings are in the area of personality presenters which have been used on RN and FM. If the ABC grows presenters, that is a benefit for both. If there is a person with particular skills, not available internally, they may be an asset. However, over the past few years there has been a push for developing name presenters which is both expensive and should not be necessary for the RN strand. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Geraldine Doogue is an exceptional presenter, who has won her place on merit and whose interviewing skills make the program what it is. However, trying to match her or find her peer for other programs is not an activity which works. If there is someone like here or Philip Adams, fine, but do not try and recreate these by looking for them.  The idea that other programs need strong presenters is not born out by research or practice. Developing good broadcasters from within is both cheaper and probably more in line with the overall ethos of public broadcasting.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Programs such as Life Matters are very important because they are one of the few areas of 'every day' life which is presented on air. The program offers a model in terms of content in covering a wide and interesting menu of programs and mixing regulars with daily type stories. Geraldine Doogue's strengths are her techniques as questioner presenter which are exceptional but hard to imitate or replace.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>News and current Affairs</B><BR>
Cuts in time for news and current affairs is disastrous for breadth and diversity. 15 minute news allows stories to be covered which are not covered elsewhere and allows for depth. The ten minute format reduces this and five minutes reduces this further. The loss of half of PM and The World Today  will effect serious limits on the topics covered and the depth of cover.  
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>The changes in RN need to be developed in the context of an overall strategy to maintain at least one network for those who want an overview, whose sense of belonging needs to be placed in a broader context, for those who want to be able to tune in and out but know it is there. A loss of RN as the national channel is a loss of identifiers and markers for us all, even those who rarely hear it. It is the ripple effects of a core commitment to a national broadcaster that benefits us all.</B>

</br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=430 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<KBD><B>Some thoughts from a thesaurus on words we need to refurbish and use!</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>public:</B> common, communal, joint , shared, civic, societal, civil, open, unrestricted general, popular, prevalent, widespread, accessible, open, people, society  
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>opposite:</B> private, individual, restricted, personal, commercial
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>domain:</B> a sphere of action or thought, area of control, territory, field terrain, speciality, realm.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>sovereign (republican subset):</B> autonomous, independent, free</BR> 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=1 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>opposite:</B> subordinate, deposed, dependent
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>civilise:</B> illuminate, enlighten and inform!</KBD>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>Eva Cox on behalf of the WETTANK</B>
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

