<HEAD><TITLE>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER AND CIVIL SOCIETY</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER<BR>
AND CIVIL SOCIETY</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> <A HREF="cox-02.html">[Political correctness and balance]</A> <A HREF="cox-03.html">[The agora or forum]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-04.html">[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla]</A> <A HREF="cox-05.html">[The metros]</A> <A HREF="cox-06.html">[Radio National (RN)]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-07.html">[Social Capital and the ABC]</A> <A HREF="cox-08.html">[The displeased piper's wanted tunes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-09.html">[The ABC too timid with alternative views?]</A> <A HREF="cox-10.html">[Some proposals for changes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> [A two day listening sample]</CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>A two day listening sample</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The issues brought up  in a couple of days monitoring on commercial talkback radio by presenters John Laws, Derryn Hinch, Allen Jones are all extremely similar, most coming straight from current news stories in the papers and listeners have to put up with constant advertising.  There are few guest speakers and seemingly no background research on topics as the presenters trot out their bigoted opinions.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The following constitutes some examples of what you could expect to hear on Commercial radio, in a day.  
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Alan Jones:  Sydney Casino - seeking tax exemption; paralympics; Liberal/National fight over seat belonging to Wendy Machin; Perot - US Elections; Health Services in New South Wales; Hugh Mackay report on people's attitudes; Fire in United States; Ballot coming up for marijuana use for medical purposes - California; Budget; Timber Workers protest; Budget protest in Canberra; a 'bloke' suing his vet about a parrot's broken leg.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
John Laws:  Health services in New South Wales; Budget Protest in Canberra; Wendy Machin's seat - Liberal/National problems; Interview with author of "Travelling Tales"; Man in Detroit shot himself in the penis when asleep;  Women shot herself after pistol fell out of her pants; Stolen baby (Travis) story.  
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Derryn Hinch:  Reads newspaper headlines for discussion topic frequently. Health cuts in New South Wales - interview with relation of victim of Port Arthur; Liberal/National fight over seat belonging to Wendy Machin; Sport - football;  Celibacy in the priesthood - is it  linked to child abuse?; Change in medicare levy;  hospital closures in New South Wales;  Australian missile carrying ship.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
As you can see, the above shows would not be appropriate listening material for the people who want information.  Their hosts could generally be said to be rude and bigoted, making unnecessary commentary on news topics, which I assume is in order to stir people up enough to phone in to the show.  I found some of the comments quite offensive, especially in regard to women.  Examples of some of the rude comments made include:  Alan Jones calling Jenny George, President of the ACTU,  a Prophetess of Doom (in a very derogatory tone of voice) and stating that she wasn't up to her job.  He also made inane, derogatory comments about Aboriginal, union and student movements: "they all want something for nothing".  As Eva mentioned earlier, John Laws calls women who dare to strive for some sort of independence "Feminazis".  
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The presenters are often male so I phoned the station manager at 2UE recently and asked about their EEO and Affirmative Action policies - his reply was that he didn't know exactly what Affirmative Action was, but they didn't have many secretaries there, mostly journalists. He wasn't joking.  With this type of attitude from the Station Manager, I guess one couldn't expect any more from his presenters. 
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Some of the issues raised in a day on Radio National in the same period as the above programs included topics such as changes in Superannuation tax benefits; Euthanasia;  Pyramid Building Society Court Case; United States Elections; Contracting out Public Services; Art in New South Wales Prison Centres;  Ian McFarlane's appointment to the Reserve Bank; Lambing season and cold Weather patterns; Cotton growing Productivity; Pollution in Coffs Harbour; The effects of chemicals on reproduction in humans;  Art auction for Science; Fishing Village program to save seahorses in the Philippines; Economics; Protest in Canberra;  Fitzgerald Enquiry;  Community policing.  
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
There can be no comparison between talkback on Radio National programs such as 'Life Matters' for example, and the simplistic drivel that comes out of the mouths of commercial radio show hosts.  
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Ron Casey, on his return to radio announced that he was needed on talkback radio because John Laws didn't give people a chance to speak if they disagreed with him and Brian Bury has talkback but there's nothing you could get offended by. ('The Sydney Morning Herald' on 26th August, 1996)  Obviously, the point is that the more offensive you can be to listeners the better the station masters like you.  
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Without the investment into research of the interesting range of programs on Radio National such as Radio Eye, Life Matters, Women Out Loud, Awaye, Background Briefing and Educational/talkback radio which many people in both rural and metropolitan areas rely upon - covering health, law, education, media and business,  the ABC could be reduced to covering sensationalised 'news stories', as do the commercial stations due to a lack of funding to research these valuable and informative programs.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
It is imperative to maintain the funding of all of Radio National's programs, as this station represents those who fund it.  The public.   The rationale behind the public funding of this institution is to maintain its independence in reporting and programming.  Any interference in this would be seen to be censorship by the Government.   
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Any funding outside of public monies would mean a curtailment of that independence if its reliance was upon commercial interests.  We wouldn't want an ABC presenter to confuse us about whether we were listening to a current topic or an advertisement (advertorial) as is frequently the case on John Laws' program, for instance.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Radio National should not be marginalised into a Specialist station either, its programming policy needs to remain complementary and comprehensive. Why not leave the Charter alone?  Just because it has been in place for 15 years, doesn't mean it has to change.  The reason that there is an 'extraordinary passion for the ABC' is that people like the ABC as it is.  They like the complementary and diverse nature of the ABC's programming.  
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The different facets of the various cultures which make up this country are what makes it so special.  The ABC's Radio National is unique as it reflects this variety of interests in an informed and intelligent way.  I believe the ABC should reflect the multiple facets of our unique national identity, which includes aspects of Anglo-Saxon, Indigenous and a variety of other cultures.  The ABC should not be reduced to a victim of economic ideologies.  It stands out far above the rest and acts as a keeper of our national identity.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<B>Marian Robinson <BR>
August 1996</B>
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

