<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER AND CIVIL SOCIETY</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER<BR>
AND CIVIL SOCIETY</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> [Political correctness and balance] <A HREF="Cox-03.html">[The agora or forum]</A><BR>
<A HREF="Cox-04.html">[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla]</A> <A HREF="Cox-05.html">[The metros]</A> <A HREF="Cox-06.html">[Radio National (RN)]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-07.html">[Social Capital and the ABC]</A> <A HREF="cox-08.html">[The displeased piper's wanted tunes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-09.html">[The ABC too timid with alternative views?]</A> <A HREF="cox-10.html">[Some proposals for changes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> <A HREF="cox-mr02.html">[A two day listening sample]</A></CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>Political correctness and balance</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The price of civilised society is eternal vigilance. Too many racist and sexist attitudes are still there and one of the frightening indications of changes in the political culture, is that some appear to be increasingly accepted. The messages being given in the political sphere are that middle Australia is basically Anglo and in traditional families. Recently, there has been a regular process of media scapegoating of groups such as the unemployed, Aboriginal services, refugees, migrants, 'middle class welfare' and those on social security and so on.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The PM, in his attacks on political correctness, has, presumably inadvertently, legitimated more virulent outpourings of the mob, the frightened but ill-informed who are looking for social scapegoats. They are likely to follow populist leaders, including those commentators who explain complex social and economic problems situations by blaming some of the victims. The searchers for simplistic solutions are prey to preachers of social snake oil.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The debate on political correctness, together with the emphasis on the supposed dominance and divisiveness of so called special interest groups, has been used to create tensions about representing minority views. There have been endless reported debates on commercial media about the presumed dominance of the air waves by the PC promoters without any examples ever being offered on local media. Similarly, the  accusations of bias against the ABC by our political masters has been based on selective quotes not on the basis of overall monitoring of the content of ABC radio or TV,  or on the spectrum of  broadcasting.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The fact that the PM and other complainants of bias were accompanied by both the Mansfield review and the budget cuts go to the core of the concept of public  broadcasting.  The conjunction gave a clear message 'don't displease the government or you will be punished!'. That process threatens free speech, and makes it harder for ABC management and staff to make proper professional judgements on what should go to air as they try to second guess their financial masters.  The ABC is owned by the public, not the government of the day, which is why there has been overwhelming support for it during this enquiry.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The existence and effectiveness of public broadcasters must be considered within a broader base of whether they, and they alone, can provide the space and resources which allow them to reflect the social mixes and diverse views which constitute the polity as well the society. There have been complaints that there are too many Aboriginal voices, for instance, but in terms of the totality of radio broadcasting, it is clear there are too few. Similarly the spaces for feminist debates or dissent are extremely limited, so the few opportunities we get on the ABC need to be balanced against the constant attacks on 'feminazis ' by Laws et al.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The rationale behind the public funding of this institution is to maintain its independence in reporting and programming.  Any interference in this would be seen to be censorship by the Government.  Any funding outside of public monies would mean a curtailment of that independence if its reliance was upon commercial interests.  We wouldn't want an ABC presenter to confuse us about whether we were listening to a current topic or an advertisement (advertorials) as are frequently the case on John Laws' program, for instance.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
We would see a public broadcasting presence as essential to provide balance in the overall broadcast system, not necessarily to always be balanced within its own programming. The limits of the programming on the commercial media would be exacerbated by any reduction in public broadcasting. It has often been the ABC which has developed new programs for TV and had these taken over by Commercial TV. The standards set by ABC documentaries and current affairs act as a benchmark for producers in other areas whose proprietors may not be interested in quality programs.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Good governance depends on the legitimation of diverse groups and interests. There is no possibility of a totally impartial broadcaster as we all carry within us our own desires, prejudices, interests and awareness. We can only set up frameworks where diversity is possible and the powerful cannot silence the less powerful.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
A public broadcaster must recognise the complexity of social issues, the diversity of views and tastes, the power imbalances which inhibit access to media. The complexity of needs within all social sectors suggests that any loss of breadth or depth within the ABC may result in excluding groups of people and views which have both the right to be heard and which also need to be heard for the development of a healthy society.
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
