<HR>
<Font size=7>Article archive</Font size=7>
<H2>Independent news service</H2>
<P>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<Font size=3>Asia-Pacific Network provides independent journalism on social, political, environmental and development issues in the Asia-Pacific region. The following is a selection of some of the articles. Seek permission from the editor before republication. <P>
<Font size=1>Copyright  <A HREF="drobie@pactok.peg.apc.org">David Robie</A> and the authors. PO Box 78028, Auckland 2, Aotearoa/New Zealand, or PO Box 273, Uni PO, NCD, Papua New Guinea.
</Font size=1>
<P>
<HR>
<IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"> <FONT SIZE=4><B><A NAME="1969">1969 VIETNAM</A></B></FONT>
<P>
<UL><LI><Font size=3><A HREF="aspac/viet.html"><IMG SRC="../images/vcover.gif" width=100 ALT="My Lai cover"><BR>
<B>MY LAI MASSACRE: 'SOMETHING DARK AND BLOODY'</A><BR>
<IMG SRC="../images/new.gif"> Sunday Observer: 14 December 1969</B><BR>
<I>Photographs by Ronald Haeberle</I><BR>
The Melbourne Sunday Observer.-- the original paper of that name which campaigned against Australian involvement as a US surrogate in the Vietnam War -- published photographs of the My Lai massacre. It was prosecuted for "obscenity" but the charge was dropped before reaching court.
<P></UL>
<HR>
<IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"> <FONT SIZE=4><B><A NAME="1995">1995</A></B></FONT>
<P>
<UL><LI><Font size=3><A HREF="http://www.oneworld.org/gemini/gemini_guinea.html"><B>POLITICS: GREAT ACHIEVEMENT -- OR SLIDE INTO DICTATORSHIP?</A><BR>
Gemini News Service: 18 July 1995</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
Papua New Guinea has thrown out its provincial government system in spite of bitter opposition from several premiers. The prime minister has hailed the new law as the "most crucial" achievement since independence. However, opponents claim the country is sliding into dictatorship.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.oneworld.org/gemini/wk42_gemini_bio.html"><B>SCIENCE: 'BIO-PIRATES' FACE CHALLENGE IN PACIFIC BLOOD FEUD</A><BR>
Gemini News Service: October 1995</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
Arguments over the patenting of products derived from plant and animal life are being given a new twist with a controvery over who will gain from the development of a cancer virus obtained from the blood of a small group of Pacific Islanders.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://acij.uts.edu.au/PJR/issues/back95/95vision.html"><B>MEDIA: SHARE THE WHOLE VISION, GOOD NEWS AND BAD</A> <BR>
Pacific Journalism Review: Vol 2 No 1 November 1995</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
Image-massagers sprucing up Pacific government images aren't enough. While issues such as the raskol problem, land disputes and Bougainville remain unresolved, there will continue to be a 'bad press'.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://acij.uts.edu.au/PJR/issues/back95/95rainbow.html"><IMG SRC="../images/french.gif" width=175 ALT="French spy cartoon"><BR><B>ENVIRONMENT: A PHOTOGRAPHER'S DATE WITH A NUCLEAR DEATH</A> *Photos<BR>
Pacific Journalism Review: Vol 2 No 1 November 1995</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
President Jacques Chirac's controversial final round of nuclear tests at Moruroa and Fangataufa atolls in 1995 unleashed an unprecedented storm of international protest. And dilemmas for journalists covering the riots in Papeete and the junkets by French authorities. The Vanuatu government banned news reports on protests. A journalist on board the original environmental campaign ship <I>Rainbow Warrior</I> -- bombed by French secret agents a decade ago -- recalls the events. He was later arrested by the French military.</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"> <FONT SIZE=4><B><A NAME="1996">1996</A></B></FONT>
<P>
<UL><LI><FONT SIZE=3><A HREF="http://www.oneworld.org/gemini/wk4_papua.html"><B>RESOURCES: CUSTOMARY LAND FIGHT OVER OIL WEALTH</A><BR>Gemini News Service: 19 January 1996</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
A legal test case of customary land rights has added a new twist to Papua New Guinea's long-running disputes between indigenous clans and big companies exploiting rich natural resources. The case comes amid threats to disrupt oil production and fears of violent clashes.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.pactok.net.au/docs/nius/library/jun96/9603231.htm"><B>MEDIA: PACIFIC PRESS FREEDOM UNDER SIEGE</A><BR>
Asia Pacific Network: 23 March 1996</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
South Pacific governments have been seeking greater "accountability" from the news media. News executives have accused governments of tampering with traditional press freedom. But the issue has largely been a war of words. Now the arbitrary detention of a Tongan editor for publishing pro-democracy letters has stunned the region.<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://pactok.net.au:80/docs/nius/library/june96/9605282.htm"><B>RESOURCES: PNG GOVERNMENT GETS 'DRILLED' BY AUSTRALIAN OIL MAN</A><BR>
Inter Press News Service: 24 May 1996</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
Fed up with the Papua New Guinea government's failure to curb violent crime, high unemployment rates and reports of abuses of power by the police force, ordinary and prominent citizens in the South Pacific nation are rallying behind an Australian businessman who dared allege corruption in the Sir Julius Chan administration.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="aspac/tribal.html"><B>HUMAN RIGHTS: TRIBULATIONS OF A TRIBAL GIRL</A><BR>
Inter Press News Service and NZ Political Review: 26 May 1996</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
A case of "payment" of a young woman in compensation over the death of a man in a poice shoot-out in Papua New Guinea has raised national interest and has renewed calls by human rights groups for the speedy establishment of a National Human Rights Commission. Yet women's non-government organisations and other groups have been reluctant to make an issue of this human "sale" 
<P>
<LI><A HREF="http://pactok.net.au:80/docs/nius/library/june96/9606214.htm"><B>BOUGAINVILLE: CHAN'S GAMBLE FACES FLAK</A> <BR>
Asia-Pacific Network: 21 June 1996</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
Frustrated by the failure torn quell the Bougainville rebels and growing tension on the Solomon Islands border with protests over incursions, the Chan government has taken a tough military option. But peace advocates warn Sir Julius Chan has embarked on a risky gamble that may backfire.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="aspac/frangipani.html"><B>MEDIA: BEHIND THE FRANGIPANI FACADE</A> <BR>
Reportage Media Bulletin: August 1996</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
Like governments and editors elsewhere, those in the South Pacific regularly trade accusations about press freedom. But the arbitrary detention of a Tongan journalist for publishing pro-democracy letters has shocked the region.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="aspac/line.html"><B>MEDIA: PNG ON THE LINE </A> <BR>
Reportage Media Bulletin: August 1996</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
A logging company that owns a national newspaper, the Pacific's 'best' newspaper renamed and revamped, and now an inquiry into media accountability -- Papua New Guinea's media is going through interesting times.</UL>
<IMG SRC="../images/updated.gif"> 28 October 1996
