<html>
<head><title>Snoop:Maralinga Remembered</title></head>

<frameset cols="20%,*">

<NOFRAMES>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#0000ff"> 
<BASEFONT SIZE=4>
 
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 
 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=630>
<TR><TD><IMG WIDTH=400 SRC="../IMAGES/snoop.gif"> 
</TD></TR></TABLE>
 
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=400>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=400><FONTSIZE=+1><B>Spring 1995</B></TD> 
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT><B>MARALINGA</B></TD></FONT>
</TR></TABLE> 

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400> 
<TR><TD WIDTH=400 VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Maralinga Remembered</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="#Cathy Pryor">By Cathy Pryor</A></FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
 
<P>IN THE inner Sydney suburb of Glebe, John Hutton is going through
his files, pulling out letters and documents which he hopes will 
tell his story. Behind him on a wall is a framed sketch which 
appeared in the Sydney Morning Herald in October 1984. It depicts 
Hutton giving evidence before the Maralinga Royal Commission. 
Hutton draws out the now yellowed press clipping which features 
the drawing. There was no mention of what happened to him, he 
says, waving it in the air, &quot;not one&quot;. 
<P> 
In 1956, Hutton was a 19 year-old field engineer working for the 
army at Maralinga, the plain in South Australia where the British 
government conducted their now infamous atomic tests during the 
1950s and 1960s. In 1984 when the Hawke government set up a royal 
commission to investigate the tests, Hutton was called as a witness. 
His tale of finding an Aboriginal family living in a bomb crater 
was to be one of the more chilling anecdotes in the year- long 
hearing. 
<P> 
More than ten years since he recounted that story, Hutton's bravado 
is fading. Like more than 45 other atomic ex-servicemen and widows, 
he is waiting for his compensation case against the Commonwealth 
to be heard. Like hundreds of others, his claim lodged under the 
workers' compensation legislation has been rejected and the Federal 
Court is the only path left. But Hutton is not counting on victory. 
&quot;The government doesn't want any part of us,&quot; he says. 
&quot;They just want us to go away and die. It's as simple as 
that, and the quicker we do, the better.&quot; 
<P> 
When the recommendations of the royal commission into British 
nuclear tests in Australia were tabled in parliament in December 
1985, none of them dealt directly with compensation arrangements 
for the ex-servicemen. Although the head of the commission, the 
then Justice James McClelland, has argued it was not the commission's 
role to look into the system of compensation, veteran groups which 
were fundamental in pushing for the inquiry, felt their claims 
were effectively ignored. For Hutton, the Royal Commission was 
an &quot;utter farce&quot; and the ex-servicemen are the &quot;forgotten 
victims&quot; of Maralinga. 
<P> 
In the decade since the royal commission, few of the 12,500 servicemen 
employed by the Australian army, navy and airforce to work at 
the test sites have received compensation for their involvement, 
There has been no lump sum settlement to them as a group and, 
since the commission, only one case through the courts has been 
successful. 
<P> 
Like other government employees who allege work-related injury, 
the ex-servicement have also been able to claim under the workers' 
compensation legislation. This legislation underwent a multitude 
of changes until the Military Compensation Scheme (MCS) was introduced 
last year and the department in charge of the claims was shifted 
in late 1991 from Comcare, the agency in charge of government 
employees' compensation, to the department of Defence. 
<P> 
The many changes have added to the confusion and feelings of neglect 
amongst the ex-servicemen, although the basic requirements for 
claims have remained largely the same. tp qualify for benefits, 
the ex-servicemen must be able to prove on the balance of probabilities 
that they were exposed to radiation, their illness was caused 
by radiattionm and was a direct result of their work for the government. 
<P> 
Yet out of the 11claims investigated by the Department of Defence 
since late 1991 only one has been successful and of the 390 claims 
lodged with Comcare just over 20 were allowed. Instead of restitution,
 the ex-servicemen have found themselves at the centre of a legal 
and medical dilemma which no-one seems able to solve. 
<P> 
Glen Tye is the Assistand Diorector of Compensation and Rehabilitation 
in the department of Defence. While he argues his department is 
sympathetic towards the ex-servicemen, there is nothing it can 
do to further accomodate them. &quot;We are certainly not about 
knocking out claims,&quot; he sys, &quot;but we are talking about 
a long, long time ago when people's memories are fairly sketchy. 
<P>

</TABLE>

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE>

<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400> 
<TR><TD WIDTH=400><FONT SIZE=+1><CENTER><B><A Name="Health">Health</A> - Three more cases</B>
</FONT></CENTER><BR>
<P>In 1987 Ric Johnston was awarded $867,000 damages for anxiety 
neurosis and agrophobia, successfully arguing his sicknesses were 
a result of working as a RAAF transport driver and mechanic at 
Maralinga in 1956. In 1994, another ex-serviceman wasn't so fortunate. 
Wesley Dingwass claimed his mental difficulties, including nightmares, 
flashbacks and a drinking problem, arose after his work in the 
army canteen 30km north of Maralinga. He lost his case. The judge 
concluded that most of Dingwall's anxieties were generated later 
when reports started surfacing in the 80s about the extent of 
radiation at Maralinga. The third case is still before the Federal 
Court. In the first cancer case of an ex-servicemanm Pedro Cubillo 
is alleging his kydney cancer was caused by exposure to alpha 
radiation while he was working as field engineer at Maralinga 
in 1957 and 1958. What safety precautions were in place at the 
time, how much risk was there, did the government do everything 
it could to prevent the risks are just some of the issues being 
addressed, as well as the inevitable question of how much radiation 
exposure Cubillo was actually exposed to and if that amount 'materially 
contributed' to his cancer. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD>
</TR>
 
<TR>
<TD>
<I><A Name="Cathy Pryor">Cathy Pryor</A> is a practising journalist and former Communications 
student of the University of Technology, Sydney</I> 
</TD>
</TR>
</TD> 
</TR> 
 
</TABLE>
