<html>
<head><title>Snoop: FILIPINO EXPORT LABOUR</title></head>

<frameset cols="20%,*">

<NOFRAMES>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#0000ff"> 
<BASEFONT SIZE=4>
 
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 
 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400>
<TR><TD><IMG WIDTH=400 SRC="../IMAGES/snoop.gif"> 
</TD></TR></TABLE>
 
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=400>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=400><FONTSIZE=+1><B>Spring 1995</B></TD> 
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Filipino Labour</B></TD></FONT>
</TR></TABLE> 

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400> 
<TR><TD WIDTH=400 VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Modern Day Slaves
</FONT><BR></B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<I>Between 2.5 and 3.5 million Filipinos work in over 140 countries.
More than 2,000 are in overseas jails, two were beheaded in Saudi
Arabia, one was hanged in Singapore, thousands suffer slavery
and abuse. What are the Philippines and the world doing about
it?<A HREF="#Lia Timson"> LIA TIMSON</A> reports.</I>
<P>
THE March execution of Filipino domestic worker Flor Contemplacion
in Singapore symbolised over two decades of exploitation and injustice
for Filipino workers worldwide.
<P>
The implications of her hanging have been felt beyond the shores
of the Philippines and Singapore, causing many to question the
role played by the Philippines and other governments in exploiting
what has been called &#147;an internationally shared resource&#148;.
<P>
Maria Elena Ang, an activist with the worldwide Filipino alliance
group Migrante and chairperson for the Centre for Filipino Concerns
(CPCA) in NSW, believes Flor Contemplacion was innocent. Mallen,
as she likes to be called, was at the University of Technology,
Sydney in May to address students on the human rights issue facing
millions of Filipinos working overseas.
<P>
&#147;Flor did not have the support of the [Filipino] consulate
officials. She was advised to confess to the crimes so her sentence
would be shortened,&#148; she said.
<P>
The Singaporean Government that hanged Contemplacion has admitted
to the use of &#147;extra firm methods&#148; to extract confessions.
Mallen talks from experience: &#147;I&#146;d say [that means]
torture. I&#146;ve been a torture victim myself.&#148; She understands
the pressure to confess to crimes one may not have committed.
<P>
The widely publicised case of Contemplacion, who was charged with
killing another maid and her ward, is just the tip of the iceberg
that is the Filipino Government&#146;s Labour Export Policy.
<P>
The Policy dates back to the late 1970s when the Government took
over from illegal recruiters and established Overseas Development
Boards to organise, legalise and benefit from the exporting of
Filipino labour.
<P>
Today, between 2.5 and 3.5 million Filipinos are categorised as
Overseas Contract Workers (OCWs) working in more than 140 countries.
<P>
Every year over 700,000 Filipinos join those already overseas
in search of a better life. &#147;They would rather take the risk
of going abroad, as long as they think there is even just a little
hope of doing better,&#148; says Boots Medina from Kangulan, a
Filipino non-government organisation focusing on migrant issues.
<P>
Around 60 per cent of all Filipino OCWs are women, many married
with children, who leave all behind because they feel extra responsibility
to care for their families.
<P>
A report entitled Filipino Migration to Canada, by the Philippine
Women Centre in Vancouver, explains the Filipino world migration
has happened over three decades in a pattern easily defined as
three waves.
<P>
The first wave in the late 1960s accounts for the nationals who
went abroad in search of jobs appropriate to their academic qualifications.
It is reported they were mostly professional nurses, midwives,
medical technicians, managers and engineers who fled to countries
such as the USA, Canada, the Netherlands, Austria, Britain, Germany
and Switzerland. Mallen said American hospitals, for example,
would collapse today if Filipino workers were to walk out; such
are their numbers. 
<P>
The second wave, in the 1970s, is linked to the declaration of martial law in the Philippines in 1972. Similarly to Maria
Elena, who believed the introduction of the law was a threat to
the freedom of the Philippines&#146; nationals, average citizens
fled the country, this time in search of freedom. They were mostly
textile, manufacturing, sales and clerical workers. This coincided
with the relaxation of immigration laws in the USA, Canada and
Asia, where cheaper labour was now needed. It also coincided with
the economic boom in Hong Kong which demanded extra labour from
neighbouring countries.
<P>
The third wave, the one most interlocked with human rights abuse,
came in the 1980s and still continues. This time, Filipinos, mostly
women, are leaving their homeland and their families because of
the worsening economic and political crisis. According to a Hong
Kong report presented at the International Consultation of Migrante
in December last year, the majority of all Filipino migrants are
professionals (teachers, accountants, engineers, architects) or
university graduates and even government employers. Most are aged
between 20 and 39.
<P>
Regardless of their background, the great majority are domestic
workers. For example, maids account for 90 per cent of the 140,000
Filipinos working in Hong Kong. The Philippine Women Centre in
Vancouver also reports that, between 1982 and 1991, more than
30,000 Filipinos were legally admitted into Canada as domestic
workers.
<P>
Australia would be forgiven for thinking Flor Contemplacion&#146;s
case is one in a million given the limited press coverage other
events have had. But research conducted by Snoop reveals the extent
of the problem created by a lack of meaningful government protection
from both the Philippines and the host countries. There have been
two reported cases of beheading of maids in Saudi Arabia. Last
year, 42 Filipinos were shipped back dead from Saudi Arabia to
their homeland. Migrante said no government enquiry followed.
<P>
In Japan, where a great number of Filipino workers are employed
in the entertainment industry, 30 Filipinos have been killed or
are reported missing but there have been no questions asked by
the Filipino authorities. World Vision of Australia reports that
one maid working in Singapore &#147;was blinded by her employer
because she forgot to hang some clothes in the wardrobe&#148;.
<P>
In late May, another Filipino domestic worker jumped off a Hong
Kong building for fear of prosecution after been found working
a part-time job. 
<P>
Over 2,000 Filipinos are remanded in overseas jails, 26 facing
death penalties. CPCA believes Filipinos are being used as scapegoats
for other peoples crimes. Being incriminated is just one of the
abuses suffered by Filipino OCWs. Other infringements of human
rights vary from simply being overworked and underpaid &#151;
some Hong Kong maids are reported to work 20-hour days &#151;
to physical and verbal abuse, racism, rape and confiscation of
passports until their &#145;debt&#146; is paid off. Some are forced
to surrender to sexual favours and prostitution to service the
debt. This is determined by some of the employers and may include expenses such
as initial airfare, accommodation and daily meals.
<P>
Poe Gretela, secretary-general for Migrante worldwide, said the
Philippines are wary of complaining about maltreatment of their
nationals by host countries in fear of jeopardising their continuous
intake of labour. Already the Foreign Maids Employment Agencies
Association in Singapore has begun importing workers from Sri Lanka instead.
<P>
Gretela, who himself was a migrant worker in Saudi Arabia is now
unemployed in the Philippines. He said the government has failed
to fix the internal unemployment and underemployment problems,
and it is not willing to enter bilateral agreements with labour
importing nations to protect workers. 
<P>
&#147;At present, the government itself is one of the problems.
They are creating laws and policies which they call protection,
but in reality they are a burden for the migrant workers,&#148;
he said.
<P>
Former Philippines Labour Secretary and International Labour Organisation&#146;s
(ILO) chairperson, Nieves Confesor was reported as saying: &#147;Filipino
overseas labour should be viewed as an internationally shared
human resource, whose work benefits both the host country and
the Philippines.&#148;
<P>
Migrante&#146;s Gretela refutes that view: &#147;That is very
degrading. How can you share your migrant workers when they are
treated as modern slaves in different countries. The expertise
of the migrant worker should be used for the development of our
own country and secondarily for the development of other countries
&#151; not to provide &#145;entertainment&#146; and cheap labour
for foreign capitalist [countries].&#148;
<P>
Migrante&#146;s long term goal is to create an attractive domestic
economy so workers will not have to go overseas to support their
families. The organisation is currently lobbying the Government
to end invitations to capitalist nations to invest in the Philippines,
as they believe this would further contribute to the worsening
of local employment. They want the Government to change its policies
on OCWs, so they don&#146;t have to sacrifice their rights to
earn a living. &#147;Maybe that&#146;s one reason why we are called
modern day heroes, because the Government really intends to sacrifice
migrant workers,&#148; Gretela said. &#147;The workers are really
in the losing end.&#148;
</TD> 
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
