<html>
<head><title>Snoop: Vietnam, Welcoming the tourist dollar</title></head>

<frameset cols="20%,*">

<NOFRAMES> 
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#0000ff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=4>
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 
 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400>
<TR><TD><IMG WIDTH=400 SRC="../IMAGES/snoop.gif"> 
</TD></TR></TABLE>
 
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=400>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT><FONTSIZE=+1><B>Spring 1995</B></TD> 
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT><B>VIETNAM</B></TD></FONT>
</TR></TABLE> 

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400> 
<TR><TD WIDTH=400 VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Vietnam - welcoming the tourist dollar
</B></FONT><BR>
</CENTER>

<P>
<I>One generation's tour of duty is fast becoming the next generation's
pleasure dome. Twenty years after the end of the war, Vietnam
is experiencing an invasion of another kind as young tourists
flock to see the land that  preoccupied a generation and spawned
decades of Hollywood blockbusters. <A HREF="#DAVID BROWNE">DAVID BROWNE</A> reports.</I>
<P>
IN THE city of Hue, Vietnam&#146;s ancient imperial capital, I
join a group of tourists in a cafe while they discuss the one
topic it seems impossible to avoid - The War. Arguments are being
made confidently in German, Irish, and English accents.
<P>
Comparing the attitudes of young Western travellers and a Vietnamese
of the same age, you get the impression they are talking about
totally different events that happened in a different place. 
But they are talking about the same war. The tourists are bringing
with them interpretations of the war that are at odds with both
the official Hanoi government history and the experiences of people
who lived through it. 
<P>
Most backpackers know Vietnam as the backdrop for popular movies
and TV series. For most of their lives it was the hyper real setting
for unofficial versions of the war like Rambo, Tour of Duty, and
Hamburger Hill that show the American troops as the good guys
betrayed by both their own nation and a brutal faceless enemy
that refuses to stand up and fight. There is an overbearing sense
that the victory was within the grasp of the Americans but somehow
it was thrown away. Many of the Vietnamese are surprised Westerners
have such strong opinions about an event that happen 20 years
ago. 
<P>
For America the loss was seen is an humiliating failure and for
the Vietnamese it marks the beginning of a period of international
isolation and a slide into poverty. The small, former French colony,
with its agricultural economy, was shattered by massive American
firepower in the North while huge amounts of American aid in the
South virtually crippled the local economy. 
<P>
But while Vietnam was cut off from the rest of the world, the
West  was cut off from Vietnam, and 20 years later people are
still trying to make sense of the war.
<P>
As the anniversary of Saigon&#146;s fall approached and passed
earlier this year the media was saturated with opinions from people
who planned the war, fought in the war, or fought against the
war. It raised massive contradictions, many of which still are
unresolved. It was a war fought on behalf of democracy, though
America&#146;s failure was blamed, by some, on weaknesses in the
democratic system. It was a war where the world&#146;s largest
industrial nation was defeated by a peasant army from a backward
agricultural country, and although it was called an unpopular
war, no other conflict has been as thoroughly reported, reviewed,
and recreated by the media. 
<P>
In the mid 1980&#146;s, before both the USSR and China, Vietnam
began to loosen control of its centrally planned economy. Since
then, despite some teething problems, it has been in a constant
upward spiral of economic growth.  Last year when US President,
Bill Clinton, lifted America&#146;s 17 year economic embargo outlawing
virtually all trade with Vietnam, the economy moved into a boom
cycle similar to other South-East Asian countries like Thailand,
Malaysia, and Indonesia.  
<P>
Tourism is an important element of the Vietnam government&#146;s
economic revival. It brings in the hard currency needed to pay
for repairs to the nation&#146;s war damaged infrastructure. While
the mainstream tourist industry is still underdeveloped, Vietnam
has become a popular destination for the bottom end backpacker
and young travellers prepared to rough it in the run down hotels
and relatively primitive conditions. During the last five years
the number of tourists visiting Vietnam has increased to the point
where accommodation shortages are occurring during the peak season.
 
<P>
In Saigon&#146;s backpacker cafes, groups of young tourists meet
to make travel plans and pass time. &#147;Why did the Americans
just give up?&#148; Alex, an Australian chemistry student asks
rhetorically. &#147;I mean they had the firepower. Why did they
give up?&#148;
<P>
Karl, a German engineer who claims to have been in a re-education
camp in the East, is even more convinced the US should have easily
defeated the communists. &#147;People should always fight against communism,&#148;
he says. 
<P>
&#147;The Americans should never have left Vietnam, no matter
what the cost. The people did not want to live under communism,
ask anyone,&#148; he says gesturing towards the crowded street.
 
<P>
But Nisha, an Irish student studying at London University, disagrees:
&#147;The war was good for Vietnam. It was a good thing. It allowed Vietnam
to be independent and showed the Americans that they couldn&#146;t
push the rest of the world around.&quot;
<P>
A group of Americans are vaguely disturbed when someone tells
them they could be breaking the US &#145;Trading with the Enemy&#146;
act that forbids spending more than 100 dollars in countries officially
listed as hostile. &#147;Yeah right, these guys are the enemy,&#148;
says one pointing at Vietnamese children playing nearby.  
<P>
Most seem content to talk about the war, the conversations are
inevitable &#147;Avoid white faces,&#148; says a New Zealand businessman
who lives in Vietnam. &#147;That&#146;s the only way to avoid
hearing about it.&#148; 
<P>
The Vietnamese seem much less interested in the war although anyone
over the age of 20 would surely have been affected by it in some
way.  In Saigon I ask a waitress for her opinion and she simply
says &#147;I don&#146;t like war,&#148; then changes the subject.
 
<P>
A student from an English college shows me his essay describing
&#147;the wars of liberation&#148;. The American conflict is just
one of the most recent in a series of struggles that cover more
than a thousand years of Vietnam&#146;s history. In general the
Vietnamese don&#146;t seem interested in discussing the war. For
them the subject doesn&#146;t contain the same contradictions
that plague Western views. They won the war and now the nation
is focused on the future. 
<P>
&#147;I find it difficult to talk about the war, because I am
a victim of the war,&#148; says a Vietnamese journalist who has
visited Australia. &#147;I lost my whole childhood to the war.&#148;
She says she is surprised it is still debated so passionately
in the West and shocked some people still claim it was a just
cause. &#147;After 20 years I thought people would forget.  The
Vietnamese have put the war behind them. At first people were
overwhelmed by the victory but in the decade after, life became
very difficult due to the embargo and economic policies. We became
very poor, and having a difficult life makes it more attractive
to look forward.&#148; In 1988 English critics Alf Lourve and
Jeffrey Walsh published an essay on media coverage of Vietnam.
It argued Hollywood&#146;s version of Vietnam tended to mirror
public attitudes. Throughout the &#145;70s, the war was all but
ignored except for films depicting veterans being transformed
into killers, drug addicts, and criminals by their experiences.
But during the &#145;80s, with Ronald Reagan in the White House,
a new spate of Vietnam films reflected a revised American patriotism.
 Movies of the Rambo era showed American troops as brave innocents
led by incompetent officers and undermined by weak liberal dissent
at home. The result was a powerful rewriting of the war&#146;s
history via popular culture. 
<P>
The Rambo generation has landed in Vietnam. The opinions of many
of the backpackers seem to be based on what they have seen in movies
and on television rather than historical accounts of the war.
There is a certainty that the US was somehow cheated, the communists used unfair tactics, and the American
anti-war movement put the army in a position where it was forced
to fight with one hand tied behind its back.  
<P>
This lasting interest with the war is not lost on the Vietnamese
who are now capitalising on it. An interested tourist can visit
the sites of famous battles like Khe Shan (the place that inspired
a Cold Chisel song) and Dien Bien Phu. Enterprising locals have
even enlarged one of the Viet Cong underground fortresses so that
Westerners can fit down the tunnels. Vung Tow, a beach town south
of Saigon, has a rifle range where, for a dollar a bullet, you
can fire a Russian made AK47 or an American M16 at your choice
of target - US Marine or Viet Cong fighter.  
<P>
Saigon has markets where American war surplus material like helmets,
duffel bags, and water cans are sold. Jewellery shops sell American
Zippo lighters engraved with slogans like &#145;Air Cav - If you
don&#146;t know what hell is like fuck with me and you&#146;ll
find out,&#146; and &#145;We are the unwilling, led by the unqualified,
doing the unnecessary, for the ungrateful.&#146;  
<P>
Other entrepreneurs have opened cafes like the &#145;Apocalypse
Bar&#146; where the stereo blasts out American music from the
60&#146;s - Jimi Hendrix and The Doors - and American drinks and
cigarettes are available from the bar. 
<P>
In the coastal town Da Nang, not far from where the first US Marines
landed in Vietnam, I talk to a group of school children. They
are 15 or 16, born after the war which doesn&#146;t come up in
their conversation. One girl, Linh, says she wants to be an English
teacher and invites my friends and I to visit her home to drink
tea and talk. In the garden there is a rusty American helmet that
looks as though it is used as a bucket or some similar purpose.
I prod it with my foot and she says &#147;That&#146;s old, kick
it aside&#148;, and continues talking about her plans for the
future. 
<P>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>
<I><A Name="David Browne">David Browne</A> is a Master of Arts (Journalism) student at UTS and
is a journalist at the ABC.</I>
</TD> 
</TR> 
</TABLE>

