<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Snoop:Are drug users victims of heroin or victims of our drug laws?</TITLE></HEAD>
  
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#0000ff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=4>
 
<HR ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 
 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=630>
<TR><TD><IMG WIDTH=400 SRC="../IMAGES/snoop.gif"> 
</TD></TR></TABLE>
 
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=400>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=400><FONTSIZE=+1><B>Spring 1995</B></TD> 
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT><B>Drug Victims</B></TD></FONT>
</TR></TABLE> 

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400> 
<TR><TD WIDTH=400 VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Eluding Reality
</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1>Are drug users victims of heroin or victims of our drug laws?
</FONT></B><BR>
</CENTER>
 
<P>
<I>Lately the chances of being killed if you use heroin are much higher. Since the arrival in March of a shipment of high-grade
&#147;rock-heroin&#148;, more than 50 people have died from heroin overdoses in NSW and the ACT. <A HREF="#Jennie Christian">JENNIE CHRISTIAN </A>reports.</I>
<P>
OVERDOSING is the main health risk for heroin users - during the last decade deaths from heroin overdose have increased 170 per cent. But the
danger is not only from higher drug purity. Heroin mixed with alcohol or other drugs can be a lethal cocktail. Because it is
illegal, heroin users cannot be sure of the drug&#146;s purity, so may end up taking more than they can handle. After an overdose
has occurred, a user&#146;s friends may decide not to call an ambulance because they fear police intervention.
<P>
Judy Byrne is co-ordinator of the ACT Intravenous Needle League, which provides needle exchange, assessment and referral to drug
users. She says: &#147;The heroin seems to be getting more and more potent, which isn&#146;t a problem for users who use every
day, and are actually getting their money&#146;s worth, but it is a problem for those who are new at it or who only use occasionally,
who have no way of gauging the quality of what they&#146;re getting.&#148;
<P>
&#147;I think there&#146;s got to be an acknowledgment that people who take heroin to that extent don&#146;t need criminal sanctions,
they need medical help and supervision. You don&#146;t ruin your life ... for the hell of it. Until we have some understanding
about drug addiction, we&#146;ve got to back off and be a bit human about it. We cringe at the way we treated people with mental
problems in mental institutions in the 18th century, and in a few years from now we&#146;ll be cringing at the way we treated
people with drug dependence. It&#146;s just part of the human scope and we don&#146;t seem to be able to acknowledge it.&#148;
<P>
Several leading health professionals, lawyers and academics have repeatedly claimed prohibitive drugs policies are devastating
to Australia&#146;s economy, health and society. Current drug laws are &#147;unsustainable, ineffective and counterproductive&#148;,
according to Dr Alex Wodak, Director of Alcohol and Drug Services at St Vincent&#146;s Hospital in NSW. For 13 years Wodak has had
daily contact with drug and alcohol abusers and is a leader in the drug and alcohol field. 
<P>
&#147;Illicit drug policies magnify the harm that they are meant to prevent,&#148; he says. &#147;There is some recognition of
this now in law enforcement circles and the police recognise that they are set up to fail in the illicit drugs area, where the more
effort and energy they put in, the more they are rewarded by seeing drug prices go higher and property crime increasing.&#148;
<P>
A report by Dr Gabrielle Bammer of the Australian National University's National Centre for Epidemiology and Population Health has recommended
the prescripotionof heroin to 40 addicts in the ACT, the first stage of a proposed $2.3m trial. A decision on whether to go ahead
isunlikely before the end of the year, and would entail state and federal government support and Commonwealth funding. If the
trial is approved, could this be the beginning of the end of heroin prohibition in Australia? 
<P>
Since the advent of worldwide drug prohibition, it has been believed
that illegal drugs can be purged by putting sufficient resources into the &#147;war on drugs&#148;. But this belief is under attack.
Since the 1961 UN convention on narcotic drugs, drug use has increased
throughout the world. Last year the $US400 billion drug trade surpassed petroleum to become the world&#146;s second largest
industry. Only the arms trade was more lucrative.
<P>
Advocates of drug law reform in Australia point to the huge cost of enforcing the drug laws through the police, courts and the
prison system; as well as the costs to society caused by a virulent black market, drug-related crime, corruption and a clogged legal
system. Not least is the risk of accidental poisoning and overdose from consuming adulterated drugs, and the spread of infectious
diseases such as hepatitis and AIDS.
<P>
In 1988, the cost of illicit drug use in Australia was conservatively estimated at $1.5 billion. Now it may be closer to $500 billion.
The annual turnover of the illegal drug trade in Australia was estimated at about $3 billion in 1989. Yet despite increased efforts
to enforce drug laws, less than 10 per cent of illegal drugs in circulation are seized.
<P>
Dr Jara Krivanek, author and formerly director of clinical drug dependence studies at Macquarie University, believes myths about
illegal drugs are propagated by governments and the media. The myths portray heroin is inherently evil, and the &#147;drug addict&#148;
is condemned as a hopeless captive of his drug, preyed upon by pushers. But Krivanek said the truth about many illegal drugs
is startlingly different.
<P>
Heroin, she says, is one of the most effective painkillers ever known. It relieves mental and physical pain, eases anxiety and
produces a feeling of tranquillity, elation and confidence. For medical use, it may be more effective than morphine in the treatment
of terminally ill patients were it legal.
<P>
Russell Fox and Ian Mathews in their book Drugs Policy refute other myths. They claim it is not true that one or two fixes of
heroin will turn you into an addict. Heroin can produce physical and psychological dependence, but this takes heavy use over a
prolonged period. It takes several months to a year of heavy use to become hooked on heroin or cocaine. Tobacco is judged more
addictive than heroin or any other illegal drug because of the severe dependency it develops. And unlike tobacco and alcohol,
pure heroin is not toxic, nor is it associated with any disease.
<P>
Recently in Australia there have been signs of a changing attitude to marijuana. Possession and use of the drug is not a criminal
offence in SA or the ACT. MPs in SA will soon vote on whether marijuana will be allowed on sale from licensed outlets such as
pharmacies. The Australian parliamentary group for drug law reform is pressing for national decriminalisation of marijuana and legislation
to allow the medical use of cannabis and heroin.
<P>
But many say decriminalisation of one drug does nothing to tackle the most visible evidence of the failure of prohibition
- the black market in illicit drugs where a kilogram of heroin is worth $1 million.
<P>
The Redfern Legal Centre in NSW has advocated making illegal drugs available in a controlled manner, regulated by the government,
to undermine the black market. They believe addictive drugs like heroin might be supplied to addicts or problem users. The centre
is conducting a campaign, headed by solicitor Stephen Bolt, to bring alternative drug policies to the attention of politicians
and the community.
<P>
Bolt says: &#147;I think that the general public see that it&#146;s necessary to stop people from using drugs, and that the drug laws
are the only way we can do it. I think both of those are challengeable. Not because the desirability of drug use is at question, because
I don&#146;t think that should be the debate. What is at question is the ability of the laws to prevent people using drugs. All
the evidence is that it has failed, continues to fail and will always fail.&#148;
<P>
Statistics show about 13 per cent of people in Australian prisons are there for drug offences, with an estimated 20 per cent to
70 per cent of prisoners convicted of drug-related crimes such as theft and burglary, motivated by the need to finance heavy 
drug use.
<P>
Corruption is another problem that may be disturbingly widespread,says Bolt. Ten years ago drug substitution was not uncommon at
government drug testing laboratories, according to a former drugs analyst who tested drugs seized by the Australian Federal Police.
On one occasion, what was reported to be seven kilograms of cocaine was actually found to be 100 per cent glucose.
<P>
&#147;A few times what happens is that a drug comes back for analysis and it&#146;s not what it&#146;s supposed to be. We find out that
it&#146;s just glucose. That&#146;s when the Federal police start an investigation. But nothing ever comes out of it. They just
hush it up. The police take a pretty active role for the first month or two. Afterwards they say &#145;we&#146;re looking into
it&#146; and the thing just goes out of sight. And no-one ever chases it up,&#148; he says.
<P>
In NSW, tests for drug quality as well as quantity are now operative
after an investigation into &#147;extraordinarily lax&#148; drug security arrangements found heroin could be substituted for glucose
without detection. A new strategy to deal with police corruption in NSW includes a plan to build a high-security drug testing laboratory
to remove drugs from police stations.
<P>
The current NSW Police Royal Commission is revealing how the drug trade&#146;s easy access to cash increases the likelyhood of police
corruption. Numerous other commissions and official enquiries have reported on corruption linked to the illegal drug trade.
The Royal Commission on the NSW Police Service has uncovered evidence
of high-level drug related corruption among Kings Cross police, such as large payments in exchange for protection of drug trafficking
operations. The Queensland Fitzgerald Commission recommended an immediate investigation into illegal drug policies, and said authorities
must acknowledge that prohibition had failed.
<P>
According to Bolt, drug laws set the police up for sale. &#147;There&#146;s
so much money involved in drug trafficking because the prices you get for drugs are so high, and the demand for drugs remains
the same or increases slightly, despite all attempts to prohibit their use,&#148; he says. &#147;The law creates a completely artificial
price, so naturally people are going to try to make money from them. There are millions of dollars at stake in the drug trade.
That necessarily means that there is an enormous pressure on individual
police and also the police service as an institution.&#148;
<P>
Patrick Law, national secretary of the Australian Federal Police Association, says the impact of illegal drugs on society was widespread
and corruption was a concern. &#147;The AFP is on the record as a corruption-free police force and we&#146;re very proud of that
and we work very hard to maintain it,&#148; he says.
<P>
On the possibility of police being tempted by their access to highly priced drugs, Law said: &#147;Well, the whole point of
the AFP system is that they don&#146;t have access to them. We have very, very strict accountability guidelines - I would suggest
the strictest in Australia - to prevent access to the drugs that are seized.&#148;
<P>
Current prohibitive drug policy does little to counter major public health concerns. About four per cent of injecting drug users in
Australia are HIV positive, and 15 per cent are infected with the hepatitis C virus - rates significantly higher than in the
rest of the population. Overseas the problem of HIV infection in injecting drug users has reached critical proportions. In the
US in 1992, 31 per cent of all new AIDS cases were caused by contaminated
needles.
<P>
Acting Director of the Drug and Alcohol Directorate in the NSW Health Department, Peter Hommel, admits Australia has a less than
perfect system, but says he sees no inconsistency with the prohibitionist
drug laws and the harm minimisation strategy applied to alcohol, tobacco and illegal drugs.
<P>
But not everyone agrees with this position. Wodak calls Australia&#146;s drug policies confused. Action directed at specific drugs was
not proportional to their contribution to health and social problems, he says. &#147;What happens under current policy is that ineffective
laws get policed and effective laws don&#146;t.&#148;
<P>
The latest statistics on drug abuse in Australia highlight the severe consequences of the use of alcohol and tobacco. In 1992,
an estimated 26,300 Australians died from drug-related causes, about one-fifth of all deaths. Of these three per cent were due
to illicit drugs, 25 per cent to alcohol and 72 per cent to tobacco.
Clearly, the drugs which cause the most deaths are the legal ones.
<P>
Simon Overland, adviser on drugs policy to federal Justice Minister,
Duncan Kerr, is unwilling to embrace proposals for drug policy reform. He believes there are strongly held views on both sides
of the argument. &#147;Our approach now is to look at the question of harm caused by drugs. Harm extends beyond just the harm caused
to the individual user of the drugs, it extends to the harm and cost to the wider society. Our policy is one of harm minimisation.&#148;
<P>
Both Dr Bammer and ACT Chief Minister Kate Carnell stress the importance of community debate on the proposed heroin trial. &#147;Essentially
the community are the people who either have to wear the risks or forgo the benefits, so in the end, they&#146;re the ones who
are going to have to decide which way they&#146;re going to go,&#148;
says Dr Bammer.
<P>
Whether or not the trial eventuates, the report has put heroin on the political agenda after 40 years of prohibition. But despite
mounting evidence that punitive drag laws are not working, it is questionable whether either politicians or the community will
be prepared to accept substantial change. If Australia is to take the first step on the route towards a rational drug policy, we
may need to re-examine some fundamental beliefs of our society. It is difficult to maintain that using heroin and marijuana is
immoral when legal drug use is unquestioned by a large part of the population. 
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
</TT></CENTER>
</TD>
</TR>

<P>
<TR>
<TD>
<I><A Name="Jennie Christian">Jennie Christian</A> is a Master of Arts (Journalism) student at the University of Technology, Sydney.</I>
</TD> 
</TR> 
