<head><title>Snoop: The cost of Privatisation</title></head>

<frameset cols="20%,*">

<NOFRAMES>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#0000ff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=4>
 
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 
 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400>
<TR><TD><IMG WIDTH=400 SRC="../IMAGES/snoop.gif"> 
</TD></TR></TABLE>
 
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=400>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=400><FONTSIZE=+1><B>Spring 1995</B></TD> 
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT><B>PRIVATISATION</B></TD></FONT>
</TR></TABLE> 

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400> 
<TR><TD WIDTH=400 VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>The cost of privatisation
</B></FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
 
<P>
<I>In the Summer &#146;94 edition of Snoop, we ran a special supplement
dealing with the costs of privatisation &#151; Rolling Back the State. In this update, <A HREF="#Mary Banfield">MARY BANFIELD</A> looks at the costs associated
with the privatisation of government cleaning services in NSW.</I>
<P>
MARIA Sveronas has had a change in employers. Eighteen months ago her government job as a cleaner ceased. The work was sold off to a private contractor. She is now required to do more work,at twice the speed, in less time, and for less money. The working
conditions of the 7,500 government cleaners have been dramatically reduced since privatisation. So much so that the newly elected Labor NSW State Government has called for an inquiry into the conditions and effect on the quality of services being provided
by the contract cleaning companies.
<P>
In 1993, Voices, a University of Technology, Sydney publication, investigated the implications of the Government Cleaning Service
being privatised by the former Liberal NSW State Government. Back then, the fear of the women was they would lose their job security.
&#147;If the government doesn&#146;t offer me a job, how am I to get another,&#148; questioned Sveronas.
<P>
This was the fear of an older woman, who migrated to Australia from Greece. Seventy-seven per cent of the cleaners are women,
and 42 per cent are from non-English speaking backgrounds. Sveronas and her workmates kept their jobs with the new employer. 
<P>
The Ethnic Communities Council of NSW (ECC) recently presented a report outlining the impact of privatisation of cleraning services
on women of a non-English speaking background. This report stated that the Government expected to save $37 million on the cost of
workers. A sense of betrayal, loss and anger felt by the women, many of whom have been employed for ten years by the government,
was noted in the report.
<P>
The Australian Liquor, Hospitality and Miscellaneous Workers Union (ALHMU) says the cleaners have been subjected to excessive workloads,
reduced hours and poor equipment. In one school, the union reports total working hours have been reduced from 160 to 78, disregarding
the extra workload created by the school taking on more students. Cleaners report that no longer is there time for breaks and their
health is being compromised.
<P>
The new inquiry, announced in June 1995, will allow principals to monitor the quality of cleaning in the schools. The union has
successfully argued that the inquiry should examine the conditions of work or exploitation of women, adequacy of raining while looking
at the health and safety records since privatisation. For Sveronas the inquiry will be welcome. &#147;Since March we&#146;ve been
under a lot of pressure because the supervisor comes in and says I&#146;m taking too long to clean that building. They say I&#146;m
too slow, I say &#145;you show me a better way&#146;.&#148;
<P>
Sveronas&#146; company has informed the workers their working hours will be cut by ten per cent, while the amount of work they
are expected to do increases out of proportion. The workers believe the company is further aiming to reduce their working hours from
28 hours per week to 21. They will still have to do the same amount of work. For Sveronas that means cleaning 23 classrooms, two corridors
and two kitchens, in five-and-a-half hours.
<P>
Ironically, according to the ECC, the Industrial Relations Commission pointed out that the decision by the previous Liberal Government
to privatise the service was made in isolation. According to the Industrial Relations Commissioner Justice Monica Schmidt, no consultation
was carried out with the union, nor employees: &#147;The decision to sell ... is clearly open to criticism.&#148;<BR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD>
<I><A Name="Mary Banfield">Mary Banfield</A> is a Graduate Diploma in Communications student
at the University of Technology, Sydney</I>
</TD> 
</TR> 

</TABLE>

