<html>
<head><title>Snoop:Selling Crown Land</title></head>

<frameset cols="20%,*">

<NOFRAMES>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#0000ff"> 
<BASEFONT SIZE=4>
 
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 
 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400>
<TR><TD><IMG WIDTH=400 SRC="../IMAGES/snoop.gif"> 
</TD></TR></TABLE>
 
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=400>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=400><FONT SIZE=+1><B>Spring 1995</B></FONT>
</TD> 
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT><FONT SIZE=+1><B>FEATURE</B></FONT>
</TD></TR></TABLE> 

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400> 
<TR><TD WIDTH=400 VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>A Swift One in the Crown Jewels</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="#Fiona Morrisson">By Fiona Morrisson</A><BR></FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>
<I>Rainforests, woodchipping, logging, endangered species, natural
habitats. These days there seems to be as many individual environmental
issues as there are environmentalists. There is one conservation
issue, however, that&#146;s been out of the public eye for the
past few years. Not because it is no longer a problem but because
it&#146;s a complex, political hot potato.</I>
<P>
IN THE lead up to the March 1995 State election, Premier Bob Carr
said in a strategy paper that his government would ensure the
protection of Crown leases. How this would be done has not yet
been formally announced. 
<P>
Crown leasehold land regularly made headline news in the late
1980s and early 1990s. When the Coalition state government changed
policies in 1989, great tracts of previously protected Crown leasehold
land was sold off to private interests. The Labor opposition screamed
&quot;fire sale&quot; and conservationists demanded a stop to
what they saw as environmentally outrageous. There was also talk
of corruption.
<P>
So loud and long was the outcry that in 1990 Premier Nick Greiner
placed a moratorium on the freehold conversion those Crown leases
with a &quot;reserve from sale&quot; note on them. The government
tried to lift the moratorium three years later but hastily reinstated
it after less than two weeks when public pressure once more proved
that Crown land was still a highly contentious issue.
<P>
A significant proportion of Crown leasehold land in NSW is natural
bushland or wilderness. When a Crown lease is converted to freehold
title, it becomes private property and little can be done to prevent
it from being cleared and subdivided.
<P>
In 1995, the moratorium still stands, informally, at least. It
is not a legislated or formally defined ban. Rather it is an unwritten
understanding between the National Parks and Wildlife Service
(NPWS) and the current Department for Water and Land Conservation,
formerly the Department of Conservation and Land Management (CALM),
that now protects Crown leases. 
<P>
Although these two departments have recently made progress towards
rationalising and standardising procedures for assessing and documenting
Crown leases, there are still no concrete measures in place to
ensure a fire sale can&#146;t be held again.
<P>
Environmentally and politically Crown leasehold land remains absolutely
critical for NSW, according to John Benson, senior plant ecologist
with the Royal Botanic Gardens and a former NPWS officer.
<P>
Benson says large portions of some of NSW&#146;s major wilderness
areas are Crown leasehold land.  This is confirmed by the Colong
Foundation.  Their records show there are over 200,000 hectares
of crown leasehold land in 27 wilderness areas throughout NSW.
<P>
&#147;I&#146;d say it&#146;s probably the most important land
for nature conservation outside the reserve system,&#148; says
Benson. &#147;It is basically one million hectares of native bushland.
I call it our defacto reserve system.
<P>
&#147;Everybody jumps up and down about endangered plant and animal
species. What they are forgetting is that many crown leases are
some of the last places you&#146;ll find many such plants and
animals. Much of this land may be critical to the viability of
many ecosystems and species.&#148;
<P>
THE recent history of Crown leasehold land is a sorry one, marked
by recurring stories of poor planning, political self-interest
and greed. At the end of the 1970s, New South Wales had a Crown
leasehold estate of some 10,000 leases, totalling five million
hectares. By the beginning of the 1990s, only 4,500 leases remained,
2,000 of which had &#147;reserve from sale&#148; notices. The
rest had either been converted to freehold or had the protective
reserved from sale notices withdrawn.
<P>
Large-scale selling off of Crown leases was not just a pastime
of Coalition governments. Successive Labor governments throughout
the 1970s and 1980s sold a substantial number of Crown leases
too. 
<P>
But after the Coalition came to power in 1988 the situation began
to get out of hand.  
<P>
One NPWS officer recalls &#147;a strong push by the National Party
in the lead up to the 1988 election to freehold all leasehold
land&#148;. After they won the election the Coalition government
first ignored the NPWS and its recommendations, then in 1993 they
tried to dismantle the Service altogether by amalgamating it with
CALM. That, according to John Benson, would have fundamentally
undermined environmental conservation in New South Wales.  &#147;If
that had happened,&#148; says Benson, &#147;there would have been
no clear voice on the environmental issues connected with Crown
land.&#148;
<P>
From 1988 to 1993 was a tough time for everyone interested in
protecting Crown leases.  
<P>
In July 1989, Ian Causley, the then Minister for Natural Resources,
suddenly decided to dump CALM&#146;s 1978 Conservation Policy
on Crown leases. Under this policy, Crown leases deemed environmentally
sensitive were &#147;reserved from sale for future public requirements&#148;.
However, this policy and the reserved from sale notices were not
legislated and could easily be overruled by the Minister responsible,
as Causley proved. 
<P>
Causley said at the time the policy had to go because it created
too many &#147;disincentives&#148; to freehold conversions and
was &#147;too restrictive, inefficient and inappropriate to protect
the environment&#148;. According to the National Party any measure
to protect Crown leasehold land was a &#147;socialist land grab&#148;.
<P>
The loss of the Conservation Policy put the NPWS in a bind. The
Service either had to purchase all leases where it objected to
conversion within five years or forgo any interest in them. With
a budget of only $2.5 million a year to buy land, and the complex
negotiations and approvals for land purchases often taking over
five years, protecting all important leases was impossible. 
<P>
With the Conservation Policy removed, the Coalition government
began openly encouraging lessees to convert their Crown leases
to freehold. 
<P>
The government sent brochures promoting the new favourable conditions
to Crown leasehold lessees, and received over 2,000 applications
for freehold title.  It also caused a great hue and cry from conservationists
and the Labor opposition. 
<P>
Even the government&#146;s own departments were concerned.
<P>
The NPWS said in a report in 1990 openly criticising the government&#146;s
policies on Crown leasehold land disposal, &#147;The current operation
of Government policy on disposal/retention of leasehold Crown
lands is to the detriment of heritage conservation.&#148;
<P>
It was this report that forced Premier Greiner to act. In August
1990, he imposed a moratorium on the sale of all Crown leasehold
lands. CALM and NPWS were told to immediately assess all the leases,
identifying those that should be protected.
<P>
According to an NPWS officer there was little time to come up
with a workable method for assessing the leases. The NPWS did
not have the time or resources to inspect each lease, so most
assessments were made from topographical maps, aerial photographs
and anecdotal evidence. &#147;There were major problems with our
methods,&#148; says the NPWS officer, &#147;but it was so hotly
political at the time that we just had to do it.&#148;
<P>
Three years later, CALM and NPWS had drafted some guidelines for
protecting Crown leases but were nowhere near finding a long-term
solution to the problem. 
<P>
NPWS proposed Conservation Agreements to protect important Crown
leases.  These however offer only limited protection. 
<P>
Benson says Conservation Agreements could be applied over hundreds
of leases but they are not logical. &#147;They take a lot of negotiation
and you can&#146;t force people to sign them. In the past leases
have been converted when people have said they&#146;ll enter an
agreement and then gone ahead and subdivided anyway because the
agreements were not legally tight.&#148;
<P>
For Conservation Agreements to work, it would seem more appropriate
to enter into them before the tenure on the land was changed.
<P>
By 1993 Premier Greiner&#146;s successor John Fahey was under
continued strong pressure from the National Party to lift the
moratorium on the sale of Crown leasehold land. He gave in on
8 May 1993.  For the next ten days Crown leases were once again
in danger.
<P>
CROWN land is a story of bureaucratic wrangling and political
self interest. This is an example.  There have been others, some more widely known, some
more important.
<P>
Conservation is a dirty word for many people in Tucabia. Tucabia
lies in the electorate of Clarence. Ian Causley has been the local
member for Clarence since 1984.
<P>
Dyson Devine has lived in the area about 18 years. However, to
locals he&#146;s still an outsider. His American accent probably
doesn&#146;t help.
<P>
Many properties in the area have been in the same family for several
generations.
<P>
They are the real locals - conservative, National Party-voting
graziers - and they don&#146;t take too kindly to strangers. Especially
ones who criticise their ways. Especially outsiders like Devine.
<P>
Devine came to Australia in 1972, the only assisted-passage American
on Australia&#146;s last migrant ship. He moved to Grafton in
1977, bought his property, cleared a few acres, dug a dam, built
a two room solar-powered house, filled it with books, and settled
down into what he says is his place in the world. 
<P>
Aside from the clearing and a tangled vegetable garden, Devine&#146;s
property is all native bushland. Tall thin eucalyptus and other
native trees, their trunks blackened by a fire last year, surround
the clearing on all sides. A couple of families of black wallaby
make his land their home too, occasionally coming up to the house
to scrounge vegetable scraps and apple cores. 
<P>
Over the past two years, Devine, with the help of the National
Parks Association, has waged a campaign that&#146;s put him on
the wrong side of not only the shire council but some local landowners
and Ian Causley. 
<P>
In May 1993, just days after the moratorium on the sale of crown
leasehold land was lifted by the then Premier John Fahey, a 492.5
hectare (1,217 acre) block of Crown leasehold land, known locally
as McCrae&#146;s Knob or simply &#147;the reserve&#148;, adjoining
Devine&#146;s property was converted to freehold and sold to the
leaseholder Trevor Kratz. 
<P>
Kratz bought it for $1 an acre.  It is now worth anywhere up to
$1.2 million.
<P>
Devine and CEC have been trying to find out how and why this could
happen. 
<P>
NPWS and CALM files obtained through the Freedom of Information
Act reveal the how of the story but not the why.
<P>
McCRAE'S Knob is steep and covered in a dense old growth forest
of native trees - ironbark, turpentine, tallowwood, and brushbox.
Small creeks, their water dyed amber from tanin, wind down through
thick remnant rain forest to the Coldstream River.
<P>
Kratz&#146;s perpetual Crown lease had permitted him grazing on
the reserve.  Instead, local councils mined gravel from two of
its ridges.  
<P>
A development application was recently lodged to greatly enlarge
the gravel quarries. However the quarry has now closed after being
found to have been operating illegally by the NSW Ombudsman. The
development application recorded that in the 1960s Ian Causley
had driven a truck in the mines.
<P>
Devine didn&#146;t hear about the conversion until three months
after it was approved. But then, neither had officers with the
Grafton NPWS and they had been working on the Pine Brush Nature
Reserve proposal for several years.
<P>
It was first recommended for dedication as a nature reserve in
April 1974. An NPWS inspection revealed the land contained remnant
rainforest, rare plants unusual to the area and 130 million year
old sandstone rock outcrops. Subsequent research by a local archaeologist
also found evidence of Aboriginal artefacts, such as stone implements
and rare stone axe grinding grooves.
<P>
For 12 years, between 1974 to 1986, every request by the NPWS
to purchase the land was met with a counter application to freehold
by Kratz and outright rejection by the local Ulmarra Shire Council.
The NPWS needs the agreement of a number of natural resource departments,
and seeks the comments of other authorities and local councils,
before it can dedicate land as a nature reserve or national park.
<P>
The NPWS eventually decided to put the Pine Brush Nature Reserve
proposal on hold, at least until their Coastal Parks Plan was
approved. The plan included the Yuragir National Park which is
also in Ulmarra Shire. 
<P>
The NPWS probably thought they&#146;d better not push their luck.
<P>
In 1988 the Forestry Commission stepped into the fray with an
undertaking to dedicate the land as State Forest. The Forestry
Commision has the power to dedicate State Forests over Crown leases.
The Commission thought the land not only a good source of a timber
but an excellent 500ha fire break between the adjoining Pine Brush
State Forest and local farmlands. 
<P>
However, as soon as he heard of the Forestry Commission&#146;s
request, Kratz lodged a series of appeals against the dedication
with his local member Causley.
<P>
Coincidentally, Causley was the then Minister for Natural Resources.
 His portfolio included the Forestry Commission. On 14 February
1990, Causley rejected his department&#146;s dedication, saying
the proposed reserve was &#147;extremely poor forest&#148;. The
Commission wrote to the NPWS saying that with &#147;disappointment&#148;
they could no longer object to Kratz&#146;s applications. 
<P>
The moratorium on the conversion of Crown leasehold lands in 1990
temporarily put an end to Kratz&#146;s chances of converting the
land. It did not however stem his freehold conversion applications.
<P>
The CALM file contains a letter dated 21 August 1991 to Causley
from Gary West, then Minister for CALM, the department then responsible
for Crown land. West acknowledges Causley&#146;s &#147;personal
representations&#148; on behalf of Kratz but writes that he can
not do anything because of the moratorium, adding that they would
have to wait until the interdepartmental taskforce finished its
analysis of all crown leasehold lands.
<P>
In mid 1992, CALM advised Kratz that the taskforce had declared
the proposed reserve of &#147;heritage value&#148;. This meant
that Kratz could continue to graze his cattle on it if he wished;
he just could never convert the lease to freehold or develop the
land without approval.
<P>
Kratz nevertheless continued to apply for freehold through Causley.
<P>
In December 1992, while the moratorium was still in place, Causley
visited the land&#146;s gravel quarries. He was accompanied by
Michael Ockwell, then head of CALM, Peter Wilson, then acting
head of the National Heritage Division of the NPWS, and Kratz.

<P>
It was a quick visit that brought some big changes in heart. 
<P>
After the inspection, Ockwell, Wilson and Causley all agreed that
McCrae&#146;s Knob could be converted to freehold, on the proviso
that Kratz first finalised a Conservation Agreement to protect
the vegetation cover. 
<P>
Premier John Fahey lifted the moratorium on 8 May 1993. The sale
of the land was completed on 12 May 1993, for $1,217. The moratorium
was reinstated, albeit informally, on 18 May 1993.
<P>
Two years later the Conservation Agreement with Kratz is not yet
finalised. According to Owen Turner of Grafton NPWS, the agreement
when it is complete will cover between one half and two thirds
of McCrae&#146;s Knob.  It is still unsure whether it will cover
the remnant rainforests and Aboriginal sites.
<P>
Kratz will still be able to do what he likes with the remainder.
He could clear it, subdivide it or both.
<P>
Chances of reversing the conversion would seem slim.  It would
now be impossible for the NPWS to buy back the land at market
prices. Blocks of 100 acres around Tucabia sell for over $100,000.
 Devine however has not given up hope of the sale being reversed.
<P>
It may well be too late to save the proposed Pine Brush Nature
reserve, but it is certainly not too late to learn from its loss.
It is not the first case of questionable freehold conversion and,
unless action is taken, it may not be the last.  Instead of being
a political issue or a vote-buying tool the conversion of Crown
leases to freehold should be systematic and controlled.
<P>
As Benson says, &#147;When it comes to Crown leases we should
be conservative, in the true sense of the word.&#148;
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD>
<I><A Name="Fiona Morrisson">Fiona Morrisson</A> is a journalism student at the University of Technology,
Sydney, and is the current editor of the university magazine &#147;Vertigo&#148;.
</I>
</TD> 
</TR>
</TABLE>

