<head><title>Snoop: HIV Marginalises Women</title></head>

<frameset cols="20%,*">

<NOFRAMES>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#0000ff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=4>
 
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 
 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400>
<TR><TD><IMG WIDTH=400 SRC="../IMAGES/snoop.gif"> 
</TD></TR></TABLE>
 
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=400>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=400><FONTSIZE=+1><B>Spring 1995</B></TD> 
<TD ALIGN=RIGHT><B>HIV</B></TD></FONT>
</TR></TABLE> 

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=400 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE CELLSPACING=5 BORDER=0 WIDTH=400> 
<TR><TD WIDTH=400 VALIGN=TOP><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>HIV Marginalises Women
</B></FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
   
<P>
<I>Women, it seems, have forever been the poor relations in the fight
against AIDS and HIV. <A HREF="#SUE JOSEPH">SUE JOSEPH</A> sheds some light on this phenomenon.</I>
<P>
Women are contracting HIV at the same rate they were ten years
ago although the rate of infection in men has dropped.
<P>
But despite this, women still feel marginalised and isolated in
their treatments, mainly because they are heterosexual, according
to a leading Sydney AIDS doctor.
<P>
Dr Virginia Furner, Head of the Medical Unit at the Albion Clinic
in Surry Hills, says: &#147;The number of women identified each
year is constant. It hasn&#146;t changed in ten years and we don&#146;t
really know what that means yet.
<P>
&#147;Many of the women may have been infected years ago; perhaps
more women are contracting the virus and simply not recognising
that they have,&quot; she said
<P>
Figures show that since the first official Australian female death
from AIDS in 1985, 860 women have contracted the virus, at a constant
annual rate of between 80 and 90 diagnoses. In contrast, more
than 15,500 men have contracted the virus, with the rate of infection
dropping by approximately one third from October 1993 to September
1994.
<P>
Dr Furner says: &#147;What we do know from retrospective studies
is that women are still marginalised and isolated in their treatments.
There are many reasons for this, the main one I think being that
most of them are heterosexual.
<P>
&#147;They don&#146;t identify as a cohesive group because there
is no commonality between many of the women except their HIV positive
status.&#148;
<P>
Women face female-specific symptoms with HIV, some of which have
only been recognised by collating bodies in the past two years.
<P>
The US Centre for Disease Control (CDC) did not recognise female-specific
HIV opportunistic infections until 1993, despite women being diagnosed
with HIV/AIDS since 1982. Because Australia, like most other developed
countries around the world, uses the CDC classification system
for identifying HIV/AIDS, both the numbers of infections and actual
deaths of women have never truly been reflected in national statistics.
<P>
Since 1993 classifications have changed and female-specific symptoms
are now included in required conditions listed with the CDC and
hence other developed countries.
<P>
Dr Furner says: &#147;It&#146;s our impression from some preliminary
studies that we&#146;ve started doing Australia wide, that less
than 50 per cent of positive women have their gynaecological needs
addressed by their health provider. Questions are never asked.
The focus is on their HIV instead of the women as a whole.&#148;
<P>
This statistic in itself presents problems as many opportunisitic
infections in HIV positive women are found to be gynaecological
to begin with.
<P>
&#147;There is a risk women will develop cervical malignancies,
plus other diseases like Pelvic Inflammatory Disease,&#148; Dr
Furner says. &#147;The problem is, once a woman is diagnosed as
HIV positive her gynaecological needs are ignored, and before
she is diagnosed HIV positive her gynaecological needs may not
be linked.&#148;
<P>
Another contentious issue disadvantaging women in their fight
against AIDS and HIV is their exclusion, until recently, in clinical
drug trials.
<P>
&#147;Basically, it was drug companies&#146; fear of litigation
which excluded women,&#148; Dr Furner explains. &#147;According
to drug company protocol, if a woman took part in a clinical test
and found she was pregnant, the risk of foetus damage from the
drug could cost the company millions. So company protocol was
to restrict women being involved in clinical trials. 
<P>
&#147;The policy is more open now because women feel they should
have as equal access as men to potentially life-saving drugs that
are undergoing research. Now all that is often required is for
doctors involved satisfying themselves that the woman involved
is not at risk of getting pregnant.&#148;
<P>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD><I><A NAME="Sue Joseph">Sue Joseph</A> is a Master of Arts (Journalism) student at the University
of Technology, Sydney.</I>
</TD> 
</TR> 
</TABLE>

