</TD></TR>

<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2><P><A HREF="telstra.htm#related"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Related<BR>Stories</FONT></B></A><BR>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><A HREF="../journos.htm"><FONT SIZE=+1>The <BR>journalists</FONT></A></B><BR>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="cover.htm">Return to Contents</A><BR></FONT></B><P>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
</TD>

<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Selling Telstra - are we being dudded?</B></FONT>
</CENTER><BR>
<P>
<I>
The Federal government tells us that privatising a third of Telstra
is vital, allowing seven billion dollars in Government debt to
be repaid, and improving the efficiency of the telecommunications
industry. But what real benefits will flow to Australia, and will
they outweigh the loss of a third of Telstra to private ownership?
<A HREF="../journos.htm#lrobertson">LOUISE ROBERTSON</A> looks beyond political rhetoric and takes a hard
look at the figures.</I>
<P>
THERE has been no clear demonstration by the Howard Federal government
that the financial benefits of partial privatisation will outweigh
the costs. Professor Bob Walker of the University of New South
Wales (UNSW), writing in the Journal of Australian Political Economy,
argues that this is not unusual. &quot;The fact is that most (if
not all) privatisation decisions have been undertaken in Australia
without any detailed disclosure of the economic rationale for
the sale,&quot; he says.
<P>
&quot;The Government has stated that by retiring $7 billion of
debt, it will reduce its annual interest bill. The benefit is
that the money that would otherwise have gone in interest payments
could then be used to fund other programs or to retire more debt.
Another benefit is that retiring foreign debt also reduces the
public sector borrowing requirement which pushes interest rates
down, leading to benefits for private borrowers, particularly
those in business.
<P>
In order to determine whether the partial sale is financially
worthwhile, we need to weigh these benefits against what the Government
will forgo through losing a third of its equity in Telstra.
<P>
Telstra is an important income source for the Commonwealth Government.
From assets of $24 billion in 1994/95, it generated $14 billion
in revenue and made an after tax profit of $1.7 billion. Telstra
is currently committed to paying the Government a dividend of
55 per cent of its annual operating profit. During 1994/95, the
Telstra dividend was worth $944 million, which when added to interest
and taxes paid by Telstra, provided a total payment to Government
of $2.4 billion. This represents nearly two per cent of the Commonwealth
Government budget.
<P>
On a crude estimation that selling off a third of Telstra will
reduce the Government's dividend by a third, the Government may
stand to lose about $315 million a year. With the current interest
rate on Government bonds at about eight per cent, the interest
saving on debt of $7 billion is $560 million a year. From this
simple equation it looks as though the Government may gain more
than it will lose through the sale.
<P>
However, Professor Walker suggests that this may be just what
the Government wants us to think. He argues that Telstra's capital
structure reduces its appearance of profitability, and that to
get a true picture of the revenue the Government receives from
Telstra, we need to look at the full cash flow from Telstra to
the Government. This means looking not only at dividends, but
interest paid on Government loans, tax payments, and other fees
and charges.
<P>
A third of Telstra's total payment to Government in 1994/95 ($2.4
billion) is $800 million, which appears much higher than $560
million the annual interest savings on debt of $7 billion.
<P>
But, of course, the Government doesn't stand to lose all of the
$800 million because a privatised Telstra will, for example, still
pay taxes (although Professor Walker points out that private sector
firms can be expected to undertake tax-minimisation strategies).
The problem is, we don't really know how partial privatisation
will affect the cash flow between the Government and Telstra.
<P>
Regardless of the debt repayment arguments, the Government also
needs to clearly demonstrate that the sale price it has set for
a third of Telstra is an accurate reflection of its worth. Is
$8 billion enough? Further, will the Government achieve this sale
price in the current financial climate?
<P>
BZW, the investment banking division of Barclays Bank, recently
indicated that the Government could do better than $8 billion
for a third of Telstra. In its report, <I>Regarding Telstra</I>,
BZW estimates the net value of Telstra at $27.9 billion, a third
of which is approximately $9 billion. Similarly, stockbrokers
J B Were &amp; Son recently put Telstra's net value higher at
between $28.5 to $42 billion, and estimated $8 to 10 billion was
a conservative price for a third of the corporation.
<P>
That the Government has chosen a conservative price of $8 billion
probably reflects its expectations about the market's ability
to absorb a share issue of this size. $8 billion dollars represents
about two per cent of the combined value of listed companies on
the Australian Stock Exchange (called market capitalisation).
According to the ASX, a good indicator of the market's ability
to absorb the Telstra issue is to consider that new capital raisings
over the past ten years have averaged about six per cent of market
capitalisation. This suggests that the ASX, with a current capitalisation
of $350 billion, should be able to support new issue of up to
$20 billion a year. However, the ASX adds that other factors need
to be taken into account including the state of the economy, how
fast the shares need to be sold, and whether shareholders perceive
the share price to be good value. It comments that there is a
tendency for large Government floats to be slightly undervalued
because a big issue can only be sold in one hit if investors perceive
the shares to be a good buy (ie undervalued).
<P>
Undervaluing may also reflect the Government's political interest
in having the issue fully sold.
<P>
Other factors that need to be considered are constraints on purchasers
and the other share issues on offer at the same time. A significant
constraint on purchasers is the Government's commitment that foreign
ownership of Telstra will be restricted to 35 per cent of the
issue. This means that 65 per cent must be absorbed domestically,
which may be difficult in the light of the sale of the final tranch
of the Commonwealth Bank, and the privatisation of Deutsche Telecom
and France Telecom, both of which are expected to be offered for
the first time in 1997.
<P>
The bottom line is that if the market cannot absorb the issue,
then the Government is likely to have to offer Telstra shares
at a discounted price. If the transaction costs of multi-tranch
issues were added, the net proceeds to Government of the partial
sale could be much less than eight billion dollars.
<P>
<B>Will Telstra be more efficient?</B>
<P>
Before considering the efficiency gains that privatisation may
achieve, we first need to consider how efficient Telstra is at
the moment. In a 1995 report, the Bureau of Industry Economics
found Telstra's performance to be reasonable by international
standards, noting that many improvements had been made in recent
years as a result of improvements in technology and the introduction
of competition.
<P>
However, Telstra failed to reach international best practice in
a number of areas and needed to make substantial improvements
to match its competitors. Telstra's labour productivity in particular,
measured in terms of revenue per employee and lines per employee,
was found to be well below international best practice. There
was also scope to reduce prices (particularly for services in
which Telstra does not face competition from Optus), improve the
reliability of the network (particularly for rural and residential
customers) and to improve the time taken to repair faults. Progress
in digitising the network (which will increase the speed and reliability
of data transmission) was considered slow.
<P>
So how will privatisation bring about these improvements? The
economic argument is that privatisation exposes a company to the
discipline of the market. The share price mechanism provides clear
signals about a company's performance, making management more
accountable for its actions and forcing it to become more streamlined
and efficient, often by reducing employees. This is assisted by
the more stringent reporting requirements for companies listed
on the Australian Stock Exchange, and the injection of a private
sector ethos through new board members.
<P>
However, Professor Bob Walker of UNSW is sceptical whether privatisation
will actually cause an increase in efficiency. &quot;One of the
most comprehensive international studies of privatisation found
that only 55 per cent of privatised firms showed an improvement
in operating performance, and that overall the mean change was
only a 0.16 per cent improvement in the reported rate of return
on equity,&quot; he writes. Even attributing these small gains
to privatisation is contentious as it assumes that any efficiency
gains could not have been secured if organisations remained in
public ownership.
<P>
Indeed, Sue Ferguson of the Communications Law Centre does not
believe that efficiency gains are the sole province of a private
sector firm. &quot;I don't see any reason why a far leaner operation
couldn't be put in place under Government ownership. As a corportatised
entity, there's no reason why you can't apply private sector practices
if thats what you're aiming for. And then you retain all the dividends
in the Government purse,&quot; she argues.
<P>
Ferguson says that the CLC has seen nothing persuasive about the
arguments for privatisation so far, and believes competition in
the telecommunications market has greater potential to bring about
efficiency gains than privatisation. &quot;Privatisation is just
a short term easy way to get a lot of money to solve short term
problems,&quot; she says.
<P>
The CLC and other consumer groups argue that the debate on privatisation
should be delayed until competitive market reforms have been implemented
and competition has become firmly established. There are serious
concerns that if privatisation occurs too early in the competitive
process, there will be less pressure on Telstra to improve its
efficiency, and those gains that it does make will be returned
to shareholders rather than consumers.
<P>
Competition was first introduced into the Australian telecommunications
market in 1991 when the Government selected Optus Communications
as Australia's second telecommunications carrier. Optus currently
provides long distance and international calls by satellite and
mobile telephone services, and has recently offered local calls
for the first time via its Pay TV network.
<P>
Competition from these carriers has already lead to price reductions.
The BIE found that between 1990 and 1994, the price of a basket
of national business services in Australia fell by 8.9 per cent,
and the price of a peak rate international call fell by 28.4 per
cent (although both these price falls were below the OECD average).
Mobile phone charges fell by 26.3 per cent over the period. 
<P>
There is greater potential for increased competition from mid-1997,
when the telecommunications market will be opened to full competition.
Telstra will be under pressure to improve its performance or lose
market share.
<P>
The Consumers Telecommunications Network (CTN), which represents
residential consumers, argues that with all these competitive
changes occurring, the debate on privatisation should be delayed
until at least the year 2000. Only then will the Government be
able to assess the benefits that competition has brought against
additional benefits of privatisation. Privatising Telstra now
confuses two quite separate processes.
<P>
Gerard Goggin of the CTN explains &quot;There's a real danger
that if you privatise too early in the competition process that
Telstra will just be placed in a position to make these wind fall
profits and there's not enough competition around to give them
a hard time and return the so called efficiencies that you want.
<P>
&quot;What could actually happen is that the benefits of that
telecommunications reform in terms of large profit are just being
captured going to shareholders, rather than going to the economy
in terms of cheaper prices and better quality of service across
the board,&quot; he adds.
<P>
Goggin also raises concerns about the type of efficiency gains
that a privatised Telstra might pursue. He suspects that quality
of service improvements and price reductions would be likely to
be directed at the high traffic business services in which competition
is the strongest, while low traffic services to rural and remote
areas would be neglected. While this might be in the best interest
of Telstra's private shareholders, Goggin questions whether we
should accept a market defined by the concept of efficiency which
places no importance on equity in services.
<P>
However, the Australian Telecommunications Users Group (ATUG),
which represents business users, has a different perspective.
Managing Director, Allan Horsley, while emphasising that ATUG
is not a proponent of privatisation, believes the introduction
of a private sector ethos into the management of Telstra and greater
accountability to shareholders will bring benefits.
<P>
Horsley has been less than impressed with some of Telstra's investment
decisions in recent years. He is concerned that Telstra was able
to commit considerable funding to its Pay TV joint venture with
The News Corporation (Foxtel) without justifying this investment
to the Government, let alone the public. In his view, funding
committed to Foxtel could have been put to better use in upgrading
the telephony infrastructure, in particular by bringing forward
the completion date for digitising the network (called Future
Mode of Operation) and by extending the digital link to premises
(called ISDN).
<P>
He is incensed that Telstra has poured billions of dollars into
Pay TV, yet neglected to set aside sufficient funds for ISDN.
While the FMO will enhance the speed of data transmission between
exchanges, premises without ISDN lose valuable speed in data transmission
because they have to convert the signal from digital back to analogue.
He likens it to an artificial bottle-neck that has major implications
for business operators. &quot;Telstra haven't gone out with a
prospectus into the market place saying we're going to spend $5
billion on Pay TV, here's the business plan, here's the investment
criteria, so come and invest some money. No bloody fear. Those
poor suckers out there, our eight million customers, we'll just
take the profits off them and plough it into pay television with
no return, and the worst thing is that the investment into the
development of the core telephone business has been delayed so
that the revenue that is being earned from the telephone business
is not being reinvested but is being hived off over here,&quot;
he says.
<P>
&quot;We've spent $4 billion on the FMO project. Absolutely tremendous
investment to make &#133; the switching and transmission components
of the network digital. A little bit better performance for voice,
but enormous improvement in speed and reliability of transfer
of data. But what they've forgotten about is that we need about
$1 billion over three years to take the capability from the exchange
to your premises (about the 15 to 20 per cent who need it). (Telstra)
Didn't bother to budget the funds.&quot;
<P>
Horsely believes that improved accountability of Telstra's management
will be an important check on this type of decision. He describes
a seemingly ironic situation in which a Government owned Telstra
has largely operated in secrecy, while the privatisation legislation
for Telstra envisages more open decision making with clearer reporting
requirements to Government.
<P>
&quot;We see that the reporting relationship between Telstra and
its (majority) shareholder the Government will be a more formal
and clear relationship than it is at the present time.... You
imagine the Board of BHP going to an annual meeting of shareholders
and saying well I'm not going to tell you anything, you're only
the shareholders. It just wouldn't happen,&quot; he says.
<P>
He emphasises that ATUG does not want the Government to become
involved in the day to day decision making of Telstra. &quot;&#133;
the last thing we want is Ministerial intervention in the operations
of Telstra &#133; The Government should set the focus, the framework,
the objectives, and they (Telstra) get on and do the business.&quot;
<P>
One area where the chance has been missed for a vast improvement
in efficiency is the double roll-out of broadband cable networks
by both Telstra and Optus in capital cities and regional centres.
While they are duplicating each other's services in densely populated
areas, neither appears to have any intention to spread their networks
to the less economical rural and remote areas, which will be stuck
with basic 1950's telephone services.
<P>
The combined cost of the networks is nearly $7 billion. If only
one network had been installed, the excess funds could have been
used to extend the network to other less economical areas, or
for future network upgrades as technology improves. Some environmental
benefits may also have arisen as the cable could perhaps have
been confined to underground. As it is, Optus's network is largely
above ground, suspended from electricity poles, while Telstra's
is largely below ground.&quot; Privatisation will be no help here.
</TD> 
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
