</TABLE>
</TD>

<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD align=right>
<IMG SRC="hanoi1.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=133>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT><FONT SIZE=2>Flood in one of Hanoi's streets
</FONT></TD></TD>
<TR><TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Hanoi...Not sinking, just drowning<BR></FONT></B>
<P>By <A HREF="../journos.htm#ttrinh">Trinh Thanh Thuy</A></CENTER>
<P>
Hanoians are obsessed with the fear of having to wade to work
along streets-turned-to-rivers after long and hard rains.
<P>
It is a scene which is all too common during the wet season. But
in this case, nature is not to blame. The flooding has been caused
by years of overdevelopment.
<P>
With six metres between its highest and lowest points, water drainage
in the Red River City is very slow. Fortunately, the city was
endowed with another means of drainage: the many lakes and ponds
in and around the city. This gift of nature not only enhanced
the city's beauty, but also served as an effective traditional
water regulating system.
<P>
Yet for many years Hanoians have been sacrificing this natural
seasonal convenience for the sake of the all-year-round comfort
of their own fast growing families: they have been filling the
lakes to expand their area for housing.
<P>
<B>The New Venice of the East?</B>
<P>
Many of Hanoi's lakes, ponds and swamps have been filled since
the city was set up ten centuries ago (when boats and rafts were
the main means of transport). But rapid population growth in the
last 20 years has sped the filling of the lakes.
<P>
n the 70s, Hanoi had about 210 lakes, less than 20 of which remain
today. Today the lakes and ponds in Hanoi, into which excessive
rain water flows, have an estimated area of only seven square
kilometres, with a total capacity of approximately 15 million
cubic metres.
<P>
However, as land for housing construction becomes scarcer, people
continue to fill these lakes and ponds with waste, scrap iron,
and rubber and then build houses for both their own use and for
illegal sale.
<P>
In Nam Dong Street, Quoc Lao Lake was reduced to a narrow ditch
of only two metres wide. In Quang Ba village, several large ponds
disappeared, giving way to new villas and houses.
<P>
Whilst in some cases this was done with the consent of the local
authorities, in most circumstances the encroacher had immediately
- and, more importantly, <I>irreversibly</I> - built a house on
the illegally occupied land. Once there, they were more than willing
to pay a fine which was a fraction of what they would gain in
the soaring housing market.
<P>
Last year, Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet ordered the demolition of
illegal houses and villas built on the safety corridor of the
river dyke in the Yen Phu-Nhat Tan area. Cracks in the dyke, caused
by the weight of the houses, were discovered just before the beginning
of the flood season. The police and the army were called in to
demolish the houses and ensure security during the process. A
number of officials involved in the scandal were arrested. It
was the most serious breach of the dyke protection law in Vietnam
to date.
<P>
Such strong action has not been taken on squatters in other parts
of the city however, and Hanoi's lake area continues to decrease.
<P>
Consequently, showers with rainfall of over 100mm usually result
in the city being submerged in a mixture of rain and domestic
waste water at 60 different places for several days. In some streets,
the flooded stretches may be as long as hundreds of metres, with
water occasionally up to waist height.
<P>
According to official figures, Hanoi has 230 kilometres of main
streets, thousands of kilometres of side streets and lanes, but
only 127 kilometres of sewers. More than half of the latter are
under streets built over 50 years ago for a population of 200
000 people. And yet today Hanoi's population is over one million
people in the city centre alone. Many sections of the system have
consequently collapsed or are seriously degraded. Meanwhile drainage
has not been given adequate consideration in a number of newly
constructed quarters.
<P>
Encroachment on the main canals and accumulation of solid matter
often blocks water flow at many parts. Furthermore, the maximum
capacity of the Thanh Liet sluice gate (the final outlet of the
city's drainage system) is 30 cubic metres per second, only one-third
over the discharge rate required when the rainfall reaches 100mm.
Hence flooding becomes inevitable once there is not enough space
for temporary storage in the city.
<P>
<B>Waste, Sewage and Fish</B>
<P>
The total liquid waste of the city, estimated by the Hanoi Water
Service to be 200 000 cubic metres per day, passes directly into
the common drainage system untreated.
<P>
Waste water, including chemicals, dyes, heavy metals, and hospital
waste, then flows into the city's lakes, ponds or local rivers
and is used for fish rearing and irrigation. Scientists fear that
this practice, although it helps deal with a considerable amount
of organic matter in the waste water and accounts for almost all
the vegetable and fish supply for Hanoi, will have negative effects
on people's health and the underground water table.
<P>
All of the lakes, except for the West Lake which remains relatively
clean due to its size. 4.15 square kilometres, are seriously polluted.
Most of these lakes have ditches connecting them to sewage outlets.
The content of hydrogen sulphide in waste water flowing into the
Bay Mau lake in Lenin Park can measure up to 12 milligrams a litre,
which is 1000 times the safe level for fish rearing. Despite this,
the lake continues to be used for that purpose.
<P>
The amount of solid matter flowing into the lakes is also on the
rise. This is adding to the metres of thick mud layer already
at the bottom of the lake.
<P>
Recently Hanoi's Drainage Service Company and Park Company began
dredging and have paved the banks of some lakes in a move to prevent
further encroachment into them and to improve their condition.
<P>
But it is only a small part of the work to be done.
<P>
The Municipal Environment Protection Committee has drawn up a
master plan for the drainage service sector in the period 1995-2010.
The $1.1 billion project, expected to be funded with Japanese
official development assistance, consists of several phases and
many components.
<P>
But despite the plan, flooding and waste water seems set to be
in the Hanoians' path for years to come.
</TD> 
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2>
