<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Snoop:Vietnam's muddy waters of mangrove conservation</TITLE></HEAD>
  
<BODY BACKGROUND="../IMAGES/bgyellow.gif" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=600 NOSHADE> 
 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=600>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=100 ROWSPAN=2 VALIGN=middle ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Winter<BR>1996</FONT></TD>
<TD width=500 valign=middle align=center><IMG WIDTH=400 SRC="../IMAGES/snoop.gif"></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=+1><I>A Magazine of U.T.S. Journalism - Internet Edition</I></FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=600 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=2 WIDTH=600>
<TR>
<TD width=100 valign=top align=center>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=2>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Next Story<BR><A HREF="hanoi.htm"><I>Hanoi...Not sinking, just drowning</A></I></FONT></B><BR>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2><P><A HREF="mangrove.htm#related"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Related<BR>Stories</FONT></B></A><BR>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><A HREF="../journos.htm"><FONT SIZE=+1>The <BR>journalists</FONT></A></B><BR>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="cover.htm">Return to Contents</A><BR></FONT></B><P>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
</TD>

<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="mangrove.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=129></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT><FONT SIZE=2>One year old replanted mangrove forest in Thai Binh province</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Muddy Waters of Mangrove Conservation</FONT><BR></B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<I>
Agent Orange defoliants sprayed by the US during the war destroyed
more than 100 000 hectares of mangrove forests in the south of
Vietnam. Now, ironically, development, not war, is their biggest
threat.<A HREF="../journos.htm#ttrinh">TRINH THANH THUY</A> reports.
</I>
<P>
HANOI - an ambitious land reclamation program is under way in
the northern province of Quang Ninh.
<P>
Experts predict it will provide an additional 2000 hectares of
land for agricultural and aquacultural purposes. This in turn
will boost expansion of the local economy as well as create many
jobs for soldiers and their families under Vietnam's Third Military
Zone Command, one of the main designers of the program.
<P>
But Vietnamese scientists are worrying that the project, called
the Bac Cua Luc project, may turn out to be a disaster for the
local environment. The reclaimed land, most of it originally covered
by mangrove, might soon become barren.
<P>
Under the program, a 17 kilometre dyke is to be built on tideland
along the coast of Hoanh Bo district on tideland. The dyke will
prevent salt water from entering the district so that the land
can be used for cultivation.
<P>
But according to experts, unless the land is regularly supplied
with enough fresh water, it will soon turn fallow in the dry season.
(Similar failures have occurred on some 50 000 hectares in the
south and 35 000 hectares in the north.) The rehabilitation of
mangroves on this land will then be almost impossible because
there will no longer be a tidal flow (an essential condition for
the development of the plant system). As it is, the embankments
built for many of the large shrimp ponds along the coast, estuaries
and river banks have already considerably reduced the extent of
tide distribution.
<P>
Mangrove forests play an important role in protecting the coastline,
widening the mainland, regulating the climate, and maintaining
local biodiversity.
<P>
In 1943, just before the two Indochina wars, Vietnam had about
400 000 hectares of mangrove forests along the country's coastline
and estuaries, mainly in the south. But Agent Orange defoliants
sprayed by the US during the war destroyed more than 100 000 hectares
of these mangrove forests. Not only did the trees die and the
animals lose their habitat, but the health of the local people
was also seriously affected, with subsequent generations continuing
to bear the consequences. Much of the forests have since been
rehabilitated, but the acreage is still estimated at just over
one-third of what it was then. Now, overdevelopment, not war,
is the biggest threat to the mangroves.
<P>
Apart from the conversion of mangrove forests for cultivation
purposes, mangroves are also been recklessly destroyed to make
shrimp ponds.
<P>
Lured by the profits made from the shrimp export, the Vietnamese
Government and local authorities in many coastal provinces have
encouraged shrimp farming. This move was intended to compensate
for the fact that catches have decreased. But meanwhile the Government
has done little to protect the now vulnerable local forests.
<P>
According to the Sea Products Export Company, the total area of
water shrimp ponds expanded rapidly from 50 000 hectares in 1981
to 120 000 hectares in 1987.
<P>
Other scourges of the mangrove forests have been their conversion
to fields for salt production or mining activities. Urbanisation
and the construction of dykes, dams and roads also endanger mangrove
forests.
<P>
In fact, many of these &quot;developmental&quot; activities have
backfired in no uncertain fashion.
<P>
The most serious and long term negative effect is said to be the
reduction in both quantity and variety of aquatic creatures such
as shrimps, crabs, fish and oysters. Shrimp reared in a large
number of ponds died en masse in 1994, causing a loss of over
290 billion dong (roughly US$29 million) for the aquacultural
sector. Other reptiles, birds and animals have also been deprived
of their habitats and food sources.
<P>
Experts say this was a result of changes in the soil's properties,
particularly in the formation of sulfuric acid through direct
exposure to sunlight following the destruction of mangroves.
<P>
The large size of the shrimp breeding pond and the relatively
few sluice gates meant that the water exchange between the pond
and the outside environment was inadequate. Rain water carried
acidic soil from adjacent hills and embankments into the pond,
quickly reducing the acidity levels. This, added to the rapid
change in salt levels caused by vaporisation during sunny weather,
proved fatal for the shrimps.
<P>
This acidification process is also one reason behind the degradation
of large areas of reclaimed land. Furthermore, unsustainable shrimp
farming and the destruction of forests has increased water pollution
and the accumulation of carbon dioxide in these areas due to greenhouse
emmissions (from the decomposition of the peat layer) no longer
being absorbed by mangroves.
<P>
Additional negative effects have even been felt inland, further
up the river.
<P>
The north-east monsoon brings salt water through rivers deep into
the mainland, affecting land both protected by the river dykes
and outside. This is because the salt water is absorbed through
the soil layers in the body and foot of the dyke. Due to the shortage
of fresh water and low humidity in the dry season, the salt comes
to the soil surface and damages cultivated plants, triggering
disputes between shrimp breeders and agricultural farmers. This
intrusion of salt water has also caused erosion along rivers.
<P>
Addressing the 'mangrove' problem,<B> </B>Prime Minister Vo Van
Kiet recently declared Vietnam's determination to protect the
mangrove forests. To the delight of environmentalists, he ordered
the replanting of mangroves in coastal areas.
<P>
But many obstacles lie ahead.<B> </B>Most of the damage caused
in the past has its roots in rapid population growth and poor
economic and resource management, especially at the local level.
Over the past 50 years, Vietnam's population has more than doubled
to an average of 200 people per kilometre. This cannot help but
continue to increase pressure on the limited resources of land,
fuel and construction materials.
<P>
Dr Phan Nguyen Hong, director of Mangrove Ecosystem Research Centre
of Hanoi National University, has been engaged for a long time
in efforts to protect and replant the forests.
<P>
Hong complains about both the lack of expertise in several responsible
state agencies as well as the short sighted policies implemented
by local leaders. These leaders, according to Hong, are either
unaware of the value of mangrove forests, or think only of the
immediate benefits of their exploitation.
<P>
&quot;We are trying to help them to understand the importance
of mangrove forests and providing necessary expertise. But the
government should have appropriate policies in this direction,&quot;
Hong said.
<P>
Indeed, shrimp farming could still be economical if appropriate
techniques were applied to regulate tidal flow into the pond so
that mangroves can thrive.
<P>
In some localities, such as Ho Chi Minh City and Minh Hai province,
part of the destroyed forests have recently been replanted. Hong,
however, notes that these efforts will be meaningless if forest
destruction is not stopped altogether. &quot;The area planted
has only been one tenth of what was cut down at the same time,&quot;
he said.
<P>
Another problem is the lack of capital for reforestation and mangrove
forest-based sustainable economic development. Except for a program
to plant wind breaker forests along the coast of a number of provinces,
most of the other projects - mainly funded by non-governmental
organisations - are very small in size.
<P>
The biggest projects, soon to be implemented, include restoring
mangrove forests in three southern provinces with a $50 million
World Bank loan, and another combining shrimp farming with forest
conservation with Australian and Thai co-operation.
<P>
Meanwhile, in the Bac Cua Luc project, the construction of a dam
(essential to supply fresh water for the reclaimed land) has not
yet started as the VND5 billion needed has not been sourced.
<P>
&quot;We have been saying again and again that they should not
start the project until there is enough fresh water, but they
are too impatient,&quot; Hong complains, adding that he was afraid
the project may fail.
<P>
Hong says his centre has also prepared and helped publish documents
disseminating essential knowledge about mangroves. These will
be distributed to farmers, school students, and organised training
courses.
</TD> 
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
</CENTER>
