<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="theatre.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=253></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT><FONT SIZE=2>The vestibule of New Theatre displays posters from past productions.</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>New Theatre</FONT><BR></B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<I>
With the 65th birthday of Australia's oldest theatre company to
be celebrated next year, <A HREF="../journos.htm#fnoakes"> Frank Noakes </A>reminisces about Newtown's
New Theatre - from its days of communist party affiliations to
its role in censorship struggles, police raids and illegal performances.</I>
<P>
BORN AS the Sydney Workers' Art Club on August 6, 1932, the New
Theatre aimed to provide culture for the working class, from plays
and lectures to music recitals and exhibitions.
<P>
The first play for the amateur company was<I>The Ragged Trousered
Philanthropists </I>in April 1933, the first of more than 400
productions to introduce thousands of people to both sides of
the footlights.
<P>
Following the emergence of the USA's New Theatre movement in the
late 1920s to counter the poverty and hardship of the Great Depression,
Sydney's New Theatre often found itself at the forefront of battles
for free speech and democracy.
<P>
Its earliest productions were rough and ready and flavoured with
activist propaganda. Short plays were often staged outside factories,
alongside dole queues and at Labor Party and Communist Party meetings.
<P>
State governments soon acted to suppress such performances.In
1936 NSW police stormed the stage to stop a performance of Clifford
Odets' anti-fascist play, <I>Till the Day I Die</I>.
<P>
Then in 1968, the theatre faced a new censorship struggle over
Jean Claude Van Itallie's play <I>America Hurrah</I>, a satirical
look at US society. After complaints about the final act in which
huge wooden dolls scrawl obscenities on a wall, the Askin Coalition
government banned the show.
<P>
Defiantly, the company organised an illegal performance in the
Teacher's Federation's Sussex Street auditorium. No advertising
was necessary; hundreds had to be turned away. According to Marie
Armstrong, one of the &quot;dolls&quot; and current vice-president
of the New Theatre, &quot;The air was electric with expectation&quot;.
<P>
Police again moved in but this time escape routes were organised
for the three &quot;dolls&quot; by burly building workers and
wharfies &quot;accidentally&quot; obstructing entry. This allowed
enough time for the actors to shed their costumes and mingle nonchalantly
with the rest of the cast. Nobody was arrested although the police
confiscated the offending set as evidence.
<P>
One of the New Theatre's most memorable moments was its 1952 performance
for underground miners of <I>The Candy Store</I> , a story of
a strike in a US department store.
<P>
Shale miners from Glen Davis, north of Lithgow, began the first
sit-in strike in a NSW colliery and the Miners Federation invited
the New Theatre to perform.
<P>
Smuggled into the mine, the actors improvised a stage with a hessian
curtain at the junction of five shafts with small, inadequate
lamps set on a rickety table. Then, as the actors stepped on stage
in the murky half-light, the miners switched on their hard-hat
lights and bathed the stage in a dusty glow.
<P>
&quot;That's a hard one to beat,&quot; said Armstrong, who also
performed that day.
<P>
Later that year the theatre performed <I>Stay Down Miner</I> by
Len Fox to another audience of striking miners inside the Hunter
Valley's Great Greta coalmine.
<P>
Throughout this period the theatre maintained a close relationship
with the trade union movement, the decline of which is regretted
by Armstrong.
<P>
The New Theatre grew to prominence by staging productions too
hot for professional theatre to touch. It was the first Australian
theatre to perform Arthur Miller's <I>The Crucible</I> in the
1960s but today, because of costs, it is harder for the New Theatre
to obtain first rights to socially relevant plays.
<P>
With 300 volunteer members, the New Theatre still adheres broadly
to humanist values and tries to do plays a little left of centre.
<P>
&quot;If something has a radical left-wing bias and it is well
written we'll want to do it,&quot; says Armstrong.
<P>
&quot;But gone are the days when the message is more important.
If a play is not well written and performed then the message suffers.&quot;
<P>
Next year the New Theatre turns 65. It has no plans to retire.
</TD> 
</TR>

