<HEAD><TITLE>Snoop:DEA sieze the day</TITLE></HEAD>
  
<BODY BACKGROUND="../IMAGES/bgyellow.gif" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=600 NOSHADE> 
 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=600>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=100 ROWSPAN=2 VALIGN=middle ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Winter<BR>1996</FONT></TD>
<TD width=500 valign=middle align=center><IMG WIDTH=400 SRC="../IMAGES/snoop.gif"></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=+1><I>A Magazine of U.T.S. Journalism - Internet Edition</I></FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=600 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=2 WIDTH=600>
<TR>
<TD width=100 valign=top align=center>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=2>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Next Story<BR><A HREF="smack.htm"><I>The life of an undercover cop</A></I></FONT></B><BR>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2><P><A HREF="dea.htm#related"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Related<BR>Stories</FONT></B></A>
<BR>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><A HREF="../journos.htm"><FONT SIZE=+1>The <BR>journalists</FONT></A></B><BR>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="cover.htm">Return to Contents</A><BR></FONT></B><P>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
</TD>

<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>DEA seize the day
</B></FONT><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<I>New South Wales police have looked to America for a new weapon
in the war against drugs. And, as <A HREF="../journos.htm#blin">BRUCE LIN</A> discovers, the results
are boosting law enforcement budgets.</I>
<P>
INSIDE a stark Kent Street building, whose walls are painted a
sterile hospital green, a select team of lawyers, accountants
and analysts congregate to fight organised crime. Enlisted by
the New South Wales Crime Commission, the team's prime task is
the confiscation of assets from suspected drug dealers.
<P>
Confiscation is a relatively new procedure in Australia; and according
to many police is already proving to be a more effective deterrent
than gaol.
<P>
The practice was pioneered in the United States where, in certain
states, the legislation even allows law enforcement bodies to
seize assets from suspected drug dealers automatically prior to
charging, even if there is no conviction. In Volutia county, Florida,
the local sheriffs have even taken to stopping cars at random
and seizing cash from any driver carrying more than $100 (the
assumption being that such a sum could <I>only </I>be acquired
through drug dealing).
<P>
Taking its cue from such American practices, the Kent Street team,
working alongside state police in the Drug Enforcement Agency,
confiscated $6.8 million worth of assets last year, ranging from
grand North coast villas to Harley Davidson motorbikes.
<P>
According to the NSW Crime Commission's senior confiscation lawyer,
Jane [surname withheld], drug traffickers are becoming increasingly
nervous about the risks of detection. Many are now employing a
legion of highly paid tax specialists and lawyers to launder their
money through offshore companies in an effort to elude authorities.
<P>
Jane's investigations have uncovered several unconventional methods
used by traffickers to disguise their assets.&quot;One fellow
never owned a car so he used to go and hire cars everywhere,&quot;
she says. &quot;Another one would order a pizza 80 kilometres
away to be delivered by taxi.&quot;
<P>
The confiscation game is about survival of the smartest. More
significantly, though, it's about money. Drug lords deal to reap
the top dollar. Cops, it can be argued, confiscate assets for
exactly the same reason.
<P>
Of the $6.8 million confiscated last year, nearly every cent was
allocated to the coffers of the NSW police ministry. Calls from
the community to use the money to set up drug rehabilitation and
education programs have repeatedly fallen on deaf ears.
<P>
One veteran detective [name withheld], who is currently working
with the Kent Street confiscation team, defends the allocation
of money by pointing out the present inadequacy of police resources.
<P>
&quot;[The money] should be ploughed back to the police that fight
the criminals. We're always three steps behind them. They have
the best phones, fastest cars, the best everything,&quot; he says.
<P>
In certain American states, funding through asset confiscation
relieves police departments of suffering at the hands of a dwindling
state budget. In Greenville county, South Carolina, a new police
training facility was financed thanks to land seized from a one-time
prosperous dealer. Similarly, assets amounting to $5 million confiscated
in Sulphur, Louisiana, have led to the introduction of immaculately
equipped sports coup&eacute; police cars on the streets of Sulphur.
<P>
The United States Drug Enforcement Agency has absolute confidence
in the all-round efficacy of its asset confiscation program. New
South Wales, in turn, has absolute confidence in the program's
universal adaptability.
<P>
Our faceless veteran detective automatically endorses the sentiment
of America's DEA boss, Robert Bonner, who awaits the day when
&quot;the drug trafficking organisations will wither and die.&quot;
<P>
Never before has waiting proved so lucrative.
</TD> 
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
</CENTER>
<BR>
</TD>
</TR>

<tr><td></td></tr>
<TR>
<TD COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><A NAME="related">Related Stories</A></FONT>
