<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2><P><A HREF="h20gate.htm#related"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Related<BR>Stories</FONT></B></A><BR>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><A HREF="../journos.htm"><FONT SIZE=+1>The <BR>journalists</FONT></A></B><BR>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="cover.htm">Return to Contents</A><BR></FONT></B><P>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
</TD>

<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD align=right>
<IMG SRC="h2ogate.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=106>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT><FONT SIZE=2>The Whitehouse
</FONT></TD></TD>
<TR><TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Watergate Unlocked<BR></FONT></B>

<P>By <A HREF="../journos.htm#toreilly">Tim O'Reilly</A></CENTER>
<P>
WATERGATE? You can put that name to many things. A break-in -
a cover-up - a scandal; the fall of a president - a muckraking
melee - a myth. Some might say a journalistic wet-dream. The only
certainty? It was - and still is - a hotel.It has also entered
the lexicon. Look up <I>The Concise Macquarie Dictionary</I> and you find
there's a new word for political scandal. Watergate, as well,
is the progenitor of Irangate, Iraqgate, Camillagate, Squidgy-gate,
Whitewatergate, even Baxtergate!
<P>
Today, Watergate continues to resonate through culture and politics.
There is obvious significance for journalism and students of political
history. Murray Hogarth ofThe Sydney Morning Herald thinks that
the Watergate affair &quot;popularised the notion of investigative
journalism for a generation which has carried it ever since.&quot;
For much of the public, this was a new field of reporting. Four
Corners' Liz Jackson says that for a journalist, Watergate &quot;seems
the highpoint of efficacy of the media in bringing public figures
to account. It's a validation of what people hope at their best
they can do.&quot;
<P>
Even Hollywood can see an angle. Oliver Stone has just directed
a bio-pic of Nixon. And has published an accompanying book that
contains the script, an interview with himself (naturally), and
original Watergate documents and tape transcripts.
<P>
24 years ago, the otherwise unremarkable Washington hotel and
apartment complex called the Watergate was the venue for a botched
break-in and bugging attempt at the then headquarters of the Democratic
Party National Committee. The cast? A hodge-podge of ex-CIA/ex-FBI
functionaries and some exiled Cuban (Bay of Pigs) veterans. These
shenanigans were the culmination of a two-year campaign of illegal
domestic espionage activities by the White House and the Committee
to Re-elect the President against their perceived political and
media enemies. The burglary was a government sanctioned crime.
It was June 16, 1972.
<P>
August 9, 1974 saw the resolution of the affair - President Richard
Nixon resigned from office over his involvement in the ensuing
cover-up. More than two years of turmoil was strewn between these
inextricably linked dates. And as Nixon walked, however reluctantly,
into infamy, a great tide of public discontent and disbelief swelled
behind him. His landslide electoral win of November 7, 1972 (while
Watergate was evolving) would be the last highpoint in his tenure
as president. It went sour as Watergate was examined by the courts,
the FBI, a senate committee, a long running grand jury investigation,
a special Watergate prosecutor, and the House Judiciary Committee.
From the moment he left the White House lawn in 1974 to his death
in 1994 he would be branded an unindicted co-conspirator in these
sordid events.
<P>
That first June day, accused James McCord admitted he had recently
worked for the CIA; a Nixon re-election campaign donation cheque
appeared in another suspect's pocket; and the name and phone number
of a White House operative, Howard Hunt, leapt from the pages
of a third thief's diary. These leads were astounding but seemingly
innocuous curiosities until painstaking investigation by the Washington
Post proved them otherwise.
<P>
The role of journalism in the Watergate affair was complex and
vigorously debated. Essentially, journalists led the chase for
the story from the moment the burglars appeared in court, until
the machinery of government and the courts began to prove effective
after Nixon's re-election. The early exposes of the Post, and
later follow-up work by the New York Times, the Los Angeles Times,
and CBS produced an outstanding body of investigative journalism
and hammered on the door of a rapidly besieged White House.
<P>
The Washington Post and two of its young reporters, Bob Wood-ward
and Carl Bernstein, became internationally famous over their pursuit
of the story. Their determination and their continual ability
to scoop other press outlets were hallmarks. Effectively they
opened up the investigation to the public in its early stages
and exposed elements of the cover-up that ensued. Together, they
followed a trail of money and personnel from the sixth floor of
the Watergate to the top levels of the Nixon administration.
<P>
Woodward and Bernstein traced the path of Nixon campaign contributions
that funded the Republican dirty tricks team into the White House
itself. They began naming White House officials as controllers
of a slush fund that directed nefarious political activities.
To do so, they pursued investigative reporting as news reporters,
and not as political roundsmen. As such, they stayed away from
formal information sites like press conferences, and were unacquainted
with the normal sources in government. Improvisation ruled, and
they created a labyrinth of sources and contacts who, as an unwitting
coalition, confirmed and supported fact, supposition and theory.
In effect, they scrambled around the margins of politics on Watergate.
This brought them to dissatisfied people at all levels who were
ready to talk or to be persuaded to do so.
<P>
Their methods are depicted in their own All The President's Men
(written before the fall of Nixon, in 1974, and made into the
successful 1976 film starring Robert Redford and Dustin Hoffman).
The two reporters talk of the trickle of information coming from
frightened, reluctant people who frequently held back more than
they told. To circumvent this and to turn the trickle to flow,
&quot;the trick was getting inside someone's apartment or house.
There, a conversation could be pursued &#133; They always identified
themselves immediately as reporters for the Washington Post but
the approach that seemed to work best was less than straightforward
&#133; &quot; They begged, borrowed and cajoled their way in -
often bluffing their way to the truth.
<P>
Frequent meetings were held with editors Barry Sussman, Howard
Simons, Harry Rosenfeld, and executive editor, Ben Bradlee, to
approve and edit stories and decide direction. The reporters usually
argued that one source was enough to support a story. But &quot;gradually
an unwritten rule was evolving: unless two sources confirmed a
charge involving activity likely to be considered criminal, the
specific allegation was not used in the paper.&quot; Some stories
needed even more.
<P>
The effectiveness of these reporting techniques is most evident
in that the stories held firm and were vindicated. Furious White
House denials of the alleg-ations and vilification of the Post
were all withstood partly because of the scrutiny to which the
evidence was subjected.
<P>
These methods suited the situation but did not always ensure accuracy.
Stories were often left unattributed. Very few sources would go
on the record, and background and deep background (in which a
source is never quoted, even anonymously) were frequently employed.
The White House often complained over published accusations that
had unidentified origins.
<P>
Woodward's executive branch contact, Deep Throat, was the most
celebrated example of the use of a confidential source on deep
background. He refused to be quoted in any story and would not
volunteer information, only confirming or denying evidence presented
to him. His information proved ultimately reliable, and his (or
her?) identity remains an enigma today. And the name of the top-secret
confidential source on TV's X-Files? In honour perhaps, Deep Throat.
<P>
Occasionally, stories were incorrect. Accusing White House Chief
of Staff H. R. Haldeman of involvement was made possible by a
web of confirmations so tenuous that it was swiftly and vehemently
rebuked, causing the Post to lose face and ground. This was despite
the story's essential truth. Accountant to the Committee to Re-Elect
the President, Hugh Sloan, had confirmed indirectly to the reporters
that Haldeman was the fifth name controlling the fund that financed
illegal activities on behalf of the Committee. Deep Throat had
informed them that they were right, and another confi-dential
source had added further weight. The story was written, however,
quoting only Sloan, and reported him naming Haldeman in his Grand
Jury Testimony. His attorney vehemently denied the allegation.
Later, Sloan indicated that Haldeman was the fifth name, but he
had not actually ever said so before the Grand Jury as no-one
had asked.
<P>
Vindication of the basic story of Watergate has quelled much valid
criticism of Woodward and Bernstein's techniques. Indeed, approbation
has pretty much always been the order of the day, although criticism
has emerged concerning the use of, and reliance on, confidential
sources. When a story is wrong, multiple back-ground sources and
chain reaction confirmation of facts are no guarantee of truth.
The use of confidential sources can be risky.
<P>
Stories by the Post earned them subpoenas from lawyers representing
the Committee to Re-elect the President (which were challenged
and dismissed), and two trips to see Judge John Sirica for approaches
to witnesses and grand jurors. Obtaining vital information often
required such tactics of questionable legality. Whether the situation
demanded skirting the edges of the law so frequently and brazenly
is still debatable.
<P>
Was the press lacking in effectiveness? Early forays by the Washington
Post had only minor initial impact. Journalists from the Sunday
Times in London thought that this was true to the extent that
&quot;by the fall of 1972 it was the press, not the administration,
that lacked credibility.&quot; In a celebrated but largely apocryphal
moment, Ben Bradlee was heard to say that at this point his newspaper
really had its dick on the table. Later, however, televised hearings
and sensational confessions of highly placed White House officials
garnered national attention and cemented the credibility of the
press.
<P>
The impact on Australian journalism? Both Murray Hogarth and Liz
Jackson speak glowingly of Watergate as a &quot;journalistic beacon&quot;
and refer to Australian journalists such as Chris Masters and
Brian Toohey, whose paths to success have partly been paved by
Woodward and Bernstein.
<P>
Toohey himself argues otherwise. To him, Watergate simply employed
available contemporary techniques and has not affected Australian
journalism to any great degree. He feels that investigative journalism
puts advertisers offside, causes trouble, doesn't pay well, and
takes months to do. Consequently, it engenders little enthusiasm
in newspaper management. Indeed, &quot;investigative journalism
has gone downhill all round the world&quot;.
<P>
Journalist Michael Schudson (and others), however, talks of an
all pervading myth of &quot;Journalism-in-Watergate&quot;. Shudson
argues persuasively against the idea that &quot;the Washington
Post brought down the President&quot;. He concludes that this
gives undue credit to the Post where properly, it should go to
those government agencies that performed admirably. The FBI, the
Federal Grand Jury investigation, and the machinations of the
justice system of the United States all made handsome contributions
to the tale of woe. Each of these governmental law enforcement
arms pursued legitimate investigation of Watergate collaborators,
and between them conducted the many government hearings that eventually
crowded and concluded the affair.
<P>
It is easy in hindsight to indicate the lack of press involvement
and influence over these hearings. But is it fair to saddle the
press with the duties of the investigative bodies? For example,
it is often understated that Nixon was halfway to impeachment
and politically pungent when he left office. Yet it was not open
to journalism to initiate or undertake this course of action.
And would we have seen the same results without theWashington
Post, et al ? Senator Sam Ervin, (in whose committee hearings
former Counsel to the President John Dean first publicly accused
the president of complicity in the cover-up), openly sought assistance
from those journalists who had reported the case.
<P>
Historian T. H. White concluded, &quot;it was three specific systems
acting by themselves and by their own dynamics - the press from
outside, the judicial system and Congressional leadership acting
from within - that moved first tentatively, then inexorably, to
bring about the downfall of Richard Nixon.&quot; The myths of
Watergate need to be tempered, but each institution - media, Judiciary
and Capitol Hill - played a part.
<P>
Did the press have a right to pursue the story? Did the White
House have a right to conceal? The First Amendment to the United
States Constitution helps to resolve this debate. Freedom of the
press is a direct stipulation that government will not interfere.
The press had a right to find out the answers, and then a duty
to endure the consequences. White says the news machine did no
more than its constitutional duty.
<P>
Watergate was, maybe, a historical aberration, an extraordinary
confluence of factors never to be repeated. Certainly, it is hard
to see the White House ever again being as careless with its activities.
Or as carefree in its relations with the media. And would a President
ever again be as foolish as to oversee, personally, such shenanigans?
In a presidential election year, republican candidate and retiring
Senator Bob Dole may give us an opportunity to find out. He does
have intimate knowledge. After all, his home in Washington is
The Watergate Hotel. 
<P>
Some other famous Gates...
<P>
<B>Irangate</B>: The covet selling of arms to the right winf Nicaraguan
Contra movement by the United states - via a third party, Iran
(Despite a Congressional Ban).
<P>
<B>Iraqgate</B>: The covert selling of arms to Iraq by the United
States (Despite a Congressional Ban).
<P>
<B>Camillagate</B>: The scandalous taping and publication of private
telephone conversations between Prince Charles and Camilla Parker-Bowles
revealing his adultery.
<P>
<B>Whitewatergate</B>: The ongoing investigation into the property
dealings of the President and Mrs Clinton when he was Govenor
of Arkansas.
<P>
<B>Baxtergate</B>: The current investigation into the attempted
removal of Des Semple as Department Head of NSW Community Services.
</TD> 
</TR>

