<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="cover.htm">Return to Contents</A><BR></FONT></B><P>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
</TD>

<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="enterpri.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=75></TD>
</TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Are Women losing out in Enterprise Bargaining?
</FONT><BR></B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<I>IN THE year since Snoop last reported on the difficulties
faced by women driving down the road of enterprise bargaining,
the situation has not improved. Indeed, as <A HREF="../journos.htm#pbenson">PAULA BENSON</A> reports,
the potholes may be getting bigger.</I>
<P>
Paul Keating stuck the toe of the Australian workplace into the
murky waters of enterprise bargaining. The new Coalition government
is throwing it into the deep end of deregulation. For female workers
the news is not good. &quot;The evidence from overseas shows that
the more decentralised the bargaining, the worse it is for women,&quot;
says Suzanne Jamieson, spokesperson for the National Pay Equity
Coalition.
<P>
Since enterprise bargaining began, Australian women in many instances
have not been able to participate or achieve better wages and
conditions for a number of reasons. They often work in poorly
unionised workplaces and they suffer from poor representation
within union bureaucracies. Female employees are concentrated
in low paying and low skilled jobs. They do high levels of part-time
and casual work and are more likely to bear the brunt of family
responsibilities.
<P>
Enterprise bargain-ing encourages productivity-based wage increases,
but female employees are concentrated in service industries where
productivity is difficult to measure. &quot;If you're a nurse
for example how do you measure productivity? Count the turnover
in beds? Well one way of doing that is to kill the patients!&quot;
Jamieson exclaims. &quot;It's very different from say a factory
where you can measure input and output.&quot;
<P>
The objective of the new legislation is to focus on the economy.
The government wants to encourage high employment and low inflation,
reduce the deficit and increase productivity; but at what cost
to female workers?
<P>
The Coalition promises that no worker will go home with less money
in their pocket as a result of the changes. However awards will
be stripped back to 18 conditions, leaving everything else up
for grabs, to be bargained for. Rosemary Keogh, Senior Industrial
Officer with the Finance Sector Union says, &quot;There is now
no pressure through the industrial system for employers to conform
to long standing conditions, and women are going to cop most of
the downgrading&quot;.
<P>
The new individual contracts, to be known as Australian Work-place
Agreements [AWAs], will completely over-ride awards. Though according
to Keogh these awards will wither away over time anyhow. Accord-ing
to Barbara Pocock, a lecturer at the Centre for Labour Studies
at the University of Adelaide, &quot;people who remain on awards
will fall behind the community standard of pay, and women will
be disproportionately left on decaying award standards&quot;.
<P>
The Coalition says workers can choose between the award and an
AWA. But what a choice! Employees may &quot;choose&quot; to make
agreements but if they choose not to they will remain on the minimum
award and lose significant award conditions. Effectively they
have no choice but to sign the agreement.
<P>
AWA's can be negotiated collectively or individually, but are
signed individually. Once the AWA is signed by the employer and
employee, a new institution, the Office of Employment Advocate
(OEA) will stamp the agreement. Although incredibly the OEA has
no mandate to examine its provisions.
<P>
&quot;The Minister [for Industrial Relations, Peter Reith] says
that the agreement cannot be lower than the award but would the
average worker know if it was lower than the award?&quot; Jamieson
asks. &quot;To think that the average ordinary individual with
no industrial relations background would have the information
they need to negotiate an equitable agreement is absurd!&quot;
agrees Keogh. &quot;We are very concerned that people will just
be signing anything to hang on to their jobs,&quot; Jamieson adds.
<P>
The only protection provisions are that AWAs must meet the government's
no disadvantage test. What is the no dis-advantage test? The employer
signs an affidavit to say that the agreement meets the minimum
provisions. In effect this means employers are keeping an eye
on themselves; which sets off alarm bells for Jamieson and Keogh.
&quot;It's a simple system of filing the agreement with the Employment
Advocate. It's a clerical process. It is not scrutinised or monitored
in any way!&quot; protests Jamieson.
<P>
The OEA will not make agreements public, which means a whole range
of pay and conditions will no longer be publicly scrutinised.
&quot;Secrecy is the great enemy of equity. It is possible that
different pay rates will exist for different workers and that
discrimination will be hard to track down and eliminate,&quot;
says Pocock. &quot;Not having the capacity to do an across the
board look at wages based on different skills means we lose the
opportunity to overturn undervaluations of women's work,&quot;
she adds.
<P>
Opponents of the legislation dismiss the Office of Employment
Advocate as impotent. &quot;The OEA does not enforce entitlements,
it just informs you of what they are. If you have a complaint
you will have to pursue it through the courts using a private
solicitor. The legal fraternity must be thrilled,&quot; says Keogh.
<P>
The Coalition has tried to pacify critics by affirming its commitment
to equal pay for work of equal value, but to no avail. &quot;We
have had equal pay for equal work since 1969 and in fact in NSW
since 1958 so that's not exactly a huge concession,&quot; scoffs
Jamieson. &quot;Anyway in terms of giving women protection it
doesn't at all. This is not where the problem lies. It lies largely
in over award payments. Women earn on average a lot less than
men in terms of over award earnings. There is a huge disparity
in take-home pay and now this won't be inquired into by the Industrial
Relations Commission (IRC),&quot; she says.
<P>
The IRC will only have the power to arbitrate over core award
conditions. Therefore the Commission will not be able to look
at gender discrimination in over award bargaining, yet currently
women receive only 54 per cent of male over award earnings. &quot;When
we met with the Minister, he said women would be able to pursue
complaints through the Sex Discrimination Act at the Human Rights
and Equal Opportunity Commission,&quot; says Jamieson. &quot;This
is clearly inadequate. The queue at the commission is long and
the whole process is cumbersome, expensive, not user friendly
and women haven't noticeably used it in the past,&quot; she adds.
<P>
Women's average weekly ordinary time earnings are now only around
84 per cent of the male wage [according to the ABS]. Jamieson
says that in total wages that figure is much lower, at around
66 per cent. Pocock fears that this gap will widen. &quot;It has
already hap-pened in the managed system of enterprise bargaining
under Labor and it's particularly visible in Kennet's Victoria,&quot;
she says.
<P>
Pocock is extremely concerned about the diminished power of the
IRC. &quot;The IRC has had a significant brief over the past 100
years, for equity in wage fixing. Everyone has the right to a
decent living wage and equity in remuneration. The Commission
can no longer arbitrate in situations of inequity. It can't play
a role to keep the system clean,&quot; she says.
<P>
The new legislation also places constraints on unions entering
the workplace. From now on, union officials will only be able
to enter a workplace if they have a written invitation from one
or more members. The official must also be dealing with the matter
specified in the invitation, making it impossible to go into workplaces
to find out what problems exist.
<P>
&quot;While imperfect vehicles, they [unions] are the only method
of protection for a lot of women, and its going to be tougher
to organise that support for yourself. Women are often in small
workplaces and are frightened of involving the union, and with
this bill the employer gets the names of the employees who asked
for a union visit. Women will not want to expose themselves as
asking for help from the union,&quot; says Pocock.
<P>
Vulnerable workers such as women, especially women from non-English
speaking backgrounds, will not thrive under the new legislation.
&quot;A minority will do well out of the deregulated system but
unfortunately because of the segmentation of the labour market
women will come out quite badly,&quot; says Keogh. &quot;I don't
like the chances of a lot of people out there.&quot; 
<P>
In 1994 <I>Snoop </I>reported the story of the female clerical
workers at the Villawood (NSW) branch of Taubmans, the well-known
paint manufacturer. Like many other clerical staff, they were
excluded from the site enterprise agreement in 1992, despite petitions
to the Industrial Relations Commission by the Federated Clerks
Union on their behalf.
<P>
Taubmans and the Liquor, Hospitality and Miscellaneous Union (LHMU)
maintained that the agreement applied only to the manufacture
and distribution of paint, and dismissed claims that increased
productivity would increase administration. <I>Snoop </I>noted
that at another Taubmans factory in Sunshine, Victoria, the clerks
negotiated their own agreement which included a $30 per week wage
rise.
<P>
The story continues. The clerks in Victoria negotiated their own
agreement because the LHMU failed to include them in their claim,
and because management refused to negotiate with their representatives,
the Australian Services Union. Taubmans entered into an agreement
with the LHMU, and asked the clerical workers to sign contracts
which included no rostered days-off, no overtime pay and an annual
review of wages. The company didn't offer payrises to compensate
for the loss of the entitlements.
<P>
The clerks took industrial action to force management to negotiate,
and they eventually gained a higher pay-rise than the LHMU members.
However, it was not to be a happy ending. <I>Inside Enterprise
Bargaining</I>, a newsletter which includes case studies on enterprise
agreements, reports that Taubmans later retrenched the workers,
centralising it's clerical work in Sydney.
</TD> 
</TR>

