<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><A HREF="../journos.htm"><FONT SIZE=+1>The <BR>journalists</FONT></A></B><BR>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="cover.htm">Return to Contents</A><BR></FONT></B><P>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
</TD>

<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Fleet St guilty - the media's mauling of James Bulger.
</FONT><BR></B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<I>IN NOVEMBER 1993, two 11-year-old boys, Robert Thompson and Jon
Venables, were tried and convicted of the killing of a young child,
James Bulger, in their home town of Liverpool, England. <A HREF="../journos.htm#rkress">RACHEL
KRESS</A> examines how the British media constructed the story known
as the Bulger case.</I>
<P>
BOTH boys come from Walton, tough neighbour-hood in a tough city,
and both come from large families presided over by single families
who are dependent on public aid.&quot; (from <I>New York Times
Index: A Book of Record, 1993.</I>)<I>The New York Times Index</I>
is a chronicle which summarises complex events and issues for
the benefit or journalists researching background information.
<P>
The above quote isn't exactly wrong (grammar aside), but it isn't
exactly right either; and this is the crux of the crime journalism
tradition: a story makes it to the newsstand not because it's
an accurate reflection of reality, but because it's a story told
with recourse to common cultural conceptions.
<P>
The British media's coverage of the Bulger case began on the evening
of Friday February 12, 1993, several hours after James Bulger
was reported missing from a Liverpool shopping centre. On Sunday
the papers had run the video-still of James being &quot;led away&quot;.
By Monday every national paper ran the story that up north in
Liverpool a young child had been abducted and probably killed
by the two unidentified boys in the security video-still.
<P>
Almost two weeks later, Robert Thompson and John Venables were
brought in for questioning. The coverage then dissipated until
just prior to the November trial, climaxing with the release of
the verdict (to which papers devoted whole lift-out sections).
By early December the coverage had all but ceased, only resurfacing
with the occasional update on the convicted boys' appeals.
<P>
The version of the Bulger case that has entered the public memory
is not a transparent record of the case, but the media's representation
of events. This representation has become an obligatory reference
point for any story about juvenile crime. A 1995 episode of ABC's
<I>Lateline</I>, &quot;Violent Innocents&quot;, was dominated
by images and 'facts' about the Bulger case culled from the media
archive. In May this year a <I>Four Corners</I> episode on the
ABC made a passing reference to the Bulger case to support an
argument that a predilection for violent videos can lead to the
committing of violent crime.
<P>
The idea that a violent video may have motivated the Bulger killing
came from a press all too willing to report speculation. No evidence
was ever found by British police, nor presented during the trial,
that Robert or Jon had ever seen the video now automatically associated
with the case, <I>Child's Play 3</I>.
<P>
And yet the issue of video violence dominated Mr Justice Moorland's
summation. Indeed his (and the media's) insistence on the link
between James' death and <I>Child's Play 3</I> led to the restriction
of films available to the general public, by amendments to the
1994 Criminal Justice Act.
<P>
The British media was prepared for Justice Moorland's summation.
After all, it was the media that first asserted that violent videos,
poor home environments, John Major's weak leadership and Liverpool's
left-wing politics were the real culprits of the crime.
<P>
In a media unusually silent on that perennial post-trial favourite
- does the media influence the outcome of a trial? - the suggestion
that the Bulger case was first and foremost a media event never
stood a chance.
<P>
The media's post-verdict frenzy was mostly a re-run of the stories
it ran when the story broke, with the verdict functioning as the
legal stamp of approval. So similar were the stories that <I>The
Times</I> even recycled a paragraph from a February article in
one of its November articles.
<P>
The entire coverage was characterised by inaccuracies and assumptions.
The tabloids, who in February had been unable to wait for an arrest
(let alone a trial) before declaring the two boys &quot;GUILTY&quot;,
were also unable to wait for a sentence. <I>The Sun</I> impatiently
imposed the maximum adult term of 20 years in text so large it
filled half the front page. It then represented Justice Moorland's
recommendation of eight years as another example of misplaced
judicial leniency.
<P>
The broadsheets weren't much better. <I>The Times</I> reported
resoundingly, but inaccurately, that four &quot;guilty&quot; verdicts
were read out. (Only two &quot;guilty&quot; verdicts were read
out, the one other charge against Robert and Jon being left to
lie on file).
<P>
Throughout the coverage of the Bulger case, the media also criticised
the lack of intervention from the 38 people who witnessed the
boys' walk to the railway line. David James Smith, in his book
about the Bulger case titled <I>The Sleep of Reason</I>, suggests
the intensity of this criticism caused eyewitnesses to alter their
original statements, to either further incriminate the boys or
to protect themselves from any possibility of blame. One woman
who had seen the boys from a bus told the police ten days after
the incident that she had &quot;commented&quot; on the scene to
her daughter sitting beside her. In court she claimed to have
alerted the entire bus. Another witness denied telling the police
she had asked the boys if they knew the young child and denied
stating that they had answered her &quot;no&quot;.
<P>
That the British media had repeatedly fulfilled all four grounds
upon which a stay of proceedings can be granted on the grounds
of undue influence under British law, and in doing so may have
predetermined the trial's outcome, was never reported in the press.
And yet the defence counsel for Robert Thompson was able to produce
a sample of 243 examples of prejudicial reporting, ranging from
assertions of the boys' guilt to portraits of them as evil monsters.
<P>
One article in<I>The Independent</I> acknowledged the press' role
when it reported the unsuccessful application for a stay of proceedings
due to undue media influence. Another minor article in <I>The
Times</I> discussed the possibility of media pressure affecting
the witness' evidence. In general, however, Bulger case articles
either assumed a distance from the event or, more convincingly,
assumed the voice of the public, against allegedly unresponsive
politicians.
<P>
But the politicians were listening and, excluding the Prime Minister
John Major who eagerly encouraged the British public to &quot;understand
a little less and condemn a little more&quot;, they were just
waiting to discover what class of culprit they were dealing with.
<P>
Once Robert and Jon had been identified as working class, and
the media had articulated the public opinion, the politicians
were more than ready to speak.
<P>
Within two weeks of James' death, the Home Secretary Kenneth Clarke
announced the Government's intention to get tough on 'bail bandits'
(those who re-offend whilst on bail); and also to allow the courts
to draw inference of guilt from an accused's silence. A further
proposal to reintroduce &quot;glasshouses&quot; (military style
youth detention centres) is still being debated.
<P>
At the time the Bulger case broke, the media, the police and the
Government were claiming that juvenile crime was escalating. A
tricky task, given the statistics were not in their favour. <I>The
Sun</I> circumnavigated this problem by printing a red rising
zigzag over their double page crime spreads, thereby signifying
surging statistics without having to produce any.
<P>
In 1993, misdemeanours of &quot;working-class&quot; children between
the ages of ten and 15 were being considered for criminalisation;
childhood was represented as nurturing the earliest seeds of criminality.
Politicians and the press linked children's misde-meanours to
the lifestyle(s) which kids later allegedly developed - those
of the habitual criminal, the welfare dependent/cheat, the drug
addict, the single mother - and of the sort of places such people
lived - the estates.
<P>
Robert and Jon's age, class and family background meant they fitted
perfectly into this schema. In addition, being so young meant
they could represent all British children; alternatively, they
could represent their parents, their community or their geographic
location.
<P>
The alacrity and frequency with which newspapers published articles
asserting that &quot;Poor parenting breeds youth crime&quot;,
and that crime has a &quot;sociological&quot; and &quot;geographical
memory,&quot; always juxtaposed with Bulger reports, demonstrates
how the media utilised popular cultural conceptions concerning
crime. Facts about the boys' families were downplayed or emphasised
to fit the standard assumptions of who is a criminal.
<P>
For example, the media<I> </I>utilised Robert Thompson's unemployed
mother and his Roman Catholic Irish descent to suggest that he
and his crime were not quite British. The tabloids ran photos
of housing estates - the usual media signifier of crime - next
to articles suggesting these were breeding grounds for crime.
The same media barely mentioned that James' family lived on a
housing estate and that his parents were unmarried, unemployed
and Roman Catholic. Furthermore Robert and Jon lived in terrace
houses which traditionally signify the &quot;good&quot; working-class.
<P>
In <I>Hooligan: A History of Respectable Fears</I>, British sociologist
Geoffrey Pearson charted the constant recycling of this age-old
story: the alarming rise in juvenile crime due to an unprecedented
collective lapse of public morality. In doing so, Pearson noted
that this story has always had its sights fixed firmly on the
working classes.
<P>
The Bulger case fitted this story so well because the crime occurred
in Liverpool. Thanks to the stories about Liverpool which get
reported in the London papers, the city is associated with a strong
unrepentant working class identity, an ongoing opposition to Thatcherite
policies, the Toxteth riots, the Hillsborough and Heysel soccer
stadium disasters. The press used these stories to insinuate that
working class Liverpool courts disaster.
<P>
In the London papers, this story blended with another, indirectly
revealing a tale of two cities: two sets of values, two views
on how to discipline a child, manage a city or govern a people.
It was with this narrative concoction that the press blamed Liverpool's
left-wing civic politics, and Robert and Jon's non-nuclear families
for producing two children representative of a generation which
was not 'childish', and by implication not British.
</TD> 
</TR>

