<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="hope.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=138></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT><FONT SIZE=2>Kevin Williams<BR> Pic by Lara McKinley</FONT></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>A glimmer of hope</FONT><BR></B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<I>
The Federal Government has Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander
organisations in its sights, threatening major funding cuts and
showing little sympathy for self determination. But when <A HREF="../journos.htm#htarare">HECTOR
TARARE </A>spoke to long time Aboriginal activist Kevin Williams he
found hope rather than despair.</I>
<P>
The mood in Aboriginal organisations over the months since the
election of the new Howard Federal government has been one of
pessimism and a feeling that gains so slowly won may be reversed.
But one activist Kevin Williams, University of Technology, Sydney
law student and leader in the Tharawal community in Sydney's west
thinks that solidarity in fighting cutbacks may bring positive
results to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander students. Instead
of destroying the movement for indigenous rights the Coalition
attacks may bring back its lost unity of purpose.
<P>
Williams has been part of the ups and down of the Aboriginal civil
rights movement for the past 30 years. He was one of a stolen
generation of Aboriginal children who spent their childhood in
institutions. From his days as a student activist in high school
to the heady time of the tent embassy outside Parliament House
in Canberra in 1972, Williams has been part of many major events
of Aboriginal history.
<P>
Looking back on the past 50 years of the Aboriginal civil rights
movement, Williams acknowledges the contribution of his mother's
generation to the struggle for equality.
<P>
&quot;My mother is 66 years old and before her time we just had
to accept what was given to us. From her generation onwards, we
started to realise we didn't have to accept this any more. We
don't have to take what is given to us, we don't have to do what
they tell us to do,&quot; Williams said.
<P>
He stresses the importance of generations passing on the baton
of experience. &quot;I have the greatest respect for the people
of my mother's generation who started the movement and who gave
us a platform to follow on with. I see it as really important
for my generation to pass the enthusiasm on to my children, to
say 'okay the fight's not won, you've got to keep fighting.
<P>
&quot;We have to do something for the next generation and make
sure that we constantly put before society that they can't do
what they have done to us in the past and get away with it.&quot;
<P>
Williams believes the progress which Aboriginal people have made
through their collective action has led to complacency in younger
Aboriginal people who no longer appreciate the struggle of previous
generations.
<P>
&quot;I think the younger generation coming through behind us
have lost the knowledge of what it is to fight for something that
you haven't got. These days it seems more easy for us to understand
that we've got something because we get access to things. The
fight has lost a bit of the early edge to it.&quot;
<P>
The Coalition government's threats of financial cuts to education
and social programs may present a rallying point to re-activate
Aboriginal civil rights programs. Many communities report that
factional disputes threaten to undo much of the work of the civil
rights movement. Part of the explanation for such disputes relates
to previous government policies in the nineteenth and twentieth
century when Aboriginal people were moved to establish new &quot;communities&quot;
regardless of differing social backgrounds.
<P>
Rallies which were held in Canberra and the major cities in May
indicate that young Aboriginal people are taking up the challenge
of resistance once again.
<P>
Kevin Williams thinks the development of a closer alliance between
Aboriginal people from city and rural areas is a high priority
in achieving self determination. The Mabo decision in the High
Court and the subsequent native title legislation has emphasised
land demands in rural areas. Aboriginal communities in cities
see the divisions between rural and urban Aborigines as a remnant
of the colonial period.
<P>
Williams is concerned that divisions in the Aboriginal movement
will reinforce attitudes which whites perpetrated in the past,
especially the view that city Aborigines are not authentic.
<P>
&quot;What we see happening in a number of cases is that we are
taking on those kinds of tools that were used to oppress us in
the past. Even in our communities some people are defining ourselves
in terms of skin colour in exactly the same way that white governments
of the part used to do with us,&quot; Williams said.
<P>
One issue which may bring Aboriginal people together could be
the failure of governments to implement the recommendations of
the Royal Commission into Aboriginal Deaths in Custody. The Royal
Commission presented a devastating picture of social conditions
in Aboriginal communities. Health standards, housing and unemployment
were shown to be at Third World levels yet governments have still
done little to address the problems.
<P>
Williams is critical of this failure. He is part of UTS's Aboriginal
research unit, Jumbunna's project on government responses to the
Royal Commission. The research findings are disturbing. &quot;The
recommendations of the Royal Commission have mostly not been implemented
or not implemented to the level that they should have,&quot; Williams
said.
<P>
&quot;The level to which Aboriginal people are oppressed daily
by the conditions around them leads to them being oppressed by
legal systems. We have to look no further than the gaols and the
courts.&quot;
<P>
Williams' advice to younger Aboriginal leaders is simple. &quot;What
I say is to be as informed as you possibly can. If you're informed
and know what your rights are, and know how to stand up and speak
up on issues, then that's the best way to deal with racism&quot;.
</TD> 
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2>
