<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="aborigin.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=121></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT><FONT SIZE=2>Demonstrators outside the Elizabeth street building on the occasion of the 150th Anniversary "Day of Mourning", 26 January, 1938. Pic: State Library of NSW</FONT></TR></TD>
</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>The fight continues over Aboriginal site</FONT><BR></B>
<P>By <A HREF="../journos.htm#hterare">Hector Terare</A></CENTER>
<P>
AN UNIMPOSING grey building in Elizabeth Street in Sydney has
been, at various time a social club, cinema and headquarters of
the Knights of the Southern Cross, a secret organisation within
the Catholic Church. The owners of the unremarkable looking building,
the trustees of the Cyprus - Hellene Club want to sell the building
to developers and move the club to outer suburbs.
<P>
But members of the Aboriginal community and their supporters regard
the building as a site of national significance. On January 1938
as white Australia celebrated 150 as a British colony and nation,
100 Aboriginal men and women gathered in the then Australian Hall
to mourn the loss of their land and demand basic human rights.
<P>
The meeting was the first nation wide civil rights protest. It
was called a &quot;Day of Mourning and Protest&quot; and those
who took part risked severe penalties for taking part in the protest.
Some of the protest leaders were removed from missions and reserves
by white managers when they tried to address local protest meetings.
<P>
The Aboriginal History Committee, which is leading the fight to
preserve the building has sought a Permanent Conservation Order
on the building.
<P>
The Aboriginal History Committee was formed at the University
of Technology, Sydney (UTS) in 1994 to pursue issues related to
Aboriginal history and heritage in response to the threat posed
to the Day of Mourning Site. Students and staff who formed the
committee decided to focus on the issue of preserving the site,
while also pursuing other issues related to Aboriginal history
and heritage.
<P>
The Committee, which is now a permanent body will soon hold a
forum to establish a national history body.
<P>
Ronald Briggs, Chairperson of the committee recognises the 1938
meeting in the Elizabeth Street building as the beginning of the
Aboriginal civil rights movement. 
<P>
&quot;We all need to value the contributions made by those who
have struggled to ensure that we have basic rights,&quot; Briggs
said.
<P>
When plans for the sale and demolition of the building were announced
in 1994, the Committee fought for a Commission of Inquiry. Esme
Beaupark, the Secretary of the Committee, an Aboriginal student
at UTS, who commenced tertiary study in her late fifties played
a key role in the successful fight for the Commission of Inquiry.
She died after a short illness in January this year.
<P>
At a Commission of Inquiry in 1995 Beaupark and other Aboriginal
activists, supported by the Australian Heritage Commission, National
Trust and Sydney City Council argued for a Permanent Conservation
order on the building.
<P>
More than one year after the inquiry, the NSW Minister for Urban
Affairs, Craig Knowles, has neither publicly released the findings
of the Committee, nor announced the decision on the conservation
order.
<P>
Briggs recently outlined the reasons for seeking a permanent order.
<P>
&quot;Since the onset of European occupation, most traditional
sites of significance have been obliterated. The errors of the
past must not be repeated. The building at 150-152 Elizabeth Street
Sydney is a site of contemporary Aboriginal heritage&quot;, Briggs
said.
<P>
The 1938 rally was attended by activists who are now recognised
as leaders in the struggle for Aboriginal civil rights. Among
those present were Jack Patten, William Ferguson, Pearl Gibbs,
Pastor Doug Nicholls, Margaret Tucker, William Cooper and Jack
Kinchella.
<P>
Those who attended the Day of Mourning put forward a ten point
recommendation which many see as the basis of Federal Government
intervention in Aboriginal Affairs.
<P>
&quot;My involvement with trying to save the Day of Mourning Site
has shown that a lot of people out there are still pretty ignorant.
I suppose legally our rights have been enhanced with civil rights,
land rights and Mabo but socially and politically we have much
more to achieve&quot;, Briggs said.
<P>
Once a Permanent Conservation Order has been granted, the Aboriginal
History Committee has proposed that the building be developed
as an Aboriginal History Centre. The Centre would include a museum
to Aboriginal heroes, resource and information centre, a base
for Aboriginal Heritage Tours and a theatre for films plays, public
lectures and special events.
<P>
According to a statement published by the Aboriginal History Committee,
&quot;the building provides a physical and atmospheric link to
the 1930's era. It evokes sensations of the 1938 event which could
not be re-created in a modern setting&quot;.
<P>
At a rally outside the building in March this year, supporters
of the campaign were joined by descendents of the civil rights
leaders to demand that the site be preserved for future generations.
<P>
The protesters heard a passionate call from the son of Jack Kinchela
to preserve the building. Pauline Gordon, the daughter of Jack
Patten attended with her grandson, Joe. Another link with the
1938 protest was June Barker, the grand-daughter of William Ferguson.
Ms Barker spoke to protesters about the significance of the Day
of Mourning Site for all Aboriginal Australians.
<P>
Ronald Briggs described the emotion at the March 9 rally this
year as older descendants told the young in attendance about the
courage of their great grandparents who attended the Day of Mourning
and Protest fifty eight years ago. &quot;Many people cried openly
as they entered the building,&quot; Briggs said.
<P>
There have been 629 Permanent Protection Orders granted to preserve
sites of white heritage in New South Wales.
<P>
The campaign to save the Cyprus-Hellene Club building is the first
bid for a Permanent Conservation Order under the NSW Heritage
Act for a site of Aboriginal Historical Significance.
<P>
The campaign to save the Day of Mourning site is not merely about
preserving a building. It is also about changing the belief, held
by many Australians that Aboriginal history ended with colonisation,
and that Aboriginal heritage is limited to cave paintings and
similar remnants of pre-1788 life.
<P>
Until now Aboriginal heritage claims have been dealt with through
National Parks and Wildlife legislation. Members of the Aboriginal
History Committee argue that Aboriginal heritage claims should
be pursued like non-Aboriginal claims, through national and state
heritage acts.
<P>
 The Aboriginal History Committee is seeking public support for
the preservation campaign. Aboriginal and non Aboriginal people
are encouraged to write to Mr Bob Carr, Premier of New South Wales
and Mr Craig Knowles, Minister for Planning, expressing concern
that the findings of the 1995 Inquiry have not been released.
<P>
The Aboriginal History Committee, PO Box A765, Sydney South, NSW
2000. Tel:(02)9267 6074, Fax: (02) 9264 6092
</TD> 
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2>
