<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Snoop:Indonesia's Big Bang; what will Australia do?</TITLE></HEAD>
  
<BODY BACKGROUND="../IMAGES/bgyellow.gif" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=600 NOSHADE> 
 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=600>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=100 ROWSPAN=2 VALIGN=middle ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Winter<BR>1996</FONT></TD>
<TD width=500 valign=middle align=center><IMG WIDTH=400 SRC="../IMAGES/snoop.gif"></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=+1><I>A Magazine of U.T.S. Journalism - Internet Edition</I></FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=600 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=2 WIDTH=600>
<TR>
<TD width=100 valign=top align=center>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=2>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Next Story<BR><A HREF="mangrove.htm"><I>Mangrove Conservation</A></I></FONT></B><BR>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2><P><A HREF="indones.htm#related"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Related<BR>Stories</FONT></B></A><BR>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><A HREF="../journos.htm"><FONT SIZE=+1>The <BR>journalists</FONT></A></B><BR>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="cover.htm">Return to Contents</A><BR></FONT></B><P>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
</TD>

<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD align=right>
<IMG SRC="indones.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=105>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT><FONT SIZE=2>School children and a nuclear power plant, Japan. Photo courtesy of Greenpeace Australia</FONT></TD></TD>
<TR><TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Indonesia's Big Bang;</FONT><BR><FONT SIZE=+1>what will Australia do?</FONT><BR></B>
<P>By <A HREF="../journos.htm#mkearney">Marianne Kearney</A></CENTER>
<P>
Indonesia's decision to proceed with the construction of the country's
first nuclear reactor in Java, raises serious safety concerns
in the aftermath of a nuclear accident, recent studies by the
Australian National University (ANU) show. The studies of nuclear
fallout predict that most of northern Australia would be covered
in radioactive cloud. Yet emergency plans for this part of Australia
are far from ready to deal with this disturbing scenario.
<P>
The Assistant Director of Emergency Management Australia (EMA),
Robin Herron admits that EMA has no nationally coordinated emergency
plan for the spread of radioactive cloud from a reactor accident.
Herron said that Australia did not have an emergency plan in the
case of this type of accident in Java or in South-East Asia because
this is an &quot;unrealistic scenario.&quot; Yet leading Indonesian
activists and academics have concerns that this scenario is very
realistic (see box).
<P>
Herron rejects the findings of the recent fallout studies done
by ANU because he says Indonesia is too far away. Although conceding
he has not read the ANU study, Herron says that the levels of
radiation would be very low and a radioactive cloud would disperse
before reaching Australia. He argues that the water cooled reactors,
built since Chernobyl, would contain the radioactive leakage if
an accident occurred.
<P>
According to Mr Mick Lucas, Director of the Northern Territory
State Emergency Service (NTSES), the Northern Territory has no
plans for a nuclear reactor accident. According to Lucas the only
emergency plan SES can fall back on for a reactor accident is
a &quot;storm surge plan&quot;. (A storm surge happens when the
cyclone whips up the tides to create a flood).
<P>
A key problem with this approach to emergency services is that
although nuclear fallout doesn't recognise state boundaries, the
response to the accident is determined by these boundaries. The
response to a radioactive cloud spreading over northern Australia
would require coordination of a number of different plans from
different states. While cooperation between states, such as between
the Northern Territory and Queensland, allows for cross border
operations, it is not an actual plan for mobilising emergency
resources.
<P>
Herron says that EMA has a comprehensive contingency plan to deal
with radiation leakage from a nuclear powered ship. However this
plan is based on organising the evacuation of a major city, for
example clearing the population of an area of three to four kilometres,
not a whole state. EMA also has an emergency plan if radioactive
debris were to fall to Australia.
<P>
The recently released nuclear fallout studies by Dr John Taylor
at the Centre for Resource and Environmental Studies, ANU, predict
that an accident would be most detrimental for northern Australia
during summer when fallout would cover the region within 48 hours.
Dr Taylor says that although his model had allowed for a reduction
in the radioactive concentration of the cloud as it travelled
from central Java, radioactivity would still be 75 percent of
the levels at the site of the accident.
<P>
The study was not based on a Chernobyl style accident but could
be applied to map fallout for any type of reactor accident.Dr
Taylor said in the months from December to February the cloud
could travel south quite quickly and it would be &quot;a good
idea&quot; to have a radiation detector somewhere off the coast
of Darwin, such as at Christmas Island. He said that if there
were rainfall just after the accident, this would probably increase
the amount of radioactive particles that reached Australian soil.
Dr Taylor said rainfall after the Chernobyl accident in 1986,
increased the dosage of fallout England received.
<P>
This study confirms the conclusions of an earlier study done by
the Strategic Centre at ANU, 1991.
<P>
If one of Java's reactors leaked radiation, Indonesia would be
obliged by international regulations to notify its neighbours,
including Australia, and the International Atomic Energy Agency
(IAEA) as soon as possible. However when the Chernobyl reactor
overheated it was several days before the Soviets notified any
of their neighbours. It was only after the high levels of radiation
in the atmosphere were detected by monitoring equipment in central
Europe that the Soviet Government admitted that there had been
an accident.
<P>
Alternatively if Indonesia failed to notify Australia of an accident,
the release of radioactive cloud into the atmosphere could be
picked up by the air radiation monitors located in either Darwin
or Perth. Filter papers which collect the sample particles are
sent to the Australian Radiation Laboratory (ARL) in Melbourne
for analysis. Currently, however radiation monitoring occurs on
a weekly basis, too slow for the early detection of high radiation
levels.
<P>
According to Malcolm Cooper from ARL this radiation testing process
could be sped up. He said if the comprehensive Test Ban Treaty,
currently being internationally negotiated, was implemented, Australia
as part of an international network of monitoring stations would
make daily checks on air radiation levels.
<P>
If daily checks were made Cooper said that within four hours of
receiving the test samples ARL scientists would be alerted to
abnormally high radiation levels. So if radioactive fallout was
collected on samples taken in Darwin in a 24 hour period, the
samples flown to Melbourne and tested within four hours, it would
take approximately 30 hours before State Emergency Services (SES)
were notified. This leaves the respective SES's 18 hours in which
to organise the evacuation of their state, or else organise alternative
safety shelters.
<P>
Cooper said that AL was &quot;looking at incorporating&quot; an
automatic radiation detector into its system within two years.
He said this system was &quot;the best sort of early warning device
for accidents&quot; used around the world. This device automatically
processes samples every 24 hours, bypassing the need for a laboratory
examination. With this system in place the notification time of
an accident would be shortened.
<P>
Assuming SES's storm surge plan was activated there may easily
be some teething problems because the storm surge plan has never
been tested. Cyclone Tracey was the closest that Darwin came to
a storm surge. Lucas from the Northern Territory's SES said Cyclone
Tracy was mild compared to the storm that would have raged through
Darwin if the tides had been high.
<P>
Lucas agrees that the effects of a storm surge and a nuclear reactor
accident are quite different. The major difference being that
the surge is only expected to cover a coastal strip for 24 kilometres
spreading two kilometres inland and SES would expect to have up
to 24 hours notice. Whereas according to the recent ANU study
a nuclear accident at the wrong time of year spreads a cloud covering
the northern Australia in 48 hours.
<P>
Lucas admits that if the whole of the Territory were to be evacuated
SES would have a logistical nightmare on their hands.
<P>
Allowing for a warning time of between six to 12 hours in which
time the media can advise people to evacuate and the different
arms of the SES can be organised, the plan assumes the &quot;orderly
departure&quot; of the population of Darwin along the major highway.
However if the whole of the Territory were to evacuate along this
route perhaps their departure would not be so orderly.
<P>
Lucas says SES's solution would be to organise shelter for the
population of the Territory. Yet there are currently no radiation
proof shelters in existence in the Territory
<P>
The emergency plan for a surge involves the evacuation of Darwin's
population of approximately 80 000 people with the assistance
of 700 emergency workers. This includes 200 police, 100 ambulance
workers and 400 volunteers. Mr Lucas wasn't sure how many SES
workers there were in the whole of the Territory but he said there
were 775 in the police force available for assistance.
<P>
Lucas was unable to give transportation details for the 1.3 million
head of cattle in the Territory but he says this would be the
responsibility of the Department of Primary Industry. The cattle
industry the most valuable primary industry in the Northern Territory
notched up $107 million in total sales in the last year alone.
A major industry which it would be impossible to protect from
a radioactive cloud is the fishing industry (worth $95 million
in total sales last year).
<P>
A major hurdle to the smooth running of the emergency plan is
how SES would evacuate all the Aborigines scattered on remote
outstations in the Territory. The latest figures from the Aboriginal
and Torres Strait Islander Commission (ATSIC) in Alice Springs,
indicate that 13 000 Aborigines, living in the vicinity of Alice
Springs, are spread over an area of 830 000 square kilometres.
<P>
Dave Price from ATSIC in Alice Springs said he was &quot;concerned&quot;
about the health effects of a radioactive cloud on the Aboriginal
people particularly as he has witnessed adverse affects on Aborigines
exposed to radiation during the Maralinga nuclear tests conducted
in South Australia.
<P>
Price said the Aboriginal communities are hard to monitor because
the size of the communities is very &quot;fluid&quot;. Most are
contactable by phone or short wave radio, but the location of
some smaller communities is known only to their families.
<P>
Price points out seasonal flooding is a feature of some of the
remote areas that Aboriginal communities inhabit. &quot;In an
emergency people would have to be flown out&quot; of these regions
says Price. He says that for six months of the year &quot;nobody
moves anywhere&quot; in the Catherine region, round the Daly River
area and in parts of Arnham Land.
<P>
Price also points out that there were several small islands off
the coast of the Northern territory where the only form of transport
is by air. The SES's storm surge emergency plan for Aboriginal
communities on small islands involves them moving to higher ground
to avoid flooding but on some islands their is no provision for
their evacuation.
<P>
Is it &quot;patronising&quot; to ask about Indonesia's safety
standards?
<P>
In Australia, Senator Parer, Minister for Energy and Resources,
suggested in March this year that it is &quot;patronising&quot;
to question whether Indonesia will be able to construct a nuclear
reactor which satisfies international safety standards. While
Indonesia's pro-nuclear spokes-people are confident that an accident
is highly unlikely.
<P>
Iyos Subki, the President of BATAN (Indonesian atomic energy agency)
assured Australians on ABC's Lateline that the likelihood of an
accident occurring would be a &quot;one in a million years&quot;
event.
<P>
Yet anecdotal evidence suggests that Indonesia's construction
procedures are not as regulated as in the West. Dr Clive Hamilton,
an economic adviser to the Indonesian Government in the early
1990's, says Western engineers were critical of Indonesians construction
and regulation standards. They cited construction workers and
engineers who took a lot of shortcuts when building major works.
Dr Hamilton questions whether strict construction procedures and
the rigorous engineering required to build a reactor would be
compromised.
<P>
Hamilton also notes BATAN's nuclear proposal was &quot;completely
quarantined&quot; and &quot;only BBPT (the Science and Technology
Ministry) had access to it&quot; when he was working there. This
raises the question of how Indonesia would be able to establish
an independent regulatory body, required by the International
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), to monitor the operation of the reactor.
<P>
Dr Hamilton also questioned whether Indonesia would be able to
financially operate a nuclear power station according to the safety
levels required internationally by the International Atomic energy
Agency (IAEA).
<P>
Indonesian anti-nuclear activists have questioned the economics
behind the Canadian Atomic Energy Company's (AECL) bid for the
construction of the reactor. &quot;Canada has found nuclear plants
are not economical, because of the public's high demand for safety
standards&quot; but &quot;now they are dumping their nuclear power
plants on us&quot; said Mohammad Anung, a campaigner with leading
environmental group WAHLI, in the <I>Jakarta Post</I> in January
this year.
<P>
According to Dr Aditjondro, a leading Indonesian environmentalist,
the feasibility study commissioned by the Indonesian Government,
failed to include an assessment of the effect of a volcanic faultline
and a minor crater at Mount Muria, the proposed site. Dr Aditjondro,
in a paper on Indonesia's nuclear industry released in April this
year, points out that the limits to the feasibility study have
been criticised by the IAEA.
<P>
Senator Parer announced in March that Australia would be keen
to sell uranium to Indonesia. The sale of uranium would need to
be covered under a bilateral agreement which followed the guidelines
of IAEA's regulations on the sale of uranium. A spokesperson from
the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade could not say when
Australia might sign such an agreement.
</TD> 
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2>
<FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF="../copyrght.htm">Copyright&#169; 1996 ACIJ</A></FONT>
</CENTER>
