<HEAD><TITLE>Snoop:Justice through Murri law</TITLE></HEAD>
  
<BODY BACKGROUND="../IMAGES/bgyellow.gif" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#0000ff">
<BASEFONT SIZE=3>

<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=600 NOSHADE> 
 
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=600>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=100 ROWSPAN=2 VALIGN=middle ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Winter<BR>1996</FONT></TD>
<TD width=500 valign=middle align=center><IMG WIDTH=400 SRC="../IMAGES/snoop.gif"></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><FONT SIZE=+1><I>A Magazine of U.T.S. Journalism - Internet Edition</I></FONT></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<HR ALIGN=left WIDTH=600 NOSHADE> 

<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=2 WIDTH=600>
<TR>
<TD width=100 valign=top align=center>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=2>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Next Story<BR><A HREF="aborig.htm"><I>Aboriginal protest site</A></I></FONT></B><BR>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2><P><A HREF="murri.htm#related"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>Related<BR>Stories</FONT></B></A><BR>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><A HREF="../journos.htm"><FONT SIZE=+1>The <BR>journalists</FONT></A></B><BR>
</TD>
</TR>

<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>
<TR><TD> </TD></TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1><A HREF="cover.htm">Return to Contents</A><BR></FONT></B><P>
</TD>
</TR>

</TABLE>
</TD>

<TD>
<TABLE CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=5 WIDTH=500>
<TR><TD></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="murri.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=136></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT><FONT SIZE=2>Left to right: Esau Frank, Barry Barr, Maxwell Frank and Elroy Josiah 'on patrol' at Kowanyama. Pic courtesy of Yalga-binbi Institute</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=500 VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=2><FONT SIZE=6><CENTER><B>Justice through Murri Law</FONT><BR></B>
<P><A HREF="../journos.htm#bsalgado">By Barbara Salgado</A></CENTER>
<P>
&quot;THE biggest one was the break in at the school&quot;, said
Peena Geia. &quot;The Justice Group really got a hold of them
and we brought them all back down to the school and stood over
them. They were not allowed to have any lunch. We punished them
in that way, 'Nothing, until you clean up this mess!'&quot;
<P>
The &quot;mess&quot; she refers to was the work of a dozen teenagers
who broke into the Home Economics room of the local school, defecated
in cooking pots and rubbish bins, threw frozen meat around and
turned the freezers off.
<P>
&quot;They had to clean up and make up for it. And nobody was
to leave. They were under supervision from morning until afternoon.
We just showed them and since then they've never broken in,&quot;
she said proudly.
<P>
Peena Geia is the Aboriginal spokesperson for the Palm Island
Justice Group. The youngest member of the group, Peena is a formidable
woman, a devout Christian with unstoppable energy.
<P>
The Palm Island Justice Group is run by a group of 25 highly respected,
local, Aboriginal elders. They believe the mainstream juvenile
justice system has failed their community. Prior to the group's
formation in 1993, most juvenile offenders from Palm Island ended
up in Queensland detention centres.
<P>
In Queensland, Indigenous kids make up 45 per cent of the youth
in detention yet only comprise four per cent of the total juvenile
population. Despite the extensive findings of the 1991 Royal Commission
into Aboriginal Deaths in Custody, Aboriginal and Torres Strait
Islander youth, nationwide, between the ages of ten and 17, are
still 19 times more likely to be held in detention than other
kids.
<P>
But these alarming statistics no longer apply to Palm Island (nor
do they apply to the several other Aboriginal-Torres Strait Islander
communities which have also adopted a local justice system). In
fact, a staggering 70 per cent of young offenders brought before
the Palm Island Group do not re-offend - a remarkable achievement
in stopping young people becoming victims of the criminal justice
system.
<P>
Kowanyama, an Aboriginal community near Magnificent Creek on the
Mitchell River delta in far North Queensland, has also formed
an elders' group. The Kowanyama Justice Council is made up of
18 elected representatives from the Kokobera, Kokomnjena and Kunjen
or &quot;top end mob&quot; clans.
<P>
In 1993, the Kowanyama Justice Council's first year, the rate
of juvenile offending dropped from 540 cases to two. One year
later, local police statistics showed a significant reduction
in local crime. Break and enter fell by 82 per cent from 207 charges
in 1993 to 37 charges in 1994. Charges for theft fell by 91 per
cent, and assault by 68 per cent.
<P>
The elders of the Kowanyama Justice Council are understandably
proud. For many, it is the first time in their lives that they
have been able to have an impact in their community. In Kowanyama,
some of the older women from the Justice Council also volunteer
to be the &quot;barefoot&quot; night patrol. Three nights a week,
armed with a stick, they walk the streets. Breaking up fights,
sending children back home, they keep a watchful eye on community
members.
<P>
In 1995 the Palm Island, Kowanyama and Pompuraaw (another remote
Aboriginal community in Cape York) Justice Groups received the
Australian Prevention of Violence Award by Government Heads of
State. The success of the Justice groups is heartening for their
old people. The Justice groups had received no more than $5000
per year in one-off grants from the Queensland Corrective Services
Commission.
<P>
Operating as informal courts, the Palm Island Justice Group and
Kowanyama Justice Council call people to appear before them. On
Palm Island, the Group's elders command such respect that, despite
having no formal enforcement power, nobody has yet refused to
appear in the tiny local court where meetings are held. Both Groups
provide peaceful settlements to local conflicts with an emphasis
on making offenders responsible for their actions. The &quot;clean-up&quot;
punishment was successfully invoked for another group of Palm
Island teenagers who vandalised the school. For two weeks they
were made to clean up the school, the pre-school, kindergarten
and school grounds. &quot;The teacher was amazed, because they
cleaned up so well,&quot; said Peena. &quot;They even dug out
all the sand and they found that there were two extra steps which
the teachers never knew they had! Now that really stopped them.
Then their attendance was really good after that!&quot;
<P>
In Kowanyama the Justice Council elders drove a group of boys
who had stolen a car, several kilometres out of the community.
They were then left to walk all the way back home.
<P>
The humiliation was very real. Crucial to the success of these
justice groups is the role of &quot;shame&quot;, explains Peena,
&quot;It sure has an impact because they know that it's a shame
thing with our people. Many of our people know that they can misuse
the white man's law, but they know they can't do it amongst their
own. They know the Murri law is stronger, it always was and it
always will be. Our laws are very real, and if they, (Europeans),
did not interfere in the first place we wouldn't have all the
trouble we have today.&quot;
<P>
The roots of the juvenile justice problems in these communities
lie with the legacy of the Queensland Department of Aboriginal
Affairs which governed them until 1986. The Department, for example,
established a reserve on Palm Island in 1918. Until the late 1960s,
the threat of being sent from the mainland missions to Palm Island
was the heaviest sanction a Department manager could invoke. In
1996 the State government finally ceded control to the local Aboriginal
Council.
<P>
Nowadays the term &quot;community&quot; describes a large settlement
of dispossessed survivors. Unemployment in many Aboriginal communities
soars at 90 per cent. Elders in Palm Island and Kowanyama deplore
the lack of opportunities available to their young and acknowledge
that a lot of youth crime occurs because of sheer boredom.
<P>
In Kowanyama, the Justice Council is actively working with the
local police, local Aboriginal Council and state school to try
to increase opportunities for the unemployed and school age kids.
A new disco, BMX track, swimming pool, and indoor cricket hall
are part of this initiative. An annual excursion for young people
to other Aboriginal communities in the Cape York region, and regular
trips with their elders out bush, are now regularly organised.
<P>
Banjo Patterson, &quot;ol Runkie Banjo&quot; as he is affectionately
known, is a Kowanyama elder. 68 years old, he is from the Kokomnjena
clan and worked for most of his life on the cattle properties
in far North Queensland. Kowanyama was also once a mission. As
he says, &quot;I was brought up the hard way&quot;. Banjo is highly
respected, feared and admired by many young people. As a Justice
Council elder, he tells the parents of kids in trouble. &quot;Make
sure you look after them, take good care of them. That's what
you're there for, to take good care of them children, rear them
up proper way, not just running them loose. When they get out
of hand, they're gone forever. You might not ever catch up on
them again.&quot; A lot of parents don't seem to understand. They
say, &quot;You can't boss somebody else's children around, you
can't!' We say, 'Well, if you don't do it, someone else has to
do it, someone else has to straighten it up elsewhere'. So we're
trying our best to straighten things up to make things good for
the parents ... someone got to do it.&quot;
<P>
Despite the Kowanyama Justice Council's success in reducing juvenile
crime, Banjo is aware of the Group's limitations. &quot;They listen
there while we give them talking up, they'll listen to us there.
But soon as they walk through the door, they do the same thing
again,&quot; he laughs. 'Yeah, you've got to keep at 'em you know.
And then, they might learn, sooner or later. That's why we're
trying our hardest, we're still trying. Most of them are getting
a bit better, not much, but they still got a lead on us, you know,
and we're going to try and get that back to make things go normal
you know, make it good.&quot;
<P>
Both groups know the importance of sitting down and talking to
their troubled youth. Many meetings involve hours of counselling.
The kid's relations are also asked to attend. The Palm Island
elders are always delighted when teenagers regarded as &quot;hard
cases&quot; come back, stepping shyly into the courtroom to give
their quiet thanks for having received advice when it was most
needed.
<P>
&quot;We've had a couple of young ones come in and be bold in
their way. 'We don't have to listen to you!', they say and they
try and storm out. Then we jump up and hit the table and stop
them in their tracks. Then you'd have old Bill speak very steady
and they'd sit down. 'You walk out that door and you'll get the
biggest shock of your life. You'll be going out and put out by
police escort; put off this place so quick and smart you won't
know what hit you!'&quot; said Peena. She nods affirmatively,
as if to say, &quot;Of course this is the way it should be.&quot;
<P>
In Kowanyama, elders have punished some juvenile offenders by
banishing them from the community or by giving them a public belting.
Elders believe that for many of the &quot;harder cases&quot; the
possibility of ending up in prison is no longer a deterrent. After
a few young men broke into the Aboriginal Council and damaged
the building, it was decided by their families, community elders
and Council staff to publicly belt them. While acknowledging that
not everyone agreed to the punishment, a staff member said, &quot;I
must say that the public belting was in no means sinister ...
It was done in public where everybody could see. The beltings
were given by an uncle of two of the men and the third person
was given a belting by his grandfather.&quot;
<P>
Public beltings are regarded by some as a controversial solution
to juvenile offending. When visiting Kowanyama I asked people
about their opinion of the &quot;floggings&quot;. Without qualification,
local educators, police and administrators supported the idea.
I also went to the local school and spoke to two boys about the
Justice Council. Both believed the elders are doing their best
for their community and that the other kids who had been publicly
punished deserved it. I later spoke to two other boys who had
been before the Kowanyama Justice Council elders on numerous occasions.
They admitted that their old people scared them, but they defended
the right of the elders to punish them. &quot;They don't care
about anybody!&quot;, one defiant boy said. But when I asked him
what he would do if he was an old man and his kids were the ones
in trouble, he quickly answered, &quot;Flog 'em!&quot;.
<P>
The use of punishments such as public beltings has without a doubt
been a controversial issue in recent debates about the use of
Aboriginal law and custom. On the one hand, various people in
some communities believe it is their right to apply the law in
that way. On the other, punishments such as beltings and spearing
breach international human rights treaties such as the Convention
on the Rights of the Child and the Convention against Torture.
<P>
Whether a community uses customary law, and to what degree it
uses it, also raises issues about Aboriginal self-determination
and peoples' rights. In Kowanyama, elders believe that applying
Aboriginal law is in the interest of their community and its people.
It is their right - their collective right - to live in peace
without an unacceptable level of violence and crime. And if belting
juveniles is the way to achieve that, they see it as their right
to use it as a punishment. For Kowanyama elders, their solution
is an exercise in self-determination.
<P>
But how an Aboriginal community deals with community strife will
depend on what each community considers acceptable. What's done
in relation to juvenile offenders in Kowanyama may not be an acceptable
solution for a similar problem in other Queensland communities.
The use of public beltings or other such punishments will, in
some areas, be seen as violating the offender's human rights.
Obviously, the tension between &quot;self-determination&quot;
and human right standards is still an issue which needs to be
worked out.
<P>
The elders know their justice groups are not simply about crime
prevention. Their commitment is to restoring Aboriginal structures
of authority. Australian and international experts often discuss
the need for effective alternatives to jailing the young. It is
inspiring to see a group of old people have such a positive impact.
In Palm Island and Kowanyama, grass roots justice is working.
The elders are proud. As one elder said, &quot;It is keeping our
people out of prison and seeing that justice is done within the
community.&quot;
</TD> 
</TR>

<TR>
<TD ALIGN=CENTER COLSPAN=2>
