<HTML> <HEAD><TITLE>SPCenCIID Courses (Journalism)</TITLE></HEAD> <BODY BGCOLOR="#70DBDB" alink="#8c7853" vlink="#006600"> <CENTER><A HREF="http://acij.uts.edu.au/UniT_SPCenCIID.html"><IMG ALT="SPCenCIID logo" ALIGN=TOP SRC="images/Samlogo.gif" WIDTH=100></A></CENTER> <HR><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=100%><TD width= 200></TD><td align=left> http://acij.uts.edu.au/UniTavur/UniT/SPCenCIID/courses.html</td><tr></table>
<HR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr><td>
<P>
<A NAME="South Pacific"><Font size=3>South Pacific Centre for Communication and Information in Development  </Font></A><P>
<Font size=7>Development media courses</A></Font size=7>
<P>
More than 150 journalism students have graduated from the University of Papua New Guinea in the past two decades, many of them now working in several other Pacific countries. Some are now in the news media in the Philippines and several African countries. Journalism students follow either a two-year programme of study leading to a <A HREF="#DIPLOMA">Diploma in Media Studies</A>, or a four-year program of study leading to a <A HREF="#DEGREE">Bachelor of Journalism degree</A>. 
<P>
A graduate <A HREF="#CERT">Certificate in
Investigative Journalism</A> began in 1995 for mid-career professional journalists. The following information is drawn from the <B>1996 Development Communications Handbook</B> published by SPCenCIID.
<P>
<HR>
<A HREF="#Development"><IMG WIDTH=30 ALIGN=BOTTOM  SRC="images/Samlogo.gif"></A> <Font size=4><B><A NAME="DIPLOMA"> Diploma in Media Studies:</A></Font></B><BR>
The diploma offers a thorough grounding in the skills of journalism, reporting and editing on a
fortnightly newspaper, <A HREF="../UniT_Home.html">Uni Tavur</A>, a 16-week period of supervised practical experience in newsroom of the national media, advanced skills in either broadcast or print journalism, skills in writing either <A HREF="#TOK PISIN">Tok Pisin</A> or <A HREF="#HIRI MOTU">Hiri Motu </A>(for Papua New Guinea students), and a selection of courses in other subjects
offered by University.
<HR>
<A HREF="#DEVELOPMENT"><IMG WIDTH=30 ALIGN=BOTTOM  SRC="images/Samlogo.gif"></A> <Font size=4><B><A NAME="DEGREE"> Bachelor of Journalism:</A></Font></B><BR>
The degree offers all the practical journalism training offered to diploma students and includes courses
in either <A HREF="#TOK PISIN">Tok Pisin Writing</A>  or <A HREF="#HIRI MOTU">Hiri Motu Writing</A>. In addition, the students must first successfully complete the  University Arts or Science Foundation Year, and follow a sequence of Part 1 and Part 2 courses in the academic discipline of their choice. Students must also study <A HREF="#MASS COMMS">Mass Communications
(25.209)</A>, the history and sociology of the mass media.
<P>
It is also possible for students who have successfully completed the two-year diploma programme to
continue doing the degree programme. They do not apply for the diploma, but do another two years'
study, concentrating on their "minor" discipline and doing Journalism courses not taken -- such as
electives <A HREF="#ELECTRONIC">Electronic Media II (25.220)</A>, <A HREF="#PRINT">Print Media Production II (25.221)</A> and Public Relations
(25.222). Students who have already completed the diploma programme are not required to do
Foundation Year.
<P>
<HR>
<A HREF="#SOUTH"><IMG WIDTH=30 ALIGN=BOTTOM  SRC="images/Samlogo.gif"></A> <Font size=4><B><A NAME="CERT"> Certificate in Investigative Journalism:</A></Font></B><BR>
A course in <A HREF="#INVEST">Investigative Journalism (25.300)</A> for professional and graduate journalists began in the Second Semester 1995. This is a full-time 12 point course designed for mid-career journalists and
qualifies towards a higher degree or carries a certificate (CertInvestJourn).
<P>
<HR>
<A HREF="#SOUTH"><IMG WIDTH=30 ALIGN=BOTTOM  SRC="images/Samlogo.gif"></A> <Font size=4><B><A NAME="CERT"> Course requirements:</A></Font></B><P>
<Font size=3><B>BACHELOR OF JOURNALISM</B>
<BR>
<OL><LI>Students must successfully complete courses covering four academic years totalling not less than 93
points. The course must include:
<P>
Either 27 points from Arts Foundation Year, to include 35.111 Introduction to Information and Mass Communication, 04.101 Foundation English and 51.113 Say It With Figures, or 24 points from
Science Foundation Year, or successful completion of the Diploma in Media Studies programme; 
<P>
<LI>Not less than 42 points in Journalism courses, to include all <B>compulsory</B> parts (indicated by **) 
<P>
<LI>Points from Arts Foundation, or 27 from Journalism and elective courses to include at least 3
points in either 28.191 Tok Pisin Writing or 28.192 Hiri Motu Writing; 
<P>
<LI>An elective choice between 25.220 Electronic Media II, or 25.221 Print Media II (or 25.222 Public
Relations -- 6 points each). 
<P>
<LI>The number of Part 1 courses should add up to 51 points, while Part 2 courses make up the balance
of 42 points: </OL>
<P>
<B>OTHER COURSES</B>
<P>
<B>Year 1, Semester 1: </B><BR>
Foundation year<BR>
** 35.111 Introduction to Information and Mass Communications (3)<BR>
** 04.101 Foundation English (3)<BR>
** 51.113 Say It With Figures (3)<BR>
= 12/15 points<BR>
<P>
