= 12 points
<P>
<B>DIPLOMA IN MEDIA STUDIES</B>
<P>
Students must successfully complete courses covering two academic years totalling a minimum 48
points, including 35.111 Introduction to Information and Mass Communications and 04.101
Foundation English.
<P>
<B>Year 1, Semester 1:</B><BR>
** 25.110 Shorthand (3)<BR>
** 35.111 Introduction to Information and Mass Communications (3)<BR>
** 04.101 Foundation English (3)<BR>
** 25.120 News Techniques (3)<BR>
** 25.121 Practical Reporting l (3)<BR>
= 12 points
<P>
<B>Year 1, Semester 2:</B><BR>
** 25.122 News Coverage (3) Two Part One<BR>
** 25.123 Practical Reporting II (3) minor courses<BR>
= 12 points
<P>
<B>Year 2, Semester 1:</B><BR>
** 25.109 Media Law and Ethics (3)<BR>
** 25.217 Electronic Media 1 (3)<BR>
or<BR>
25.218 Print Media Production 1 (3)<BR>
and either Tok Pisin Writing or Hiri Motu Writing (3) plus<BR>
one other Part 2 course: (3)<BR>
= 12 points
<P>
<B>Year 2, Semester 2:</B><BR>
** 25.213 News Practice (12)<BR>
or<BR>
Credit application<BR>
= 12 points
<P>
<B>CERTIFICATE IN INVESTIGATIVE JOURNALISM</B>
<P>
Students wishing to enrol for this course must (a) have been awarded a Diploma in Media Studies, or
equivalent, and have spent a minimum of three years as a professional journalist in a news media
organisation, or (b) have been awarded a Bachelor of Journalism degree and a minimum of two years
as a professional journalist. The course involves fulltime study and preparation of assignments for one
semester.<BR>
= 12 points
<P>
<HR>
<A HREF="#SOUTH"><IMG WIDTH=30 ALIGN=BOTTOM  SRC="images/Samlogo.gif"></A> <Font size=4><B><A NAME=""> <B>Course descriptions:</B></Font><BR>
Part One Courses
</A><P>
<Font size=3><B>BACHELOR OF JOURNALISM</B>
<BR>
<P> 
<B>35.111 INTRODUCTION TO INFORMATION AND MASS COMMUNICATION</B><BR> 
(3 points)
Semester 1<BR>
Coordinator: Leah Kalamoroh<BR>
Replaces: 35.001,35.003<BR>
Prerequisites: None<BR>
Course description: An overview of information and mass communication and is essential background
for all students undertaking Centre programs. Topics include definitions; history of activities in PNG
and the Pacific; policy and legislative framework in PNG; role of information in development;
development communications; information resources in PNG; indigenous knowledge; use and
awareness of information; user studies; access to information; organisation and coordination of
information; human factors and profession- alism; communication of information; information
technology and systems; regional and international issues; global information infrastructure.<BR>
Lectures: Two hours of lectures a week; one hour tutorial.
Assessment: Test, essays, final exam.<BR>
Texts: To be advised.
<P>
<B>25.109 MEDIA LAW AND ETHICS</B><BR>
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 1<BR>
Lecturer: Sorariba Nash<BR>
Prerequisite: None<BR>
Course description: A course designed to give students an understanding of the law in relation to the
Journalism profession, media ethics, and how the laws of Papua New Guinea and the Pacific affect the
media. Special attention is paid to the PNG Constitution, legal system, court reporting, contempt of
court and Parliament, defamation, privilege, blasphemy, obscenity, sedition and freedom of
information. A study of the fundamentals of media ethics.<BR>
Lectures: Two hours of lectures per week; one hour tutorial.<BR>
Assessment: 70 per cent semester assignments; 30 per cent final exam.<BR>
Texts: <BR>
* Peter Henshall and David Ingram, The News Manual (3): Ethics and the Law (Port Moresby:
Poroman Press, 1991).<BR>
* David Robie (ed), Nius Bilong Pasifik: Mass Media in the Pacific (Port Moresby: UPNG Press,
1995).<BR>
* Pacific Journalism Review
<P>
<B>25.110 SHORTHAND</B><BR>
(3 points)<BR>
Both semesters<BR>
Lecturer: To be advised.<BR>
Prerequisite: None<BR>
Course description: A course in shorthand for reporters.
<P>
<B>25.120 NEWS TECHNIQUES </B><BR>
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 1<BR>
Lecturer: David Robie<BR>
Prerequisite: 04.1 01 Foundation English, 35.111 Introduction to Mass Communications.<BR>
Course description: A course designed to teach students the nature of news, how to gather and assess
news, interviewing techniques and basic news writing techniques.<BR>
Lectures: Two hours lectures per week; one hour tutorial.<BR>
Assessment: 70 per cent semester assignments; 30 per cent final exam.<BR>
Texts:<BR> 
* David Robie, Newsroom Handbook (Port Moresby: SPCenCIID, 1995).<BR>
* Introduction to Macintosh for the Newsroom (Port Moresby: SPCenCIID, 1994).<BR>
* Robie (ed), Nius Bilong Pasifik: Mass Media in the Pacific (Port Moresby: UPNG Press, 1995).<BR>
* Pacific Journalism Review<BR>
* Post-Courier, The National, Saturday Independent<BR>
* Other materials supplied by lecturer
<P>
<B>25.121 PRACTICAL REPORTING I</B><BR>
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 1<BR>
Lecturer: David Robie<BR>
Course description: Students produce a fortnightly newspaper, <B>Uni Tavur</B>, covering the life of the
University community, PNG and the Pacific region. Under supervision by the lecturers, students learn
the importance of writing accurately, establishing news sources while they learn from 25.120 News
Techniques.<BR>
Lectures: A minimum 10 hours a week practical news-gathering for <B>Uni Tavur</B> and a weekly editorial
conference.<BR> 
Assessment: Reporting for <B>Uni Tavur</B> 50 per cent; two assignments 20 per cent, practical reporting
exam 30 per cent.<BR>
Texts:<BR>
* David Robie, Newsroom Handbook (Port Moresby: SPCenCIlD,1995).<BR>
* Introduction to Macintosh for the Newsroom (Port Moresby: SPCenCIID,1994).<BR>
* Post-Courier, The National, Saturday Independent<BR>
* Pacific Journalism Review
<P>
<B>25.122 NEWS COVERAGE</B><BR>
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 2<BR>
Lecturer: Sorariba Nash<BR>
Prerequisite: 25.109 Media Law and Ethics, 25.120 News Techniques.<BR>
Course description: An advanced reporting course building on 25.120 News Techniques. Students
learn how to apply basic news-gathering and writing techniques to a range of fields, such as politics,
crime and courts, finance and economy, churches, sport and other issues.<BR>
Lectures: Two hours lectures per week, one hour tutorial.<BR>
Assessment: 70 per cent semester tests, assignments; 30 per cent final exam.<BR>
Texts:<BR>
* Peter Henshall and David Ingram, The News Manual (2): Advanced Reporting (Port Moresby:
Poroman Press, 1991). <BR>
* David Robie (ed), Nius Bilong Pasifik: Mass Media in the Pacific (Port
Moresby: UPNG Press, 1995).<BR>
* Pacific Journalism Review<BR>
* Materials supplied by lecturer. 
<P>
<B>25.123 PRACTICAL REPORTING II</B><BR>
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 2<BR>
Prerequisite: 25.1 21 Practical Reporting I.<BR>
Lecturer: David Robie<BR>
Course description: Students carry out more advanced reporting for <B>Uni Tavur</B>, establish news contacts
and become responsible for various rounds or write features and take photographs. They are required
to report exclusively for <B>Uni Tavur</B> while on the Practical Reporting Courses, but are free to report for
the PNG Post-Courier, The National, the Saturday Independent after completing the first year of core
journalism subjects.<BR>
Lectures: Five hours practical news-gathering for <B>Uni Tavur</B>, including weekly editorial conference.<BR>
Assessment: Reporting for <B>Uni Tavur</B> 50 per cent; two assignments 20 per cent, practical reporting
exam 30 per cent.<BR>
Texts:<BR>
* David Robie, Newsroom Handbook (Port Moresby: SPCenCIID, 1995).<BR>
* Introduction to Macintosh for the Newsroom (Port Moresby: SPCenCIID, 1994).<BR>
* Post-Courier. The National, Saturday Independent<BR>
* Pacific Journalism Review<BR>
* Materials supplied by lecturer.
<P>
<B><A NAME="TOK PISIN">28.191 TOK PISIN WRITING -- TRANSLATION I</A></B><BR>
<I>(Offered by Language & Literature Department) </I><BR>
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 1<BR>
Lecturer: Dicks Thomas<BR>
Course Description: The aim of the course is to provide students with advanced competence in writing
Tok Pisin, focusing on the sentence and paragraph levels, including features of cohesion and
development for written forms. Students be given practical guidance in the writing of effective Tok
Pisin papers, including social events, reports, summaries, memos, short stories and folklore.<BR>
Texts: To be advised.
<P>
<A NAME="HIRI MOTU"><B>28.192 HIRI MOTU WRITING -- TRANSLATION I</B></A><BR>
<I>(Language & Literature Department)</I><BR>
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 1<BR>
Lecturer: Mary Bray<BR>
Course Description: The aim of the course is to provide students with competence in writing Hiri Motu,
focusing on the sentence and paragraph levels including features of cohesion and development for
written forms. Guidance will be given to student son emerging forms of standardisation along with
in-depth practice in applying to Hiri Motu translation principles related to lexical equivalence,
transliteration and the creation of new terminology.<BR>
Texts: To be advised
<P>
<Font size=4>Part Two courses </Font>
<P>
 <B>15.262 PHILOSOPHY AND JOURNALISM</B><BR>
<I>(Offered by Politics and Public Administration Department)</I><BR>
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 1<BR>
Lecturer: William Ferea<BR>
Prerequisite: For Journalism students: 25.209 Mass Communications.<BR>
Course description: The course will discuss issues such as objectivity, truth, credibility, ethical
behaviour, journalistic quality, meaning, logical discourse, propaganda and the news, and impact of
journalism. A study of how philosophical insight can help journalists in their profession.<BR>
Lectures: Two lectures, one tutorial.<BR>
Assessment: Exercises, tests and final examination.<BR>
Texts:<BR>
* J.C. Merrill and S.J. O'Dell, Philosophy and Journalism.<BR>
* David Robie (ed), Nius Bilong Pasifik: Mass Media in the Pacific (Port Moresby: UPNG Press,
1995).
<P>
<A NAME="MASS COMMS"><B>25.209 MASS COMMUNICATIONS</B></A><BR>
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 2<BR>
Lecturer: David Robie<BR>
Prerequisite: For Journalism Students: 25.109 Media Law and Ethics, 25.120 News Techniques,
25.122 News Coverage.<BR>
Course description: An introduction to mass communication theories and models. Exploration of issues
in the mass media, including the history and sociology of the mass media, media ownership, language
in the media, advertising, development journalism and bias, race and gender, media and culture. An
overview of South Pacific news media, political and social issues.<BR>
Lectures: One two-hour lecture; one tutorial.<BR>
Assessment: Semester essay assignments and seminar 60 per cent; 40 per cent final exam.<BR>
Texts:<BR> 
* Bourne, Richard, News on a Knife-edge: Gemini Joumalism and a Global Agenda (London: John
Libbey, 1995).<BR>
* Hester, AI & Wai Lan To (eds), Handbook for Third World Journalists (Athens, Georgia: Centre for
International Mass Communications, 1987).<BR>
* Layton, Suzanna, The Contemporary Pacific Islands Press (St Lucia: University of Queensland Press,
1992).<BR>
* Millett, John (ed), Development and the Media (Port Moresby: INA, 1988).<BR>
* Pacific Journalism Review (UPNG Press, 1994/95/96).<BR>
* Robie, David, Blood on their Banner: Nationalist Struggles in the South Pacific (London: Zed Press,
1989).<BR>
* Robie, David (ed), Nius Bilong Pasifik: Mass Media in the Pacific (Port Moresby: UPNG Press,
1995).<BR>
* Robie, David, Pacific Handbook for Mass Communications (Port Moresby: SPCenCIID, Press,
1995).<BR>
* Ward, Ian, The Politics of the Media, (Melbourne: Macmillan, 1995).<BR>
* Windschuttle Keith, The Media (Melbourne: Penguin, 1988).
<P>
<B>25.213 NEWS PRACTICE</B><BR>
(12 points)<BR>
Semester 2<BR>
Lecturers: David Robie and Sorariba Nash<BR>
Prerequisite: Final year BJourn or second year DIMS.
Course description: A 16 week full-time attachment (internship) with one or more news media
organisations. Students are supervised by working professionals or chiefs of staff in their attachment
newsroom. They are required to be punctual and disciplined in their work. BJourn candidates must do
their News Practice with a media organisation not a PR agency, or corporation. An elective Public
Relations Practice (35.202) course is available.<BR>
Assessment: Jointly by fortnightly progress reports by the news organisations' editors and lecturers.<BR>
Pass/Fail grade.<BR>
<P>
<I>Alternative:</I> Students working on paid employment for a news media organisation can apply for a credit
after they have completed their 16 weeks. They must submit a supporting letter from the editor of the
media organisation and produce a file of news reports and other journalism for assessment by the
lecturers.
<P>
<A NAME="ELECTRONIC"><B>25.217 ELECTRONIC MEDIA I</B></A> <BR>
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 1<BR>
Lecturer: Sorariba Nash<BR>
Prerequisites: 25.109 Media Law and Ethics, 25.120 News Techniques, 25.121 Practical Reporting I,
25.123 Practical Reporting II, 25.122 News Coverage.<BR>
Course description: An introduction to electronic news media, broadcast writing (radio and TV);
students learn production techniques for news, current affairs and documentary programmes. They also
learn how to operate portable tape recorders and do script writing. Techniques of writing for radio and
TV are an important part of the course. Interviewing techniques are also taught and practised.<BR>
Lectures: Two hours lectures, two hours practicals.
Assessment: Assignments 50 per cent; attendance 10 per cent; major project 40 per cent.<BR>
Texts:<BR> 
* De Maeseneer, Paul Here's the News: A Radio News Manual (Paris: UNESCO, 1987).<BR>
* Sorariba Nash G., Introduction to Radio Journalism (Port Moresby: UPNG, 1993).
<P>
<A NAME="PRINT"><B>25.218 PRINT MEDIA PRODUCTION I</B></A><BR>
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 1 and 2<BR>
Lecturer: David Robie<BR>
Prerequisites: 25.109 Media Law and Ethics, 25.120 News Techniques, 25.121 Practical Reporting I,
25.123 Practical Reporting II, 25.122 News Coverage.
Course description: An introduction to basic editing, headline writing and desktop publishing skills.
Students become subeditors on the fortnightly Journalism newspaper <B>Uni Tavur</B> which covers news of
the University community, Papua New Guinea and the Pacific. Supervised by lecturers and Print
Media Production II editors, the subeditors process news stories by the student reporters (25.122 and
25.123 Practical Reporting) and other copy for the paper.
Lectures: Minimum 20 hours a week of practical print production and lectures, and a weekly editorial
conference.<BR>
Equipment needed: An ems rule or centimetre rule, picture proportional scale, pasteup cutting blade.
Assessment: Subediting on <B>Uni Tavur</B> 60 per cent; computer and editorial theory tests 40 per cent.<BR>
Texts:<BR>
* Barton, Frank, The Newsroom (Berlin: International Institute of Journalism, 1981).<BR>
* Robie, David, Print Media Handbook, (Port Moresby: UPNG, 1994).<BR>
* Course materials supplied by lecturer.<BR>
* Post-Courier, The National, Saturday Independent.
<P>
<B>25.220 ELECTRONIC MEDIA II</B><BR>
(6 points)<BR>
Semester 2<BR>
Lecturer: Sorariba Nash<BR>
Prerequisite: 25.217 Electronic Media.<BR>
Course description: Students are taught editing (audio and video) techniques, studio management,
advanced broadcast writing (radio and TV scripting), production techniques like sound mixing, and the
use of broadcast or telecast facilities. Students are also assigned to produce special radio or TV
documentaries (University on Air) either to be used by NBC or EM TV.<BR>
Lectures: Two hours lectures; two hours practicals.
Assessment: Assignments 50 per cent; attendance 10 per cent; major assignment 40 per cent.<BR>
Text:<BR>
* Masterton, Murray and R. Patching, Now the News in Detail (Geelong, Australia: Deakin University
Press, 1990).
<P>
<B>25.221 PRINT MEDIA PRODUCTION II</B><BR>
(6 points)<BR>
Semester 1 and 2<BR>
Lecturer: David Robie<BR>
Prerequisite: 25.218 Print Media Production I.<BR>
Course description: Advanced editing and desktop publishing skills. Students taking this course take
the senior role of editor, chief-of-staff or chief subeditor on the Journalism newspaper <B>Uni Tavur</B>.
Among their tasks are writing editorials, conducting the editiorial conference and assigning the
subeditors and reporters their tasks under supervision by the lecturer. They will also undertake
responsibility for a desktop publishing project, such as a community paper, a newsletter or sport
publication.<BR>
Lectures: Students will be required to be self-motivated in the editorial organisation of <B>Uni Tavur</B>
(under lecturer's guidance) and on individual publishing projects. A minimum 20 hours a week.<BR>
Equipment needed: An ems rule or centimetre rule, picture proportional scale, pasteup cutting blade.<BR>
Assessment: Subediting on <B>Uni Tavur</B> 50 per cent; special publication project tests 30 per cent; theory
tests 20 per cent.<BR>
Texts:<BR>
* Barton, Frank, The Newsroom (Berlin: International Institute of Journalism, 1981).<BR>
* Robie, David, Print Media Handbook, (Port Moresby: UPNG, 1994).<BR>
* Course materials supplied by lecturer.<BR>
* Post-Courier, The National Saturday Independent.
<P>
<Font size=4>Special elective courses on application: </Font>
<P>
<B>35.240 ADVANCED NEWS PRACTICE (Advanced Field Work)</B><BR> 
(6 points)<BR>
Semester 1/2 and Lahara
Coordinator: David Robie
Prerequisite: At least one of the following 25.220 Electronic Media I or 25.221 Print Media Production
II and 25.213 News Practice with good marks, (or equivalent).<BR>
Course description: This course is intended to provide further intensive practical experience for students
on the Degree programme. Students will work in selected news media to develop skills and knowledge.
An option would be advanced work on <B>Uni Tavur</B>, or a special publication project.<BR>
Practical: Two seminars and 14 weeks' field work (including optional five weeks during the
November/December Lahara period), report on attachment.<BR>
Assessment: Students will be supervised throughout, and two seminar presentations, and a detailed
report will be required.<BR>
Texts: To be advised.
<P>
<B>35.287 COMMUNITY PUBLISHING (Project)</B><BR> 
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 1/2 and Lahara<BR>
Coordinator: David Robie<BR>
Prerequisite: All second-year journalism core subjects (or equivalent).<BR> 
Course description: A fulltime one/two week course in desktop publishing, covering similar criteria as
in 25.218 Print Media Production I but with special reference to a specialist area, eg. non-government
organisations, corporate newsletters. This will be followed by supervision of newsletters/publications
over a three-month period and an evaluative seminar. 
Assessment: Pass/Fail grade based on the coordinator's report, periormance as observed by
Coordinator, and publishing of newsletters/publications.<BR>
Texts: To be advised.
<P>
<B>35.288 SPECIAL TOPICS IN JOURNALISM (Reading Course)</B><BR> 
(3 points)<BR>
Semester 1/2 and Lahara<BR>
Coordinator: David Robie<BR>
Prerequisite: At least one of the following: 25.220 Electronic Media I or 25.221 Print Media Production
II and 25.213 News Practice with good marks, (or equivalent).<BR>
Course description: This course will usually be available for a Degree student with good marks to
pursue a particular field of interest in depth or research under Faculty supervision. Approval will be
needed by Head of Centre in consultation with the lecturers.<BR>
Assessment: Hours, assessment and detailed content to be arranged with course lecturers.
