<A HREF="#SOUTH"><IMG WIDTH=30 ALIGN=BOTTOM  SRC="images/Samlogo.gif"></A> <Font size=4><B>Graduate course: </B></Font>
<P>
<A NAME="INVEST"><B>25.300 INVESTIGATIVE JOURNALISM</B></A><BR>
(12 points)<BR>
Semester 2 (alternate years -- offered next in 1997)<BR>
Coordinator: David Robie (with input from investigative journalists and media and company law
specialists from Australia, New Zealand, Philippines, United States and Papua New Guinea).<BR>
Prerequisite: Diploma of Media Studies and minimum of three years' professional journalism in a news
media organisation, or a Bachelor of Journalism degree and two years' professional experience.<BR>
Alternatively, at the lecturers' discretion, a professional journalist with a recognised expertise in the
profession. The course could count either towards a Bachelor of Journalism, or a Certificate will be
awarded.<BR>
Course description: A course designed to teach experienced journalists advanced strategies in
investigative journalism, techniques in agenda setting journalism, advanced feature and special writing,
current affairs TV documentary making and analytical studies in media ethical dilemmas. Participation
will be restricted to approximately four/six journalists. In their practical work they would form an
investigative reporting unit and prepare major reports for publication in mainstream print media and/or
for broadcast on electronic media.<BR>
Lectures: Approx 10 hours lectures, workshops and seminars a week; approx: 30 hours
research/writing a week.<BR>
Assessment: Four major investigative assignments to be completed under supervision of lecturers and
published or broadcast in mainstream media, or Uni Tavur (60 per cent of total); a methodology report
on the investigations (10 per cent); and two three-hour exams on investigative/agenda-building theories
and techniques, and advanced media law and ethics, or an exam and a seminar (30 per cent).<BR>
Texts include: <BR>
* Bacon, Wendy, Journalism and the Law (Sydney: Australian Centre for Independent Journalism,
1992).<BR>
* Fogg, Christine, Mastering the Maze: A Library Guide for Journalists and Researchers in the Media
(Sydney: ACIJ, 1994).<BR>
* Herman, Edward & Noam Chomsky, Manufacturing Consent: The Political Economy of the Mass Media (New York: Vintage Books, 1994).<BR>
* Protess, David (et al), The Journalism of Outrage: Investigative Reporting and Agenda Building in
America (New York: Guildford Press, 1991).<BR>
* Maslog, Crispin, Communication, Values and Society (Manila: Philippine Association of
Communication Educators, 1992).<BR>
* Robie, David (ed), Investigative Journalism: A Pacific Reader (Port Moresby: SPCenCIID, 1995).<BR>
* Robie, David (ed), Investigative Joumalism: A Pacific Reader 2 (Port Moresby: SPCenCIID, 1996).<BR>
* Robie, David (ed), Nius Bilong Pasifik: Mass Media in the Pacific (Port Moresby: UPNG Press,
1995).<BR>
